本书仅供参考，并非旨在替代专业建议。作者和出版商明确声明，对于因使用本书信息而直接或间接产生的任何责任，概不负责。您的具体医疗状况应咨询专业人士。本书中提及的任何产品，并不代表作者或出版商对该产品的认可。

斯科特·亚当斯的更多内容

More Content from Scott Adams

scottadams.locals.com的订阅者可以得到新的Dilbert Reborn每日连载漫画（经典Dilbert的更辛辣和未经过滤的版本）、一部名为Robots Read News的新漫画（对头条新闻的不敬分析）、超过 200 个（并且还在增加）关于生活改善和才能积累的微课程、其他地方无法获得的频繁直播视频、我的小说《上帝的碎片》和《宗教战争》以及其他特殊内容。

Subscribers on scottadams.locals.com get the new Dilbert Reborn daily comic strip (a spicier and unfiltered version of classic Dilbert), a new comic called Robots Read News (an irreverent analysis of the headlines), more than 200 (and counting) micro lessons on life improvement and talent stacking, frequent livestream videos available nowhere else, my novels God’s Debris and The Religion War, and other special content.

有些日子，订阅者会帮忙创作漫画，并实时观看创作过程。其中也有很多政治内容，所以不必感到惊讶。Locals 社区已经发展成为一个数字好友群，这就是它的氛围。

On some days, subscribers help write comics and watch the drawing process in real time. There is a lot of political content too, so don’t be surprised by that. The Locals community has evolved into a digital friend group, and that’s the vibe.

仅需阅读Dilbert Reborn漫画（不含其他废话），请在 X（以前称为 Twitter）上关注并订阅 @Scott AdamsSays。

For just the Dilbert Reborn comic without the other nonsense, follow and subscribe on X (formerly known as Twitter), @ScottAdamsSays.

第二版前言

Preface to the Second Edition

西2013年，当我完成本书第一版时，我完全没有想到它会对商业世界和个人成功领域产生如此巨大的影响。如果书中某些内容看起来似曾相识，那是因为您已经在其他畅销书、无数播客和视频片段中看到过我的作品——尤其是关于天赋堆叠、系统重于目标、微步骤、热情、运气等等的理念。

When I finished writing the first edition of this book in 2013, I had no idea how much impact it would have on the business world and on the field of personal success. If some of the content in these pages looks familiar, it’s because by now you have seen my work referenced in other bestselling books and countless podcasts and video clips—particularly the ideas around talent stacks, systems over goals, micro-steps, passion, luck, and more.

几乎每天，我都能听到读者说，他们运用从这本书中学到的知识减肥、找到爱情、保持健康、找到理想的工作、戒酒，总之，在他们关心的每件事上都取得了成功。这正是我希望这本书能为人们带来的。只是没想到它的效果这么好。

Nearly every day, I hear from readers who used what they learned from this book to lose weight, find love, get fit, land a dream job, quit drinking, and generally win at everything that matters to them. That’s what I hoped the book would do for people. I just didn’t expect it to work so well.

我写作时，喜欢为一位真实或虚构的读者而写。这是一种找到我正确声音的技巧。当我写这本书的第一版时，我想象着我当时还小的继子有一天会读到它。这激励着我花了两年时间把它作为我的副业。你可以把这些文字想象成我认为一个年轻人在生活中取得成功所需知道的一切。

When I write, I like to write for one real or imaginary reader. It’s a technique for finding my right voice. When I wrote the first edition of this book, I imagined my then-young stepson someday reading it. That was my motivation for making it my side project for two years of my life. You could think of these pages as everything I thought one young man needed to know to succeed in life.

不幸的是，贾斯汀没能读完这本书，就被芬太尼迷住了。他也不知道命运让他意外地成为了改变的推动者，改变了成千上万的人，而这些人终有一天会读到这本为他写的书。

Unfortunately, Justin didn’t get a chance to finish reading it before fentanyl took him. Nor did he know fate had made him an accidental agent of change for thousands of people who would someday read a book written for him.

自从我撰写了他的书的第一版以来，我的人生经历了一些显著的起伏，但我发现，运用我在这里描述的方法，我几乎可以摆脱任何困境，并最终走向成功。如果你愿意，这些方法也同样适用于你。

My life went through some notable ups and downs since I authored the first edition of his book, but I find I can dig myself out of almost any hole—and eventually come out ahead—using the methods I describe here. The methods will work for you, too, if you let them.

在本书的新版本中，我决定保留所有关于我第一任妻子雪莉的提及，因为她是我最初写作时生活的一部分。提及她的例子是重要的背景，多年后仍然“有效”。

For this new edition of the book, I decided to keep all references to my first wife, Shelly, because she was part of my my life during the initial writing. The examples that mention her are important context and still “work” all these years later.

因此，怀着感激和赞赏的心情，我向你介绍了《如何在几乎所有事情上失败但仍然取得巨大成功：第二版》。

So with gratitude and appreciation, I give you How to Fail at Almost Everything and Still Win Big: Second Edition.

 

 

介绍

Introduction

我如果你已经达到了你渴望的成功，无论是个人生活还是职业发展，那么这本书很可能只是一个关于一个人如何通过失败走向成功的半娱乐性故事。但你或许也会注意到我的故事中有一些熟悉的模式，这些模式会证实（或者说证实偏差），你的成功并非完全是运气。而这种肯定是你在家人和朋友那里得不到的，因为他们把你看得一团糟。

If you’re already as successful as you want to be, both personally and professionally, all you are likely to get from this book is a semi-entertaining tale about a guy who failed his way to success. But you might also notice some familiar patterns in my story that will give you confirmation (or confirmation bias) that your own success wasn’t entirely luck. That’s the sort of validation you can’t get from your family and friends who see you as a hot mess.

这是一个人在无数次令人尴尬的失败中，最终获得意想不到的成功的故事。如果你刚刚踏上通往成功的旅程——无论你如何定义成功——或者正在思考自己一直以来究竟做错了什么，我希望你能从中找到一些新奇的想法。或许，你所知道的，加上我自认为知道的，足以让你远离那条“胡扯”。

This is the story of one person’s unlikely success within the context of scores of embarrassing failures. If you’re just starting your journey toward success—however you define it—or are wondering what you’ve been doing wrong until now, I expect you’ll find some novel ideas here. Maybe the combination of what you know plus what I think I know will be enough to keep you out of the woodchipper.

我最终的成功，主要是天赋、运气、努力，还是偶然之间恰到好处的平衡？我唯一能确定的是，我采取了一种有意识的策略，以一种更容易让好运降临到我身上的方式去管理我的机会。我的策略起了作用吗？还是运气只是运气而已，其他一切都只是借口？说实话，我不知道。所以我建议你把我的故事和其他成功人士的故事进行比较，看看你是否能发现一些规律。这正是我从小就一直沿用的方法，要么它奏效了，要么我只是运气好而已。我永远也不会知道究竟是哪一种。如果你从这本书中汲取了一些灵感，并最终取得了巨大的成功，你也不会知道究竟是什么导致了这种差异。但你可能会认为自己知道，而这个原因很可能与你身上那些不同程度的卓越之处有关。人类的大脑就是这样运作的。不过，也许对你来说，答案是肯定的。对我来说，我更愿意接受自己的无知，并把它留作一个开放性的问题。

Was my eventual success primarily a result of talent, luck, hard work, or an accidental just-right balance of each? All I know for sure is that I pursued a conscious strategy of managing my opportunities in a way that would make it easier for luck to find me. Did my strategy make a difference, or is luck just luck, and everything else is just rationalization? Honestly, I don’t know. That’s why I suggest you compare my story with the stories of other people who found success and see if you notice any patterns. That’s exactly the process I have used since childhood, and it either worked for me or I simply got lucky. I’ll never know which it was. If you pick up some ideas in this book and go on to great success, you won’t know exactly what made the difference either. But you might think you do, and that reason will probably have something to do with your many levels of awesomeness. That’s how human brains work. But hey, maybe in your case it’s true. In my case, I prefer to embrace my ignorance and leave it an open question.

话虽如此，这不是一本建议书。如果你曾经听过漫画家的建议，很可能结果并不好。首先，很难分辨漫画家什么时候是认真的，什么时候是在精心设计一个恶作剧。我设计过一些持续多年的恶作剧，有时除了我之外没有人参与其中。有些恶作剧至今仍在酝酿中。我在网上甚至在现实生活中假扮过其他人。我写下一些我并不真正认同的观点，只是为了看看会有什么反应。我曾经乔装打扮，潜入一个高层商务会议，只为为《呆伯特》收集素材。

That said, this is not an advice book. If you’ve ever taken advice from a cartoonist, there’s a good chance it didn’t end well. For starters, it’s hard to know when a cartoonist is being serious and when they are constructing an elaborate practical joke. I’ve crafted pranks that spanned years, sometimes when no one was in on the joke but me. Some of those pranks are still percolating. I have posed as other people online and even in person. I have written opinions I don’t actually hold just to see what reaction I would get. I once wore a professional disguise and infiltrated a high-level business meeting just to get material for Dilbert.

更糟糕的是，我写这本书是拿钱的，我们都知道，金钱会像穿丁字裤的河马一样扭曲真相。而且别忘了，对大多数读者来说，我是个陌生人。相信陌生人永远不是个好主意。

On top of that, I got paid to write this book, and we all know that money distorts truth like a hippo in a thong. And let’s not forget I’m a stranger to most people reading this. It’s never a good idea to trust strangers.

无论以何种客观标准衡量，我或许都是世界上最不可信的人之一。但我坦然承认，如果让我在说真话和说笑话之间做出选择，我会选择最有娱乐价值的那一条。

By any objective measure, I might be one of the least credible people on earth. I’m not too proud to admit that given a choice of saying what’s true versus what’s funny, I’ll take the path with the greatest entertainment value.

我什么都不是专家，包括我自己的工作。我画画就像醉醺醺的吼猴，写作风格也介于令人费解和幼稚之间。我一直不明白为什么我能一直拿到钱。

I’m also not an expert at anything, including my own job. I draw like an inebriated howler monkey, and my writing style falls somewhere between baffling and sophomoric. It’s an ongoing mystery to me why I keep getting paid.

更糟糕的是，一个人以书本的形式给另一个人提供建议，这种想法本身就存在问题。没有放之四海而皆准的方案。如果这本书里真的有什么内容能同时适用于所有人，那我才惊讶呢。

To make matters worse, there are inherent problems with the whole idea of one person giving advice to another in book form. One size doesn’t fit all. I’d be surprised if there’s anything in this book that makes sense for all people all the time.

所以，现在是时候跳过前面的内容，提前预览一下接下来那些“从失败走向成功”的话题了。我这样做是因为我预料到了你的好奇心。你不会从我简短的清单中学到很多东西，但如果它能激起你的兴趣，或许就能给你一个读完这本书的理由。

So this is a good time to skip ahead and give you a preview of the failing-toward-success topics that will follow. I do this because I anticipate your curiosity. You won’t learn much from my abbreviated list, but if it gooses your interest, it might give you a reason to finish the book.

书评

Book Tease

  1. 目标是为失败者准备的。成功者依靠的是系统。
  2. Goals are for losers. Winners rely on systems.
  3. 你的大脑并不神奇，它只是一台你可以编程的计算机。
  4. Your mind isn’t magic. It’s a moist computer you can program.
  5. 要追踪的最重要的指标是你的个人能量。
  6. The most important metric to track is your personal energy.
  7. 你掌握的每项技能都会使你的成功几率加倍。
  8. Every skill you acquire doubles your odds of success.
  9. 幸福就是健康加上自由。
  10. Happiness is health plus freedom.
  11. 运气可以得到控制...某种程度上。
  12. Luck can be managed . . . sort of.
  13. 通过做一个大骗子（以一种好的方式）来克服害羞。
  14. Conquer shyness by being a huge phony (in a good way).
  15. 健身是推动世界的杠杆。
  16. Fitness is the lever that moves the world.
  17. 简单使平凡变得令人惊叹。
  18. Simplicity transforms ordinary into amazing.

如果我做得好，就不需要任何信誉来做到这一点。在引用研究的章节中，我会标明我的资料来源。我会像赛车手一样，利用那些值得信赖的人的信誉来写作。（干得好，值得信赖的人！）但大多数时候，我会描述我的个人经历，我保证这些都是真实的。我喜欢恶作剧，但承诺就是承诺。据我所知，你在这本书里读到的关于我生活的一切都是准确的。

If I do my job well, I won’t need any credibility to pull this off. In chapters in which I refer to studies, I’ll show my sources. I’ll be like a race car driver drafting off the credibility of people who earned it. (Good work, credible people!) But most of the time, I’ll be describing my personal experiences, and I promise those are real. I love a good practical joke, but a promise is a promise. Everything you read about my life in this book is accurate as far as I know.

二十几岁的时候，我身边没有人能告诉我如何成为漫画家，如何写书，或者如何获得成功。这对我来说是一个巨大的障碍。似乎其他人都能从朋友和家人的智慧中获益匪浅。正是这种不平等让我感到恼火，同时也激励着我。因此，我花了几十年的时间，试图弄清楚在成功这个话题上，什么方法有效，什么方法无效。如果你想在任何领域取得成功，那就让我成为你的起点吧。在本书中，我将描述一种成功的模板，可以作为你的起点。我并不总是能找到适合你具体情况的正确方案，但我可以帮助你缩小选择范围。

When I was in my twenties, I didn’t know anyone who could tell me how to become a cartoonist, how to write a book, or how to be successful in general. This was a big obstacle to my success. It seemed as if other people were benefitting greatly from the wisdom of their friends and families. That’s exactly the sort of inequality that pisses me off and motivates me at the same time. As a result, I’ve spent decades trying to figure out what works and what doesn’t on the topic of success. If you want to be successful in just about any field, let me be your starting point. I’ll describe over the course of this book a sort of template for success that can serve as your launching pad. I won’t always have the right formula for your specific situation, but I can help narrow your choices.

在你判断本书中我所说的是否有用之前，你需要一个系统来区分真假。大多数人都认为自己拥有完美的“废话探测器”。但如果真是这样，陪审团的意见就永远一致了，我们也会都拥有相同的宗教信仰。实际上，大多数人分辨真假的能力都很差，而且也没有客观的方法来判断你是否特别擅长。想想那些经常反对你的人。看看他们看起来多么自信，其实他们错得离谱？在他们眼里，你就是那样的。

Before you decide whether anything I say in this book is useful, you need a system for sorting truth from rubbish. Most people think they have perfectly good bullshit detectors. But if that were the case, trial juries would always be unanimous, and we’d all have the same religious beliefs. Realistically, most people have poor filters for sorting truth from fiction and there’s no objective way to know if you’re particularly good at it or not. Consider the people who routinely disagree with you. See how confident they look while being dead wrong? That’s exactly how you look to them.

当面对任何重大或复杂的问题时，谦逊是唯一明智的观点。然而，我们凡人需要像理解世界一样去探索它。另一种选择——随机行事——将是荒谬的。因此，为了最大限度地减少生活中的荒谬感，我建议使用一个特定的系统来区分真相与虚构。这个系统在阅读本书时会很有用，在你的生活中可能更为重要。这个系统认识到至少有六种常见的区分真相与虚构的方法，有趣的是，每一种都可能完全崩溃。

When it comes to any big or complicated question, humility is the only sensible point of view. Still, we mortals need to navigate our world as if we understand it. The alternative—acting randomly—would be absurd. So to minimize the feeling of absurdity in your life, I recommend using a specific system for sorting truth from fiction. The system will be useful for reading this book, and it could be even more important in your life. The system recognizes that there are at least six common ways to sort truth from fiction, and interestingly, each one is a complete train wreck.

真相的六个过滤器

The Six Filters for Truth

  1. 个人经历（人类的感知是不确定的。）
  2. Personal experience (Human perceptions are iffy.)
  3. 您认识的人的经验（更加不可靠。）
  4. Experience of people you know (Even more unreliable.)
  5. 专家（他们为金钱工作，而不是为真理工作。）
  6. Experts (They work for money, not truth.)
  7. 科学研究（相关性不等于因果关系。）
  8. Scientific studies (Correlation is not causation.)
  9. 常识（完全自信地犯错的好方法。）
  10. Common sense (A good way to be mistaken with complete confidence.)
  11. 模式识别（模式、巧合和个人偏见看起来很相似。）
  12. Pattern recognition (Patterns, coincidence, and personal bias look alike.)

在我们混乱不堪、瑕疵百出的生活中，我们最接近真理的就是一致性。一致性是科学方法的基石。科学家通过进行受控实验并试图观察一致的结果来逐渐接近真理。在你日常的非科学生活中，你也会做同样的事情，但这并不那么令人印象深刻，也不那么可靠。例如，如果你每次吃爆米花，一小时后你都会放一个很响的屁，以至于袜子都鼓起来了，那么你可以合理地假设爆米花会让你胀气。这不是科学，但它仍然是一个非常有用的模式。一致性是我们拥有的真理的最佳标志，尽管它可能不完美。

In our messy, flawed lives, the nearest we can get to truth is consistency. Consistency is the bedrock of the scientific method. Scientists creep up on the truth by performing controlled experiments and attempting to observe consistent results. In your everyday non-scientist life, you do the same thing, but it’s not as impressive, nor as reliable. For example, if every time you eat popcorn, one hour later you fart so hard that it inflates your socks, you can reasonably assume popcorn makes you gassy. It’s not science, but it’s still an entirely useful pattern. Consistency is the best marker of truth that we have, imperfect though it may be.

寻求真理时，最好的办法是至少在我列出的两个维度上寻求佐证。例如，如果一项研究表明，只吃巧克力蛋糕是减肥的绝佳方法，但你尝试这种饮食的朋友却越来越胖，那么你们就有两个维度不一致了。（如果算上常识，则是三个维度。）这就是缺乏一致性。

When seeking truth, your best bet is to look for confirmation on at least two of the dimensions I listed. For example, if a study indicates that eating nothing but chocolate cake is an excellent way to lose weight, but your friend who tries the diet just keeps getting fatter, you have two dimensions out of agreement. (Three if you count common sense.) That’s a lack of consistency.

一旦你开启了“废话过滤器”，想想如何着手解决任何新的复杂问题。如果条件允许，你总会先做一步：问问一位聪明的朋友，他或她是如何解决同样的问题的。聪明的朋友可以为你节省大量的时间和精力。你们中的许多人已经拥有一两个聪明的朋友，拥有他们真是幸运。但我观察到，在追求成功和幸福的道路上，有相当一部分成年人根本没有聪明的朋友来帮助他们。

Once you have your bullshit filter working, think about how you begin the process of tackling any new and complicated problem. There’s one step you will always do first if it’s available to you: You’ll ask a smart friend how he or she tackled the same problem. A smart friend can save you loads of time and effort. Many of you have a smart friend or two already, and you are lucky to have them. But my observation is that a startling percentage of the adult population literally has no smart friends to help them in their quest for success and happiness.

我特此以本书的形式，代表我成为你们的“聪明朋友”。如果你已经有一些“聪明朋友”，那太好了。朋友再多也不嫌多。我带来的是，我愿意与你讨论各​​种与成功相关的话题，而这些话题在你们的朋友们看来，或许是晚餐时尴尬的话题。

I hereby deputize myself to be your smart(ish) friend in the form of this book. If you already have some smart friends, that’s great. You can’t have too many. What I bring to the party is a willingness to discuss a wide range of success-related topics that your in-person friends might consider awkward dinner conversation.

我并非本文讨论的任何主题的专家，但我是一位专业的简化者。过去几十年来，我的主要工作是创作“呆伯特”漫画。创作漫画的过程就是从场景中剔除不必要的干扰，只留下荒诞却真实的核心。漫画家必须用短短四句话就能完成这一壮举。我已经表演了近九千次，有时甚至成功了。

I’m not an expert in any of the topics I’ll discuss here. But I am a professional simplifier. My main job for the past few decades has been creating the Dilbert comic strip. Making comics is a process by which you strip out the unnecessary noise from a situation until all that is left is the absurd-yet-true core. A cartoonist has to accomplish that feat with as few as four short sentences. I’ve performed that trick nearly nine thousand times, sometimes successfully.

资本主义是体现简约力量的最佳例证。资本主义的核心精髓在于，它的所有复杂性、公司之间的所有差异，以及所有挑战、决策、成功和失败，都可以归结为一个数字：利润。正是这种简化让资本主义得以运作。商业领域仍然存在着潜在的复杂性，但创造一个清晰简单的进步衡量标准，使资本主义成为可能。任何精明的投资者都不会在不了解公司过去和预期利润的情况下购买其股票。利润会告诉管理层，他们何时做得对，何时需要做出改变。正是这种简化——利润的概念——位于资本主义引擎的顶端，并在很大程度上引导着它，尽管有时会朝着错误的方向。人们可以争论将利润视为商业首要任务的道德性，但你无法否认它确实有效。你最多只能说有些公司做得过头了。但任何工具都有风险。锤子只有在钉子完全钉进去后停止敲打才有用。持续敲打只会破坏木头。

The best example of the power of simplicity is capitalism. The central genius of capitalism is that all its complexities, all the differences across companies, and all the challenges, decisions, successes, and failures can be boiled down into one number: profits. That simplification allows capitalism to work. The underlying complexity still exists in business, but creating a clear and simple measure of progress makes capitalism possible. No smart investor would buy stock in a company without knowing its past and projected profits. Profits tell management when they are doing something right and when they need to do something different. That one simplification—the idea of profit—sits atop the engine of capitalism and largely steers it, albeit sometimes in the wrong direction. One can debate the morality of viewing profits as the top priority in business, but you can’t argue that it works. At most, you can argue that some companies take it too far. But that is the risk of any tool. A hammer is only good if you stop pounding after the nail is all the way in. Keep pounding and you break the wood.

在本书的后面，我将描述一种简化方法，它可以指导你迈向个人成功的所有步骤。它相当于人类的利润。它是你唯一可以衡量的简单事物，它能让你清晰地理解生活中所有复杂的决策。但那是以后的事了。

Later in this book I will describe a simplification that can inform all the steps you take toward your own personal success. It’s the human equivalent of profit. It’s the one simple thing you can measure that will give clarity on all the complicated decisions in your life. But that’s later.

我希望能给你一个万无一失的成功秘诀，但生活并非如此。我能做的就是描述一个模型，让你可以将其与你目前的做事方式进行比较。对你来说，正确的答案可能是你正在做的事情和你在这里读到的内容的某种结合。你最了解什么对你有效，只要你通过模式识别、尝试和观察来获得这种智慧。

I wish I could give you a sure-fire formula for success, but life doesn’t work that way. What I can do is describe a model that you can compare to your current way of doing things. The right answer for you might be some combination of what you’re already doing and what you read here. You’re the best judge of what works for you, as long as you acquire that wisdom through pattern recognition, trial, and observation.

总而言之，请允许我声明：如果你觉得我的某个观点完全是胡扯，那么你很可能是对的。但我的目标并非百分之百正确。我只是在提供一些新的思路，来思考寻找幸福和成功的过程。你可以将它与你所知道的、你所做的事情以及其他人的建议进行比较。每个人都有自己独特的秘诀。

In summary, allow me to stipulate that if you think I’m full of crap on any particular idea or another, there’s a healthy chance you’re right. But being 100 percent right isn’t my goal. I’m presenting some new ways to think about the process of finding happiness and success. Compare it to what you know, what you do, and what others suggest. Every person finds their own special formula.

第一章

Chapter 1

我疯狂的时光

The Time I Was Crazy

我2005年春天，我的医生诊断我患有某种精神疾病。他没有用这些词或类似的措辞，但他推荐我去看凯撒医疗中心（我的医疗机构）的内部心理医生。我明白了。

In the spring of 2005, my doctor diagnosed me with a form of mental illness. He didn’t use those exact words or anything like them, but he did refer me to the in-house psychologist at Kaiser, my health care organization. I can take a hint.

心理医生听了我的故事后，得出了同样的结论：疯了。但和我的医生一样，她没有用“疯了”这个词。心理医生建议我服用安定，并提出了她有根据的猜测：降低我的压力水平或许能让我恢复某种正常的行为。

The psychologist listened to my story and came to the same conclusion: crazy. But like my doctor, she didn’t use the actual word. The psychologist suggested Valium and offered her educated guess that reducing my stress level might return me to some sort of normal behavior.

我拒绝服用安定，因为我感觉自己没疯。我甚至没感到那么大的压力，或者至少在医生和心理医生一致认为我可能疯了之前，我都没有这种感觉。我当然理解为什么两位专业人士都倾向于这个诊断。无论如何，我最近的行为都显得疯狂，甚至我自己都觉得如此。

I declined the Valium because I didn’t feel crazy. I didn’t even feel all that stressed, or at least I didn’t feel that way until a doctor and a psychologist agreed that I was probably losing my mind. I certainly understood why both professionals leaned toward that diagnosis. By any measure, my recent behavior appeared crazy, even to me.

我的症状是，我突然失去了与人说话的能力，尽管我可以独自一人或与我的猫说话时正常说话。我的常规医生和凯撒的内部专家系统地排除了导致我出现言语问题的每一个更可能的原因。过敏？不是。常见的呼吸系统问题？不是。胃酸反流？不是。喉咙里的肿瘤或息肉？不是。中风？不是。神经系统问题？不是。我看似身体健康，只是我突然失去了与其他人说话的能力。我可以正常地和我的猫说话。我独自一人时可以正常说话。我可以背诵一首诗。但在电话里，我几乎无法挤出一个可理解的句子。我得了某种奇怪的社交性喉炎。总之：疯了。

My symptom was that I had suddenly lost my ability to speak to human beings even though I could speak normally while alone or when talking to my cat. My regular doctor and Kaiser’s in-house specialists had systematically eliminated each of the more likely causes for my speech problem. Allergies? Nope. Common respiratory problem? Nope. Acid reflux? Nope. Tumors or polyps in my throat? Nope. Stroke? Nope. Neurological problem? Nope. I was in seemingly perfect health, except that I had suddenly lost the ability to speak to other humans. I could speak normally to my cat. I could speak normally when alone. I could recite a poem. But on the phone, I could barely squeeze out an intelligible sentence. I had some sort of weird social laryngitis. Bottom line: crazy.

当你面对作家和艺术家时，精神错乱总是一个合理的诊断。有时，疯子和艺术家之间唯一的真正区别在于，艺术家会写下他们想象中看到的东西。在过去的几十年里，几乎每周都会有陌生人在网上质疑我的精神健康。我理解这一点；我也读过我的作品。我大脑中理性的那一部分知道，如果有足够多的人暗示我可能疯了，我就需要考虑这种可能性。

Insanity is always a reasonable diagnosis when you’re dealing with writers and artists. Sometimes the only real difference between crazy people and artists is that artists write down what they imagine seeing. In the past few decades, hardly a week has gone by without a stranger on the Internet questioning my mental health. I understand that; I’ve read my writing, too. The rational part of my brain knows that if enough people suggest I might be crazy, I need to consider the possibility.

我的基因里也有一些疯狂。我外公曾经进过疯人院（或者说，不管当时叫什么）。如果我没记错的话，他接受过电击治疗。显然，这种治疗没起作用，因为我的母亲和祖母后来永远地离开了他，只带走了她们身上的衣服，而他则手里拿着钝器，在路上追赶她们，显然，他满脑子都是杀人的念头。我不能排除我继承了导致外公精神失常的基因。

I also have some craziness in my genes. My mother’s father spent some time in the loony bin, or whatever it was called at the time. If I recall, he was the recipient of electroshock treatments. Apparently that didn’t work because my mother and grandmother later left him forever, taking nothing but the clothes on their backs, as he chased them down the road with a blunt object in his hands and, apparently, homicide on his mind. I couldn’t rule out the possibility that I inherited whatever caused Grandpa to flip out.

作为一个疑似疯子的生活很艰难。当我试图和人说话时，我的声带会不由自主地在某些辅音上收缩，就像一个糟糕的手机通话，每三个音节就会漏掉一个音。在餐厅点一杯健怡可乐，结果服务员通常会用同情的眼神看着我，然后给我一杯普通的可乐。或者更糟的是，服务员会说：“我很好。谢谢惠顾。”然后我就什么饮料也得不到。

Living as a presumptive crazy person was hard work. When I tried speaking to humans, my vocal cords clenched involuntarily on certain consonants, giving the impression of a very bad cell phone call that drops every third syllable. Asking for a Diet Coke at a restaurant turned into “. . . iet . . . oke.” I usually ended up with a sympathetic look and a regular Coke. Or worse, the server would say, “I’m fine. Thanks for asking.” And I would get no beverage at all.

这是一个令人困惑、令人抓狂的问题。我可以流利地唱歌，尽管唱得很糟糕，但这对我来说完全正常。我也可以毫不费力地背诵记忆中的乐曲。但在对话中，我却无法说出一句正常、易懂的句子。

It was a confounding, maddening problem. I could sing fluently, albeit hideously, which was entirely normal for me. And I could recite memorized pieces without much of a hitch. But I couldn’t produce a normal, intelligible sentence in the context of a conversation.

就像口吃者一样，我学会了避开那些会让我犯错的问题音节。如果我想吃口香糖，我知道它会发出“……嗯”，所以我会尝试一些变通的方法，比如“我想要你嚼的东西”。这种方法通常都行不通。人们在日常交谈中通常不会想到谜语，无论我把线索说得多么清楚，得到的回应总是一脸困惑和“啊？”

Like a stutterer, I learned to avoid problem syllables that would trip me up. If I wanted gum, I knew it would come out as “. . . um,” so instead I would try a workaround such as “I want the stuff you chew.” That approach generally failed. People don’t expect riddles in their casual conversations, and no matter how clearly I laid out the clues, all I got in return was a puzzled expression and “Huh?”

失去说话能力显然是一场社交噩梦。那种感觉太不真实了，感觉就像一个幽灵待在拥挤的房间里。我说的是字面意思；那种感觉就像真的遇到鬼一样，或者至少是人们想象中的感觉。孤独令人衰弱。研究表明，孤独对身体的损害与衰老类似。1,2那种感觉确实如此。每天都感觉像是在输掉一场战斗。

Losing your ability to speak is obviously a social nightmare. It’s so surreal that you feel like a ghost in a crowded room. And I mean that literally; it feels like an actual ghost experience, or at least how one imagines that might be. The loneliness was debilitating. Research shows that loneliness damages the body in much the same way as aging.1,2 It sure felt that way. Every day felt like losing a fight.

我明白了，孤独感并不能通过倾听他人倾诉来解决。只有自己倾诉，并且——最重要的是——被倾听，才能治愈孤独。在接下来的三年半里，尽管有家人和朋友的爱与支持，我还是完全脱离了正常的生活，感到深深的孤独。我的生活质量每况愈下，甚至不值得我为此付出任何努力。

I learned that loneliness isn’t fixed by listening to other people talk. You can only cure your loneliness by doing the talking yourself, and—most importantly—being heard. For the next three-and-a-half years, I experienced a total disconnect from normal life and a profound sense of aloneness despite the love and support of family and friends. My quality of life was dipping below the point of being worth the effort.

在我嗓子出现问题的最初几个月里，我面临的问题比孤独更紧迫。除了担任《呆伯特》漫画的联合漫画家之外，我还是一名收入颇丰的专业演讲者。几周后，我安排了一场活动，这是我失去说话能力以来的第一次。我无法预测我的声音是否能像唱歌或背诵诗歌那样，顺利地完成我的录音演讲。我的声带会在舞台上突然闭合并一直保持这种状态吗？我会站在一千个人面前，喋喋不休、难以理解吗？

In the early months of my voice problems, I had a more immediate problem than loneliness. In addition to being a syndicated cartoonist for the Dilbert comic strip, I was a highly paid professional speaker. And I had an event scheduled in a few weeks, the first since I lost my ability to talk. I couldn’t predict whether my voice would work for my canned speech in the same way I could sing or repeat a poem. Would my vocal cords slam shut on stage and stay that way? Would I stand in front of a thousand people and yammer incomprehensibly?

我通过电子邮件告知了我的客户情况，并给了他的机构一个取消的机会。他们决定继续冒险。我也同意冒这个险。幸运的是，我不像普通人那样感到尴尬，我将在下一章中讨论这一点。在一千个陌生人面前出丑，其中很多人可能会用视频记录这场灾难，这种可能性并不像你想象的那么大。对我来说，这值得冒这个险，因为我需要知道在那种情况下我的声音会发生什么。我需要找出规律。如果我在一千人面前表演一段几乎背下来的台词，我的声音还能用吗？只有一种方法可以找到答案。

I informed my client of the situation by email and gave his organization a chance to cancel. They decided to forge ahead and take the risk. I agreed to take the chance, too. Luckily for me, I don’t feel embarrassment the way normal people do, which I’ll discuss in an upcoming chapter. The prospect of humiliation in front of a thousand strangers, many of whom would likely be video recording the disaster, wasn’t as much of a showstopper as you might think. It was worth the risk to me because I needed to know what would happen with my voice in that context. I needed to find out the pattern. Would my voice work if I presented a mostly memorized routine in front of a thousand people? There was only one way to find out.

第二章

Chapter 2

演讲日

The Day of the Talk

我我做过一百次类似的演讲。某种程度上来说，每一次演讲活动都一样：签合同。订机票。到场。和组织者闲聊。登台。逗大家笑。签名。摆姿势拍照。冲向等候的租车服务处。乘车去机场。飞回家。

I’d given a hundred similar talks. On some level, every speaking event was the same: Sign the contract. Book a flight. Show up. Make small talk with the organizers. Hit the stage. Make people laugh. Sign some autographs. Pose for pictures. Rush to a waiting car service. Ride to the airport. Fly home.

这次，闲聊没起作用。在后台，就在我被介绍到挤满人的舞厅前的几分钟，组织者试图和我攀谈。我尽力了，但他们几乎听不懂我的意思。我低声说着，打着手势，用着我的变通说法，试图向他们保证，台上的情况会更好。但说实话，我当时并不知道这是真的。我能看出他们眼中的恐慌。很有可能，我一上台，每说三个音节，我的喉咙就会哽咽一声。

This time, the small talk wasn’t working. Backstage, minutes before I was introduced to a packed ballroom, the organizers tried to engage me in conversation. I did my best, but they couldn’t decipher much of what I was trying to say. I whispered and gestured and used my workaround sentences, trying to assure them that things would be better onstage. But honestly, I didn’t know that to be true. And I could see the panic in their eyes. The odds were high that I would walk on stage and my throat would snap shut on every third syllable.

专家说，公开演讲是人最害怕的事情之一。但我通常并非如此。我训练有素，经验丰富，天生就是个演戏高手，我的听众大多都是友善的呆伯特爱好者。但我从未站在后台等待介绍，同时怀疑自己是否具备演讲能力。

Experts say public speaking is one of the most terrifying things a person can do. That wasn’t generally the case for me. I was well-trained, experienced, a natural ham, and my audiences were generally full of friendly Dilbert lovers. But I had never before stood backstage waiting for an introduction while wondering if I possessed the ability to speak.

这是新的。

This was new.

主持人开始介绍我时，我踏上金属台阶，来到侧台。音响师们摆弄着混音器，准备对我的麦克风进行热身。活动组织者们渐渐消失在后台的黑暗中。观众们焦急地等待着。我的介绍似乎永无止境。

As the host launched into my introduction, I climbed the metal steps to the side stage. The sound technicians fiddled with the mixer and prepared to go hot on my microphone. The event organizers faded into the backstage darkness. The audience was restless with anticipation. My introduction seemed to last forever.

我偷偷看了一眼观众，感受了一下现场气氛。这些人都是我的同事：技术人员和办公室职员。我深吸了几口气。主持人用了我准备的笑话作为开场白，观众们都笑了。他们已经做好了准备。

I peeked out to see the audience, to get a feel for the room. These were my people: technical folks and office workers. I took a few deep breaths. The moderator used a joke I supplied for my introduction and the audience laughed. They were primed and ready.

我费力地拨弄着衬衫，好让它恰到好处地塞进去。我检查了一下麦克风线，确保多余的部分整齐地藏在腰带下面。主持人为了营造效果，提高了音量，大声喊道：“欢迎《呆伯特》的创作者斯科特·亚当斯！ ”我的心跳得如此剧烈，甚至能感觉到自己的鞋子在跳动。我走进了耀眼的舞台灯光下。观众们都疯狂了。他们喜欢《呆伯特》，也很高兴见到我。我穿过舞台，和主持人握手。我们眼神交流，点了点头。一切都慢动作地进行着。我走向艾摩——一个可以在大屏幕上播放我的漫画的数字视频设备。我把材料放在桌子上，向旁边走了两步。我像演讲者一样，双手放在身前，指尖并拢，吸收着掌声，并将其转化为正能量。这股能量让我感觉很好。无论好坏，我都沉浸在观众的氛围中。

I fidgeted with my shirt to get it tucked in just right. I checked the microphone cord to make sure the excess was neatly hidden under my belt. The moderator raised his voice for effect and bellowed, “Please welcome the creator of Dilbert, Scott Adams!” My heart pounded so hard that I could feel it in my shoes. I walked into the blinding glare of the stage lights. The audience went wild. They loved Dilbert and by extension were happy to see me. I crossed the stage and shook hands with the host. We made eye contact and nodded. Everything moved in slow motion. I walked toward the Elmo—a digital video device that would display my comics on the big screens. I placed my materials on the table and took two steps to the side. I put my hands in front of me, fingertips together, as speakers do, while I absorbed the applause and converted it to positive energy. The energy felt good. I was jacked-in to the audience, for better or worse.

一瞬间，我的心跳如期恢复正常，就像我以前在数百人面前演讲时那样。我的训练开始发挥作用，我的自信也随之而来。在我心中，我拥有了观众，他们别无选择。从某种意义上说，他们是来臣服的。我只需要让他们知道我明白这一点。而要做到这一点，我必须能够演讲。

In an instant, and right on schedule, my heartbeat dropped to a normal state, just as it had a hundred times before in front of a hundred other crowds. My training was kicking in, and with it came my confidence. In my mind, I owned the audience, and they would have it no other way. They came to surrender, in a sense. All I had to do was show them I knew it. And to do that, I needed to be able to speak.

我深吸两口气，环顾四周。我对着观众微笑。我很高兴来到这里——真的很高兴。我天生就是为了这个。舞台总有家的感觉。

I took two deep breaths and looked around. I smiled at the audience. I was happy to be there—genuinely happy. I was born for this. The stage always feels like home.

我等着掌声停止。掌声停了之后，我又等了一会儿，因为我之前就学会了。站在观众面前，你的时间感会被扭曲。这就是为什么缺乏经验的演讲者会语速过快。我调整了自己的生物钟，以适应观众的时间感。我还希望他们静静地等待一两拍，以激发他们的好奇心。我从经验中知道，观众经常会好奇呆伯特的创造者会是什么样。那天，我也想知道同样的问题。

I waited for the applause to stop. And when it did, I waited a little longer, as I had learned. When you stand in front of an audience, your sensation of time is distorted. That’s why inexperienced presenters speak too rapidly. I mentally adjusted my internal clock to match the audience’s sense of timing. I also wanted them to wait in silence for a beat or two, to engage their curiosity. I knew from experience that audience members often wonder what the creator of Dilbert will sound like. That day, I wondered the same thing.

读到这里，你可能会有这样的疑问：什么样的傻瓜会让自己在千人面前遭受羞辱？

At this point in my story, you might have the following question: What kind of idiot puts himself in a position to be humiliated in front of a thousand people?

这个问题问得好。答案很长，可能需要写整本书才能回答清楚。简而言之，多年来，我与失败培养了一种独特的关系。我欢迎它，我挺过来，我欣赏它，然后我拼命地摆脱它。

It’s a fair question. The answer is a long one. It will take this entire book to answer it right. The short answer is that over the years I have cultivated a unique relationship with failure. I invite it. I survive it. I appreciate it. And then I mug the shit out of it.

失败总能带来一些宝贵的东西。我不会让它离开，直到我提取出那份价值。我长期以来都从失败中获益。例如，我的漫画生涯就是在企业环境中失败的直接后果。

Failure always brings something valuable with it. I don’t let it leave until I extract that value. I have a long history of profiting from failure. My cartooning career, for example, is a direct result of failing to succeed in the corporate environment.

那天，我一直在寻找自己说话的规律。我需要知道为什么在某些情况下我能正常说话，而在其他情况下却不行。为什么语境很重要？是肾上腺素水平的问题，还是我的语调，又或者我用来记忆的大脑区域？如果我能找到这个规律，我想或许就能找到解决我声音问题的办法。在观众面前，我的声音会比平时更好还是更差？我很快就要找到答案了。

I was looking for a pattern with my speech that day. I needed to know why I could speak normally in some situations and not in others. Why does context matter? Is it something about my adrenaline level, or the tone of my voice, or the region of my brain that I access for memorization? If I could find the pattern, I thought it might reveal a solution to my voice problem. Would my voice be better than normal or worse than normal in front of an audience? I was about to find out.

我张开嘴开始讲话。我的声音不太好，但听起来却有点沙哑。大多数人可能以为我感冒了。我讲了四十五分钟，展示了一些让我惹上麻烦的喜剧，也讲了一些有趣的趣闻轶事。观众们都兴奋起来。

I opened my mouth and began to speak. My voice wasn’t good, but it worked in a raspy sort of way. Most people probably thought I had a cold. I spoke for forty-five minutes, showing comics that got me in trouble, and told amusing anecdotes. The audience ate it up.

走下舞台，我立刻失去了说话的能力。当从背诵的讲稿转为正常的对话时，我的喉咙就堵住了。

When I walked off the stage, I immediately lost my ability to speak. When the context changed from my memorized speech to normal conversation, my throat locked up.

该死，问题肯定出在我的脑子里。

Damn, the problem was definitely in my brain.

在接下来的三年里，我一直在寻找能够解决我嗓音问题的规律，让我摆脱像幽灵一样的社交生活。在这本书中，我会告诉你我的探索过程，因为这个故事几乎包含了我所知道的一切，关于如何扼住失败的咽喉，直到它咳出一团成功的细丝。

For the next three years, I looked for patterns that would reveal a solution to my voice problems and free me from my ghostlike social existence. Over the course of this book, I’ll tell you how that search went because embedded in that story is pretty much everything I know about grabbing failure by the throat and squeezing it until it coughs up a hairball of success.

第三章

Chapter 3

激情是胡说八道

Passion is Bullshit

是你经常听到成功人士的建议：“追随你的激情”。乍一听，这听起来很有道理。激情大概会给你带来高昂的精力、更强的抗拒力和坚定的决心。充满激情的人也更有说服力。这些都是好事，对吧？

You often hear advice from successful people that you should “Follow your passion.” That sounds perfectly reasonable the first time you hear it. Passion will presumably give you high energy, high resistance to rejection, and high determination. Passionate people are more persuasive, too. Those are all good things, right?

反驳的观点是：我在旧金山一家大银行担任商业贷款员时，老板教导我们，永远不要贷款给那些追随自己热情的人。比如，你不会想把钱借给一个为了追求自己对运动的热情而开了一家体育用品店的体育爱好者。这种人，无论热情如何，都是个糟糕的选择。他做生意的目的完全错误。

Here’s the counterargument: When I was a commercial loan officer for a large bank in San Francisco, my boss taught us that you should never make a loan to someone who is following his passion. For example, you don’t want to give money to a sports enthusiast who is starting a sports store to pursue his passion for all things sporty. That guy is a bad bet, passion and all. He’s in business for the wrong reason.

我当时的老板，做了三十多年的商业贷款人，他说最好的贷款客户是那种毫无激情，只想努力工作，只为在电子表格上看起来不错的东西的人。也许贷款客户想开一家干洗店，或者投资一家快餐连锁店——那些无聊的东西。你押注的就是这种人。你想要的是那种只会磨刀霍霍的人，而不是热爱自己工作的人。

My boss at the time, who had been a commercial lender for over thirty years, said the best loan customer is one who has no passion whatsoever, just a desire to work hard at something that looks good on a spreadsheet. Maybe the loan customer wants to start a dry cleaning store or invest in a fast food franchise—boring stuff. That’s the person you bet on. You want the grinder, not the guy who loves his job.

那么，谁是对的呢？激情是成功的利器，还是只会让人失去理性？

So who’s right? Is passion a useful tool for success, or is it just something that makes you irrational?

我的假设是，充满激情的人更有可能在追求不太可能实现的目标时承担巨大风险，因此，在充满激情的人中，失败和巨大成功并存是意料之中的。失败的充满激情的人没有机会向我们其他人提供建议。但成功的充满激情的人每天都在写书、回答采访问题，分享他们的成功秘诀。这些成功人士自然希望你相信，成功是他们卓越才能的产物，但他们也希望保持谦逊。一个人不能谦虚地说“我成功是因为我比一般人聪明得多”。但你可以说你的激情是你成功的关键，因为每个人都可以对某事或其他事情充满热情。激情听起来更容易理解。如果你很笨，你对此无能为力，但我们认为，在适当的环境下，任何人都可以产生激情。激情让人感觉非常民主。它是人民的天赋，人人皆可拥有。

My hypothesis is that passionate people are more likely to take big risks in the pursuit of unlikely goals, so you would expect to see both more failures and more huge successes among the passionate. Passionate people who fail don’t get a chance to offer their advice to the rest of us. But successful passionate people are writing books and answering interview questions about their secrets for success every day. Naturally those successful people want you to believe that success is a product of their awesomeness, but they also want to retain some humility. One can’t be humble and say, “I succeeded because I am far smarter than the average person.” But you can say your passion was a key to your success because everyone can be passionate about something or other. Passion sounds more accessible. If you’re dumb, there’s not much you can do about it, but passion is something we think anyone can generate in the right circumstances. Passion feels very democratic. It is the people’s talent, available to all.

这也大多是胡说八道。

It’s also mostly bullshit.

人们很容易对那些正在顺利的事情充满热情，而这会扭曲我们对热情重要性的认知。我一生中参与过几十次商业冒险，每一次都让我在一开始就兴奋不已，甚至可以称之为热情。那些失败的项目——大多数都是这样——在失败的过程中慢慢地消耗了我的热情。而少数成功的项目，在成功之后，却变得更加令人兴奋。

It’s easy to be passionate about things that are working out, and that distorts our impression of the importance of passion. I’ve been involved in several dozen business ventures over the course of my life and each one made me excited at the start. You might even call it passion. The ones that didn’t work out—and that would be most of them—slowly drained my passion as they failed. The few that worked became more exciting as they succeeded.

例如，当我和一位经营合伙人投资一家餐厅时，我的热情高涨。第一天，看到顾客排起长队，我的热情更是高涨。后来，随着生意遭受重创，我的热情逐渐变成了沮丧和烦恼。热情最终消失了。

For example, when I invested in a restaurant with an operating partner, my passion was sky-high. And on day one, when there was a line of customers down the block, I was even more passionate. In later years, as the business got pummeled, my passion evolved into frustration and annoyance. The passion disappeared.

另一方面，《呆伯特》漫画最初只是我愿意尝试的众多致富计划之一。当它看起来可能成功时，我对漫画的热情更加高涨，因为我意识到它可能是我的金钥匙。事后看来，我最热衷的项目似乎也都是成功的。但客观地说，我的热情程度随着我的成功而变化。成功引发热情，而不是热情促成成功。

On the other hand, the Dilbert comic started out as just one of many get-rich schemes I was willing to try. When it started to look as if it might be a success, my passion for cartooning increased because I realized it could be my golden ticket. In hindsight, it looks as if the projects I was most passionate about were also the ones that worked. But objectively, my passion level moved with my success. Success caused passion more than passion caused success.

热情也可以是天赋的简单标志。我们人类往往喜欢做自己擅长的事情，而不喜欢做自己不擅长的事情。我们也相当擅长在尝试之前预测自己可能擅长什么。我从拿起球拍的第一天起就对网球充满热情，而且我打了一辈子网球。但我也立刻知道，网球是我可能擅长的，不像篮球或足球。所以，有时候，热情只是知道自己会擅长某件事的副产品。

Passion can also be a simple marker for talent. We humans tend to enjoy doing things we are good at while not enjoying things we suck at. We’re also fairly good at predicting what we might be good at before we try. I was passionate about tennis the first day I picked up a racket, and I’ve played all my life. But I also knew in an instant that it was the type of thing I could be good at, unlike basketball or football. So sometimes passion is simply a byproduct of knowing you will be good at something.

我讨厌销售，但我知道这是因为我不擅长销售。如果我是个出色的销售员，或者有潜力成为一名出色的销售员，我可能会对销售充满热情。而那些目睹我成功的人会认为我的热情才是我成功的原因，而不是仅仅体现了我的才能。

I hate selling, but I know it’s because I’m bad at it. If I were a sensational salesperson or had potential to be one, I’d probably feel passionate about sales. And people who observed my success would assume my passion was causing my success as opposed to being a mere indicator of talent.

如果你问一位亿万富翁成功的秘诀，他可能会说是热情，因为这听起来既性感又谦逊。但几杯酒下肚后，他可能会说，他的成功是渴望、运气、努力、决心、智慧和冒险精神的结合。

If you ask a billionaire the secret of his success, he might say it’s passion because that sounds like a sexy answer that is suitably humble. But after a few drinks, he’d probably say his success was a combination of desire, luck, hard work, determination, brains, and appetite for risk.

所以，当你规划成功之路时，别再想激情了。在接下来的章节中，我会介绍一些提升个人能量的方法，这些方法对我而言很有效。你已经知道，当你的能量充足时，你在做任何事情时都会表现得更好，包括学习、工作、运动，甚至你的个人生活。能量是好的。激情是胡扯。

So forget about passion when you’re planning your path to success. In the coming chapters, I’ll describe some methods for boosting personal energy that have worked for me. You already know that when your energy is right you perform better at everything you do, including school, work, sports, and even your personal life. Energy is good. Passion is bullshit.

第四章

Chapter 4

我的一些失败总结

Some of My Many Failures in Summary Form

我我很高兴地承认，我比我认识的任何人都经历过更多挑战，失败的次数也更多。读了这本书，你很有可能也会走上一条通往辉煌失败和巨大失望的道路。别客气！如果我之前忘了说，那正是你想要的——深陷失败。这很美好，因为失败往往是成功藏身之处。你想要的人生目标都蕴藏在那个巨大而沸腾的失败之桶里。诀窍在于，把好东西都挖掘出来。

I’m delighted to admit that I’ve failed at more challenges than anyone I know. There’s a non-zero chance that reading this book will set you on the path of your own magnificent screw-ups and cavernous disappointments. You’re welcome! And if I forgot to mention it earlier, that’s exactly where you want to be—steeped to your eyebrows in failure. It’s a good place to be because failure is where success likes to hide in plain sight. Everything you want out of life is in that huge, bubbling vat of failure. The trick is to get the good stuff out.

如果成功很容易，那每个人都能做到。成功需要付出努力。这对你有利，因为它能把懒人挡在门外。如果你也很懒，也不用担心。这本书的大部分内容都包含一些无需付出太多努力就能提升能量的技巧。事实上，仅仅是阅读这本书的过程，就可能让你略感乐观。我设计这本书的目的就是为了达到这个目的。所以，你已经朝着正确的方向前进了。

If success were easy, everyone would have it. It takes effort. That fact works to your advantage because it keeps lazy people out of the game. And don’t worry if you’re lazy, too. Much of this book involves tricks for ramping up your energy without much effort. In fact, the process of simply reading this book might give you a little boost of optimism. I designed it to do just that. So you’re already moving in the right direction.

我天生乐观，或许是受其教育——很难说清两者之间究竟孰轻孰重——但无论原因何在，我始终视失败为一种工具，而非结果。我相信，用这种方式看待世界，对你来说也同样有益。

I’m an optimist by nature or perhaps by upbringing—it’s hard to know where one leaves off and the other begins—but whatever the cause, I’ve long seen failure as a tool, not an outcome. I believe that viewing the world in that way can be useful for you, too.

尼采有句名言：“凡是打不死我们的，都会让我们更强大。”这话听起来很有道理，但却是失败者的哲学。我不希望失败仅仅让我变得更强大*，我把这理解为让我更能应对未来的挑战。变得更强大显然是件好事，但这远非乐观。当然，我希望失败能让我变得更强大，但我也希望变得更聪明、更有才华、人脉更广、更健康、更有活力。如果我在门前台阶上发现一坨牛粪，我不会满足于知道我会做好心理准备迎接未来的牛粪。我想把那坨牛粪铲到我的花园里，希望牛每周都回来，这样我就不用再买肥料了†。失败是一种可以管理的资源。

Nietzsche famously said, “What doesn’t kill us makes us stronger.” It sounds clever, but it’s a loser philosophy. I don’t want my failures to simply make me stronger,* which I interpret as making me better able to survive future challenges. Becoming stronger is obviously a good thing, but it’s only barely optimistic. I do want my failures to make me stronger, of course, but I also want to become smarter, more talented, better networked, healthier, and more energized. If I find a cow turd on my front steps, I’m not satisfied knowing that I’ll be mentally prepared to find some future cow turd. I want to shovel that turd onto my garden and hope the cow returns every week so I never have to buy fertilizer again†. Failure is a resource that can be managed.

在推出《呆伯特》漫画之前和之后，我经历了一系列日常工作和创业冒险，最终都失败了。以下是我列出的最糟糕的经历。我可能忘了大概十几个。我之所以列出这部分，是因为成功人士通常会粉饰他们最光鲜亮丽的失败，给人留下他们拥有某种你没有的魔力的印象。读完这份清单后，你就不会再对我抱有这种错觉了，这就是重点。即使你95%的时间都犯了大错，成功也是完全可以实现的。

Prior to launching the Dilbert comic and after, I failed at a long series of day jobs and entrepreneurial adventures. Here’s a quick listing of the worst ones. I’m probably forgetting a dozen or so. I include this section because successful people generally gloss over their most aromatic failures, which leaves the impression they have some magic you don’t. When you’re done reading this list, you won’t have that delusion about me, and that’s the point. Success is entirely accessible even if you happen to be a huge screw-up 95 percent of the time.

我最喜欢的失败：

My Favorite Failures:

Velcro™ 松香袋发明：七十年代，网球运动员有时会使用松香袋来防止握球拍的手出汗。大学时，我制作了一个松香袋的原型，它可以固定在网球短裤的 Velcro 带上，以便随时取用。我的律师告诉我，这个松香袋不值得申请专利，因为它只是两种现有产品的组合。我联系了一些体育用品公司，但只收到了拒绝信。我放弃了这个想法。但在这个过程中，我学到了一个宝贵的教训：好的想法没有价值，因为世界上已经有太多了。市场奖励的是执行，而不是想法。从那时起，我开始专注于那些我可以执行的想法。我在通往成功的道路上已经失败了，但我还不知道。

Velcro™ Rosin Bag Invention: In the seventies, tennis players sometimes used rosin bags to keep their racket hands less sweaty. In college I built a prototype of a rosin bag that attached to a Velcro strip on tennis shorts so it would always be available when needed. My lawyer told me it wasn’t patent-worthy because it was simply a combination of two existing products. I approached some sporting goods companies and got nothing but form letter rejections. I dropped the idea. But in the process, I learned a valuable lesson: Good ideas have no value because the world already has too many of them. The market rewards execution, not ideas. From that point on, I concentrated on ideas I could execute. I was already failing toward success, but I didn’t yet know it.

我的第一次面试：那是我在哈特威克学院读高三的时候，我开始面试一些现实生活中的工作。有一天，哈特威克学院在校园里举办了一次招聘会。唯一让我感兴趣的公司是施乐公司。他们当时正在寻找两名现场销售人员。当时，施乐公司看起来是一家长期发展前景不错的公司。我只需要先从入门级的销售工作开始，然后逐步晋升。我的几个同学也参加了这两个职位的面试。我了解他们的学术背景，而且我知道我的成绩是他们中最好的。我以为我的学术优秀将成为我获得销售职位的优势。我当时真是太无知了。

My First Job Interview: It was my senior year at Hartwick College, and I started interviewing for real-world jobs. One day, Hartwick hosted a career day on campus. The only company that interested me was Xerox. They were looking for two field salespeople. At the time, Xerox seemed like a good company for the long run. I just needed to get my foot in the door with an entry-level sales job and work my way up. Several of my classmates were interviewing for the same two openings. I was familiar with their academic standings, and I knew I had the best grades of the bunch. I figured my academic excellence would be the advantage I needed for a sales position. That is how ignorant I was.

据我当时所知，我和招聘人员的面试进行得很顺利。我解释说我没有销售经验，但我喜欢争论。我反问道，销售不就是和客户争论到赢吗？是的，我确实采取了这种策略。

As far as I knew at the time, my interview with the recruiter went well. I explained that I had no sales experience, but I loved to argue. And what is selling, I asked rhetorically, if not a form of arguing with customers until you win? Yes, I really took that approach.

那次失败教会我寻找那些我拥有天赋优势的机会。后来我决定尝试画漫画，是因为我知道世界上能画出有趣的图画，又能写出风趣幽默文字的人并不多。我的失败教会我寻找那些我拥有优势的机会。

That failure taught me to look for opportunities in which I had some natural advantage. When I later decided to try cartooning, it was because I knew there weren’t many people in the world who could draw funny pictures and also write in a witty fashion. My failure taught me to seek opportunities in which I had an advantage.

冥想指南：大学毕业后不久，我和一个朋友写了一本冥想入门指南。我冥想多年，从中受益匪浅。我们在一些小众刊物上宣传我们的冥想指南，卖出了大约三本。我学到了很多关于本地广告、市场营销和产品开发的知识。这些知识后来都派上了用场。

Meditation Guide: Soon after college, a friend and I wrote a beginner’s guide to meditation. I had meditated for years and found a lot of benefits in it. We advertised our meditation guide in minor publications and sold about three copies. I learned a good deal about local advertising, marketing, and product development. All of that came in handy later.

电脑游戏1 ：八十年代初，我花了大约一半的净资产买了一台便携式电脑。那时还没有笔记本电脑，“便携式”指的是一个上肢力量强的成年人就能举起它。两年来，我几乎每个晚上和周末都花在自学编程上，试图创作一款太空主题的街机游戏。我成功设计并制作了这款游戏，而且运行良好。但由于创作时间太长，当时的电脑游戏设计水平已经突飞猛进，让我那款简单的太空游戏显得有些过时。我在电脑类出版物的封底刊登了这款游戏的广告，结果卖出了不到二十份。（注：有一位非常成功且知名的电脑游戏设计师名叫斯科特·亚当斯。我不是他。）

Computer Game 1: In the early eighties, I spent about half of my net worth buying a portable computer. This was before the age of laptops, when “portable” meant that an adult with good upper-body strength could lift it. I spent almost every night and every weekend for two years trying to teach myself enough about programming to create a space-themed, arcade-type game. I managed to design and build the game, and it worked quite well. But it took me so long to create it that the state of the art for computer game design had surged ahead, making my simple space game look archaic. I advertised the game in the back of computer publications and sold fewer than twenty copies. (Note: There is a successful and well-known computer game designer named Scott Adams. I’m not him.)

电脑游戏2 ：我决定再玩一款太空主题的游戏，这次的视角是宇宙飞船的驾驶舱，玩家需要穿越星空，搜寻卫星并将其发射升空。这款游戏的难度比第一款高得多，我花了一年的时间才完成。游戏运行良好，但我是唯一一个玩过它的人。当时的技术太过原始，无法构建出我想象中的游戏。又或许是我的技术不够好。或许两者兼而有之。

Computer Game 2: I decided to take another run at a space-themed game, this time with a point-of-view from the cockpit of a spaceship as you navigated through the stars and hunted satellites to blast from the sky. This was a much higher level of difficulty than the first, and it took all my free time for a year. The game worked, but I’m the only person to ever play it. The technology of the time was too primitive to build the game I imagined. Or maybe my skills were inadequate. It was probably a combination.

心灵感应练习程序：我编写了一个计算机程序来追踪和绘制用户的“心灵感应”能力。这是一个简单的程序，只需从四张牌中选择一张显示在屏幕上的正确牌即可。我的目的是看看你是否能保持在25%以上。我不相信心灵感应的力量，我的随机数生成器也没有我想要的那么随机，但这没关系。我只是想玩玩而已。乐趣在于，有时纯粹靠运气，你的心灵感应能力就能在短时间内保持在25%以上。在高于平均水平的运行过程中，你会感觉自己有心灵感应，或者至少很幸运。由于我们大脑的运作方式，即使我们知道这只不过是偶然的，好运连连也会让我们感觉良好。

Psychic Practice Program: I wrote a computer program to track and graph the “psychic” ability of users. It was a simple program that involved picking the right onscreen card from a choice of four. The idea was to see if you could stay above 25 percent. I don’t believe in psychic powers, and my random number generator was less random than I would have liked, but that didn’t matter. It was just for fun. The fun was derived from the fact that sometimes, by pure chance, you could stay above 25 percent for a brief run. During the above-average runs, you would have the sensation of being psychic, or at least lucky. The way our brains are wired, the lucky streaks feel good even if we know they are nothing but chance.

几个月来，我把所有业余时间都投入到开发这个程序上。它运行良好，但我觉得它不够特别，不值得费力去推广。它实在没什么吸引力。

For months I dedicated all my spare time to creating the program. It worked well, but I decided it wasn’t special enough to be worth the trouble of marketing it. It just wasn’t exciting.

我所有的电脑游戏创意都失败了，但在这个过程中，我学到了足够多的个人电脑知识，在计算机发展的早期——也就是八十年代——我看起来像个技术天才。这些知识运用到我在银行的日常工作中，后来也运用到我的漫画创作生涯中。

All my computer game ideas failed, but in the process I learned enough about personal computers to look like a technical genius in those early days of computing—the eighties. That knowledge transferred to my day job at the bank and later to my cartooning career as well.

地鼠职位：在我二十多岁从事银行业期间，我引起了银行一位高级副总裁的注意。显然，我在会议上的胡扯能力令人印象深刻。他给我提供了一份地鼠/助理的工作，并含糊地保证说，我会在日常工作中与重要的高管会面，这样他就能轻而易举地把我绑在屁股上——俗话说——让我在公司里步步高升。但缺点是，挑战在于如何适应他那不太礼貌的管理风格，并听命于他几年。我拒绝了他的邀请，因为我当时已经在管理一个小团队，所以成为一名地鼠对我来说简直是倒退。我记得这位高级副总裁对我这个决定的确切评价是“愚蠢至极！！！”他最终雇佣了我的一位同事来做这份工作，几年后，那家伙成为了银行历史上最年轻的副总裁之一。

Gopher Offer: During my banking career in my late twenties, I caught the attention of a Senior Vice President at the bank. Apparently my bullshit skills in meetings were impressive. He offered me a job as his gopher/assistant with the vague assurance that I would meet important executives during the normal course of my work, and that would make it easy for him to strap a rocket to my ass—as the saying went—and launch me up the corporate ladder. On the downside, the challenge would be to survive his less-than-polite management style and do his bidding for a few years. I declined his offer because I was already managing a small group of people, so becoming a gopher seemed like a step backwards. I believe the Senior Vice President’s exact characterization of my decision was “F#@*&G STUPID!!!” He hired one of my coworkers for the job instead, and in a few years that fellow became one of the youngest Vice Presidents in the bank’s history.

我在旧金山的克罗克国民银行工作了大约八年，从最基层做起，一路晋升到基层管理层。由于我遇到了多元化的瓶颈，那段职业生涯最终以失败告终。但在我的银行生涯中，秉承着尽可能多学习商业之道的策略，我对银行、金融、技术、合同、管理以及其他十几项实用技能有了非常透彻的了解。这让我得以跳槽到一份薪水更高的工作……

I worked for Crocker National Bank in San Francisco for about eight years, starting at the very bottom and working my way up to lower management. That career ultimately failed when I hit the diversity ceiling, but during the course of my banking career, and in line with my strategy of learning as much as I could about the ways of business, I gained an extraordinarily good overview of banking, finance, technology, contracts, management, and a dozen other useful skills. That allowed me to jump ship to a much higher paying job at . . .

电话公司生涯：我在太平洋贝尔公司又工作了八年，主要从事财务工作——预算和撰写项目商业案例。但我也曾在一家技术实验室做过“假工程师”（字面意义上的工程师），涉足战略、市场营销、研究、界面设计和其他几个领域。那段职业生涯就像我的银行业生涯一样，遭遇了多元化的瓶颈，但在这个过程中，我从各个角度学到了大量的商业知识。我所有的企业经验构成了《呆伯特》 创作的知识基础。

Phone Company Career: I worked at Pacific Bell for another eight years, mostly doing financial jobs—budgeting and writing business cases for projects. But I also worked as a fake (literally) engineer in a technology lab, and I had a finger in strategy, marketing, research, interface design, and several other fields. That career hit the diversity ceiling just as my banking career did, but in the process I learned a huge amount about business from every angle. And my total corporate experience formed the knowledge base upon which Dilbert was built.

Zippy Ship ：我花了大约一年时间利用空闲时间编写了一个程序，让调制解调器之间的文件传输更加便捷。那时电子邮件还无法轻松发送大文件。我把我的小公寓改造成了一个技术实验室。那时，我一边在电话公司上班，一边制作《呆伯特》系列。

Zippy Ship: I spent about a year writing a program in my free time to make modem-to-modem file transfers easier. This was before email could easily send large files. I turned my little condo into a technology lab. By then I was working my day job at the phone company while also producing Dilbert.

我敢肯定 Zippy Ship 这个名字已经被人用了，但那是我之前给它起的暂定名。它最酷的功能是菜单。启动程序后，屏幕上会出现一个拉链，然后迅速解开，并伴有合适的音效。矩形菜单会从拉链的侧面弹出，看起来就像阴茎的形状，我觉得这肯定会引起人们的热议。

I’m sure the Zippy Ship name is taken, but that was my working name for it. Its coolest feature was the menu. When you fired up the program, a zipper appeared on screen and quickly unzipped with an appropriate sound effect. The rectangular menu popped out of the zipper sideways in a suggestively phallic manner that I thought would get people talking about it.

我投入了大量精力，试图让这项技术兼容所有类型的调制解调器，但最终却徒劳无功。调制解调器的标准化程度还不够高，我当时的资源和专业知识匮乏，根本无法实现这一目标。我所能做的最好的尝试，也只是让它在两种特定的调制解调器上工作。但这毫无意义。我停止了产品的研发，虽然我没有获得任何后来对我有帮助的新技术知识，但我更清楚地认识到，要想让某样东西正常工作，需要费尽心思，钻研各种技术，是多么困难。

I put an enormous amount of work into getting the technology to work across all modem types, but it was a lost cause. Modems weren’t standardized enough to pull it off with my meager resources and know-how. The best I could accomplish was making it work on two specific modems. That was useless. I stopped working on the product, and while I didn’t gain any new technical knowledge that helped me later, I did gain a clearer understanding of how hard it would be to gnaw through a wall to make something work.

奇思妙想网站：我喜欢奇思妙想，因为它们本身就很有趣，而且常常能激发出有价值的想法。我也喜欢提出自己的奇思妙想，有时一天能想出好几个。我想其他人可能也会喜欢。我通过我的联合公司创建了一个网站，供用户提交奇思妙想。我希望，如果有人偶然想出一个以其他方式无法实现的好主意，也许它就能改变世界。这个网站是原版呆伯特网站的子公司，后者流量很大，所以很容易获得曝光。问题是，人们提交的想法太糟糕了，甚至达不到奇思妙想的水平。没过多久，这个网站就被大量善意的垃圾信息淹没，变得毫无价值。我们把它关闭了。

Crackpot Idea Website: I like crackpot ideas because I find them inherently interesting, and often they inspire ideas that have merit. I also like coming up with my own crackpot ideas, sometimes several per day. I figured other people might like the same thing. I created a website through my syndication company for user-submitted crackpot ideas. I hoped that perhaps it could change the world if someone were to accidentally come up with a great idea that wouldn’t have found oxygen in any other way. The site was a subsidiary of the original Dilbert website, which had plenty of traffic, so it wasn’t hard to get exposure. The problem is that the ideas people submitted were so awful they didn’t even rise to the level of crackpot. It didn’t take long for the site to be populated with so much well-intentioned garbage that it became worthless. We shut it down.

在失败的过程中，我学到了很多关于网站设计和新功能实现的知识。这些知识在我完成的几个项目中发挥了重要作用。

In the process of failing, I learned a lot about website design and new feature implementation. That knowledge has served me well on several projects.

互联网视频：在互联网泡沫时期，一家初创公司联系了我，他们计划让任何拥有电脑的人都能在互联网上发布视频，供所有人共享观看乐趣。他们请我利用我的“呆伯特”聚光灯来宣传这项服务。这家初创公司资金有限，所以他们给了我一大笔股票。我接受了。我在我的“呆伯特”简报中介绍了这项新服务，发布了我自己的搞笑视频，并就此接受了几次采访。

Video on Internet: During the dotcom frenzy, I was approached by a startup that planned to allow anyone with a computer to post videos on the Internet for the collective viewing pleasure of all. They asked me to help use my Dilbert spotlight to get the word out. The startup didn’t have much funding, so they offered me a generous chunk of stock instead. I accepted. I talked about the new service in my Dilbert newsletter, posted my own funny videos, and gave some interviews on the topic.

几年后，谷歌以16.5亿美元收购了YouTube，股东们赚得盆满钵满。可惜的是，我故事里的视频服务并非YouTube，而是更早出现的服务。我之前合作的那家公司起步较早，因为当时的网速还不足以支撑在线视频分享的普及。这家公司挣扎了几年，最终倒闭了。YouTube抓住了最佳时机。大约在那个时候，我开始明白，时机往往是成功最重要的因素。除非你有通灵能力，否则很难把握好时机，所以尝试不同的方法，直到你幸运地抓住最佳时机，这才是明智之举。

Several years later, Google bought YouTube for $1.65 billion and the shareholders made a fortune. Unfortunately, the video service in my story was not YouTube. It was a service that came before. The company I worked with was premature because Internet speeds were not quite fast enough for online video sharing to catch on. The company struggled for a few years and then shut down. YouTube got the timing right. That was about the time I started to understand that timing is often the biggest component of success. And since timing is often hard to get right unless you are psychic, it makes sense to try different things until you get the timing right by luck.

杂货送货上门：我和一位工程师朋友决定合作研发一项技术，让杂货送货上门更加便捷。我们的想法是，开发一种技术，让送货车能够打开你的车库门，这样即使你不在家，司机也能把货物放进车库，比如放在冷藏箱里。我们的计划是把这项技术卖给那些想要送货上门的杂货店。

Grocery Home Delivery: An engineer friend and I decided to work together to create technology that would make home delivery of groceries more practical. The idea was to create technology that would allow a delivery van to open your garage door so the driver could place the delivery inside even when you were not home, perhaps in a cooler. Our plan was to sell the technology to grocery stores that wanted to start delivering.

我知道，我知道。安全问题确实很多。我就不多说了，但我们认为可以设计一些保障措施，把风险降到几乎为零。我们本来可以就这是否可行展开长时间的辩论，但这无关紧要，因为我的朋友忙于其他项目，退出了。这并没有取得足够的进展，无法带来任何知识或才能上的收益，而且我也没有投入太多精力。

I know, I know. Lots of security concerns. I’ll spare the details, but we thought we could design some safeguards to bring the risks to nearly zero. We could have a long debate on whether that was possible, but it didn’t matter because my friend got busy on other projects and bowed out. That didn’t get far enough to generate any benefits in knowledge or talent, but I hadn’t put much effort into it either.

Webvan ：几年后，在互联网时代，一家名为 Webvan 的初创公司承诺要彻底改变食品杂货配送。你可以通过互联网订购食品杂货，他们的一辆卡车会将你的订单装载到他们现代化的配送中心，然后出发为你所在地区的所有顾客提供服务。我认为 Webvan 之于食品杂货就像亚马逊之于图书一样。这是一个难得的入门机会。我买入了大量 Webvan 的股票，感觉很好。当股价暴跌时，我又买入了一些。我重复了几次这个过程，每次都舔着嘴唇，因为我以我知道的便宜价格买入了更多股票。

Webvan: Some years later, in the dotcom era, a startup called Webvan promised to revolutionize grocery delivery. You could order grocery store items over the Internet, and one of their trucks would load your order at their modern distribution hub and set out to service all the customers in your area. I figured Webvan would do for groceries what Amazon did for books. It was a rare opportunity to get in on the ground floor. I bought a bunch of Webvan stock and felt good about myself. When the stock plunged, I bought some more. I repeated that process several times, each time licking my lips as I acquired ever larger blocks of the stock at prices I knew to be a steal.

当管理层宣布他们的几个枢纽之一实现了正现金流时，我知道我成功了。如果这个模式在一个枢纽奏效，那么它就被证明是有效的，而且肯定也会在其他枢纽奏效。我又买入了更多股票。现在我几乎拥有了一大堆股票。

When management announced they had achieved positive cash flow at one of their several hubs, I knew I was on to something. If it worked in one hub, the model was proven, and it would surely work at others. I bought more stock. Now I owned approximately, well, a boatload.

几周后，Webvan 倒闭了。投资 Webvan 并非我做过最愚蠢的事，但它确实是一个有竞争力的公司。损失不足以改变我的生活方式。但心理上却很痛苦。我得为自己辩解一下，我知道这是一场赌博，而不是一项投资。

A few weeks later, Webvan went out of business. Investing in Webvan wasn’t the dumbest thing I’ve ever done, but it’s a contender. The loss wasn’t enough to change my lifestyle. But boy did it sting psychologically. In my partial defense, I knew it was a gamble, not an investment per se.

我从那次经历中学到的是，公司管理层根本不会提供什么有用的信息。现在我分散投资，让谎言被我投资中的其他变量所掩盖。

What I learned from that experience is that there is no such thing as useful information that comes from a company’s management. Now I diversify and let the lying get smoothed out by all the other variables in my investments.

专业投资者：在Webvan惨败之后，我觉得我可能需要一些专业的投资帮助。《呆伯特》的版税源源不断地涌来，我却没有时间自己做研究。我也不相信自己的理财能力，这是有原因的。

Professional Investors: After my Webvan disaster, I figured I might need some professional investing help. Dilbert royalties were pouring in, and I didn’t have the time to do my own research. Nor did I trust my financial skills, and for good reason.

我的银行富国银行向我推荐了他们的投资服务，我决定把一半可投资资金委托给他们。“信任”这个词可能不太恰当，因为我只给了他们一半；我一半信任他们。我用另一半资金进行自己的投资。富国银行的专家们很有帮助地把我的钱投资于安然、世通和其他一些如今已成为亏损代名词的公司。显然，我的投资专家掌握的信息不如我多。我从他们的管理机构撤回了资金，从那以后就自己做投资，主要投资于大盘非管理型基金。（结果更好。）

My bank, Wells Fargo, pitched me on their investment services, and I decided to trust them with half of my investible funds. Trust is probably the wrong term because I only let them have half; I half-trusted them. I did my own investing with the other half of my money. The experts at Wells Fargo helpfully invested my money in Enron, WorldCom, and some other names that have become synonymous with losing money. Clearly my investment professionals did not have access to better information than I had. I withdrew my money from their management and have done my own thing since then, mostly in broad-market unmanaged funds. (That worked out better.)

Folderoo ：在《呆伯特》的早期，软盘还在广泛使用，同事之间通常会把文档和软盘一起递给他们，以防他们需要修改。问题是，当时没有一种优雅的方式可以将软盘粘贴到纸张上。我的妙招是发明一种马尼拉纸文件夹，正面有一个袋鼠式的口袋，用来装软盘。它的生产成本不会比普通文件夹高多少，但实用性却加倍。我觉得这款产品可以与《呆伯特》主题搭配，因为《呆伯特》的衬衫口袋很像我放在文件夹上的那个。我制作了一个原型（花了五分钟），并把它推销给了我的联合传媒集团。我希望他们能找到一个授权商来生产和销售这款产品，同时我们为《呆伯特》协会收取版税。但这个想法最终没有成功，因为联合传媒从事的是授权业务，而不是产品设计业务，而这个想法超出了他们的预期。我猜想 Folderoo 这个名字现在归别人所有了。后来，一些文件夹公司开始生产和销售带有磁盘口袋的文件夹。我不知道他们的业绩如何。

Folderoo: In the early days of Dilbert, when floppy disks were still in widespread use, it was common to hand a coworker a document along with a floppy disk in case the coworker needed to make changes. The problem was that there was no elegant way to attach a floppy disk to a piece of paper. My brilliant idea was to invent a manila folder with a kangaroo-type pocket on the front to hold the disk. It wouldn’t cost much more than a regular folder to produce, and it would be twice as useful. I figured the product could have a Dilbert tie-in because Dilbert has a shirt pocket much like I was putting on the folder. I made a prototype (which took five minutes) and pitched it to my syndicate, United Media. I hoped they could find a licensee who would produce and market the product while we collected royalties for the Dilbert association. This idea went nowhere because United Media was in the licensing business, not the product design business, and this idea was out of their strike zone. I assume the name Folderoo is owned by someone else at this point. Eventually some folder companies made and sold folders with pockets for disks. I don’t know how well they did.

日历专利：我曾有一个想法，想以一种巧妙的方式将广告嵌入电子日历中，让人们觉得它很有用。这个想法是让一个程序读取你的日历条目，并将你的计划与符合日历预测活动的供应商优惠进行匹配。例如，如果你计划下个月去买一辆小型货车，只需在日历中添加这条记录。然后，供应商会将本地优惠和促销信息添加到这条记录中。你只有点击才能看到这些优惠。广告将通过第三方（我们今天称之为“云端”）进行管理，因此供应商永远不会直接看到任何用户的日历信息。这项专利被驳回了，因为据称一项完全不相关的专利——也就是说它与日历完全无关——包含了我所描述的流程。我对现有专利的理解是，它与我的想法无关，但我咨询了我的专利律师，最终放弃了它。有趣的是，现有专利的所有者可能并不知道自己正坐拥一座金矿。

Calendar Patent: I had an idea for embedding ads in electronic calendars in a clever way that people would find useful. The idea was for a program to read your calendar entries and match your plans with vendor offers that made sense for the activities predicted by the calendar. For example, if you planned to go car shopping for a minivan next month, just put that entry on your calendar. Then vendors would populate the entry with local deals and offers. You would only see the offers if you clicked on them. The ads would be managed through a third party (in the “cloud,” as we might say today), so vendors would never directly see any user’s calendar information. The patent was rejected because a totally unrelated patent—meaning it had nothing to do with calendars at all—allegedly included the process I described. My reading of the existing patent was that it had nothing to do with my idea, but I consulted with my patent attorney and let it drop. Interestingly, the owner of the existing patent probably doesn’t know he’s sitting on a gold mine.

键盘专利：我申请了一项关于十键键盘文本输入创意的专利。当时正值智能手机时代之前，人们用普通的十键手机发短信，需要反复敲击某个按键才能输入想要的字符。我的想法是在脑海中投射出键盘上的字母，并根据字母的形状特征为每个字母创建一个双键快捷键。这项专利最终获得了批准，但随着手机技术的不断发展，它很快就被淘汰了。

Keypad Patent: I filed a patent on an idea for text entry on a ten-key keypad. This was in the pre-smartphone era when people texted on their regular ten-key phones, tapping a key however many times it took to designate the character you intended. My idea involved mentally projecting a letter on the keypad and creating a two-key shortcut for each letter that was based on its shape characteristics. The patent was granted, but the evolution of phone technology quickly made it obsolete.

迪尔伯特：在迪尔伯特进军流行文化的那几年里，我常常忙得没时间好好吃饭。正如俗话所说，我也想回馈这个世界，这个世界比我微薄的才华所能提供的要慷慨得多。于是，我萌生了一个想法，创造一种富含100%每日所需维生素和矿物质的食品。我与一位食品专家（我唯一的员工）合作，他设计了一系列墨西哥卷饼——名为“迪尔伯特”——并成功地将它们销往了美国几乎所有大型连锁超市，以及7-11、好市多和沃尔玛。然而，这些产品每次都未能售出，原因多种多样，主要与货架摆放有关。货架底层的产品很少卖得好，而我们又没有足够的影响力去争取更好的位置。此外，当你的竞争对手派人把你“埋”在他们所有货架上的产品后面时，你什么也卖不出去——这种常用的卑鄙伎​​俩对我们非常有效。

Dilberito: During the busiest years of Dilbert’s climb into popular culture, I was often too busy to eat well. I also wanted to give back, as the saying goes, to a world that was being more generous than I thought my meager talent deserved. I came up with the idea of creating a food product that was fortified with 100 percent of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. I worked with a food expert, my only employee, who designed a line of burritos—dubbed the “Dilberito”—and successfully sold them into almost every major grocery chain in the United States plus Seven-Eleven, Costco, and Walmart. In each case the product failed to sell and for a variety of reasons, mostly related to shelf placement. Few products on the bottom shelf sell well, and we didn’t have the clout to earn better space. Also, nothing sells when your competitor sends people to “bury” you behind their own products on every store shelf—a common dirty trick that worked like a charm on us.

我们也没怎么回头。强化矿物质的味道很难掩盖，而且因为里面有蔬菜和豆类，吃三口迪尔贝里托就会让你放个屁，屁劲儿大到肠子都长出来了。

We also didn’t do much in the way of repeat business. The mineral fortification was hard to disguise, and because of the veggie and legume content, three bites of the Dilberito made you fart so hard your intestines formed a tail.

几年后，花费了数百万美元，我卖掉了知识产权并退出。

Several years and several million dollars later, I sold off the intellectual property and exited.

餐厅1 ：偶然结识了一位经验丰富的餐厅经理后，我同意与她合作，在加州普莱森顿创办一家新餐厅。我们将餐厅命名为Stacey's Café，因为我觉得如果她的名字挂在门上，她会更加努力。我负责融资、指导、法律和财务事宜，而她则负责所有创意、创业和管理工作。尽管食物和服务都略逊一筹，但餐厅开业第一天就迎来了大批顾客。利润滚滚而来。我们最初成功的秘诀在于，该地区的餐厅数量相对于人口而言相对较低。无论质量或价格如何，该地区的每家餐厅都很繁忙。

Restaurant 1: After a chance encounter with an experienced restaurant manager, I agreed to partner with her to create a new restaurant in Pleasanton, California. We named the place Stacey’s Café because I figured she would work harder if her name was over the door. I did the funding, mentoring, legal and financial stuff, and she did all the creative, entrepreneurial, management stuff. The restaurant opened to long lines despite less-than-stellar food and service on day one. Profits poured in. The secret to our initial success was the low number of restaurants in the area relative to population. Every restaurant in the area was busy regardless of quality or price.

令我们始料未及的是，随着食品质量和服务从平庸提升到山谷顶级水平，其他一切都开始走向了错误的方向。运营成本稳步上升，新餐厅开始陆续开业，蚕食着我们的客源。虽然第一家餐厅仍在盈利，但我们认为最大的问题是客流量最大的夜晚座位不足，所以……

What we didn’t expect was that as the food quality and service improved from mediocre to among the best in the valley, everything else trended the wrong way. Operating costs rose steadily, and new restaurants started opening and nibbling at our customer base. While the first restaurant was still profitable, we decided our biggest problem was insufficient seating for the busiest nights, so . . .

餐厅2 ：我们在五英里外开了第二家餐厅，菜单不同，装潢更高端，面积也扩大了一倍。但租金也几乎是第一家的三倍。我们觉得这还好，因为能填满这么大的空间简直是金矿。但我们没想到的是，人们不会因为餐厅面积大就选择它。我们获得了相当可观的客流量，而这些客流量原本只够我们开一半大小的餐厅。与此同时，经济不景气，原本计划在我们周围设立大型园区的大公司纷纷撤离了该地区。我们的户外座位变成了风洞，交通噪音很大。顾客们也觉得装潢过于高档，对家庭来说价格昂贵，而且不如去附近的旧金山享用一顿特别的餐点那么令人兴奋。我见过的最糟糕的餐厅运气就是，步行距离内就出现了一个全是餐厅的购物中心。第二家餐厅从一开始就亏损严重，从未接近收支平衡。

Restaurant 2: We opened a second restaurant five miles down the road, with a different menu, higher-end décor, and twice the space. It was also nearly triple the rent of the first. We figured that was okay because filling a space that large would be a gold mine. What we didn’t count on is that people don’t choose a restaurant because it’s large. We got our fair share of business, which would have been just enough for a place half the size. Meanwhile, the economy tanked and big corporations that had planned on surrounding us with major campuses pulled out of the area. Our outdoor seating turned out to be a wind tunnel with major traffic noise. And customers found the décor too upscale and expensive for families and also not as exciting as a trip to nearby San Francisco for special meals. In the worst restaurant luck I have ever seen, a strip mall of nothing but restaurants opened within walking distance. The second restaurant bled money from the start and never came close to breakeven.

与此同时，原来的餐厅却无利可图，主要原因是两家大型连锁餐厅在附近开店，严重蚕食了我们的业务。

Meanwhile, the original restaurant turned unprofitable, thanks mostly to two major chain restaurants setting up shop nearby and cutting deeply into our business.

然后法律问题就开始了。我们接连面临诉讼或威胁诉讼，大多都是因为一些荒唐的理由。由于和解协议，我无法透露细节，但其中三起案件足以让人作呕。所有法律威胁或诉讼都不是来自客户。这些都是你闻所未闻的事情。我财力雄厚，背上背着一个大大的红靶心。

Then the legal problems started. We had one lawsuit or threatened lawsuit after another, mostly for ridiculous reasons. I can’t get into details because of settlement agreements, but three of the situations would make you vomit in your own mouth. None of the legal threats or lawsuits came from customers. It was the sort of stuff you’ve never even heard of. I had deep pockets and a big red bullseye on my back.

我卖掉了所有资产，退出了餐饮业。不得不说，在餐厅的丰富体验绝对物有所值。我当时有能力承担损失，而且不用改变生活方式，所以我一点也不后悔。在自己开的餐厅吃饭，绝对是一段​​非常美好的时光。这肯定比在家做饭洗碗要好得多。在我所有的失败经历中，我最喜欢的还是在餐厅工作。

I sold off the assets and got out of the restaurant business. I have to say the richness of the whole restaurant experience was totally worth the money. I was in a position to afford the losses without altering my lifestyle, so I don’t regret any of it. Eating dinner at a restaurant you own can be an extraordinarily good time. It sure beats cooking at home and washing the dishes. Of all my failures, I enjoyed the restaurants the most.

初次尝试漫画：我第一次尝试专业漫画创作，是向两家稿费最高的杂志投稿：《花花公子》和《纽约客》。这些漫画质量极差，两家杂志都明智地拒绝了它们。

First Attempt at Cartooning: My first attempt at professional cartooning involved sending some single-panel comics to the two magazines that paid the most: Playboy and The New Yorker. The comics were dreadful. Both magazines wisely rejected them.

Ninja Closet：我有个想法，想做一个网站，方便大家知道该给孩子买什么礼物，尤其是给非亲生孩子。如果你的孩子每两周就要被邀请参加一次生日派对，买礼物可就麻烦了。小蒂米已经有某个玩具了吗？他想要吗？还有谁也想给他买同样的玩具？谁愿意出钱买更贵的礼物？目前的流程需要大量的猜测，还要发送大量的电子邮件和打电话。

Ninja Closet: I had an idea for a website that would make it easier to know what gifts to buy for kids, especially kids that are not your own. Gift-buying can be a huge hassle if your kid is getting invited to a birthday party every two weeks. Does little Timmy already have a particular toy? Does he want one? Who else is thinking of buying him the same toy? Who wants to pitch in for a more expensive gift? The current process involves too much guesswork and too many emails and phone calls.

我决定在印度雇几个收费低廉的程序员，为孩子们开发一个基于网络的礼物登记系统。我把它叫做“忍者衣橱”，因为它的隐喻是，朋友和家人可以窥探你心愿的秘密衣橱，还能看到你已经拥有的东西，还能协商共同购买礼物等等。我想孩子们也会喜欢看看其他孩子拥有的东西。除非得到父母的许可，否则任何人都无法查看孩子的衣橱。

I decided to hire some inexpensive programmers in India to build a web-based gift registry (essentially) for kids. I called it Ninja Closet because the metaphor was that friends and family could peak into your secret closet of wishes but also see what stuff you already owned, negotiate for shared gift-buying, and more. I figured kids would love seeing what other kids owned, too. No one would be able to see a kid’s closet unless a parent granted permission.

我仍然认为这是一个好主意，但由于时差、语言问题以及我自己的时间限制，管理印度的程序员对我来说并不现实。在这个副业上投入了太多时间和金钱后，我放弃了。

I still think it was a great idea, but managing programmers in India turned out to be impractical for me because of time differences, language issues, and my own time limitations. After too much time and expense on this side project, I let it go.

*公平地说，尼采所说的“更强大”可能指的是任何能让你更有能力的东西。我本想请他解释一下，但讽刺的是，他已经用尽了所有能让他不死的东西。

*To be fair to Nietzsche, he probably meant the word “stronger” to include anything that makes you more capable. I’d ask him to clarify, but ironically he ran out of things that didn’t kill him.

†我应该提醒你，我 75% 的类比都与粪便、婴儿或史蒂夫·乔布斯有关。我对此并不感到抱歉。

†I should warn you that 75 percent of my analogies involve feces, babies, or Steve Jobs. I do not apologize for that.

第五章

Chapter 5

我最喜欢的惊人失败

My Absolute Favorite Spectacular Failure

米大多数失败都与运气不佳、无知以及有时普通的愚蠢有关。有一天，在大学里，我成功地将这三种经历融合在一起。这真是令人叹为观止。

Most failures involve bad luck, ignorance, and sometimes ordinary stupidity. One day in college, I managed to combine all three into one experience. It was breathtaking.

大四那年的冬天，我开始觉得自己或许具备成为一名优秀会计师的条件，或许有一天能成为注册会计师。我觉得这条职业道路能让我更好地从数字层面了解商业的本质。无论我以后自己创办什么样的公司，我都需要这样的经验。我所需要的只是在当时所谓的“八大”会计师事务所之一找到一个入门级职位。我设法在距离校园两小时车程的纽约州锡拉丘兹安排了一次面试。

In the winter of my senior year, I started to think I might have the right stuff to become a good accountant, perhaps someday a CPA. I figured that career path would be a good way to learn the innards of business from the numbers side. I would need that sort of experience no matter what kind of business I someday started on my own. All I needed was an entry-level position with one of the so-called Big Eight (at the time) accounting firms. I managed to line up an interview in Syracuse, New York, a two-hour drive from campus.

采访当天，纽约州北部正遭遇一场典型的半暴风雪，气温低得像要冻死人一样。我决定不用穿外套，因为我只需要从一栋楼走到车上，然后再回来。这只是我那天做的几个极其愚蠢的决定之一。

The day of the interview featured a typical upstate New York half-blizzard with ass-freezing temperatures. I decided I didn’t need a jacket for the trip because I was only going from building to car and back. This was only one of the remarkably stupid decisions I made that day.

我的第二个错误是没有意识到去会计师事务所面试应该穿西装打领带。我以为他们知道我是大学生，因为我的简历上写着呢，所以为什么不穿得像个大学生呢？没错，我就是这么无知。要知道，我甚至不认识任何在传统白领环境中工作的人。我也没有西装或领带。

My second mistake was not realizing I should wear a suit and tie to an interview with an accounting firm. I figured they knew I was in college since it said so on my résumé, so why not dress like a college student? Yes, I was that ignorant. Remember, I didn’t even know anyone who worked in a traditional white-collar environment. Nor did I own a suit or a tie.

面试官看了我一眼，说我显然不知道自己为什么会来。他送我到门口，建议我下次去面试的时候或许应该穿西装。我当时崩溃了。但今晚的糟糕经历远未结束。到目前为止，我只是在炫耀我的无知和愚蠢。今天倒霉的部分还在后头。

My interviewer took one look at me and remarked that apparently I didn’t know why I was there. He escorted me to the door and suggested that the next time I go to an interview perhaps I should wear a suit. I was devastated. But my evening was far from over. So far, I had only exercised my ignorance and my stupidity. The bad luck part of the day was ahead.

回家的路上，我沿着一条新建的公路，穿过卡茨基尔山脉人烟稀少的山谷。我的引擎突然熄火，我费力地把车滑进了路边的一个雪堆。路上两个方向都没有其他车辆。天色已晚，原本就寒冷的气温正在迅速下降。方圆数英里内，我看不到任何文明的迹象。气温大约是零华氏度。这可不是把外套留在家里的好日子。在手机出现之前的年代，这简直是最糟糕的情况。

On the way home, I took a newly constructed highway through a sparsely populated valley in the Catskill Mountains. My engine conked out, and I managed to coast the car into a snow bank on the side of the road. There were no other cars on the road in either direction. It was after dark, and the already-frosty temperature was dropping fast. I saw no signs of civilization for miles. The temperature was about zero Fahrenheit. It wasn’t a good day to leave my jacket at home. In the days before cell phones, this was the worst-case scenario.

我知道我不能在车里待太久。引擎一熄火，车内的温度就开始下降。我知道我没法沿着来时的方向跑回去，因为我已经跑了好几英里没看到房子了。我跑不了那么远。我唯一的希望就是向前跑，祈祷拐弯处或山坡那边有房子。于是我开始跑。

I knew I couldn’t stay in the car for long. The temperature inside started dropping the moment the engine died. I knew I couldn’t run back in the direction from which I came because it had been miles since I saw a house. I wouldn’t make it that far. My only hope was to run forward and hope there were homes around a bend or over a hill. And so I started running.

不到一分钟，冰冷的空气就吸走了我身体的温暖，散播到空气中。我的双脚就像冰块般，在冰冻的路面上发出咚咚的声响。我的呼吸在头顶形成一团团积云。我的双手几乎失去了知觉。我的脚踝也僵硬了。我估计再过三十分钟，我就要倒在最近的雪堆里冻得要死。现在我的腿也开始无力了。我再也跑不动了，一旦停下脚步，我就知道寒冷会将我彻底击垮。

In less than a minute, the frozen air sucked the warmth from my body and distributed it into the atmosphere. My feet were like blocks of ice clunking on the frozen pavement. My breath formed cumulus clouds around my head. I lost most of the feeling in my hands. My ankles hardened. I figured I was about thirty minutes from falling into a frozen death sleep in the nearest snowbank. And now my legs were failing. I couldn’t go much further, and when I stopped running, I knew the cold would finish me off.

当我挣扎着站直并继续前行时，我对自己许下了一个承诺：如果我能活下来，我会用我的破车换一张去加利福尼亚的单程机票，并且在我的余生中再也不会见到另一个该死的雪花。

As I struggled to stay upright and keep moving, I made myself a promise: If I lived, I would trade my piece of shit car for a one-way plane ticket to California and never see another f@$#!#& snow flake for the rest of my life.

车灯出现在地平线上。我站在路中间，像个傻瓜一样，挥手示意车子停下来。一个开着破旧旅行车的流动售鞋员救了我一命。他一路开车送我回了校园。

Headlights appeared on the horizon. I stood in the middle of the road and signaled, like the frozen idiot I was, for the car to stop. A traveling shoe salesman in a beat-up station wagon saved my life. He drove me all the way back to campus.

几个月后，我兑现了自己的承诺。我买了一张单程机票，飞往经济繁荣、气候宜人的北加州。这是我做过的最明智的决定。在纽约州北部冰冻苔原上险些丧命的经历，激励我搬到了加州。谢谢你，失败。现在出门在外，我不再惧怕死亡了。

A few months later, I kept my promise to myself. I bought a one-way plane ticket to the vibrant economy and easy climate of Northern California. It was the smartest decision I ever made. The experience of nearly dying in the frozen tundra of upstate New York inspired me to move to California. Thank you, failure. I no longer fear death when I go outdoors.

第六章

Chapter 6

目标与系统

Goals Versus Systems

一个二十一岁那年，我手握大学文凭，生平第一次登上了飞机。目的地是加州。我深知成功不易：在纽约州温德姆，人口只有2000人的地方，成功绝非易事。几年前，我那位更具冒险精神的哥哥戴夫开着他的大众甲壳虫，横跨全美来到洛杉矶，寻找温暖的气候和迷人的女性。他睡在车里，沿途露营。我的计划是飞到洛杉矶，在他那堆满面包屑的沙发上睡一觉，直到在银行找到工作，然后在加州安家落户。
