At the age of twenty-one, college diploma in hand, I boarded an airplane for the first time in my life. Destination, California. I knew one thing about success: It wouldn’t be easy to find in Windham, New York, population 2,000. A few years earlier, my older and more adventurous brother Dave had driven his Volkswagen Beetle cross-country to Los Angeles, looking for warmer weather and attractive women. He slept in his car and camped along the way. My plan was to fly to Los Angeles, sleep on his crumb-laden couch until I could find a job in banking, and make my home in the Golden State.

在飞往加州的前几天，我把那辆锈迹斑斑的达特桑510汽车换成了现金，这样我就能买得起去加州的单程票了。（之后会详细介绍这个故事。）我骄傲地穿上了父母送给我的廉价三件套西装，那是我大学毕业时送给我的礼物——这是我的第一套正式西装。当时，我以为每个人坐飞机都会穿商务装或正式服装。我生长在一个小镇，认识的人里，坐过商用飞机的人不多。我父亲二十多年前坐过几次飞机，但他并没有主动透露太多相关信息，或者其他任何信息。他是个沉默寡言的人。我家附近只有几个亲戚，而且他们都没坐过飞机。我基本上只能靠猜测，不想因为衣着不当而被赶下飞机。我经常犯这种错误。

A few days before my flight to California, I traded my rusted-out Datsun 510 to my sister for cash so I could afford that one-way ticket to California. (More on that story later.) I proudly donned the cheap three-piece suit my parents gave me as a college graduation present—my first real suit. At the time, I assumed everyone dressed in business or formal attire to fly. I grew up in a small town and didn’t know many people who had flown in a commercial aircraft. My father had taken some flights twenty-some years earlier, but he didn’t volunteer much information about it or anything else for that matter. He was a man of few words. I had only a few relatives nearby, and none of them had ever flown. I was mostly guessing how the process worked, and I didn’t want to take a chance of getting kicked off the flight for being poorly dressed. That’s exactly the sort of mistake I make.

我也不知道如果西装在行李箱里皱了，该怎么熨。我估计一到加州就要去面试，所以这套独一无二的西装需要看起来不那么像个流浪汉。所以在飞机上穿它就很合理了。

I also didn’t know how I would go about getting my suit ironed if it got wrinkled in my luggage. I figured I would be going on job interviews as soon as I reached California and needed my one-and-only suit to look relatively less hobo-ish. It just made sense to wear it on the flight.

我坐在一位大概六十出头的商人旁边。我觉得自己看起来有些奇怪，举止严肃，发型糟糕，西装廉价，显然与我格格不入。他问我的故事，我一一解释了。我问他做什么工作，他告诉我是一家生产螺丝钉的公司的CEO。然后他给了我一些职业建议。他说，每次找到新工作，他都会立刻开始寻找更好的工作。对他来说，找工作不是迫不得已才做的事情，而是一个持续的过程。如果你仔细算一下，就会明白这完全说得通。很可能，最适合你的工作并不会恰好在你宣称自己准备好的时候出现。他解释说，你最好的选择就是一直寻找更好的工作。更好的工作有它自己的时间表。我相信他是这样解释的：你的工作不是你的工作；你的工作是找到更好的工作。

I was seated next to a businessman who was probably in his early sixties. I suppose I looked like an odd duck with my serious demeanor, bad haircut, and cheap suit, clearly out of my element. He asked what my story was, and I filled him in. I asked what he did for a living, and he told me he was CEO of a company that made screws. Then he offered me some career advice. He said that every time he got a new job, he started immediately looking for a better one. For him, job-seeking was not something one did when necessary. It was an ongoing process. This makes perfect sense if you do the math. Chances are, the best job for you won’t become available at precisely the time you declare yourself ready. Your best bet, he explained, was to always be looking for the better deal. The better deal has its own schedule. I believe the way he explained it is that your job is not your job; your job is to find a better job.

这是我第一次体会到，一个人应该有一个体系，而不是一个目标。这个体系就是不断寻找更好的选择。而这个体系对这位商人来说非常有效，因为他在各个公司之间跳槽，一路积累经验，最终成为CEO。如果他在职业生涯中设定了一个特定的目标，或者设定了具体的工作目标（比如，争取老板的职位），他的选择就会严重受限。但对他来说，整个世界都是他下一份潜在的工作。新工作必须比上一份更好，并且能让他学到一些对下一次跳槽有用的东西。

This was my first exposure to the idea that one should have a system instead of a goal. The system was to continuously look for better options. And it worked for this businessman, as he had job-hopped from company to company, gaining experience along the way, until he became a CEO. Had he approached his career with a specific goal in mind or perhaps specific job objectives (e.g., gunning for his boss’s job), that would have severely limited his options. But for him, the entire world was his next potential job. The new job simply had to be better than the last one and allow him to learn something useful for the next hop.

这位商人是否应该对他现在的雇主保持忠诚？在他看来，没有。这位商人并没有发明资本主义，也没有制定其规则。他只是在规则框架内行事。他的雇主会毫不犹豫地以任何符合其业务需求的理由解雇他。他只是效仿了他们的行事方式。

Did the businessman owe his current employers loyalty? Not in his view. The businessman didn’t invent capitalism, and he didn’t create its rules. He simply played within those rules. His employers wouldn’t have hesitated to fire him at the drop of a hat for any reason that fit their business needs. He simply followed their example.

在那趟航班上，我学到的第二件事——或者说，实际上证实了这一点——就是外表很重要。飞机下飞机时，CEO递给我一张名片，几乎保证只要我愿意，就能得到他公司的工作。如果我穿着破烂的牛仔裤、破旧的T恤和破旧的运动鞋登机，情况可能就不一样了。

The second thing I learned on that flight—or confirmed, really—is that appearance matters. By the end of the flight, the CEO had handed me his card and almost guaranteed me a job at his company if I wanted it. Had I boarded the flight wearing my ratty jeans, threadbare tee shirt, and worn-out sneakers, things would have gone differently.

在我的整个职业生涯中，我一直在寻找那些运用系统而非目标的人的例子。据我所知，大多数情况下，运用系统的人表现更佳。系统驱动的人找到了一种以全新且更有益的方式看待熟悉事物的方法。

Throughout my career, I’ve had my antennae up looking for examples of people who use systems versus goals. In most cases, as far as I can tell, the people who use systems do better. The systems-driven people have found a way to look at the familiar in new and more useful ways.

说白了，目标是为失败者而设的。大多数情况下确实如此。比如，如果你的目标是减掉十磅，那么在达到目标之前的每一刻——如果你真的能达到的话——你都会感觉自己离目标还很远。换句话说，以目标为导向的人几乎总是处于一种失败的状态，他们希望这种失败只是暂时的。这种感觉会折磨你。久而久之，它会变得沉重而令人不适，甚至可能让你放弃目标。

To put it bluntly, goals are for losers. That’s literally true most of the time. For example, if your goal is to lose ten pounds, you will spend every moment until you reach the goal—if you reach it at all—feeling as if you are short of your goal. In other words, goal-oriented people exist in a state of nearly continuous failure that they hope will be temporary. That feeling wears on you. In time, it becomes heavy and uncomfortable. It might even drive you out of the game.

如果你实现了目标，你会庆祝，感觉棒极了，但直到你意识到，你失去了那个赋予你目标和方向的东西。你的选择可能是感到空虚和无助，或许会享受成功的喜悦，直到厌倦为止；又或者设定新的目标，重新进入永久的“成功前失败”的循环。

If you achieve your goal, you celebrate and feel terrific, but only until you realize you just lost the thing that gave you purpose and direction. Your options are to feel empty and useless, perhaps enjoying the spoils of your success until they bore you, or set new goals and reenter the cycle of permanent pre-success failure.

当然，系统与目标的观点受制于语义。你可能会说每个系统都有一个目标，无论它多么模糊。这在某种程度上确实如此。你也可以说，每个追求目标的人都有某种系统来实现目标，无论它是否被明确表达出来。如果你愿意，你可以将目标和系统简单地拼凑在一起。我只是想说，将目标和系统视为截然不同的概念是有力量的。目标导向的人处于一种持续的未成功状态，往好了说是持续的失败，往坏了说是永久的失败，如果事情永远无法顺利进行。系统导向的人每次应用他们的系统都会成功，因为他们完成了他们打算做的事情。“目标”导向的人每次都在与沮丧的感觉作斗争。系统导向的人每次应用他们的系统都会感觉良好。这在将个人精力保持在正确方向上方面有着巨大的差异。

The systems-versus-goals point of view is burdened by semantics, of course. You might say every system has a goal, however vague. And that would be true to some extent. And you could say that everyone who pursues a goal has some sort of system to get there, whether it is expressed or not. You could word-glue goals and systems together if you choose. All I’m suggesting is that thinking of goals and systems as very different concepts has power. Goal-oriented people exist in a state of continuous pre-success failure at best and permanent failure at worst, if things never work out. Systems people succeed every time they apply their systems in the sense that they did what they intended to do. The “goals” people are fighting the feeling of discouragement at each turn. The systems people feel good every time they apply their system. That’s a big difference in terms of maintaining your personal energy in the right direction.

系统与目标模型可以应用于大多数人类活动。在节食领域，减掉20磅是一个目标，但健康饮食是一个系统。在运动领域，在4小时内跑完一场马拉松是一个目标，但每天锻炼是一个系统。在商业领域，赚100万美元是一个目标，但成为一名连续创业者是一个系统。

The system-versus-goals model can be applied to most human endeavors. In the world of dieting, losing twenty pounds is a goal, but eating right is a system. In the exercise realm, running a marathon in under four hours is a goal, but exercising daily is a system. In business, making a million dollars is a goal, but being a serial entrepreneur is a system.

为了我们的目的，我们假设目标是一个具体的目标，你要么在未来的某个时候实现它，要么就无法实现它。系统是你定期做的事情，它可以长期增加你获得幸福的几率。如果你每天都在做某件事，它就是一个系统。如果你等待着未来某一天实现它，它就是一个目标。

For our purposes, let’s say a goal is a specific objective that you either achieve or don’t sometime in the future. A system is something you do on a regular basis that increases your odds of happiness in the long run. If you do something every day, it’s a system. If you’re waiting to achieve it someday in the future, it’s a goal.

语言本身就很复杂，我知道你们有些人会觉得每天锻炼听起来像个目标。目标的通用定义当然允许这种解读。为了我们的目的，我们先同意，目标是可以达成并完成的事情，而系统是你定期做的事情，并合理地期望这样做能让你的生活更美好。系统没有截止日期，而且在任何一天，你可能无法判断它是否在朝着正确的方向前进。

Language is messy, and I know some of you are thinking that exercising every day sounds like a goal. The common definition of goals would certainly allow that interpretation. For our purposes, let’s agree that goals are a reach-it-and-be-done situation, whereas a system is something you do on a regular basis with a reasonable expectation that doing so will get you to a better place in your life. Systems have no deadlines, and on any given day, you probably can’t tell if it’s moving you in the right direction.

我的主张是，如果你研究成功人士，你会发现他们大多遵循的是系统，而不是目标。当目标导向的人取得巨大成功时，这就会成为新闻。至少，这会成为一个有趣的故事。这会让你对目标驱动的人的成功频率产生扭曲的看法。当你用你自己的“真相过滤器”来过滤“系统优于目标”这一观点时，请只考虑你认识的人。如果你认识一些格外成功的人，可以问一些探究性的问题，了解他们是如何取得如今成就的。我认为你会发现，这一切背后都有一个系统，而且通常也有一些非凡的运气。（在本书的后面，我会告诉你如何提高获得好运的几率。）

My proposition is that if you study people who succeed, you will see that most of them follow systems, not goals. When goal-oriented people succeed in big ways, it makes the news. At the very least, it makes an interesting story. This gives you a distorted view of how often goal-driven people succeed. When you apply your own truth filter to the idea that systems are better than goals, consider only the people you know personally. If you know some extra-successful people, ask some probing questions about how they got where they did. I think you’ll find a system at the bottom of it all and usually some extraordinary luck as well. (Later in this book, I’ll tell you how to improve your odds of getting lucky.)

想想奥运会运动员。当一位奥运选手赢得一枚或多枚金牌时，这都会成为头条新闻。但每一位奖牌获得者背后都有成千上万的人，他们的目标是登上领奖台，但却未能如愿。这些人有目标，但没有系统。我不认为日常训练和专业教练是一个系统，因为每个人都事先知道，任何特定个体通过这些活动赢得奖牌的几率微乎其微。一个系统的最低要求是，一个理性的人预期它能够经常发挥作用。买彩票，无论你多么频繁地买，都不是一个系统。

Consider Olympic athletes. When one Olympian wins a gold medal or multiple gold medals, it’s a headline story. But for every medalist there are thousands who had the goal of being on that podium and failed. Those people had goals and not systems. I don’t consider daily practices and professional coaching a system because everyone knows in advance that the odds of any specific individual winning a medal through those activities are miniscule. The minimum requirement of a system is that a reasonable person expects it to work more often than not. Buying lottery tickets is not a system no matter how regularly you do it.

从系统角度来看，以Facebook创始人马克·扎克伯格为例。显然，他的成功秘诀包括刻苦学习、取得优异成绩、考入顶尖大学（比如哈佛大学）以及培养一套在当今世界几乎可以保证致富的技术技能。事实证明，他的财富是通过Facebook的爆炸式增长迅速积累起来的。但如果这一切未能奏效，他很可能会通过其他初创公司，或者仅仅凭借在现有公司担任高薪技术天才而成为百万富翁。扎克伯格的系统（或者我推断是他的系统）几乎肯定会奏效，但当时没有人能够想象它会如此有效。

On the system side, consider Mark Zuckerberg, founder of Facebook. It’s apparent that his system for success involved studying hard, getting extraordinary grades, going to a top college—in his case Harvard—and developing a skill set with technology that virtually guaranteed riches in today’s world. As it turns out, his riches came quickly through the explosive growth of Facebook. But had that not worked out, he would likely be a millionaire through some other startup or just by being a highly paid technical genius for an existing corporation. Zuckerberg’s system (or what I infer was his system) was almost guaranteed to work, but no one could have imagined at the time how well.

沃伦·巴菲特的投资体系是买入被低估的公司并永久持有，或者至少持有到出现重大变化为止。这个体系（我之前把它简化了）几十年来一直很成功。相比之下，个人投资者买入股票是因为他们预期未来一年股价会上涨20%；那只是目标，而不是体系。不出所料，个人投资者的回报通常低于市场平均水平。

Warren Buffett’s system for investing involves buying undervalued companies and holding them forever, or at least until something major changes. That system (which I have grossly oversimplified) has been a winner for decades. Compare that to individual investors who buy a stock because they expect it to go up 20 percent in the coming year; that’s a goal, not a system. And not surprisingly, individual investors generally experience worse returns than the market average.

我有个朋友是天才销售员。他什么都能卖，从房子到烤面包机。他选择的领域（我不会透露，因为他不喜欢突然涌入的竞争）让他能够销售几乎总是自动续费的服务。换句话说，他只需销售一次服务，就能享受持续的佣金，直到客户去世或公司倒闭。他人生中最大的问题是他总是用自己的船换一艘更大的船，这需要付出很多努力。旁观者称他为幸运儿。我看到的是一个精准识别自身技能组合并选择了一套系统的人，这套系统大大增加了他获得“好运”的几率。事实上，他的系统非常稳固，能够承受相当多的厄运而不至于崩溃。这个人对自己选择的领域有多大的热情？答案是零。他拥有的是一个非常棒的系统，而这套系统每次都能战胜热情。

I have a friend who is a gifted salesman. He could have sold anything, from houses to toasters. The field he chose (which I won’t reveal because he wouldn’t appreciate the sudden flood of competition) allows him to sell a service that almost always auto-renews. In other words, he can sell his service once and enjoy ongoing commissions until the customer dies or goes out of business. His biggest problem in life is that he keeps trading his boat for a larger one, and that’s a lot of work. Observers call him lucky. What I see is a man who accurately identified his skill set and chose a system that vastly increased his odds of getting “lucky.” In fact, his system is so solid that it could withstand quite a bit of bad luck without buckling. How much passion does this fellow have for his chosen field? Answer: zero. What he has is a spectacular system, and that beats passion every time.

第七章

Chapter 7

我的系统

My System

西六岁那年，我迷上了漫画《花生漫画》 。那些图画深深地吸引着我。它们如此简单，却又如此完美，难以言喻。我刚学会阅读，就如饥似渴地读完了每一本我能找到的《花生漫画》。我向父母承诺，有一天我要成为像查尔斯·舒尔茨那样著名的漫画家。这是我的目标，清晰至极。我花了无数的时间，用蜡笔、铅笔、马克笔和纸，不断练习，却始终未能达到最佳水平。我甚至不是班里四十个孩子中最优秀的画家。但我没有放弃。

When I was six years old, I got hooked on the comic strip Peanuts. The drawings fascinated me. They were so simple and yet so perfect in an indescribable way. As soon as I learned to read, I devoured every Peanuts book I could get my hands on. I declared to my parents that one day I would be a famous cartoonist like Charles Schulz. That was my goal, clear as can be. I spent countless hours with crayons, pencils, markers, and paper. I practiced and practiced. But I never became good. I wasn’t even the best artist in my class of forty kids. I didn’t give up though.

十一岁时，我申请了名家少年艺术学校。这是一个函授课程。这对我来说非常完美，因为我不用离开家，否则会很麻烦。我填写了申请表，画了他们要求的作业，并回答了关于设计的多项选择题。可惜的是，我被名家少年艺术学校拒绝了，因为他们的录取年龄是十二岁。我太小了。我崩溃了。

At the age of eleven, I applied to the Famous Artists School for Young People. It was a correspondence course. This was perfect for me because I wouldn’t need to leave home, which would have been problematic. I filled out the application, drew the assignments they requested, and answered the multiple-choice questions about design. Sadly, I was rejected by the Famous Artists School for Young People because their cutoff age was twelve. I was too young. I was crushed.

我的母亲，以当时的风格告诉我，只要我下定决心，就能做到任何事。她说我可以成为总统、宇航员，或者成为下一个查尔斯·舒尔茨。我相信她，因为在那个时候，我还没有意识到她欺骗的模式。她的谎言包括圣诞老人、牙仙子、复活节兔子，以及骗子永远不会成功之类的。

My mother, in the style of the times, told me I could do anything I set my sights on. She said I could be the president, an astronaut, or the next Charles Schulz. I believed her because at that point in my life, I hadn’t yet noticed the pattern of her deceptions. Her lies included Santa Claus, the Tooth Fairy, the Easter Bunny, and something about cheaters never prospering.

渐渐地，我开始理解所谓的“几率”。有些事情，就其本质而言，很有可能发生，而有些则不然。我通过观察了解到，那些追求极不可能目标的人，往好了说是过于乐观，往坏了说是妄想，大多数时候简直就是愚蠢至极。在我那个共和党占主导地位的小镇上，聪明人制定了切实可行的计划并坚持执行。有些人加入了海军陆战队，积累经验并接受教育。有些人接手了家族生意。有些人结婚生子，成为家庭主妇和母亲。一些超级明星努力学习，在医学和法律领域工作。当时，如果你让我说出一个成年人可以从事的20种不同的工作，我说了15种之后我就会放弃。我听说过的工作，都是我在小镇周围看到的，加上我在电视上看到的。我说的电视，是指我们用兔耳天线接收的、有声有画的那个频道。

In time, I started to understand something called “the odds.” Some things were, by their very nature, likely, and some were not. I learned by observation that people who pursued extraordinarily unlikely goals were overly optimistic at best, delusional at worst, and just plain stupid most of the time. The smart people in my little Republican-dominated town made practical plans and stuck to them. Some joined the Marines to get experience and education. Some went into the family business. Some married and became homemakers and moms. A few superstars studied hard and pursued jobs in medicine and the law. At the time, if you had asked me to name twenty different types of jobs an adult could have, I would have tapped out after fifteen. The jobs I had heard of were the ones I saw around me in my little town plus whatever I saw on television. And by television, I mean the one channel we received via rabbit ears that had both a picture and sound.

我父亲在当地邮局工作，天气好的时候晚上就刷房子。他建议我和弟弟从事邮政行业。美国邮政局的工作很稳定，大部分时间都在室内，福利也很好。有时候，母亲忙的时候，我和弟弟妹妹会和父亲一起在邮局闲逛。我们被那把随时可及的上膛手枪迷住了。显然，政府希望员工能够拿起枪，开枪扫射，以抵御武装抢劫。那可是截然不同的时代。

My father worked at the local post office and painted houses at night when the weather allowed. His advice to my brother and me was to pursue a career in the postal profession. The United States Postal Service was steady work, it was mostly indoors, and it had excellent benefits. Sometimes when my mother was busy, my siblings and I would hang out at the Post Office with my dad. We were fascinated by the loaded handgun that was always within easy reach. Apparently, the government expected its employees to resist armed robberies by reaching for their pieces and blazing away. Those were different times.

三个孩子长大到可以独立生活后，母亲决定尝试房地产销售。她成了一名房产经纪人，生意做得不错，攒了一些钱，足够我们上大学。从我们能听懂话的时候起，母亲就告诉我们，不管愿不愿意，我们三个都要上大学。我们家只有一个阿姨上过大学。母亲决定改变这种现状。后来，房地产市场充斥着各种经纪人和代理人，她找了一份在流水线上拿着最低工资的工作，每天工作八小时，给扬声器磁铁绕铜线。这笔钱也用来支付我们的学费了。虽然远远不够，但这是朝着正确方向迈出的一步。

My mother decided to try her hand at selling real estate once her three kids were old enough to stay alive on their own. She became an agent and did well enough to build up some savings that would go toward our college educations. My mother told us from the time we could understand language that all three of us were college-bound, like it or not. In my family, only an aunt had ever attended college. My mother decided to change that. Later, when the real estate market got saturated with brokers and agents, she took a job for minimum wage on an assembly line, winding copper wires around speaker magnets for eight hours a day. That money, too, went toward our education. It wasn’t nearly enough, but it was a step in the right direction.

母亲决定让我当一名律师。她费了好大劲才说服我，说这是个好主意。我们镇上有两个律师都挺不错的，我的成绩也足够优秀，足以让我在法律界闯出一片天地。我对律师这份工作不太了解，但我喜欢赚大钱，而且有朝一日还能离开我的小镇。我同意了母亲的计划，立志成为一名法律工作者。我只需要想办法支付大学学费。

My mother decided that I should become a lawyer. She spent a good deal of energy convincing me that it was a good plan. The two lawyers in our town were doing well, and my grades seemed strong enough to make a legitimate run at the legal profession. I didn’t know much about the job of lawyering, but I did like the idea of making good money and someday escaping my little town. I signed on to my mother’s plan and set my sights on a career in law. All I needed to do was figure out how to pay for college.

有一天，在十一年级的健康课上，我们的体育老师/健康老师提到，我们这个小学校（我们班大约有 40 个孩子）从来没有培养出过获得大学学术奖学金的学生。他解释说，有一个身材异常高大、运动能力极强的学生在大一膝盖受伤之前，设法获得了篮球奖学金，但是还没有人仅凭学术成绩就获得大学奖学金。老师自信地推测这种情况即将改变。他宣布我们年级有一名学生很可能获得学术奖学金。这个消息让我大吃一惊。我环顾着狭小的教室，不知道他指的是谁。好奇心占了上风，我举起了手。“你在说谁？”他用体育教练的眼神盯着我，似乎对这个问题感到恼火或惊讶。然后他自信地回答道：“你。”

One day in eleventh grade health class, our gym teacher/health teacher mentioned that our small school (there were about forty kids in my class) had never produced a student who earned an academic scholarship to college. He explained that one unusually tall and athletic student had managed to get a basketball scholarship before blowing out his knee in his freshman year, but no one had earned a college scholarship based on academics alone. The teacher speculated with confidence that this was about to change. He announced that one student in our grade was likely to get an academic scholarship. This news surprised me. I looked around my small classroom and couldn’t figure out who he meant. Curiosity got the best of me, and I raised my hand. “Who are you talking about?” He stared at me in a gym coach way, either annoyed or surprised by the question. Then he answered in a confident voice, “You.”

我不相信他。他只是个有自己想法的人。但我妈妈告诉我，无论如何我都会上大学，所以我开始琢磨该如何上大学。那时家长们还没有那么积极地参与到申请中。我几乎是孤军奋战。我们的升学顾问指着墙上摆满大学宣传册和书籍的书架，给了我宝贵的职业指导：选几所看起来不错的大学，然后填写申请表。这可不是人们所期望的那种精准的职业建议。我浏览了几本大学书籍，却感到茫然。我怎么可能知道哪个选择最适合我呢？

I didn’t believe him. He was just one guy with an opinion. But my mother told me I was going to college one way or another, so I set about the task of figuring out how that happens. This was well before the days of highly involved parents. I was pretty much on my own. Our guidance counselor pointed to a wall-length shelf that was full of college pamphlets and books and gave me this valuable career guidance: Pick a few colleges that look good and fill out some applications. This was not the precise sort of career advice that one would hope for. I skimmed a few college books and felt lost. How could I possibly know the best choice for me?

幸运的是，一年前我的班里加入了一个新学生。新生很少见。我和大约35个一起上幼儿园，毕业的40个孩子中，大多数都在同一栋楼里。这个新来的孩子，彼得，来自某个充满异国情调的城市，或者可能是郊区，那里的人了解世界是如何运转的。我跟随他，做了他所做的事。我决定主修经济学，因为彼得告诉我，这会是一个不错的法律预科学位。然后，我跟着他翻遍了辅导员那本小小的大学资料库，了解到每所大学的申请流程都在那些资料里有详细说明。最终，我选了两所纸面上看起来不错的大学。我的意思是，这两所学校都在驾车可达的范围内，提供经济学学位，而且校园照片也赏心悦目。

Luckily, a new kid had joined my class a year earlier. New students were rare. I attended kindergarten with about thirty-five of the forty kids I graduated with, and most of those classes were in the same building. This new kid, Peter, came from some exotic city, or maybe it was a suburb, where people knew how the world worked. I followed his lead and did what he did. I decided to major in economics because Peter told me that would be a good pre-law degree. Then I followed him around in the guidance counselor’s tiny library of college information and learned that the process for applying to each college was described in those books. Eventually, I picked two colleges that looked good on paper. And by that I mean the schools were located within driving distance, they offered degrees in economics, and the photographs of the campus were pleasing.

我的第一志愿康奈尔大学有两个不利因素。首先是悲惨的男女比例，这注定我会以处女身份毕业。另一个问题是我申请得太晚，错过了他们的截止日期。康奈尔大学通知我，我在他们的候补名单上。我唯一能进入那所学校的机会，就是某种快速蔓延的瘟疫杀死所有知道申请截止日期的人。

My first choice, Cornell, had two factors working against it. The first was a tragic men-to-women ratio that guaranteed I would graduate a virgin. The other problem is that I applied too late and missed their deadline. Cornell informed me that I was on their wait list. My only chance of getting into that school was if some sort of fast-moving plague killed all the people who knew there was a deadline for applying.

我申请的另一所大学是纽约州奥尼昂塔的哈特威克学院。哈特威克学院有很多优势。离家只有一个小时的车程，所以交通费用不高。他们有一个备受推崇的护理专业，所以女生比男生多。而且他们录取了我。这是我唯一的选择。这时我明白了，不应该向一个叫彼得的孩子寻求改变人生的建议，他的主要资历就是曾经住在郊区，或者可能是城里。无论如何，只申请两所大学是个坏主意，而根据招生简章上的照片质量来选择这两所大学则更糟糕。（坦白说：就读男女比例合适的大学，结果证明是个天才之举。）

The only other college I applied to was Hartwick College in Oneonta, New York. Hartwick had several things going for it. It was a one-hour drive from home, so travel would be affordable. They had a well-respected nursing major so there were more women than men. And they accepted me. It was my only option. This is when I learned that one should not seek life-altering advice from a kid named Peter whose primary credentials were that he once lived in a suburb or maybe a city. Either way, it was a bad idea to apply to only two colleges and a worse idea to choose those two colleges based on the quality of the photographs in the brochures. (Full disclosure: Attending a college with a favorable male-female ratio turned out to be genius.)

我的下一个问题是，父母负担不起我去哈特威克学院的费用，那是一所学费昂贵的私立大学。所以我申请了学术奖学金。出乎我的意料，但我的体育老师兼健康老师却并不意外，哈特威克学院给了我部分学术奖学金。我还获得了纽约州的一些小额奖学金。父母的积蓄，加上我多年来修剪草坪、铲雪攒下的钱，差不多够用了。我想我可以在学校打几份工来弥补缺口。就这样，我的大学生活开始了。我打算学习经济学，以后的目标是读法学院。我勉强离开了纽约州的温德姆。生活并没有因此变得更容易。

My next problem was that my parents couldn’t afford to send me to Hartwick, which is a pricey private college. So I applied for an academic scholarship. To my surprise, but not the surprise of my gym teacher/health teacher, Hartwick granted me a partial academic scholarship. I also received some small scholarships from the state of New York. With my parents’ savings plus my own savings from mowing lawns and shoveling snow for years, I had almost enough. I figured I could work a few jobs at school and close the gap. And so my college career began. I would study economics and aim for law school later. I escaped from Windham, New York, but just barely. Things would not get easier.

在哈特威克学院的第一个学期刚开始不久，我就发现了一些有趣的消遣，或许可以归类为成年人的乐趣。那时候，法定饮酒年龄是十八岁，而我刚刚摆脱了酒瘾。很快，由于各种令人愉悦的消遣，我的成绩跌到了哈特威克学院对奖学金获得者的期望值以下。院长给我发了一封信，警告我：如果我不提高成绩，奖学金将被取消。大约在同一时间，我患上了世界级的单核细胞增多症。学院的护士们对此印象深刻；他们从未见过如此严重的病例。我的腺体肿得厉害，喉咙几乎完全堵塞。我甚至无法吞咽。学院的医生告诉我，我会因为过度疲劳和困倦而无法学习，最好的办法是收拾东西退学。他建议我以后可以重返校园，重新开始。他解释说，这是我的选择，但他的医生建议是，重新调整状态，在家休养，下次再去上大学。我才上大学一个学期，就已经濒临彻底失败。

Soon into my first semester at Hartwick, I discovered several interesting pastimes that might fit under the heading of adult fun. The drinking age was eighteen in those days, and I was fresh off the leash. Soon, thanks to many delightful distractions, my grades dipped below the level that Hartwick expected from an academic scholarship recipient. The dean sent a letter putting me on notice. The scholarship would be rescinded unless I got my grades up. At about that same time, I came down with a world-class case of mononucleosis. The college nurses were impressed; they had never seen a case so severe. My glands were so swollen that my throat almost closed entirely. I couldn’t even swallow. The college physician advised me that I would be too drained and sleepy to study, and my best bet was to pack up my stuff and drop out. He suggested that maybe I could come back to college someday and start over. It was my choice, he explained, but his medical advice was to regroup, recover at home, and try college another time. I had only been in college for one semester, and I was on the verge of complete failure.

这次，愿望和决定之间的差别至关重要。我不想继续上学；我决定了。接下来的两个星期，我躺在大学医务室的床上，努力保持清醒，读完课本，跟上我预想的课程进度。出院后，我发现有些课程我实际上比预想的提前了一个月。我的成绩回到了应有的水平，我继续前进。

This was one of those times when the difference between wishing and deciding mattered. I didn’t wish to stay in school; I decided. For the next two weeks, I stayed in a bed in the college infirmary, struggling to stay awake long enough to read my textbooks and keep up to where I assumed the class would be. Upon release, I discovered I was actually a month ahead in some of my classes. My grades climbed back where they needed to be, and I marched on.

我当时没有听从父亲的建议，去邮政局工作。后来证明，这是个好主意。我没怎么接受辅导员的帮助就考上了大学，而且不顾医生的建议，继续上学。大约就是在那时，我对专家和权威人士的评价开始逐渐下降，这种情况一直持续到今天。

I had ignored my father’s advice to work for the Postal Service. That turned out to be a good idea. I got into college without much help from my guidance counselor, and I stayed in school against my doctor’s advice. This was about the time that my opinion of experts and authority figures in general began a steady descent that continues to this day.

随着我对法律职业的了解越来越多，我意识到它并不适合我的性格。我不是那种为了赢而让对方损失同等甚至更大价值的人。如果我为我的客户赢得一场不该得的胜利，而且仅仅是凭借我狡猾的手段，我会感觉更糟。我从小就被教育要拒绝亲朋好友送的糖果，因为我觉得自己没做任何事，不配得到这些。我是那种需要一份能给别人带来快乐，最好还能让我自己变得富有和出名的工作的人。而为了实现这个目标，我需要一个体系。

As I learned more about the legal profession, I realized it wasn’t a good fit for my personality. I’m not the sort of person who feels comfortable winning when it means the other side loses something of equal or greater value. I’d feel even worse if I were to win a victory for my client that was ill-deserved and accomplished only through my weaseltastic skills. I had been raised to decline offers of candy from family friends under the theory that I had done nothing to deserve it. I was the kind of person who needed a job that made other people happy, ideally with a side benefit of making me rich and famous, too. And for that I needed a system.

我认定我的才能最适合创建和运营某种公司。为了获得必要的技能，我要完成经济学学位，然后在一家大银行找到一份入门级的工作。我会尽可能多地参加公司付费的培训课程，从银行的角度学习所有商业知识。我还希望用公司的钱在晚上完成我的MBA学位。我并不确定未来自己会经营什么样的公司。我唯一确定的是，我需要在合适的时机做好准备。

I decided that my talents would be best suited for creating and running some sort of company. To acquire the necessary skills, I would complete my economics degree and get an entry-level job at a big bank. I would take as many company-paid training classes as I could and learn all there was to know about business from a banking perspective. I also hoped to complete my MBA at night on the company’s dime. I was agnostic about what specific sort of business I would someday run. All I knew for sure is that I needed to be ready when the time was right.

这让我想起了我的创业体系。我至今还保留着从哈特威克大学毕业时写的日记，其中概述了我的创业计划。我的想法是创造一些有价值的东西，而且——接下来的部分是关键——我希望产品能够轻松无限地复制。我不想出售我的时间，至少不是直接出售，因为这种模式存在上限。例如，我不想建造自己的汽车厂，因为汽车不易复制。我不想做任何定制工作，比如建造房屋，因为建造每栋房子都需要同样多的工作量。我想创造、发明、撰写或以其他方式炮制一些广受欢迎且易于复制的东西。

This brings me to my system. I still have the diary I wrote when I graduated from Hartwick in which I outlined my entrepreneurial plan. The idea was to create something that had value and—this next part is the key part—I wanted the product to be something that was easy to reproduce in unlimited quantities. I didn’t want to sell my time, at least not directly, because that model has an upward limit. And I didn’t want to build my own automobile factory, for example, because cars are not easy to reproduce. I didn’t want to do any sort of custom work such as building homes because each one requires the same amount of work. I wanted to create, invent, write, or otherwise concoct something widely desired that would be easy to reproduce.

我的计划并非通往成功的唯一可行途径。另一个完美的计划可能是成为一名销售员，在经营珍稀艺术品、飞机或办公楼等极其昂贵物品的行业中赚取佣金。进入这样的职位可能需要数年时间，但没有人说过成功会很快或很容易。我没有销售员的基因，所以销售昂贵物品对我来说不是一个好计划。我认为我的竞争优势是创造力。我会一个接一个地尝试，直到某个有创意的东西引起公众的共鸣。然后我会疯狂地复制它。短期内，这意味着一次又一次的失败。从长远来看，我正在创造一种让好运降临到我身上的局面。

My plan wasn’t the one and only practical path to success. Another perfectly good plan might involve becoming a salesperson who works on commission in an industry that handles extraordinarily expensive items such as rare art, airplanes, or office buildings. It might take years to get into one of those positions, but no one said success would be fast or easy. I don’t have the salesperson gene, so selling expensive items wasn’t a good plan for me. I figured my competitive edge was creativity. I would try one thing after another until something creative struck a chord with the public. Then I would reproduce it like crazy. In the near term, that would mean one failure after another. In the long term, I was creating a situation that would allow luck to find me.

至少有一个总体策略和一定程度的专注力会大有帮助。这个世界提供了如此多的选择，你需要一个快速的筛选器来排除一些选项，并关注其他选项。无论你的计划是什么，专注力始终至关重要。

It helps a great deal to have at least a general strategy and some degree of focus. The world offers so many alternatives that you need a quick filter to eliminate some options and pay attention to others. Whatever your plan, focus is always important.

我的系统是创造公众想要的东西，然后大批量生产，这几乎注定了一连串的失败。我所有的努力都注定是遥不可及的。如果我以目标为导向而不是以系统为导向，我想我会在最初的几次失败后就放弃。那感觉就像用头撞墙一样。但以系统为导向，我感觉自己每天都在进步，无论我当时正在做的项目的命运如何。在那些年里，我每天醒来时都会抱着同样的想法，揉揉惺忪的睡眼，关掉闹钟。

My system of creating something the public wants and reproducing it in large quantities nearly guaranteed a string of failures. By design, all my efforts were long-shots. Had I been goal-oriented instead of system-oriented, I imagine I would have given up after the first several failures. It would have felt like banging my head against a brick wall. But being systems-oriented, I felt myself growing more capable every day, no matter the fate of the project I happened to be working on. And every day during those years I woke up with the same thought, literally, as I rubbed the sleep from my eyes and slapped the alarm clock off.

今天就是那一天。

Today’s the day.

第八章

Chapter 8

我的公司生涯失败了

My Corporate Career Fizzled

我1979年春天，我穿着飞往加州时穿的那套廉价西装，走进克罗克国民银行旧金山分行，申请一份出纳员的工作。经理当场就录用了我这个刚从哈特威克大学毕业的毕业生。我需要一份工作，因为我只有几件不合身的衣服、一个塑料闹钟、一块偶尔能走的手表、一个洗漱包，以及父母攒下的2000美元大学毕业礼物。我的计划是从底层做起，一步步爬到顶层。

In the spring of 1979, adorned in the same cheap suit I wore on the flight to California, I walked into a San Francisco branch of Crocker National Bank and asked for a job as a teller. The manager hired me, the fresh Hartwick grad, on the spot. I needed a job right away because all I owned was my ill-fitting clothes, a plastic alarm clock, a watch that worked occasionally, a toiletry bag, and $2,000 that my parents scraped together as a college graduation present. My plan was to start at the bottom and claw my way to the top.

我的经济学学位让我在出纳员这个职位上有些资历过高，但我还是做得很糟糕。我的人际交往能力还不错，但几乎每次值班我都会莫名其妙地把钱放错地方或把数字弄错。我不擅长任何必须一次就做好的事情。我的性格更像是那种先做错再改正的人。

My degree in economics made me somewhat overqualified for the teller job, and yet I still managed to be dreadful at it. My people skills were good enough, but I somehow found a different way to misplace money or transpose numbers nearly every shift. I’m not good at any sort of task that must be done right the first time. I’m more of a do-it-wrong-then-fix-it personality.

我的主管很喜欢我，但我在记录人们的交易记录方面很马虎——那时候，记录交易需要用纸笔记录数字——这让我不适合这份工作。主管警告我，如果我不迅速改进，她将被迫解雇我。我知道我处理细节的能力不太可能提高。我的第一份工作很失败。

My supervisor liked me, but my sloppiness at keeping track of people’s transactions—which in those days involved writing down numbers with a pen and paper—made me unfit for the job. My supervisor warned me that unless I improved quickly, she would be forced to let me go. I knew I wasn’t likely to get better at handling details. I was a failure at my first job.

我觉得辞职有两种可能。要么被炒鱿鱼，要么——乐观一点——升职。我给分行系统的高级副总裁写了一封信，他可能比我高七八层管理层，信中描述了我所有关于改进银行的幼稚建议。我的想法有一个共同点：它们不切实际，原因一个21岁的年轻人还无法理解。信的结尾，我请求参加管理培训项目，获得一个难得的、令人垂涎的职位，快速晋升到高层管理岗位。对于一个在永久工作记录上写着“能力不足，连纸上写数字都写不出来”的人来说，这几乎是不可能的。

I figured I had two ways to leave my job. I could get fired or—and here’s the optimist emerging—I could get promoted. I wrote a letter to the Senior Vice President for the branch system, who was probably seven or eight layers of management above me, and described all my naïve suggestions for improving the bank. My ideas had one thing in common: They were impractical for reasons a twenty-one-year-old wouldn’t yet appreciate. I closed my letter by asking for a rare and coveted spot on the management training program, a fast track to upper management. It was a long shot for a guy who had on his permanent work record some version of “Too incompetent to write numbers on a piece of paper.”

我在信里列举了我的资历，其中还幽默地提到了我在工作期间两次被持枪抢劫的经历，这的确是真的。巧的是，那位高级副总裁身高六尺十寸，红头发，留着络腮胡，是个很有幽默感的精灵。他读了我的信，邀请我去他的办公室面试。

I included in my letter a list of my qualifications that contained a witty reference to getting robbed twice at gunpoint in the course of my work, which was true. As luck would have it, the Senior Vice President was a 6’10” red-headed, bearded elf of a man who had a great sense of humor. He read my letter and invited me to his office for an interview.

高级副总裁告诉我，我提出的改进银行的建议不太令人满意，但他喜欢我的幽默感，因此对我的潜力很有预感。一个月后，我开始了管理培训项目。不知何故，我却在通往更好工作的道路上失败了。

The Senior Vice President told me that my suggestions for improving the bank were underwhelming, but he liked my sense of humor, and because of that had a hunch about my potential. A month later, I started the management training program. Somehow I’d failed my way to a much better job.

我在银行工作的八年里，一个又一个岗位都无法胜任。我做过不同的工作，比如分行实习生、项目经理、电脑程序员、产品经理、贷款专员、预算主管，以及其他一些我记不清的职位。我从未在一个岗位上待过足够长的时间来培养任何真正的能力，而且我也不确定额外的经验是否会对我有所帮助。我唯一有价值的技能似乎就是面试下一份工作。我在银行几乎每一份工作都成功了，而且每次都是升职加薪。我开始觉得，我或许可以通过面试晋升到某个高级管理职位，而没有人会注意到我完全没有技能。这正是我的希望。

In my eight years at the bank, I was incompetent at one job after another. At various times I was a branch banking trainee, a project manager, computer programmer, product manager, lending officer, budget supervisor, and a few other jobs I’ve forgotten. I never stayed in one job long enough to develop any legitimate competence, and I’m not entirely sure additional experience would have helped in my case. It seemed as if my only valuable skill was interviewing for the next job. I got hired for almost every job I pursued in the bank, and each was a promotion and a raise. It was starting to seem as if I might be able to interview my way to some sort of senior executive position in which no one would notice I was totally skill-free. That was my hope.

我的银行生涯就此结束，老板把我叫到办公室，告诉我下令停止提拔白人男性。媒体注意到，公司的高层几乎全是白人男性，公司需要更加努力地实现所谓的“多元化”。没人知道这需要多少年，所以我整理好简历，发给了当地其他几家大公司。我的银行生涯彻底失败了，而且，出乎意料的是，我的无能并非原因。

My banking career ended when my boss called me into her office and informed me that the order had come down to stop promoting white males. The press had noticed that senior management was comprised almost entirely of white males, and the company needed to work harder to achieve something called “diversity.” No one knew how many years that might take, so I put my résumé together and sent it to some of the other big companies in the area. I had officially failed at my banking career and, against all odds, my incompetence wasn’t the cause.

当地电话公司太平洋贝尔（Pacific Bell）很不明智地给了我一份工作，我接受了。由于我的面试技巧，以及我几乎在伯克利完成了MBA学位，并且经常上夜校课程，我又一次获得了大幅加薪。我的简历看起来很棒。但他们没有意识到，简历上的优秀正是我最擅长的技能。

The local phone company, Pacific Bell, unwisely offered me a job, and I accepted. Once again I got a big raise, thanks to my interviewing skills and to the fact that I had nearly completed my MBA at Berkeley, attending classes at night. I looked great on paper. Little did they realize that looking good on paper was my best skill.

离开克罗克几周后，一家收购银行解雇了我留下的部门的所有人。我作为一名银行家的失败让我得以在被解雇前找到了一份新工作。这只是众多例子之一，说明宇宙确保企业界的工作绩效与结果之间没有太大的联系。

A few weeks after leaving my job at Crocker, an acquiring bank fired everyone in the department I left behind. My failure as a banker allowed me to escape to a new job before the firing. This was one of many examples in which the universe makes sure there isn’t much of a link between job performance in the corporate world and outcomes.

太平洋贝尔公司把我安排在了他们所谓的“快速晋升通道”上，他们称之为“活页夹”。高层管理人员把那些有前途的人选打印出来，放在三孔活页夹里，这样他们就可以指导我们，而且据我推测，他们也是为了规避风险，以防万一我们中有人在管理阶梯上超过他们。对一个五年后可能成为你老板的人出言不逊可不是个好主意。

Pacific Bell put me on their version of the fast-track, which they referred to as being “in the binder.” Higher levels of management kept printed lists of the up-and-comers in three-ring binders so they could mentor us and, one presumes, so they could hedge their bets in case one of us passed them on the management ladder. It’s a bad idea to be a jerk to someone who might be your boss in five years.

我在太平洋贝尔公司工作大约60%的时间都用来装作很忙的样子。我负责预算，但实际工作对我来说也没什么挑战性。我的预算表格里大部分都有公式错误，但这无关紧要，因为各个部门的输入全是谎言和胡扯。如果说有什么区别的话，我的错误或许能抹平一些胡扯，让它更接近真相。这真是荒谬至极。

About 60 percent of my job at Pacific Bell involved trying to look busy. I was in charge of budgeting, and the actual work was far from challenging, even for me. Most of my budget spreadsheets had formula errors, but that didn’t matter because all the inputs from the various departments were complete lies and bullshit. If anything, my errors probably smoothed out some of the bullshit and brought it closer to truth. It was a truly absurd existence.

我最大的抱怨是，那时候办公室里允许吸烟，而我隔壁的隔间里就坐着一个老烟枪。我整天都坐在她身上的烟味里。我试着劝她别抽烟，但她却变成了一个不友好的吸烟者，这丝毫没有改善我的处境。我请求老板把我的隔间挪一挪，但吸烟的人太多了，新隔间里的烟味也一样浓重。

My biggest complaint was that smoking was allowed in offices in those days, and a chain smoker was in the cubicle next to me. I sat in a cloud of her tobacco stench all day. I tried asking her not to smoke, but all that did was turn her into an unfriendly smoker, and that wasn’t an upgrade. I asked my boss to relocate my cubicle, but there were so many smokers that the new location had just as much of a tobacco fog.

幸运的是，公司有一个完善的工作场所安全计划。有一天，他们分发了一份文件，列出了常见的工作场所危害，并要求我们签字。其中一项危害就是二手烟。公司鼓励员工积极主动地做好安全工作，所以我就照做了。我声明我的工作场所存在安全隐患，并告知老板我需要待在家里，直到问题得到解决。但我觉得他并没有认真对待我的话。

As luck would have it, the company had a robust workplace safety program, and one day they passed around a document listing common workplace hazards and asked us to sign it. One of the listed hazards was secondhand smoke. The company encouraged employees to be proactive about safety, so I did just that. I declared my workplace a safety hazard and informed my boss that I would need to stay home until it was remediated. I don’t think he took me seriously.

第二天，我待在家里，打电话询问隐患是否已经消除。老板说没有，于是我兴高采烈地感谢他更新信息，并表示我会继续关注。我很高兴能为提高工作场所的安全性尽一份力。由于互联网还处于萌芽阶段，远程办公还不现实，所以我甚至不需要在家办公。到目前为止，我有一天带薪休假，除了呼吸新鲜空气之外什么也没有。我的计划正在奏效。

The next day I stayed home and called in to see if the hazard had been eliminated. My boss said it had not, so I cheerily thanked him for the update and said I would keep checking back. I was happy to do my part to make the workplace safer. Telecommuting wasn’t yet practical because the Internet was still a zygote, so I didn’t even need to work from home. So far, I had a paid day off and nothing but fresh air to breathe. My plan was working.

第二天，我老板的老板打电话问我出了什么问题。我解释了情况，他听了。他是一名受过专业训练的工程师，在我的推理中找不到任何漏洞。我完全按照公司政策的要求执行。他不吸烟，所以我想他明白我的意思。我感谢他的倾听，并说我会定期检查工作场所是否安全，我可以回去。我表现得非常专业，也非常乐观，部分原因是我觉得这样更有趣。

By day two, my boss’s boss called and asked what the problem was. I explained the situation, and he listened. He was an engineer by training and couldn’t find a flaw in my reasoning. I was applying the company policy exactly as it was intended. He wasn’t a smoker, so I think he saw the point. I thanked him for listening and said I would check back periodically to see if the workplace was safe for me to return. I was professional and upbeat about it in part because I thought it was funnier that way.

我以为会被解雇。我还以为事后会给当地报纸打电话，看看他们是否想看个有趣的报道。这是我第一次意识到争议对我有多么的吸引力。

I expected to get fired. And I expected to call the local newspaper afterwards and see if they wanted an interesting story. This was the first time I realized how attracted I am to controversy.

我记得，到了第三天，我老板的老板打电话说，他和上级讨论了这个问题，他们同意除了自己的私人办公室外，其他所有地方都禁烟。他们还同意，吸烟时要关门。我回到工作岗位，很高兴地发现我的小隔间里相对来说没有烟味了，而且，更棒的是，高层管理人员的吸烟者也关上了门，把他们的办公室变成了超级有效的致癌热箱。很难想象还有比这更好的结果了。

By day three, if I recall, my boss’s boss called to say he discussed the issue with a few levels of management above and they agreed to make everything but their own private offices smoke-free. And they agreed to close their doors when they smoked. I returned to work, happy in the knowledge that my cubicle was relatively smoke free and, as a bonus, the smokers in senior management were closing their doors and turning their offices into extra-effective carcinogenic hot-boxes. It’s hard to imagine a better result.

我以为我在太平洋贝尔的职业生涯进展顺利。我在伯克利的夜校完成了MBA课程，晋升幅度可能比“活页夹”里的几个人都要高。有一天，一个地区经理的职位空缺，我觉得自己是竞争者之一，或者至少我是这么认为的。我老板的老板的老板把我叫到办公室，解释说公司下令停止提拔白人男性。太平洋贝尔存在多样性问题，即使能解决，也可能需要数年时间。我争取太平洋贝尔高层管理职位的尝试正式宣告失败。

I thought my career at Pacific Bell was going well. I finished my MBA classes at Berkeley’s evening program and probably moved ahead of a few people in “the binder.” One day a District Manager position opened, and I was a contender, or so I thought. My boss’s boss’s boss called me into his office and explained that the order had come down to stop promoting white males. Pacific Bell had a diversity problem, and it might take years to fix it, if ever. My bid for upper management at Pacific Bell was officially a failure.

好的一面是，我不再觉得需要为雇主付出最大的努力，甚至不需要长时间工作却没有额外的报酬。这是一种不想要的自由，但终究是自由。我花了一些时间练习我的网球技艺，并开始认真思考新的方向，理想情况下，一个不需要老板指导的方向。

On the plus side, I no longer felt the need to give my employer my best efforts or even to work long hours for no extra pay. It was an unwanted freedom but freedom nonetheless. I took some time to work on my tennis game, and I started thinking seriously about a new direction, ideally one that didn’t require me to have a boss.

我决定重拾久违的热情，尝试画漫画。但考虑到我完全缺乏艺术天赋，而且漫画行业成功案例寥寥无几，这几乎成了一个遥不可及的梦想。于是，我决定尝试一下“肯定句”（我将在本书后面更详细地描述）。我买了一些美术用品，每天早上上班前练习绘画，每天写下十五遍“肯定句”：“我，斯科特·亚当斯，将成为一名著名的漫画家。”

I decided to revive a long-lost passion and try my hand at cartooning. But it was an unlikely dream given my complete lack of artistic talent and the rarity of success stories in that business. So I decided to try affirmations, which I will describe in more detail later in the book. I bought some art supplies, practiced drawing every morning before work, and wrote my affirmation fifteen times a day: “I, Scott Adams, will be a famous cartoonist.”

第九章

Chapter 9

决定还是想要

Deciding Versus Wanting

哦我听过的最好的建议之一是这样的：如果你想成功，那就先想清楚代价，然后付出代价。这听起来微不足道，显而易见，但如果你深入思考，就会发现它蕴含着非凡的力量。

One of the best pieces of advice I’ve ever heard goes something like this: If you want success, figure out the price and then pay it. It sounds trivial and obvious, but if you unpack the idea, it has extraordinary power.

我认识很多人，他们渴望自己富有、出名，或者拥有其他什么了不起的成就。他们渴望拥有游艇、仆人和城堡，渴望驾驶私人飞机环游世界。但这些都只是愿望而已。这些满怀希望的人中，很少有人真正下定决心去实现他们所渴望的一切。这是一个关键的区别，因为一旦你下定决心，就会采取行动。愿望始于内心，并且通常会停留在那里。

I know a lot of people who wish they were rich or famous or otherwise fabulous. They wish they had yachts and servants and castles, and they wish they could travel the world in their own private jets. But these are mere wishes. Few of these wishful people have decided to have any of the things they wish for. It’s a key difference, for once you decide, you take action. Wishing starts in the mind and generally stays there.

当你决定取得巨大成功时，你承认代价，并愿意为此付出。这些代价可能意味着为了在学校取得好成绩而牺牲个人生活，可能意味着选择极其枯燥却利润丰厚的大学专业，可能意味着推迟生育，可能意味着失去与家人相处的时间，也可能意味着承担商业风险，最终导致自己陷入尴尬、离婚或破产的境地。成功人士并非渴望成功，而是决定追求成功。为了有效地追求成功，他们需要一个体系。成功总是有代价的，但事实上，代价是可以协商的。如果你选择了正确的体系，最终的代价将更接近你愿意付出的代价。

When you decide to be successful in a big way, you acknowledge the price, and you’re willing to pay it. That price might mean sacrificing your personal life to get good grades in school, pursuing a college major that is deadly boring but lucrative, putting off having kids, missing time with your family, or taking business risks that put you in jeopardy for embarrassment, divorce, or bankruptcy. Successful people don’t wish for success; they decide to pursue it. And to pursue it effectively, they need a system. Success always has a price, but the reality is that the price is negotiable. If you pick the right system, the price will be a lot nearer what you’re willing to pay.

我无法改变成功需要付出大量努力的事实。但如果你学会欣赏系统的力量而非目标，或许就能降低成功的代价，让成功值得一试。

I can’t change the fact that success requires a lot of work. But if you learn to appreciate the power of systems over goals, you might lower the price of success just enough to make it worth a go.

第十章

Chapter 10

自私的错觉

The Selfishness Illusion

D在你通往成功的道路上，你会发现自己不断地试图平衡自身需求和他人需求。你总是会怀疑自己是太自私还是不够自私。我很高兴能在这里帮助你理清这一切。

During your journey to success, you will find yourself continually trying to balance your own needs with the needs of others. You will always wonder if you are being too selfish or not selfish enough. I’m glad I could be here to help you sort it all out.

首先，说到慷慨这个话题，世界上有三种人：

For starters, when it comes to the topic of generosity, there are three kinds of people in the world:

  1. 自私
  2. Selfish
  3. 愚蠢的
  4. Stupid
  5. 给他人带来负担
  6. Burden on others

这就是全部清单。你最好的选择是自私，因为愚蠢或成为社会的负担对任何人都没有好处。社会希望你能以优雅和同情的态度对待你的自私。如果你正确地自私，你自然会成为社会的净收益。成功人士通常不会给世界带来负担。企业掠夺者、薪酬过高的CEO和暴虐的独裁者是例外。大多数成功人士通过纳税、慈善工作、创造就业机会等形式给予的财富超过了他们个人消费的财富。我估计，我个人将消费掉我职业生涯中创造的总财富的10%左右。其余的则用于纳税、子孙后代、初创企业投资、慈善事业和刺激经济。

That’s the entire list. Your best option is to be selfish because being stupid or a burden on society won’t help anyone. Society hopes you will handle your selfishness with some grace and compassion. If you do selfishness right, you automatically become a net benefit to society. Successful people generally don’t burden the world. Corporate raiders, overpaid CEOs, and tyrannical dictators are the exceptions. Most successful people give more than they personally consume in the form of taxes, charity work, job creation, and so on. My best estimate is that I will personally consume about 10 percent of the total wealth I create over my career. The rest goes to taxes, future generations, startup investments, charity, and stimulation of the economy.

作为未来或现在的富人，你可能会因为自私地追求收入而缴纳远超应有份额的税款。自私的成功人士不会给关心他们的人带来担忧和压力。作为一个自私的成功人士，你可以成为他人的榜样。如果自私的成功人士积攒了所有所需，并且毫无怨言，他们可能会成为有趣的伙伴。

As a future or current rich person, you might pay far more than your share of taxes because of your selfish pursuit of income. Selfish successful people don’t cause worry and stress for those who care about them. As a selfish successful person, you can be a role model for others. Selfish successful people can be fun company if they’ve squirreled away all they need and have no complaints to voice.

我所说的自私，不是指那种为了不让同事得到最后一个甜甜圈而抢走它的自私。那不是开明的自私，因为这种小气事以后可能会给你带来麻烦。而且，如果你感到内疚或被抓住，你可能会损失一些精力。

By selfishness, I don’t mean the kind where you grab the last donut so your coworker doesn’t get it. That wouldn’t be enlightened selfishness because that sort of pettiness can bite you in the ass later. And it might rob you of some energy if you feel guilty about it or get caught.

最重要的自私形式是投入时间健身、合理饮食、追求事业，同时还要与家人朋友共度美好时光。如果你忽视自己的健康或事业，你就会滑向第二种境界——愚蠢——这很快就会成为社会的负担。

The most important form of selfishness involves investing time on your fitness, eating right, pursuing your career, and still spending quality time with your family and friends. If you neglect your health or your career, you slip into the second category—stupid—which is a short slide to becoming a burden on society.

我认为，西方世界成年人健康状况的糟糕是社会造成的。我们从小就被灌输这样的观念：奉献是高尚而美好的。如果你有宗教信仰，你可能会面临双倍的压力，要求自己变得无私。我们一生都被告知，施比受更有福。社会、父母，甚至某种程度上，基因都塑造了我们无私的行为。问题在于，我们对慷慨的痴迷导致人们目光短浅。我们为了多花一个小时帮忙做家务而放弃锻炼。我们为了节省时间去帮助同事解决问题而买快餐。我们无时无刻不在欺骗自己的未来，让自己今天显得慷慨大方。

I blame society for the sad state of adult fitness in the Western world. We’re raised to believe that giving of ourselves is noble and good. If you’re religious, you might have twice as much pressure to be unselfish. All our lives, we are told it’s better to give than to receive. We’re programmed for unselfish behavior by society, our parents, and even our genes to some extent. The problem is that our obsession with generosity causes people to think short term. We skip exercise to spend an extra hour helping at home. We buy fast food to save time to help a coworker with a problem. At every turn, we cheat our own future to appear generous today.

那么，你该如何为自己做出正确的长期选择，从而在长远上造福他人，同时又不让自己在日常选择中显得自私呢？这个问题没有立竿见影的良方，但朝着正确方向迈出的一步需要运用“允许”的力量。我允许你先照顾好自己，这样你才能在长远上更好地展现慷慨。

So how can you make the right long-term choices for yourself, thus being a benefit to others in the long run and without looking like a selfish turd in your daily choices? There’s no instant cure, but a step in the right direction involves the power of permission. I’m giving you permission to take care of yourself first so you can do a better job of being generous in the long run.

什么？

What?

你可能会好奇，漫画家允许自私能有什么用处。答案出乎意料，在我看来，确实如此。如果你读到这里，你就会明白我们之间存在着某种关系。这是一种作者与读者的关系，但这已经足够好了。我们人类天生就很容易受到与我们有关系的人的影响，无论这种关系是什么。有时我们把这种影响称为“同侪压力”。有时它被称为榜样或模仿。有时它被称为通过实例学习。大多数时候，这只是我们下意识地、不假思索地做的事情。

You might be wondering how a cartoonist’s permission to be selfish can help in any way. The surprising answer is that it can, in my opinion. If you’ve read this far, we have a relationship of sorts. It’s an author-reader relationship, but that’s good enough. We humans are wired to be easily influenced by the people who are in relationships with us, no matter what those relationships are. Sometimes we call that influence “peer pressure.” Sometimes it’s called modeling or imitating. Sometimes it’s learning by example. And most of the time it’s just something we do automatically, without thinking.

幸运的是，我们大多数人都有过滤器，可以防止自己受到那些最明显有害的影响。如果我鼓励你买一支带高倍瞄准镜的步枪，然后在舰桥上等待进一步的指示，你可能不会这么做。当被影响的人对建议的改变没有异议时，影响才能发挥最大的作用。通常，一个人只需要某种形式的许可就能发起改变，而许可的形式或是否合理并不总是那么重要。我相信你已经渴望健康、成功和快乐。你已经渴望放弃一些家务或工作来照顾自己的需求。我只是你的漫画家朋友，告诉你，慷慨的人会首先照顾好自己的需求。事实上，这样做是一种道德上的需要。世界需要你最好的一面。

Luckily, most of us have filters that prevent us from being influenced in the most obviously damaging ways. If I were to encourage you to buy a rifle with a high-powered scope and wait on a bridge for further instructions, you probably wouldn’t do that. Influence works best when the person being influenced has no objection to the suggested change. Often all one needs is some form of permission to initiate a change, and it doesn’t always matter what form the permission is in or if it even makes sense. I’m sure you already want to be fit and successful and happy. You already want to skip some of your chores at home or at work to take care of your own needs. I’m simply your cartoonist friend telling you that generous people take care of their own needs first. In fact, doing so is a moral necessity. The world needs you at your best.

我应该在这里停下来，为那些更注重字面意思的读者解释一下，自私并不意味着你应该让一辆失控的婴儿车滚进车流中，如果你认为拦下它会让你上班迟到十秒钟。人类在情感和社会层面上彼此紧密相连，以至于我们能为自己做的最好的事情往往就是帮助他人。我相信你们能够意识到这些情况。自私并不意味着成为一个反社会人格者。它只是意味着你要从长远角度看待事物。

I should pause here for my more literal readers and explain that being selfish doesn’t mean you should let a runaway baby carriage roll into traffic if you think stopping it will make you ten seconds late for work. Humans are so emotionally and societally connected with each other that often the best thing we can do for ourselves is to help others. I’ll trust you to recognize those situations. Being selfish doesn’t mean being a sociopath. It just means you take the long view of things.

当我开始赚得比花的钱还多时，最让我惊喜的事情之一就是，我的优先事项自动发生了改变。我可以买得起任何我想要的车，但突然间，除了实用性之外，我对这些物品的关注度就没那么高了。一旦我所有的个人需求都得到满足，我的思绪自然而然地转向了如何让世界变得更美好。我没有计划过这种转变。这不是我思考后决定要做的事情。它自然而然地发生了。显然，人类天生就优先考虑自己的需求，然后是家庭、部落、国家，最后是世界，大致如此。

One of the more interesting surprises for me when I started making more money than I would ever spend is that it automatically changed my priorities. I could afford any car I wanted, but suddenly I didn’t care so much about my possessions beyond the utility they provided. Once all my personal needs were met, my thoughts automatically turned to how I could make the world a better place. I didn’t plan the transformation. It wasn’t something I thought about and decided to do. It just happened on its own. Apparently, humans are wired to take care of their own needs first, then family, tribe, country, and the world, roughly in that order.

我敢肯定，有很多自私的家伙赚了几十亿美元，却把钱都花在直升机和豪宅上，从不考虑别人的福祉。我工作中遇到过很多超级成功人士，尤其是在旧金山湾区，我的观察是，很少见到自私的成功人士。我猜想，有些甚至大多数成功人士一开始都是自私的，但成功会改变你。布拉德·皮特在卡特里娜飓风灾后帮助重建家园，比尔·盖茨是有史以来最重要的慈善家之一，这并非巧合。成功就是这样的。

I’m sure there are plenty of selfish turds who make billions and spend it all on helicopters and mansions with never a thought given to the wellbeing of others. I meet a lot of super-successful people in my line of work, especially living in the San Francisco Bay Area, and my observation is that it’s rare to find a selfish successful person. I assume some or even most successful people started out selfishly, but success changes you. It’s not a coincidence that Brad Pitt helped rebuild homes after the Hurricane Katrina disaster or that Bill Gates is one of the most important philanthropists of all time. Success does that.

看待自私最健康的方式是，它是你挣扎时的一种必要策略。在困境中，甚至在尚未成功之前，社会，甚至至少有一位漫画家，都希望你先照顾好自己。如果你追求自私的目标，并且做得好，总有一天你的注意力会转向外部世界。这是一种非凡的感觉。我希望你也能体会到。

The healthiest way to look at selfishness is that it’s a necessary strategy when you’re struggling. In hard times or even pre-success times, society and at least one cartoonist want you to take care of yourself first. If you pursue your selfish objectives and do that well, someday your focus will turn outward. It’s an extraordinary feeling. I hope you can experience it.

第十一章

Chapter 11

能量指标

The Energy Metric

西人类渴望很多东西：健康的身体、财务自由、成就感、美好的社交生活、爱情、性、娱乐、旅行、家庭、事业等等。所有这些渴望的问题在于，你花在追求其中一个愿望上的时间，就无法用来追求其他愿望了。那么，你该如何合理安排有限的时间，才能获得最佳结果呢？

We humans want many things: good health, financial freedom, accomplishment, a great social life, love, sex, recreation, travel, family, career, and more. The problem with all this wanting is that the time you spend chasing one of those desires is time you can’t spend chasing any of the others. So how do you organize your limited supply of time to get the best result?

我处理多重优先事项的方法是专注于一个主要指标：我的精力。我会做出最大化个人精力的选择，因为这样更容易管理所有其他优先事项。

The way I approach the problem of multiple priorities is by focusing on just one main metric: my energy. I make choices that maximize my personal energy because that makes it easier to manage all the other priorities.

最大化我的个人能量意味着合理饮食、锻炼身体、避免不必要的压力、充足的睡眠，以及采取所有其他显而易见的措施。这也意味着我的生活中有一些让我醒来时感到兴奋的事情。当我拥有良好的个人能量时，我的工作质量会更高，我也能更快地完成工作。这能让我的事业步入正轨。当所有这些都发挥作用，我感到放松和精力充沛时，我的个人生活也会变得更好。

Maximizing my personal energy means eating right, exercising, avoiding unnecessary stress, getting enough sleep, and taking all other obvious steps. It also means having something in my life that makes me excited to wake up. When I get my personal energy right, the quality of my work is better, and I can complete it faster. That keeps my career on track. And when all of that is working, and I feel relaxed and energetic, my personal life is better, too.

你可能熟悉一档名为《狗语者》的电视节目。在节目中，训狗专家 Cesar Millan 帮助人们控制住看似疯狂的狗狗。Cesar 的主要技巧是训练人类控制自己的情绪状态，因为狗能从主人身上感受到疯狂的气息。当主人学会控制自己时，狗也会平静下来。我认为这种方法也适用于人与人之间的互动。你已经亲眼看到，当一个悲伤的人进入房间时，房间里的气氛就会低落。而当你和一个充满活力的开朗的人交谈时，你会不由自主地感到精神振奋。我建议，通过成为一个充满活力的人，你可以激励周围的人。这种积极的改变将改善你的社交生活、爱情生活、家庭生活和事业。

You might be familiar with a television show that was called The Dog Whisperer. On the show, Cesar Millan, a dog training expert, helped people get their seemingly insane dogs under control. Cesar’s main trick involves training the humans to control their own emotional states because dogs can pick up crazy vibes from the owners. When the owners learn to control themselves, the dogs calm down, too. I think this same method applies to humans interacting with other humans. You’ve seen for yourself that when a sad person enters a room, the mood in the room drops. And when you talk to a cheerful person who is full of energy, you automatically feel a boost. I’m suggesting that by becoming a person with good energy, you lift the people around you. That positive change will improve your social life, your love life, your family life, and your career.

当我谈到提升你的个人能量时，我指的不是那种狂热的、靠咖啡因驱动的、兴奋得快要爆炸的能量。我指的是平静、专注的能量。在别人看来，你只是看起来心情很好而已。而你确实会这样。

When I talk about increasing your personal energy, I don’t mean the frenetic, caffeine-fueled, bounce-off-the-walls type of energy. I’m talking about a calm, focused energy. To others, it will simply appear that you are in a good mood. And you will be.

在成为漫画家之前，我曾在公司做过一些糟糕的工作。但我仍然热爱工作，一部分原因是我几乎每天晚上都会锻炼，醒来后通常感觉很好——另一部分原因是我总有一两个可以让我自由发挥的副业项目。漫画只是我在公司工作期间尝试过的十几个创业想法之一。多年来，能够开创“自己的事业”并告别办公室的束缚，这一念头给了我巨大的能量。

Before I became a cartoonist, I worked in a number of awful corporate jobs. But I still enjoyed going to work partly because I exercised most evenings and usually woke up feeling good—and partly because I always had one or two side projects going on that had the potential to set me free. Cartooning was just one of a dozen entrepreneurial ideas I tried out during my corporate days. For years, the prospect of starting “my own thing” and leaving my cubicle behind gave me an enormous amount of energy.

这本书是另一个让我精力充沛的例子。我喜欢想象有人可能会读到这本汇集的想法，并从中得到一些有益的思考。这种可能性对我来说是极大的激励。所以，虽然写作会让我暂时远离朋友和家人，但和他们在一起时，我会变得更好。我更快乐，对生活也更满意。能量指标让我更容易做出选择。

This book is another example of something that gets my energy up. I like to think that someone might read this collection of ideas and find a few thoughts that help. That possibility is tremendously motivating for me. So while writing takes me away from my friends and family for a bit, it makes me a better person when I’m with them. I’m happier and more satisfied with my life. The energy metric helps make my choices easier.

能量这个词很简单，却能概括出一系列令人眼花缭乱的复杂事件。为了方便我们理解，我将你的个人能量定义为任何能给你带来积极提升的东西，无论是精神上还是身体上。就像艺术一样，你一看到它就能感受到。举个例子会有所帮助。

Energy is a simple word that captures a mind-boggling array of complicated happenings. For our purposes, I’ll define your personal energy as anything that gives you a positive lift, either mentally or physically. Like art, you know it when you see it. Examples will help.

对我来说，购物简直就是能量杀手。一走进熙熙攘攘的商店，我就感觉身体的能量正在流失。疲惫一开始只是精神上的，但几分钟后，我就感觉身体仿佛跑完了一场马拉松。购物真的太累了。

For me, shopping is an energy killer. The moment I walk into a busy store, I feel the energy drain from my body. The exhaustion starts as a mental thing, but within minutes I feel as if my body has been through a marathon. Shopping is simply exhausting for me.

你的情况可能有所不同。对有些人来说，购物是一种快感，它能提升能量。所以用我的例子来说，像我这样的人应该尽量减少购物（我的确这么做了），而那些从购物中获得快感的人应该尽情享受，只要它不会影响你生活中其他的优先事项。

Your situation might be different. For some people, shopping is a high. It boosts energy. So using my example, a person like me should seek to minimize shopping (and I do) while a person who gets a buzz from it should indulge, so long as it doesn’t take too much away from other priorities in life.

管理个人能量就像管理公司预算一样。在商业领域，一个部门的每一个财务决策都与其他部门息息相关。如果研发部门今天削减开支，最终会波及整个组织，并在未来某一年减少利润。同样，管理个人能量时，仅仅在短期或特定领域最大化它是不够的。理想情况下，你应该从长远和全局的角度来管理个人能量。午夜多喝一杯鸡尾酒或许能让你当时精力充沛，但第二天你付出的代价却是双倍的。

Managing your personal energy is like managing budgets in a company. In business, every financial decision in one department is connected to others. If the research and development group cuts spending today, eventually that will ripple through the organization and reduce profits in some future year. Similarly, when you manage your personal energy, it’s not enough to maximize it in the short run or in one defined area. Ideally, you want to manage your personal energy for the long term and the big picture. Having one more cocktail at midnight might be an energy boost at the time, but you pay for it double the next day.

读到这儿，请允许我停下来，承认你对我“围绕个人能量概念来组织生活有用”这一观点的怀疑是完全合理的。我赞赏你这种合理的怀疑态度。但我恳请你先不要评判个人能量作为一种组织原则的实用性，等你看到它是如何融入到接下来的章节中去的。

At this point in the book, allow me pause to acknowledge your entirely appropriate skepticism about my notion that organizing your life around the concept of personal energy is useful. I applaud your healthy skepticism. But I’ll ask you to hold off on judging the usefulness of personal energy as an organizing principle until you see how it’s woven into the following chapters.

打个比方，想象一下向一个从未听说过资本主义的人解释资本主义的概念。你会遭到强烈的怀疑和合理的质疑：

By analogy, imagine explaining the idea of capitalism to someone who had never heard of it. You’d be greeted with severe skepticism and legitimate questions:

这难道不会导致你现在削减开支并减少投资吗？

Wouldn’t it cause you to cut expenses now and underinvest?

这难道不会让你对你的员工变得很无礼吗？

Wouldn’t it cause you to become sort of a jerk to your employees?

这难道不会导致你尽一切可能欺骗你的客户吗？

Wouldn’t it cause you to cheat your customers whenever you can?

所有这些担忧的诚实答案是肯定的，它们完全合理。资本主义在各个层面都腐朽不堪，但随着时间的推移，它最终会形成对社会极其有益的东西。资本主义的悖论在于，将一堆听起来糟糕的想法叠加在一起，却创造出了令人难以置信的、利大于弊的东西。资本主义激励人们努力工作，承担合理的风险，并为客户创造价值。总的来说，资本主义将自私引导到有利于文明的方向，这还不包括那些一时想出如何操纵体系的富豪们。

The honest answer to all those concerns is yes, they are entirely valid. Capitalism is rotten at every level, and yet it sums up to something extraordinarily useful for society over time. The paradox of capitalism is that adding a bunch of bad-sounding ideas together creates something incredible that is far more good than bad. Capitalism inspires people to work hard, to take reasonable risks, and to create value for customers. On the whole, capitalism channels selfishness in a direction that benefits civilization, not counting a few fat cats who have figured out how to game the system for a short while.

你的个人能量也存在同样的悖论。如果你审视任何能提升你个人能量的行为，它看起来都像是自私。你这个自私的混蛋，为什么明明应该去流浪者收容所工作，却要去滑雪？！

You have the same paradox with personal energy. If you look at any individual action that boosts your personal energy, it might look like selfishness. Why are you going skiing when you should be working at the homeless shelter, you selfish bastard?!

我的建议是，组织好你的生活以优化你的个人能量将会带来令人难以置信的好处，而不是坏处。

My proposition is that organizing your life to optimize your personal energy will sum up to something incredible that is more good than bad.

在我写下这段文字的时候，我的家人和几个好朋友都在纳闷，我为什么这么自私地落后，不和他们一起晒一下午太阳。我很快就会到的。到时候，我会感到精力充沛、心满意足，而且和他们在一起会更开心。从长远来看，没有人会因为我迟到了三十分钟而对我产生不好的印象，毕竟他们已经开始了一整天的玩乐。但每个人都会感激我到场时心情更好。这就是代价。就像资本主义一样，某些形式的自私也得到了开明的体现。

As I write this paragraph, my family and a few good friends are wondering why I’m selfishly lagging behind and not meeting them for an afternoon of sitting in the sun. I’ll get there soon. And when I do, I’ll feel energized, satisfied, and far more fun to be around. No one will think worse of me in the long run for being thirty minutes behind for a full day of fun that they have already started. But everyone will appreciate that I’m in a better mood when I show up. That’s the tradeoff. Like capitalism, some forms of selfishness are enlightened.

心理状态与活动匹配

Matching Mental State to Activity

最大化生产力最重要的技巧之一是让你的精神状态与任务相匹配。例如，我刚醒来的时候，大脑很放松，创造力旺盛。写漫画的想法很有趣，而且相对容易，因为我的大脑正处于最适合这项任务的状态。经验告诉我，在下午三四点的时候试图发挥创造力是浪费时间。到了下午2点，我所能做的就是把在其他地方看到的想法重新消化一遍。早上6点，我是一个创作者，而到了下午2点，我变成了一个抄写员。

One of the most important tricks for maximizing your productivity involves matching your mental state to the task. For example, when I first wake up, my brain is relaxed and creative. The thought of writing a comic is fun, and it’s relatively easy because my brain is in exactly the right mode for that task. I know from experience that trying to be creative in the midafternoon is a waste of time. By 2:00 PM, all I can do is regurgitate the ideas I’ve seen elsewhere. At 6:00 AM, I’m a creator, and by 2:00 PM I’m a copier.

每个人都不一样，但你会发现大多数作家都在清晨或午夜后工作。那是创作灵感最容易涌现的时候。

Everyone is different, but you’ll discover that most writers work either early in the morning or past midnight. That’s when the creative writing juices flow most easily.

午餐时间到了，我喜欢吃点快餐，然后去健身房或打网球。在那个时候，我精力充沛，所以锻炼似乎是个好主意。我知道，如果等到晚饭后，我的体力就不够了，无法说服自己锻炼。我二十多岁的时候，半夜锻炼都没问题，所以请记住，你可能需要随着时间的推移调整你的日常习惯。

When lunchtime rolls around, I like to grab a quick snack and go to the gym or play tennis. At that time of day, I have plenty of energy, so exercise seems like a good idea. I know that if I wait until after dinner I won’t have the sort of physical energy I need to talk myself into exercising. In my twenties, I could exercise at midnight with no problem, so keep in mind that you might want to make adjustments to your daily patterns over time.

我的漫画创作过程分为两个阶段，以最大限度地利用我的自然能量循环。傍晚和傍晚时分，我的手比较稳定。运动过后，我放松下来，准备做一些简单、无需动脑的机械任务，比如为《呆伯特》画最终稿或者在线支付账单。这真是天作之合——我较低的能量水平与无需动脑的任务完美契合。如果没有运动，我就没有足够的注意力来处理无聊的任务。我会在各种事情之间来回奔波，最终一事无成。

My comic-creating process is divided into two stages to maximize my natural energy cycles. In the late afternoon and early evening, my hand is steady. I’m relaxed from exercising and ready to do some simple, mindless, mechanical tasks such as drawing the final art for Dilbert or paying bills online. It’s the perfect match—my lower energy level to a mindless task. Without the exercise, I wouldn’t have the attention span to handle boring tasks. I would be bouncing around from one thing to another and accomplishing nothing.

大多数人没有那么幸运，能拥有灵活的时间安排。我在职场生涯的前16年里也没有。所以我退而求其次，早睡早起，凌晨4点起床，开始我的创意副业。其中一个项目就是《呆伯特》的草图。

Most people aren’t lucky enough to have a flexible schedule. I didn’t have one either for the first sixteen years of my corporate life. So I did the next best thing by going to bed early and getting up at 4:00 AM to do my creative side-projects. One of those projects became the sketches for Dilbert.

你可能不觉得自己是个早起的人。我也不这么认为。但一旦你习惯了，你可能就再也不想回去了。你在别人醒来时完成的工作，比大多数人一整天完成的还要多。

You might not think you’re an early morning person. I didn’t think I was either. But once you get used to it, you might never want to go back. You can accomplish more by the time other people wake up than most people accomplish all day.

简化器与优化器

Simplifiers Versus Optimizers

有些人是我所说的简化者，有些人则是优化者。简化者倾向于用简单的方法完成任务，同时知道付出一些额外的努力可能会带来更好的结果。而优化者则寻求最佳解决方案，即使这意味着额外的复杂性会增加出现意外问题的几率。请允许我比较一下这两种方法。

Some people are what I call simplifiers, and some are optimizers. A simplifier will prefer the easy way to accomplish a task while knowing that some amount of extra effort might have produced a better outcome. An optimizer looks for the very best solution even if it means that the extra complexity increases the odds of unexpected problems. Allow me to compare and contrast the two approaches.

我的妻子雪莉是一位世界级的“优化大师”。而我，则像猴子啃椰子一样，执着于简单。在我撰写本章之际，我们今晚计划在离家三十分钟路程的地方吃一顿简单的晚餐，然后去餐厅附近看场电影。我们会中途停下来接一些住在最短路径上的朋友。到了餐厅，我们甚至不用挪车。停车很方便，避开所有交通高峰，时间安排也恰到好处，让我们可以度过一个无忧无虑的悠闲夜晚。我，一个简化者，制定了这些计划。

My wife, Shelly, is a world-class optimizer. I, on the other hand, cling to simplicity like a monkey on a coconut. As I write this chapter, we have plans tonight for a simple dinner thirty minutes from home followed by a movie that is near the restaurant. We’ll stop to pick up friends who conveniently live on the shortest path to our destination. Once we get to the restaurant, we don’t even need to move the car. Parking will be easy, the drive will avoid all rush hour traffic, and the timing allows for a leisurely evening with no worries. I, the simplifier, made these plans.

大约一个小时后，家里的优化师就会结束她正在优化的工作回家，并可能对我的计划做出一些调整。如果这些调整有效，我们的夜晚会比我想象的还要好，甚至可能更高效。这太棒了！但这些调整也会带来新的变数。这种平衡对雪莉来说很有效，因为她意志坚强。而我则更像是一只闯入怪物卡车拉力赛的松鼠，缺乏进行优化的体质。

In about an hour, the optimizer in the family will return home from whatever she is optimizing and potentially introduce several changes to my plan. If the changes work, our evening will be even better than I imagined or perhaps more productive. That’s great! But the changes will also introduce new opportunities for things to go wrong. This balance works well for Shelly because she has nerves of steel. I’m more like a squirrel that wandered into a Monster Truck rally. I don’t have the constitution to optimize.

今晚，雪莉可能会在我们出发前完成几项紧急任务，这可能会让我们晚点出发，但也不会太晚。这没什么大不了的。然后，雪莉可能会建议我们开她的车，因为她的车没油了，这样我们可以在路上加点油。她早上需要加油，到时候时间不多了。但在我们出门前，雪莉可能会拿出一个购物袋，里面装着一件需要退回商店的商品，而那件商品“正在路上”。收据也可能放错了地方，这意味着店里可能需要一些讨价还价。所有这些都会让我们比预订的晚餐时间晚十五分钟，而且还有可能失去餐桌。想到这里，我的血压就会飙升，直到我的头开始像温度计的底部一样，通红鼓鼓。我需要提醒自己，雪莉优化的计划大约90%的时间都能奏效。放松，斯科特。放松就好。

Tonight, Shelly might try to complete several urgent tasks before we leave, which might make us get a late start, but not too late. No big deal. Then perhaps Shelly will recommend that we drive her car, which has no gas, so we can refuel it on the way. She needs it in the morning and won’t have much time then. But before we leave the house, Shelly might produce a shopping bag with an item that needs to be returned to the store that is “right on the way.” Perhaps the receipt will be misplaced, which means there might be some negotiating in the store. All of this would make us fifteen minutes late for our dinner reservation and put us at risk of losing our table. That thought would spike my blood pressure until my head begins to look like the bottom of a thermometer, all red and bulbous. I would need to remind myself that Shelly makes her optimized plans work about 90 percent of the time. Relax, Scott. Just relax.

请允许我像实时叙述一样预测故事的后续情节。为了描述清楚，我可能略有夸张。

Allow me to predict the rest of the story as if narrating in real time. I might be exaggerating a little just to paint the picture.

离开家时，雪莉建议抄一条我不熟悉的近路。我开车，雪莉告诉我，只要听她指路就行了。没问题。至少我一开始觉得没问题，直到我正需要知道该往哪儿走的时候，她的手机响了。现在雪莉正在打电话，讨论一些棘手的问题，比如导弹防御或气候变化，偶尔说些听起来像是在跟我说话的话。“右”是指我应该向右转吗？还是她只是在附和电话里和她通话的人？

As we leave the house, Shelly suggests we take a shortcut that I am not familiar with. I’m driving, and Shelly tells me that all I need to do is listen to her directions. No problem. At least I think it’s no problem until her cell phone rings just when I need to know which way to go. Now Shelly is talking on the phone and solving some thorny issue like missile defense or climate change while occasionally saying things that sound as if they might be meant for me. Does “Right” mean I should turn right, or is she just agreeing with whoever she’s talking to on the phone?

很快我就迷路了，于是向雪莉求助。她让我先走，因为她正忙着解决手机里的问题。我把车停在路边，看了看手表。我想到了一个好主意，可以用GPS找到商店，但我不太确定是哪家。购物袋在后备箱里。所以现在我打开后备箱，找到购物袋，希望能在智能手机上找到商店的地址。但这段高速公路上我的手机没有网络。所以我一边开车，一边像信号仪一样拿着手机，等待数据图标出现，祈祷警察没在监视我。

Soon I am lost, and I look to Shelly for help. She waives me off because she’s deep into solving whatever problem is happening on the phone. I pull over and look at my watch. I get the brilliant idea of using GPS to find the store, but I’m not entirely sure which store it is. The shopping bag is in the trunk. So now I’m opening the trunk, finding the bag, and hoping to find the store’s address on my smartphone. But my phone has no Internet connection on this stretch of highway. So I drive while holding my phone like a signal meter, waiting for a data icon to appear and hoping the police are not watching.

我找到信号了，把车停在路边，试图找到商店的地址，但在手机上搜索了好久才找到。终于，我找到了！现在我把地址输入GPS，却忘了把路线偏好从高速公路改成最短路线。雪莉看到我在交通高峰期正往匝道驶去，就开始比划着什么，像是在说我应该换个方向，又像是在说砍柴或者滑行飞机。我没能理解这些手势的意思。我把车停在路边，等着电话结束。

I find a signal, pull over, and try to find the store’s address, but it takes forever on my phone. Finally, I got it! Now I enter the address into GPS, but I forget to change the route preferences from freeway to shortest route. Shelly sees me heading for an on ramp during rush hour traffic and starts gesturing in a way that means I should go in a different direction or possibly it means something about chopping wood or taxiing a plane. I can’t interpret the gestures. I pull over and wait for the call to end.

现在已经太晚了，我们的计划要成功，除非餐厅允许我们晚到三十分钟，而且我们四个人都想看的电影要晚点才行。我觉得这不太可能。

By now we are so late that our plan will only work if the restaurant allows us to be thirty minutes late and if there is a different movie all four of us want to watch that starts later. This seems unlikely to me.

但就像我说的，90% 的情况下，我们尝试优化后，都能完成几件差事，找到一张完美的餐桌，享用一顿美餐，甚至还能看一场甚至可能比我们最初选择的电影更精彩的电影。优化经常奏效，足以强化这个习惯。

But like I said, 90 percent of the times we try to optimize, we get several errands completed, get a perfectly good table, have a nice meal, and see a movie that might even be better than the one we first picked. Optimizing works often enough to reinforce the habit.

优化的代价是它令人精疲力竭，压力重重，至少对我这样的人来说是这样。有时我甚至觉得自己快要心脏病发作了。优化还需要全神贯注。我更喜欢简单、万无一失的计划，这样我的心脏才能正常跳动，思绪才能飘向小狗和玫瑰花瓣的美好想象。（更新：我们的晚餐和电影按照我的简单计划进行，完美无缺。雪莉那天晚上没有进行优化。我之前预测的优化混乱并没有发生。想象可能出错的地方让我看起来比平时更像个混蛋，这很有趣，所以我决定保留这一章。）

The cost of optimizing is that it’s exhausting and stress-inducing, at least for people like me. Sometimes I think I’m literally going to have a heart attack from all the optimizing. It also requires full concentration. I prefer simple, foolproof plans that allow my heart to beat normally and my mind to wander toward blissful thoughts of puppies and rose petals. (Update: Our dinner and movie followed my simple plan and worked flawlessly. Shelly took the night off from optimizing. My prediction of optimized mayhem did not come to pass. Imagining what might have gone wrong makes me look like more of a jerk than usual, which is funny, so I decided to leave this chapter intact.)

我倾向于简化，但在某些情况下，优化确实是更好的选择。那么，如何知道在特定情况下哪种方法更有效呢？

I have a bias for simplification, but surely there are situations in which optimizing is the better play. So how do you know which approach works better in a given situation?

如果情况涉及与他人沟通，简化几乎总是正确的答案。如果任务你可以独自完成，或者与志同道合的伙伴一起完成，那么如果你能控制大部分变量，优化可能是更好的选择。现实情况是，有时你必须在两小时内完成三个小时的任务，所以我们并不总是有选择简单路径的奢侈。

If the situation involves communication with others, simplification is almost always the right answer. If the task is something you can do all by yourself or with a partner who is on your wavelength, optimizing might be a better path if you can control most variables in the situation. And realistically, sometimes you simply must get three hours of tasks completed in two hours, so we don’t always have the luxury of being able to choose simple paths.

每当我选择使用的系统时，我都倾向于简洁。人们更容易遵循简单的系统，而不是复杂的系统。在后面关于健身和饮食的章节中，我会给你一些例子。最优化的饮食或健身计划也可能是最复杂的。但很少有人有足够的意志力去坚持复杂的计划。

I prefer simplicity whenever I’m choosing a system to use. People can follow simple systems better than complicated ones. I’ll give you some examples of that in later chapters about fitness and diet. The most optimized diet or fitness plan will also be the most complicated. But few people have enough willpower in reserve to follow complicated plans.

如果你无法判断简单计划和复杂计划哪个更好，那就选择简单的。如果只能抛硬币，你不妨选择更简单的那个。

If you can’t tell whether a simple plan or a complicated one will be the best, choose the simple one. If it’s a coin toss, you might as well do whatever is easier.

如果失败成本很高，那么简单的任务会更好，因为它们更容易管理和控制。错过晚餐预订并不是什么大事，所以在这种情况下进行一些优化是合理的。但如果你要开车去参加一个重要的商务会议，你肯定不想把一些“正在路上”的差事塞进去，因为这会带来不必要的压力和不确定性。

If the cost of failure is high, simple tasks are better because they are easier to manage and control. Missing a dinner reservation isn’t the end of the world, so doing some optimizing in that case is defensible. But if you are driving to an important business meeting, you don’t want to don’t want to pile on some errands that are “on the way” because that introduces unwanted stress and uncertainty.

在我的职业生涯中，我一直觉得我追求简洁的天赋是一种超能力。比如，当我画《呆伯特》时，大多数画格中我几乎不添加背景图，即使添加，通常也很简单。这能节省大量时间。我猜其他漫画家提前退休至少部分是因为他们擅长优化，而这种精力很难长期维持。

In my career, I’ve always felt that my knack for simplicity was a sort of superpower. For example, when I draw Dilbert, I include little or no background art in most panels, and when I do, it’s usually simple. That’s a gigantic time-saver. I assume that other cartoonists retire early at least in part because they were optimizers, and that level of energy can be hard to sustain in the long run.

没人会为了作品而读呆伯特漫画。我可以用 Wacom Cintiq™ 设备（一种可以绘画的电脑屏幕）直接在电脑上画一些简单的图画。我用一种基于自己笔迹创建的特殊字体来输入对话框。多年来，我已经精简了这个流程，如果需要的话，我可以在大约一小时内完成一部漫画，尽管我通常需要更长时间。呆伯特漫画从一开始就设计得简单易懂，而且我继续简化这个过程。这种简化带来了巨大的回报，因为它让我可以自由地每天发帖和直播、写书、做有趣的业余项目，同时仍然享受生活。更新：现在我有一位艺术总监，他根据我的草稿完成最终的艺术创作。

No one reads Dilbert comics for the artwork. I have the luxury of being able to do simple drawings directly on the computer using a Wacom Cintiq™ device (a computer screen on which you can draw). I type the dialog using a special font I created based on my own handwriting. Over the years, I have streamlined this system to the point I can bang out a comic in about an hour if I need to, although I usually take longer. Dilbert was designed from the start to be simple to create, and I continue to streamline the process. That simplicity has paid off big-time because it frees me to post and livestream every day, write books, do interesting side projects, and still enjoy life. Update: these days I have an art director who does the final art from my rough drafts.

优化通常是那些拥有明确目标并觉得需要竭尽全力去实现目标的人的策略。简化通常是那些以系统视角看待世界的人的策略。最好的系统是简单的，这是有充分理由的。复杂的系统更容易失败。人类的天性就是我们擅长遵循简单的系统，而不太擅长遵循复杂的系统。

Optimizing is often the strategy of people who have specific goals and feel the need to do everything in their power to achieve them. Simplifying is generally the strategy for people who view the world in terms of systems. The best systems are simple, and for good reason. Complicated systems have more opportunities for failure. Human nature is such that we’re good at following simple systems and not so good at following complicated ones.

简单的系统或许是取得成功的最佳途径。一旦取得成功，优化便会变得更有价值。成功人士和成功企业拥有随着时间的推移不断优化至完美的优势。初创公司通常会先拼凑出一个八成好的东西，然后观察公众的反应，从而取得更好的效果。如果市场对产品感兴趣，之后还有时间进行改进。

Simple systems are probably the best way to achieve success. Once you have success, optimizing begins to have more value. Successful people and successful businesses have the luxury of being able to optimize toward perfection over time. Startups often do better by slapping together something that is 80 percent good and seeing how the public responds. There’s time to improve things later if the market cares about the product.

简化的另一大优势是它可以释放时间，而时间是世界上最宝贵的资源之一。如果你给一只蚂蚁无限的时间，它就能独自搬动一座大山。就我而言，我可以用通常一份工作才能完成的40小时，同时兼顾三个不同的职业（漫画家、作家、企业家）。

Another big advantage of simplification is that it frees up time, and time is one of your most valuable resources in the world. If you give an ant infinite time, it can move a mountain all by itself. In my case, I can run the equivalent of three separate careers (cartoonist, author, entrepreneur) in the same forty-hour week that would normally accommodate one job.

简化可以释放能量，让你做的其他事情都变得轻松一些。这很重要。你肯定不希望面试过程因为在去面试的路上完成了四件复杂的差事而变得压力重重，最终导致面试失败。当你决定优化还是简化时，要考虑你的一整天，而不是那几项任务。换句话说，要最大限度地利用你的个人能量，而不是任务的数量。
