Simplification frees up energy, making everything else you do just a little bit easier. That’s a huge deal. You don’t want your job interview to go poorly because you completed four complicated errands on the way to the interview that turned you into a ball of stress. When you are trying to decide on optimizing or simplifying, think of your entire day, not the handful of tasks in question. In other words, maximize your personal energy, not the number of tasks.

正如我之前提到的，我们并不总是可以选择简单，尤其是在我们一天要完成上千件事的时候，就像雪莉经常做的那样。但制定一个总体计划，在机会允许的情况下逐步简化系统，是一个好主意。随着时间的推移，你可以逐渐减少生活中的复杂性。简单是一个值得追求的长期目标。这样你才能释放你的个人能量，从而将其集中在你需要的地方。

As I mentioned earlier, we don’t always have an option of choosing simplicity, especially if we have a thousand things to complete in a day, as Shelly often does. But it’s a good idea to have an overarching plan to move toward simple systems as opportunities allow. You can chip away at the complexity of your life over time. Simplicity is a worthy long-term goal. That’s how you will free your personal energy so you can concentrate it where you need it.

坐姿

Sitting Position

你的大脑会从你的身体活动中获得一些暗示。我的经验是，当我以一种我认为与放松相关的姿势坐着，比如瘫坐在沙发上时，我的大脑就会启动懒惰的放松程序。但如果我以良好的姿势坐着，双脚着地，我的身体似乎就会向大脑发出信号，告诉我该集中精力工作了。

Your brain takes some of its cues from what your body is doing. My experience is that when I sit in a position I associate with relaxation such as slumping on the couch, my brain will start the lazy relaxation subroutine. But if I sit with good posture, both feet on the floor, it seems that my body signals to my brain that it’s time to concentrate on work.

保持一致性可能比你选择的特定姿势更重要。如果你训练自己坐在沙发上用笔记本电脑时能够深度集中注意力，那么这个姿势或许会成为你工作的好地方。但不要犯这样的错误：工作时和放松时用同样的坐姿。如果你喜欢在沙发上打盹或看电视，那么它可能不适合认真工作。

Consistency might be more important than the specific position you choose. If you train yourself to do deep concentration when sitting on the couch with your laptop, that position might become a good place for you to work. Just don’t make the mistake of using the same sitting position for work that you use for relaxation. If the couch is where you like to nap or watch television, it will probably be a poor place for doing serious work.

睡眠专家会告诉你，最糟糕的看电视地点是床上。如果你经常看电视，如果不先看点东西，你就睡不着。观看发人深省或扣人心弦的节目，可不是放松身心进入睡眠的好方法。更好的方法是把床当做爱、睡觉的地方，别做别的事。7,8

Sleep experts will tell you that the worst place to watch TV is in bed. If you do it often enough, you won’t be able to fall asleep without watching something first. Watching a thought-provoking or emotion-grabbing show is a bad way to relax into your evening snooze. A better approach is to use your bed for sex, sleep, and nothing else.7,8

同样，将特定的坐姿和工作空间用于工作，将其他空间用于放松或娱乐，也是一个好主意。这使得你的物理环境成为大脑的一种用户界面，并成为一种操控你能量水平和注意力的方式。要改变你的感受和思维方式，你只需改变你的坐姿即可。

Likewise, it’s a good idea to dedicate certain sitting positions and workspaces to work, and other spaces to relaxation or play. That makes your physical environment a sort of user interface for your brain, and it becomes a way to manipulate your energy levels and concentration. To change how you feel and how you think, you can simply change where you are sitting.

除非你亲自尝试一段时间，否则你很可能会觉得这个想法不重要。以我的经验来看，坐姿对我的效率影响巨大。

This is the sort of idea you’re likely to dismiss as unimportant unless you try it yourself for an extended time. In my experience, the way I sit makes a huge difference to my productivity.

整洁

Tidiness

整洁是个人喜好，但它也会影响你的精力。你每看到凌乱的房间，每想着收拾它，都会分散你对更重要事情的注意力。

Tidiness is a personal preference, but it also has an impact on your energy. Every second you look at a messy room and think about fixing it is a distraction from your more important thoughts.

我意识到杂乱和凌乱对每个人的影响并不相同。有些人需要把东西摆放得恰到好处，而另一些人似乎并不介意生活在混乱之中。我的经验是，在整理好办公室，处理完一堆杂乱的任务后，我会感觉头脑更清醒，精力更充沛。我不认为我的经验具有普遍性，但就我而言，这种因果关系非常强烈，所以我建议你也尝试一下。你只需要注意一下整理好工作空间后的感觉，与之前凌乱不堪时的感觉进行比较。

I realize that clutter and messiness don’t affect everyone the same way. Some people need to have things just right, and others don’t seem to mind living in chaos. My experience is that after straightening up my office and working through the piles of miscellaneous tasks, I feel more clear-headed and energetic. I don’t assume my experience is universal, but the cause-and-effect in my case is so strong that I do recommend you experiment with it. All you need to do is pay attention to how you feel after you have tidied up your workspace compared to how you felt when it was a mess.

清洁整理空间是一件枯燥乏味的工作，你可能永远不会把它当成优先事项。我学到的一个技巧是，如果我知道有人来访，我就会自动对整理产生热情。这就是为什么定期邀请别人来家里做客是个好主意。这会激励你保持空间整洁，进而让你的大脑更有活力。

Cleaning and organizing your space is boring work, and you might never see it as a priority. One trick I’ve learned is that I automatically generate enthusiasm about tidying up if I know someone is stopping by. That’s why it’s a good idea to invite people over on a regular basis. It will inspire you to keep your space straightened up, and that might in turn cause your mind to have a bit more energy.

知识与知识的缺乏

Knowledge and the Lack Thereof

成功的最大障碍之一——也是最令人精疲力竭的——就是害怕自己不知道如何完成理想职业规划中要求的事情。例如，你可能有一个很棒的小生意点子，但却不知道如何取个虚拟名称、如何做会计、如何搭建网站、如何分配工作等等。当你对某个特定主题一无所知时，很容易认为它很难快速学会。我经常遇到这种情况，并且总结了一些技巧和解决方法，或许对你有帮助。

One of the biggest obstacles to success—and a real energy-killer—is the fear that you don’t know how to do the stuff that your ideal career plans would require. For example, you might have a terrific idea for a small business, but you don’t know how to get a fictitious name, how to do your accounting, how to build a website, how to delegate work, and so on. When you don’t know anything about a particular topic, it’s easy to assume it would be too hard to learn it quickly. I run into that all the time, and I’ve developed a few tricks and workarounds you might find helpful.

当我的第一位漫画编辑打电话邀请我签订报纸联合出版的合同时，我很快就答应了，但心里却担心自己不懂如何为周日漫画上色。我敬畏那些似乎能完美地在线条内上色的资深漫画家。他们用了什么工具？是用特殊的马克笔还是水彩？为什么报纸上的颜色如此完美？我慌了——我连自己选择的职业的基本工具都不懂。而且我觉得我不可能在合理的时间内学会。我怀疑这些是不是某种艺术学校里教的。

When my first editor of comics called to offer me a contract for newspaper syndication, I quickly said yes, but I secretly worried that I didn’t know how to do the coloring for the Sunday comics. I was in awe of the established cartoonists who seemed to color within the lines so perfectly. And what tools did they use? Were they using special marker pens or watercolors? Why was the color in the newspaper so perfect? I panicked—I didn’t know the basic tools of my own chosen profession. And I didn’t think I could learn in a reasonable time. I wondered if this was all taught in some sort of art school.

我决定向编辑坦白，我对漫画上色艺术一窍不通。她只是简单地说：“印刷厂会做这个。” 我只需要指出我需要在哪个位置用什么颜色就行了。故事就到这里。（今天我用 Photoshop，把油漆桶图标指向我想要上色的区域。这可能是我这周工作中最轻松的事情了。）

I decided to confess to my editor my lack of knowledge in the comic coloring arts. She simply said, “The printer does that.” All I needed to do was indicate which colors I wanted where. End of story. (Today, I use Photoshop and point the paint bucket icon at the area I want to color. It’s probably the easiest work-related thing I do all week.)

在我的职业生涯中，大约90%令我望而生畏的话题都是如此。当你开始提问时，你常常会发现有一个简单的解决方案，一个可以处理它的网站，或者一个收费合理的专业人士来处理。请记住，每当你想知道如何做某事时，可能有几亿人也在思考同样的问题。这通常意味着这些信息已经被打包、简化，在某些情况下甚至被出售。但通常情况下，提问是免费的。

And so it has been with about 90 percent of the topics that have intimidated me throughout my career. When you start asking questions, you often discover that there’s a simple solution, a website that handles it, or a professional who takes care of it for a reasonable fee. Keep in mind that every time you wonder how to do something, a few hundred million people have probably wondered the same thing. And that usually means the information has already been packaged and simplified and in some cases sold. But it’s usually free for the asking.

我非常喜欢快速搜索，就是那种用谷歌不到一分钟就能搞定的搜索。你可能觉得某个主题太复杂，你很难掌握，但只要你肯查，不到一分钟就能明白。我每周都会这样做好几次；我琢磨着某个东西到底有多复杂，然后就去查了。我经常会惊讶地发现，有人也问了同样的问题，还留下了一条简单的线索让我跟着走。

I’m a big fan of flash research, the type you do in less than a minute using Google. You might think a topic is too complicated to master for your use, but you might learn otherwise in less than a minute if you bother to check. I do that process several times per week; I wonder how complicated something is, and I check it out. I’m routinely surprised that someone else had the same question and left a simple breadcrumb trail for me to follow.

我的商业失误——其中有很多——很少是因为找不到自己需要的信息。我遇到的大多数问题都是由我自己的错误决策、技能不足和运气不佳造成的。我从未想过自己因为找不到需要的信息而停滞不前。我想大多数企业家都会告诉你同样的事情。更重要的是，本章的主题是……当你知道如何做某事时，你会更有活力去完成它。

My business mistakes, of which there have been plenty, were rarely caused by not being able to find the information I knew I needed. Most of my problems were caused by my own bad decisions, lack of skill, and bad luck. I can’t think of a single instance in which I was stopped because there was information I needed but couldn’t find. I think most entrepreneurs would tell you the same thing. And more to the point of this chapter . . . when you know how to do something, you feel more energized to take it on.

不要做混蛋

Don’t Be an Asshole

在群体环境中，最容易污染能量的方式之一就是做一个彻头彻尾的混蛋。你或许能成功地激发人们的活力，但这不会带来什么成效。如果你把自己的不良行为视为一种生活方式的选择，比如“做你自己”或“坦诚相待”，你可能会忽略它对你个人能量的消耗。当你惹恼了周围的人时，必然会有一些反噬，也会让你徒劳地去收拾你造成的烂摊子。这一切都会让人分心，身心俱疲。

One of the best ways to pollute the energy in a group situation is by being a total asshole. You might succeed in getting people fully energized, but it won’t be in a productive way. If you think of your bad behavior as a lifestyle choice, as in “being yourself” or “just being honest,” you might be ignoring the cost to your personal energy. When you piss off the people around you, there is bound to be some blowback and wasted efforts cleaning up the mess you made. It can all be quite distracting and draining.

我注意到，有数量惊人的人已经接受了“混蛋”的生活方式，并且觉得这种生活方式效果很好，所以决定继续保持下去。虽然“混蛋”这个词通常会让人联想到男性，但在这里，它涵盖了所有性别。

I’ve noticed that an alarming number of people have adopted the asshole lifestyle and decided it works well enough to stay on that path. While the word asshole usually makes you think of males, in this context it’s gender-inclusive.

关于“混蛋”的定义，并没有一个统一的、公认的定义。它可能包括自私、傲慢、刻薄，或者其他任何性格缺陷。你一眼就能看出什么是混蛋行为。如果你是个正常人，你可能至少在人生的几分钟里做过混蛋。

There’s no single, agreed definition of what it means to be an asshole. It might include selfishness, arrogance, mean-spiritedness, or any number of character flaws. You know asshole behavior when you see it. And if you’re normal, you’ve probably been one for at least a few minutes of your life.

我将混蛋定义为那些因为看似无用或不必要的理由而选择让别人的生活变得不那么愉快的人。

I would define an asshole as anyone who chooses to make the lives of others less pleasant for reasons that don’t appear productive or necessary.

混蛋行为：

Asshole behaviors:

  1. 把话题转到他们自己身上。
  2. Changing the subject to themselves.
  3. 主导谈话。
  4. Dominating conversation.
  5. 吹牛。
  6. Bragging.
  7. 欺骗或撒谎。
  8. Cheating or lying.
  9. 不同意任何建议，无论其多么微不足道。
  10. Disagreeing with any suggestion no matter how trivial.
  11. 用诚实作为残忍的借口。
  12. Using honesty as a justification for cruelty.
  13. 出于某种扭曲的社会正义感而拒绝提供简单的恩惠。
  14. Withholding simple favors out of some warped sense of social justice.
  15. 放弃打招呼或眼神交流等不言而喻的文明行为规则。
  16. Abandoning the unspoken rules of civil behavior such as saying hello or making eye contact.

我认为混蛋行为之所以存在，是因为做这件事的时候感觉很好。从这个意义上说，它就像上瘾一样。长期做混蛋的代价对沉迷于这种生活方式的人来说可能不是什么好事，但短期内肯定感觉很好。

I assume asshole behavior exists because it feels good when you do it. In that sense, it’s like an addiction. The long-term cost of being an asshole can’t be good for the person immersed in the lifestyle, but it must feel good in the short term.

这是个糟糕的权衡。只要你能，做一个通情达理的人最符合你的自身利益。

That’s a bad tradeoff. Your self-interest is best served by being a reasonable person whenever you can muster it.

优先事项

Priorities

把你的优先事项想象成一个同心圆，就像射箭的靶子一样，这很有用。圆心是你的最高优先事项：你自己。如果你把自己搞垮了，你就无法处理其他任何优先事项了。所以，照顾好自己的健康是你的首要任务。

It’s useful to think of your priorities in terms of concentric circles, like an archery target. In the center is your highest priority: you. If you ruin yourself, you won’t be able to work on any other priorities. So taking care of your own health is job one.

下一个环节——也是你的第二大优先事项——是经济。这包括你的工作、投资，甚至你的房子。你可能会对我把经济置于你的家人、朋友和世界其他事物之上感到不满，但这是有原因的。如果你的个人财务引擎运转不正常，你就会给其他人带来负担，从你的家人到整个国家。

The next ring—and your second-biggest priority—is economics. That includes your job, investments, and even your house. You might wince at the fact that I put economics ahead of your family, friends, and the rest of the world, but there’s a reason. If you don’t get your personal financial engine working right, you place burdens on everyone else, from your family to the entire country.

当你身心健康、经济状况良好时，就到了第三个环节：家人、朋友和爱人。身体健康和充足的金钱是获得基本幸福的必要条件，但要想充分享受生活，你还需要与家人、朋友和伴侣相处融洽。

Once you are both healthy and financially sound, it’s time for the third ring: family, friends, and lovers. Good health and sufficient money are necessary for a base level of happiness, but you need to be right with your family, friends, and romantic partners to enjoy life to the fullest.

接下来的几个环依次是你的社区、国家和世界。在你掌控好你优先考虑的事情的核心部分之前，不要费心去改变世界。

The next rings are your local community, country, and the world, in that order. Don’t even bother trying to fix the world until you get the inner circles of your priorities under control.

当然，我这个简洁的优先级小模型的问题在于，生活从来都不是那么简单。你不能因为想去散步，就跟老板说你的任务要晚交。你所有的优先级都会重叠甚至冲突。你需要的是一个简单的规则，让你在处理不可避免的例外情况的同时，还能保持优先级的正确性。一个简单的方法就是判断你的每个选择会如何影响你的个人能量。这并非万无一失的衡量标准，但如果你知道某条路会让你感到压力更大、不健康、精疲力竭，那么它很可能就是错误的选择。正确的选择可能具有挑战性，但它们通常会给你注入活力。当你走在正确的道路上时，你会感觉对了，真的对。

The problem, of course, with my neat little model of priorities is that life is never that simple. You can’t tell your boss that your assignment will be late because you want to go for a long, healthy walk. All your priorities overlap and conflict. What you need is a simple rule for keeping your priorities on track while handling the inevitable exceptions. One simple way to keep your priorities straight is by judging how each of your options will influence your personal energy. It’s not a foolproof gauge, but if you know a particular path will make you feel more stressed, unhealthy, and drained, it’s probably the wrong choice. Right choices can be challenging, but they usually charge you up. When you’re on the right path, it feels right, literally.

例如，如果你的老板要求你周末加班去完成一件有价值且具有挑战性的事情，你可能愿意放弃一些个人生活和健康。有意义的工作可以让人充满活力。如果工作顺利，你或许还会因为你的努力而获得晋升。这样的权衡可能会在短期和长期都给你带来动力。

For example, if your boss asks you to work the weekend to finish something worthwhile and challenging, you might be willing to give up a little of your personal life and health. Meaningful work can be energizing. And if things work out, perhaps you will be promoted because of your efforts. That’s a tradeoff that might charge you up both in the short and long run.

另一方面，如果你的老板经常要求你加班，除了处理大量令人头脑麻木的行政工作之外没有任何正当理由，你可能需要找一份新工作。

On the other hand, if your boss routinely asks you to work overtime for no good reason other than to claw through piles of brain-deadening administrative work, you probably need to look for a new job.

在这两个例子中，你的老板都要求你做额外的工作，而牺牲了你的优先任务，但只有其中一种情况会增加你的个人精力。

In both examples, your boss is asking for extra work at the cost of your higher priorities, but only one of those situations increases your personal energy.

用精力作为指导的风险在于，很多糟糕的选择虽然能让你短期内精力充沛，但实际上，我们都知道，比如，把可卡因塞进鼻子里就不是一个好的长期策略。愚蠢的选择通常显而易见。

The risk with using energy as your guide is that there are plenty of bad choices that also get you energized in the short run. But realistically, we all know, for example, that shoving cocaine up our noses isn’t a good long-term strategy. The dumb choices are generally obvious.

我所说的优先事项，并非指你最爱的事物。你可以爱家人胜过爱工作，但仍然可以整天工作，为家人提供食物和机会。优先事项是指你需要做好的事情，这样你所爱的事物才能蓬勃发展。

When I speak of priorities, I don’t mean that in terms of what you love the most. You can love your family more than you love your job and still spend all day working so they have food and opportunities. Priorities are the things you need to get right so the things you love can thrive.

第十二章

Chapter 12

管理你的态度

Managing Your Attitude

是我们的大脑天生就会不断分析你的环境、你的想法和你的健康状况，然后利用这些信息产生一种你称之为态度的感觉。经验告诉我们，当你的态度良好时，你的工作效率会更高，生活也会更快乐。如果你能直接控制自己的态度，而不是让环境左右你每一天的感受，那就像是一种小小的超能力。事实证明，你确实拥有这种超能力。你可以通过控制你的思想、你的身体，甚至你的环境来控制你的态度。

Your brain is wired to continuously analyze your environment, your thoughts, and your health, then to use that information to generate a sensation you call your attitude. You know from experience that you do better work and enjoy life more when your attitude is good. If you could control your attitude directly as opposed to letting the environment dictate how you feel on any given day, it would be like a minor superpower. It turns out you do have that superpower. You can control your attitude by manipulating your thoughts, your body, and even your environment.

你的态度会影响你追求成功和幸福的所作所为。管理态度的最好方法是理解你的基本天性，即一个可以被编程为快乐的湿润机器人——前提是你了解用户界面。首先，注意观察最近锻炼过的人的态度。你会发现他们几乎总是快乐而乐观。现在再看看最近吃过东西的人和饥饿的人的态度。你会发现很大的不同。疲倦的人脾气暴躁；休息好的人则不那么暴躁。如果你想提升你的态度并增加你的能量，运动、饮食和睡眠应该是你首先要按下的按钮。但是，如果你在身体健康方面做得很好，但仍然没有像你认为的那样享受生活，该怎么办？

Your attitude affects everything you do in your quest for success and happiness. The best way to manage your attitude is by understanding your basic nature as a moist robot that can be programmed for happiness—if you understand the user interface. For starters, pay attention to the attitudes of people who have recently exercised. You’ll discover they are almost always happy and upbeat. Now also look at the attitudes of people who have recently eaten versus people who are hungry. You’ll see a big difference. Tired people are grumpy; rested people are less so. Exercise, food, and sleep should be your first buttons to push if you’re trying to elevate your attitude and raise your energy. But what if you’re doing everything right on the physical health front yet are still not enjoying life as much as you think you should?

你可以尝试一个简单的技巧，那就是增加快乐想法与烦恼想法的比例。如果你的生活没有提供足够多的快乐想法，那就试着幻想一下未来的美好事物。别担心你的白日梦不太可能实现。白日梦的力量就像那些能让你开怀大笑或落泪的优秀电影一样。你的身心会对它花费最多时间思考的画面自动做出反应。如果你想象自己获得诺贝尔奖、拥有自己的私人岛屿或在NBA打球，别担心这些事情不太可能发生。让自己进入这种充满想象力的心态会让你充满活力。想象力是你态度的接口。你真的可以想象自己拥有更高的能量水平。

A simple trick you might try involves increasing your ratio of happy thoughts to disturbing thoughts. If your life doesn’t provide you with plenty of happy thoughts to draw upon, try daydreaming of wonderful things in your future. Don’t worry that your daydreams are unlikely to come true. The power of daydreaming is like the power of well-made movies that can make you laugh or cry. Your body and your mind will respond automatically to whatever images it spends the most time pondering. If you imagine winning a Nobel Prize, buying your own private island, or playing in the NBA, don’t worry that those things are unlikely. Putting yourself in that imagination-fueled frame of mind will pep you up. Imagination is the interface to your attitude. You can literally imagine yourself to higher levels of energy.

这就是为什么你应该避免接触过多令人沮丧的新闻，以及为什么最好避免接触令人沮丧的音乐、书籍和电影。你觉得谁总是心情愉快，我就能告诉你谁（很可能）不会过度接触悲伤的娱乐内容。管理情绪最简单的方法就是尽可能多地享受令人愉悦的娱乐。

This is the same reason why you should avoid exposure to too much news of the depressing type—and why it’s a good idea to avoid music, books, and movies that are downers. Show me someone who you think is always in a good mood, and I’ll show you a person who (probably) avoids overexposure to sad forms of entertainment. The easiest way to manage your attitude is to consume as much feel-good entertainment as you can.

现实一点，当你心情不好时，你最不想听到的建议就是“想一些开心的事”。如果你真的遭遇不幸，你可能只需要时间和距离来恢复。白日梦策略更像是一种日常练习，它并不能让你摆脱深深的低迷。对于真正糟糕的情绪，运动、营养、睡眠和时间才是明智的选择。一旦你恢复到幸福的基线水平，你就能更好地从白日梦中获益。

Realistically, the last advice you want to hear when you are in a terrible mood is “Think of something happy.” If you’re experiencing genuine misfortune, you probably just need time and distance to recover. The daydreaming strategy is more of an everyday practice. It won’t get you out of a deep slump. For the truly bad moods, exercise, nutrition, sleep, and time are the smart buttons to push. Once you get back to your baseline level of happiness, you’ll be in a better position to get the benefits of daydreaming.

白日梦方法的一个强有力的变体是，从事那些真正有可能改变世界、造福人类或赚取十亿美元（或三者兼具）的项目。我努力始终保持一个或多个能够改变世界的项目在进行中。

A powerful variation on the daydreaming method involves working on projects that have a real chance of changing the world, helping humanity, or making a billion dollars (or all three). I try to have one or more change-the-world projects going at all times.

写这篇文章的时候，我正在寻找资金合作伙伴，共同推动一个有可能改变全球经济的想法，前提是它能按计划进行。它会成功吗？可能不会。但这个想法让我兴奋不已，让我今天充满活力。这就是我的策略。

As I write this, I’m shopping for money partners to launch an idea that has the potential to be transformative to the entire economy of the world, assuming it works as planned. Will it succeed? Probably not. But the idea of it excites me and raises my energy today. That’s my system.

当你读到这本书的时候，这些努力已经取得了丰硕的成果。任何新事业都充满风险。但在过去的几个月里，我的态度和精力都异常高涨，因为我的项目拥有让世界变得更美好的潜力。我想象中的未来就像一个信号，让我今天保持着高昂的情绪。

By the time you read this book, a lot will have transpired with those efforts. Any new business is risky. But for the past several months, my attitude and energy have been sky-high because of the potential my project has for making the world a better place. My imagined future acts as a cue to keep my mood elevated today.

你可能会想，这对著名作家和漫画家来说当然不错，但普通人改变世界的机会并不多。我不同意。创意常常会改变世界，而这些创意大多源自普通人。你可能拥有一个专利创意、一个产品创意或一个流程创意，它们都可能改变世界。在我的漫画生涯之前，我有很多伟大的创意，但都未能成功。一个创意失败后，我通常会有两个创意来取而代之。我的每一个创意，即使成功的可能性很小，也都拥有在现实世界中实现的潜力。

You might be thinking this is all well and good for famous authors and cartoonists, but ordinary people don’t have many chances to change the world. I disagree. Ideas change the world routinely, and most of those ideas originate from ordinary people. You might have a patent idea, a product idea, or a process idea that could change the world. Before my cartoon career, I had plenty of big ideas that didn’t work out. When one idea failed, I usually had two more to take its place. And every one of my ideas had real-world potential even if the odds were bad.

别担心你的想法是否遥不可及。这现在并不重要。今天，你应该梦想着你的想法能够取得巨大的成功，这样你才能享受这种感觉。让你对未来的想法今天就为你注入能量。无论你想在生活中做什么，更高的能量都会帮助你实现目标。

Don’t worry if your idea is a long shot. That’s not what matters right now. Today, you want to daydream of your idea being a huge success so you can enjoy the feeling. Let your ideas for the future fuel your energy today. No matter what you want to do in life, higher energy will help you get there.

拥有一个改变世界的大型项目的另一个好处是，你几乎总能在失败的过程中学到一些有价值的东西。只要你胸怀大志，大多数时候你都会失败。但请记住，目标本来就是为失败者准备的。更明智的做法是，将你的宏大创意项目视为提升你的精力、人脉和技能的系统的一部分。从这个角度来看，如果你正在筹备一个有趣的大型项目，那么你每次醒来都是一个赢家。

Another benefit of having a big, world-changing project is that you almost always end up learning something valuable in the process of failing. And fail you will most of the time, so long as you are dreaming big. But remember, goals are for losers anyway. It’s smarter to see your big idea projects as part of a system to improve your energy, contacts, and skills. From that viewpoint, if you have a big, interesting project in the works, you’re a winner every time you wake up.

当我考虑接手一个新的大项目时，我首先会问自己，我认识哪些人会有帮助，哪些人可能愿意合作、投资，或者只是提供建议。在我的人脉圈里——就我目前的职业生涯而言，这已经相当庞大了——我遇到的这些人中有一半都是在经历各种失败的过程中遇到的。如果我问自己，下一个伟大的想法需要哪些技能和知识，那必然意味着要借鉴我过去在某个注定失败的项目中摸索时获得的知识。

When I consider taking on a new, big project, I first ask myself who I know that would be helpful and who might want to partner, invest, or just give advice. In my universe of contacts, which is fairly huge at this point in my career, I would say I met half of those folks in the process of failing at one thing or another. And if I ask myself what skills and knowledge I need for my next big idea, invariably that means drawing on knowledge I gained while circling the drain in some doomed project of yore.

假设你明天醒来，精力充沛地投入到激动人心的新项目中。在这一天里，你在研究过程中学到了一些知识，并且结识了一些新朋友。如果你做到了这些，那么无论项目进展如何，你都算是成功了。

Let’s say you wake up tomorrow full of energy for your exciting new project. Over the course of the day, you learn a few things in the process of doing your research, and you meet some new people along the way. If you accomplish that and nothing more, you’re succeeding—no matter what happens with your project.

微笑的力量

The Power of Smiling

微笑能让你感觉更好，即使你的笑容是假的。这最清楚地说明了你的大脑如何拥有用户界面。当你心情不好时，强颜欢笑的肢体动作可能会触发大脑中与幸福相关的愉悦化学反应。1,2

Smiling makes you feel better, even if your smile is fake. This is the clearest example of how your brain has a user interface. When you’re in a bad mood, the physical act of forcing a smile may trigger the feel-good chemistry in your brain that is associated with happiness. 1,2

“微笑让你快乐”这个怪癖，其实是“假装快乐直到快乐”这个更大且非常有用的现象的一部分。你会在各种各样的人类活动中看到这种双向因果关系。稍后我会告诉你，穿上运动服会让你有锻炼的欲望。我还发现，表现得自信会让你感觉更自信。精力充沛会让你想运动，但运动也会让你感觉精力充沛。爱一个人会让你想做爱，但做爱也会释放让你感受到爱的结合化学物质。高睾酮水平可以帮助你赢得比赛，但赢得比赛有时也会提高你的睾酮水平。3-7疲倦会让你想躺下，但休息好后躺下会让你有小睡一会儿的心情。饥饿会让你想吃简单的碳水化合物，但吃简单的碳水化合物会让你感到饥饿。

The smiling-makes-you-happy quirk is part of the larger and highly useful phenomenon of faking-it-until-you-make-it. You’ll see this two-way causation in a wide variety of human activities. Later, I’ll tell you that putting on exercise clothes will make you feel like working out. I’ve also discovered that acting confident makes you feel more confident. Feeling energetic makes you want to play a sport, but playing a sport will also make you feel energetic. Loving someone makes you want to have sex, but having sex also releases the bonding chemicals that make you feel love. High testosterone can help you win a competition, but winning a competition can also sometimes raise your testosterone.3-7 Being tired makes you want to lie down, but lying down when you are rested can put you in the mood for a nap. Feeling hungry can make you want to eat simple carbs, but eating simple carbs can make you feel hungry.

理解这种双向因果关系对于提升个人能量非常有益。为了更好地利用它，我发现将我的思维想象成两个人之间的对话会很有帮助。之所以有这种感觉，是因为我会用句子思考，就像在与另一个同样是“我”的实体对话。其中一个“我”倾向于理性通情达理，而另一个“我”则更感性、更本能。当理性的“我”想要激发感性的“我”——掌控能量的那一部分——时，理性的“我”必须像程序员一样，按下正确的按钮。

Understanding this two-way causation is highly useful for boosting your personal energy. To take advantage of it, I find it useful to imagine my mind as a conversation between two individuals. It feels that way because I think in sentences, as if talking to another entity that is also me. One of me tends to be rational and reasonable while the other me is a bit more emotional and instinctual. When the rational me wants to perk up the emotional me—the part of me that controls my energy—the rational me has to act as a programmer and push the right buttons.

下次心情低落时，试着对街上遇到的陌生人微笑。你会惊讶地发现，很多人会本能地回以微笑。如果你经常微笑，最终这种暗示会启动你大脑中的快乐子程序，释放出你渴望的、让你感觉良好的化学物质。

The next time you’re in a gloomy mood, try smiling at a stranger you pass on the street. You’ll be surprised how many people reflexively return the smile, and if you smile often enough, eventually that cue will boot up the happiness subroutine in your brain and release the feel-good chemicals you desire.

更棒的是，微笑还能让你更有魅力。8-10当你更有魅力时，人们对你的回应会更加尊重和体贴，更多笑容，有时甚至充满渴望。这些正是能让你开心的事情。

As a bonus, smiling makes you more attractive to others.8-10 When you’re more attractive, people respond to you with more respect and consideration, more smiles, and sometimes even lust. That’s exactly the sort of thing that can cheer you up.

如果你不习惯假笑，那就试着和那些天生幽默的朋友交往。同样重要的是，避开那些总是让人沮丧的朋友。你想要的是能分享好与坏的朋友，但你不是心理医生。远离那些吸干你灵魂的人。你有权追求幸福，也同样有权尽可能快地逃离那些否认幸福的人。

If you’re not comfortable faking a smile, try hanging around friends who are naturally funny. Equally important, avoid friends who are full-time downers. You want friends with whom you can share both the good and the bad, but you aren’t a therapist. Walk away from the soul-suckers. You have a right to pursue happiness and an equal right to run as fast as you can from the people who would deny it.

成功溢价

Success Premium

我开始相信，任何领域的成功都会对其他领域产生溢出效应。你可以利用这种效应，精通那些只需练习就能做到的事情。一旦你擅长一些不太重要的事情，比如爱好或运动，成功的习惯就会伴随你走向更重要的追求。当你尝到成功的滋味时，你会渴望更多。而这种渴望会赋予你能量，而这种能量对于更大的成功至关重要。

I’ve come to believe that success at anything has a spillover effect into other areas. You can take advantage of that effect by becoming good at things that require nothing but practice. Once you become good at a few unimportant things such as hobbies or sports, the habit of success stays with you on more important quests. When you’ve tasted success, you want more. And the wanting gives you the sort of energy that is critical to even greater success.

就我而言，我在几款简单的游戏中表现出了超强的天赋：

In my case, I was extra-talented at several trivial games:

  • 拼字游戏
  • Scrabble
  • 水池
  • Pool
  • 网球
  • Tennis
  • 乒乓球
  • Ping-Pong

在每一项活动中，我所谓的“天赋”不过是长时间疯狂练习的结果。我生长在一个小镇，那里几乎没有什么娱乐方式。我们家的地下室/防空洞改建而成，里面有一张世界上最便宜、最差的台球桌。它便宜到连石板台面都没有，买来没多久就变形了。如果击球太软，球就会滚到一边，然后就停在那里。在桌子的两端，桌子和墙壁之间没有足够的空间，所以我需要把球杆举到天花板的角落，然后向下击打母球。这可不是什么漂亮的动作。但我花了很多时间独自练习，一杆接一杆，最终打得相当不错。在我人生的这个阶段，唯一能在台球上经常赢我的人，是那些把更多青春时光浪费在练习上的人。

In each of those activities, my so-called “talent” was little more than the result of insane hours of practice. I grew up in a small town where there weren’t many ways to stay entertained. We had the world’s cheapest and worst pool table in our converted cellar/bomb shelter. It was so cheap that it didn’t have a slate bed, and it became warped soon after we got it. A soft shot meant your ball would roll to one side and stay there. On two ends of the table there wasn’t enough room between the table and the wall, so I needed to raise the cue stick toward the corner of the ceiling and shoot down on the cue ball. It wasn’t pretty. But I spent so many hours by myself practicing shot after shot that I became quite good. At this point in my life, the only people who can regularly beat me at pool are the ones who wasted an even greater proportion of their youth practicing.

拼字游戏、乒乓球和网球也是如此。在这些游戏中，我比世界上99%的人都强，因为我投入的练习时间比世界上99%的人都多。这没什么神奇的。

The same was true for Scrabble, Ping-Pong, and tennis. I’m better than 99 percent of the world‡ in each of those games because I put in more practice time than 99 percent of the world. There’s no magic to it.

正是这些微小的成功经历，让我对做好一件事需要投入多少时间有了更清晰的认识。这阻止了我过早放弃。更重要的是，我知道了胜利的滋味（太棒了！），它激励我去追求更多。从这个意义上来说，我就像任何受过训练的动物一样，渴望得到奖励。

Thanks to my experience with these exceedingly minor successes, I have a realistic understanding of how many hours it takes to be good at something. That keeps me from bailing out of things too soon. But more importantly, I know what winning feels like (great!), and it energizes me to seek more of it. In that sense, I’m like any trained animal seeking a treat.

人生成功的一个妙招是精通某件事，任何事，并让这种感觉推动你走向新的、更好的胜利。成功可以养成习惯。

A great strategy for success in life is to become good at something, anything, and let that feeling propel you to new and better victories. Success can be habit-forming.

选择有效的错觉

Pick the Delusion That Works

当我的狗狗士力架想在后院玩接球游戏时，它会跟着我，用怪异的专注力盯着我的眼睛，仿佛要对我施展它的绝地武士力量。这招通常很管用。我知道它想要什么，我会放下工作来满足它。有趣的是，我不确定它是否明白，陪不陪它玩是我的选择。它对我的精神控制如此可靠，以至于我确信它认为，最重要的就是它盯着我的眼神有多专注，以及它想象自己追网球的画面有多逼真。

When my dog, Snickers, wants to play fetch in the backyard, she follows me around and stares into my eyes with freakish intensity, as if using her Jedi doggy powers on me. More often than not, it works. I know what she wants, and I take a break from work to accommodate her. The interesting thing is that I’m not sure she understands that it’s my choice whether I go play with her or not. Her mental control of me works so reliably that I’m certain she thinks all that matters is how hard she stares at me and how vividly she imagines§ herself chasing a tennis ball.

对我来说，士力架对世界的错误认知最吸引人的地方在于，它竟然完美地运作着。她有一套系统来获取自己想要的东西，而且这套系统似乎也有效，尽管原因与她想象的不同。更深层次的现实是，我了解到她盯着我看意味着该去打网球了。我与士力架的经历引出了一个更大的问题：人类和狗真的有那么大的不同吗？我们对现实的假设真的完全错误吗？我们这些错误的假设真的有效吗？是因为我们无法理解的原因吗？

To me, the fascinating thing about Snickers’ flawed view of the world is that it works perfectly. She has a system for getting what she wants, and it seems to work, albeit for different reasons than she imagines. The deeper reality is that I’ve learned that her stares mean it’s time for some tennis ball fun. My experience with Snickers begs bigger questions: Are humans so different from dogs? Do we have totally flawed assumptions about reality? Do our flawed assumptions work for reasons we don’t understand?

众所周知，运动员会在比赛期间停止刮胡子，或者穿上他们认为幸运的袜子。这些迷信或许在某种程度上有助于增强他们的自信心，进而影响他们的成功。幸运袜子是不是真的并不重要。即使穿着者对其中的原因一无所知，这些袜子仍然能够提升运动员的表现。

Athletes are known to stop shaving for the duration of a tournament or to wear socks they deem lucky. These superstitions probably help in some small way to bolster their confidence, which, in turn, can influence success. It’s irrelevant that lucky socks aren’t a real thing. The socks can still improve an athlete’s performance even if the wearer has a flawed idea of why.

我们的大脑对现实本质的认知能力有限。大多数时候，我们对现实的误解是良性的，有时甚至有益。但其他时候，则不然。

Our brains have a limited capacity to know the true nature of reality. Most times, our misconceptions about reality are benign, sometimes even helpful. Other times, not so much.

物理学家告诉我们，现实似乎取决于观察者。如果你我以相同的速度和方向穿越一个空旷而无限大的宇宙，我们会感觉自己仿佛没有移动。而且可以说，情况确实如此，因为运动只有与其他物体相关才有意义。如果你我在这个空旷的宇宙中，背上一模一样的火箭，面向同一方向，然后点火，我们是否真的在移动，这仍是一个有争议的问题。你会感觉到火箭压在你的背上，但你不知道那是向前动量的开始，还是仅仅是背部受到的压力，过了一段时间就会消失。（好吧，好吧，在太空中，身体受到的压力总是会引起运动，你足够聪明，应该知道这一点。但为了举个例子，我们假设你在科学课上没有认真听讲。）

Physicists tell us that reality seems to depend on the observer. If you and I were to move through an empty and infinitely large universe at the same speed and in the same direction, we would feel as if we weren’t moving at all. And arguably that would be the case since movement only makes sense in relation to other objects. If you and I strap identical rockets to our backs in this otherwise empty universe, face the same direction, and fire them up, it would be a matter of debate whether we were moving at all. You’d feel the rocket press into your back, but you wouldn’t know if that was the beginning of forward momentum or just a pressure on your back that relaxed after some time. (Okay, okay, a pressure on your body in space will always cause movement, and you’re smart enough to know that. But let’s assume for this example that you didn’t pay attention in science class.)

粒子和波的量子世界之外的现实或许是固定且客观的，至少大多数科学家如此认为。但我们对现实的认知显然会定期发生变化。我们都有过这样的经历：初次见面时，对某人的第一印象非常不准确，这反过来又影响了我们对他们的行为方式。后来，随着你对这个人有了更多的了解，你的行为方式就会开始改变。外部现实不会改变，但你的观点会改变。在很多情况下，影响你行为的是你的观点，而不是宇宙。即使你无法改变潜在的现实，你也可以控制你的观点。

Reality outside the quantum world of particles and waves might be fixed and objective, at least according to most scientists. But how we think of our reality is clearly subject to regular changes. We’ve all had the experience of meeting someone for the first time and having a wildly inaccurate first impression, which in turn drove the way we acted toward them. Later, once you know more about the person, you start behaving differently. The external reality doesn’t change, but your point of view does. In many cases, it’s your point of view that influences your behavior, not the universe. And you can control your point of view even when you can’t change the underlying reality.

十多年来，我因创作了《呆伯特》而小有名气，但在公众场合仍然鲜有人认出我。初次见面时，如果没有事先做完整介绍，人们对待我就像对待普通陌生人一样。但如果谈起我的工作，人们就会立刻变得友好起来，仿佛我们一直是朋友。根本的现实并没有改变，但人们对我的看法却改变了，这改变了他们的行为。

For over a decade, I’ve been semi-famous for creating Dilbert, but I’m still generally unrecognized in public. When I meet people for the first time without the benefit of a full introduction, I’m treated like any other stranger. But if the topic of my job comes up, people immediately become friendlier, as if we had been friends forever. The underlying reality doesn’t change, but the way people think of me does, and that changes how they act.

关于感知，我的主要观点是，你不应该犹豫，去调整你的感知，让它变得让你快乐，因为你对现实的本质的理解很可能是错误的。如果要我用我的生命打赌，我会说人类更像是我的狗，它试图用超能力跟我玩接球游戏，而不是像那些开明的生物，能够深刻理解周围的环境。我们之前的每一代人，都像士力架一样，相信自己已经把事情弄清楚了。我们现在知道，之前的每一代人，在很多事情上都犯了错误。你是否可能出生在历史的转折点，人类对现实的了解足以让我们说我们理解它？这又是一个谦逊是你的朋友的例子。当你能够放下自我，足够长时间地认识到你的感知是不完整的或误导性的，你就能自由地想象新的、可能更有用的世界观。

My main point about perceptions is that you shouldn’t hesitate to modify your perceptions to whatever makes you happy because you’re probably wrong about the underlying nature of reality anyway. If I had to bet my life, I’d say humans are more like my dog trying to use psychic powers on me to play fetch than we are like enlightened creatures who understand their environment at a deep level. Every generation before us believed, like Snickers, that they had things figured out. We now know that every generation before us was wrong about a lot of it. Is it likely that you were born at the tipping point of history in which humans know enough about reality to say we understand it? This is another case where humility is your friend. When you can release your ego long enough to view your perceptions as incomplete or misleading, you set yourself free to imagine new and potentially more useful ways of looking at the world.

从实际角度来说，我的狗之所以每天三次开心地玩接球游戏，是因为它选择了一种有效的幻觉。我相信它想象着只要想象就能让我玩接球游戏。你有时也能通过运用一种实用的幻觉来达到你想要的效果。现实被高估了，而且不可能以任何确定的程度去理解。你确实知道的是，有些看待世界的方式比其他方式更有效。即使你不知道原因，也要选择有效的方式。

In practical terms, the reason my dog happily plays fetch three times a day is that she chose an illusion that works. I believe she imagines she can make me play fetch just by visualizing it. You, too, can sometimes get what you want by adopting a practical illusion. Reality is overrated and impossible to understand with any degree of certainty. What you do know for sure is that some ways of looking at the world work better than others. Pick the way that works even if you don’t know why.

写这本书的过程就是一个很好的例子，可以说明我所说的。写书是件苦差事——远比大多数人想象的要难得多，你或许也觉得它难上加难。我激励自己完成这项艰巨任务的方法是，想象自己有一些引人入胜、实用的东西可以分享，能够帮助他人。但现实可能大相径庭。我看不到未来，所以我可以选择用任何能给我带来最大效用的方式来想象它。我选择想象这本书会大卖，因为这种幻想非常鼓舞人心，它能提升我的能量。

The process of writing this book is a good example of what I’m talking about. Writing a book is hard work—far harder than most people imagine, and you probably imagine it to be plenty hard. The way I motivate myself to take on a task this large is by imagining that I have fascinating and useful things to say that will help people. The reality might be quite different. I can’t see the future, so I have the option of imagining it in whatever way gives me the greatest utility. I choose to imagine that the book will do well because that illusion is highly motivating. It increases my energy.

最糟糕的情况是，我会花很多时间写一本没人觉得有用或有趣的书。这并非第一次。但正因为我想象的未来，这本书会被数百万人阅读，所以我能够在写作中找到极大的满足感。无论未来现实如何，我想象的未来版本在今天都非常有用。

The worst-case scenario is that I will spend a lot of time writing a book no one will find useful or entertaining. It wouldn’t be the first time. But because of my imaginary future in which the book is enjoyed by millions, I’m able to find great satisfaction in writing it. No matter what reality delivers in the future, my imagined version of the future has great usefulness today.

摆脱压抑现实的枷锁。对你来说，真实的是你的想象和感受。如果你明智地管理你的幻想，你或许能得到你想要的，但你未必能理解它为何奏效。

Free yourself from the shackles of an oppressive reality. What’s real to you is what you imagine and what you feel. If you manage your illusions wisely, you might get what you want, but you won’t necessarily understand why it worked.

‡我的估计包括婴儿、昏迷患者以及从未听说过这些游戏的人。

‡I’m including in my estimate babies, coma patients, and people who have never heard of those games.

§我假设存在一种狗脑版的想象力。如果没有，别让这个比喻偏离主题。

§I’m assuming there is such a thing as a dog-brained version of imagination. If not, don’t let the analogy derail the point.

第十三章

Chapter 13

它已经发挥作用了

It’s Already Working

是你已经通过了通往成功的第一道门槛。读了这本书，你就确立了自己是一位求知者的身份。求知者显然比那些坐等的人收获更多。你决定阅读这本书，这证明你是一个积极行动的人，渴望提升效率。我反复强调这一点，是为了帮助你牢牢记住它。

You already passed the first filter for success. By reading this book, you’ve established yourself as a seeker of knowledge. Seekers obviously find more stuff than the people who sit and wait. Your decision to read this book is confirmation that you are a person of action who has a desire to be more effective. I’m reinforcing that thought to help lock it in.

阅读本书并从某种意义上加入一个新群体，你也会获得一些自然而然的益处。具体来说，你正在成为读过本书的人之一。当你将自己定义为任何群体的一员时，你就会开始自动认同其他成员，并融入该群体的一些特质。1,2那些阅读成功书籍的群体是一个非常棒的群体。你们是最有可能成功的人，因为你们对成功的机制进行了认真的思考和研究。

You also get some automatic benefits by reading this book and in a sense joining a new group. Specifically, you’re on your way to being one of the people who have read this book. When you define yourself as a member of any group, you start to automatically identify with the other members and take on some of the characteristics of the group.1,2 The group of people who read books on how to succeed is an excellent group to be in. You’re the people most likely to succeed because you’re putting real thought and research into the mechanics of success.

你或许会问，这是否无关紧要。我想每个读过这本书的人都会受到不同的影响，而且这种影响是无法准确衡量的。但我想你在生活中一定见过这样的例子：一个人在成为一个团体的成员、获得晋升，或者做了任何能够重新定义自己身份的事情后，发生了巨大的改变。

You might fairly ask if this is a trivial point. I suppose everyone who reads this book will be influenced in a different way, and there’s no way to accurately measure this sort of thing. But I think you’ve seen examples in your life in which a person changes dramatically upon becoming a member of a group, getting a promotion, or doing anything that redefines them as a person.

这种效应最显著的例子发生在我身上。在联合传媒公司宣布联合发行《呆伯特》漫画后一周内，我的漫画创作技巧便突飞猛进。成为一名正式职业漫画家的这一事实，对我进一步挖掘自身潜能产生了深远的影响。

The most striking example of this effect happened to me. My cartooning skills improved dramatically within a week of United Media offering to syndicate Dilbert. The simple knowledge that I had become an official professional cartoonist had a profound effect on unlocking whatever additional talent I had.

在我的职场生涯中，我常常惊叹于人们从普通员工晋升为管理层后，变化之快。我亲眼目睹一位同事在晋升两个月内，就从犹豫不决、平庸无奇的性格转变为自信强势的形象。这其中显然有某种“演技”，但无论我们怎么做，我们最终都会变成现实。我们伪装自己，直到伪装变成现实。我们的核心性格不会改变，但我们会迅速适应与新身份和职位相关的行为举止和技能。

In my corporate career, I often marveled at how people changed as soon as they got promoted from worker bee to management. I saw one of my coworkers transform from a hesitant and unimpressive personality to confident and powerful within two months of his promotion. Obviously there was some acting involved, but we are designed to become in reality however we act. We fake it until the fake becomes real. Our core personality doesn’t change, but we quickly adopt the mannerisms and skills associated with our new status and position.

所以，恭喜你成为一名研究成功机制的人。这比你想象的要重要得多。

So congratulations on being a person who studies the mechanics of success. It’s a bigger deal than you might realize.

第十四章

Chapter 14

我的小指发疯了

My Pinky Goes Nuts

B九十年代初，《呆伯特》取得了不小的成功，但远没达到让我想要辞去太平洋贝尔电话公司日常工作的高度。我每天早上四点起床，在通勤前画画，然后在格子间里工作一整天，再回到家画一整夜。我的绘画时间总是被压缩，这给我画画的手带来了很大的压力。过度使用让我付出了代价，每当我碰笔在纸上时，我的小指就会开始痉挛，几乎无法画画。

By the early nineties, Dilbert was a modest success, but it was nowhere near the point where I was tempted to quit my day job at the phone company, Pacific Bell. I would wake at 4:00 AM to draw before my commute, then work all day in my cubicle prison and come home to draw all night. My time windows for drawing were always compressed, which put a lot of pressure on my drawing hand. The overuse took its toll, and my pinky finger started to spasm whenever I touched pen to paper, making it nearly impossible to draw.

我去凯撒医疗集团看医生，他说他可能认识集团里另一位医生，是这方面的专家。巧合的是，世界上对这种疾病最有研究的医生之一就在凯撒医疗集团工作，而且他的诊所就在我家附近。

I went to see my doctor in the Kaiser healthcare system, and he said he might know another doctor in the system who was an expert in this very problem. By wonderful coincidence, one of the world’s most knowledgeable doctors in this specific condition worked for Kaiser, and his office was just down the road from my home.

停下来思考一下。当时世界上有超过60亿人口，而该领域最有影响力的专家之一就在我家附近工作。永远不要想当然地认为你了解事物的概率。

Pause for a moment to reflect on that. There were over six billion people in the world at the time, and one of the most published experts in the field worked within walking distance of my home. Never assume you understand the odds of things.

我去看了医生，几分钟内他就给我做了诊断。我得了一种叫做局灶性肌张力障碍的病，这种病常见于那些用手重复性工作的人，主要是音乐家、绘图员之类的。这不是腕管综合症。这次不一样。

I met with the doctor, and he diagnosed me in minutes. I had something called a focal dystonia, common to people who do repetitive tasks with their hands, primarily musicians, draftsmen, and the like. It wasn’t carpal tunnel. This was different.

“有什么治疗方法？”我问。

“What’s the cure?” I asked.

“换工作吧，”他说，“目前还没有有效的治疗方法。”

“Change jobs,” he said. “There’s no known treatment.”

我走出医生的办公室，感觉生活彻底崩溃了。我当一辈子漫画家的梦想彻底破灭了——除非我能找到方法，成为世界上第一个战胜局灶性肌张力障碍的人。

I walked out of the doctor’s office with my life demolished. My dream of being a cartoonist for the rest of my life was over—unless I found a way to be the first person in the world to beat a focal dystonia.

那有什么奇怪的？

What were the odds of that?

我的乐观情绪过了好几天才恢复。我的乐观就像一只老猫，喜欢消失好几天，但我总是期待着它回来。坦白说，在那之前我生活中累积的事件让我感觉自己不受正常概率的束缚，这或许就是我乐观的根源。如果你需要一个更科学的解释，也许我只是不擅长估计事情发生的概率。又或许我有选择性记忆，会忘记那些不顺利的事情。无论你如何解释这种感觉，我都喜欢为希望留有余地，而希望本身就具有实际价值。我不需要知道为什么我的远景目标比我那不靠谱的大脑预期的更经常成功；我只需要感知到——无论准确与否——它确实发生了。

It took a few days for my baseline optimism to return. My optimism is like an old cat that likes to disappear for days but I always expect to return. And frankly, the cumulative events in my life up to that point gave me a sensation of being exempt from the normal laws of chance, and that’s probably the source of my optimism. If you need a more scientific-sounding explanation, perhaps I’m just bad at estimating the odds of things. Or perhaps I have selective memory and forget the things that don’t work out. No matter how you explain the perception, I like to leave room for hope, and hope has practical value. I don’t need to know why my long shots seem to work out more often than my faulty brain expects; I just need to perceive—accurately or not—that it happens.

说实话，我成为地球上第一个战胜局灶性肌张力障碍的人的概率有多大？百万分之一？千万分之一？我不在乎。那个人就是我。由于我奇特的人生经历和更奇特的基因，我天生就认为，无论事情看起来多么不可能，最终都会好起来。

Realistically, what were my odds of being the first person on Earth to beat a focal dystonia? One-in-a-million? One-in-ten-million? I didn’t care. That one person was going to be me. Thanks to my odd life experiences and odder genes, I’m wired to think things will work out well for me no matter how unlikely it might seem.

在一次复诊中，医生问我是否愿意尝试一些实验性疗法，和他正在研究的其他人体实验鼠一起。我同意了。接下来的几个星期里，我尝试了各种手部锻炼，去看了物理治疗师，还尝试了冥想、皮肤电反应反馈、自我催眠，以及任何看起来有点效果的方法。但一点效果都没有，一点儿也没有。

In a follow-up visit, the doctor asked if I would be willing to try a few experimental treatments, joining with some other human guinea pigs he was working with. I agreed. For weeks, I tried various hand exercises, went to a physical therapist, and tried meditation, galvanic skin response feedback, self-hypnosis, and anything else that seemed like it made a grain of sense. Nothing worked, not even a little.

与此同时，我尝试用左手画呆伯特，这需要付出很多努力。我的左右手都比较灵活，但用非惯用手画画非常困难。我感觉用左手画画不是长久之计。那段时间，我的画画特别糟糕，有几个月都画得很糟糕。

Meanwhile, I tried to draw Dilbert left-handed, which I could do with a lot of effort. I’m mildly ambidextrous, but drawing with the non-dominant hand is highly difficult. I could tell that drawing lefty wouldn’t be a long-term solution. My drawings were extra terrible for a few months during that period.

我试过用绑带绑住我的小指，但奇怪的是，这导致我手的其他部分无法活动。而且疼得要命。

I tried strapping down my pinky, but that had the odd effect of making the rest of my hand dysfunctional. And it hurt like crazy.

我还失去了用笔在纸上写简单笔记的能力，这显然给我的日常工作带来了不便。奇怪的是，小指痉挛只发生在书写或绘画的特定动作中。除此之外，我的手完全正常。更奇怪的是，当我用左手画画时，右手的小指也会痉挛，所以显然问题出在我大脑的神经连接上，而不是手的结构上。我的经历与医生的研究一致。所有患有局灶性肌张力障碍的人的手部结构似乎都没有任何异常。这似乎是大脑的某种短路。

I also lost the ability to write simple notes using pen on paper, which was obviously inconvenient at my day job. Oddly, the pinky spasms only happened during the specific motions involved in writing or drawing. Otherwise, my hand was 100 percent normal. Weirder still, when I drew with my left hand, the pinky on my right hand would spasm, so obviously the wiring in my brain was the problem, not the architecture of my hand. My experience was consistent with the doctor’s research. None of the people who have focal dystonias seem to have anything abnormal in the structure of their hands. It seems to be some sort of short-circuit in the brain.

在我的日常工作中，每当我坐在无休止的无聊会议中，我就开始练习我的绘画动作：用笔触碰纸张，然后在痉挛开始前收回。每次开会，我都会在桌子底下，用放在腿上的记事本敲击纸张数百次。我的想法是逐渐重塑我的大脑，重新学习我可以触碰笔触而不会痉挛。我实际上是在试图“破解”我的大脑。我的催眠训练（稍后会详细介绍）表明，这可能是可行的。

At my day job, as I sat through endless boring meetings, I started practicing my drawing motion by touching my pen to paper and then pulling up before the spasm started. I tapped the page hundreds of times per meeting under the table on the notepad on my lap. My idea was to rewire my brain gradually, to relearn that I can touch pen to paper and not spasm. I was literally trying to hack my brain. My hypnosis training (more on that later) suggested this might be possible.

接下来的几周里，我注意到我能够把笔放在纸上坚持整整一秒钟，然后才会感觉到小指痉挛。最终，是两秒，然后是五秒。有一天，我训练自己把笔放在纸上坚持几秒钟而不痉挛，之后我的大脑突然意外地自我修复，彻底消除了肌张力障碍。显然，我打破了痉挛循环，并强化了非痉挛的联想。

Over the next several weeks, I noticed I could hold my pen to paper for a full second before feeling the onset of a pinky spasm. Eventually, it was two seconds, then five. One day, after I trained myself to hold pen to paper for several seconds without a spasm, my brain suddenly and unexpectedly rewired itself and removed the dystonia altogether. Apparently, I broke the spasm cycle and reinforced the non-spasm association.

所以，至少就我所知，我是世界上第一个治愈局灶性肌张力障碍的人。我完全有可能错了，因为我无法知道其他人是怎么做的，也不知道什么方法对他们有效。不过，这仍然是一个不太可能的结果。

And so I was the first person in the world to cure a focal dystonia, at least as far as I know. It’s entirely possible that I’m wrong about that since I can’t know what everyone else is doing or what worked for them. Still, it was an unlikely result.

我又开始用右手画画，调整了自己的节奏，好几年都没再出问题。我的手科医生说，虽然我的名字没有被提及，但我现在已经成了这方面的文献的一部分。

I went back to drawing right-handed, paced myself, and didn’t have a problem again for years. My hand doctor said I’m part of the literature on this topic now, although my name is not mentioned.

2004年，我又一次在紧张的时间内画了太多画，肌张力障碍又复发了。这次，我尝试了一个更聪明的解决方法。我做了一个有根据的猜测，世界上某个地方可能有公司正在生产平板电脑或屏幕，让我可以在上面画漫画。我的假设是，在电脑上绘画的感觉和在纸上画的感觉足够不同，所以肌张力障碍不会引发，即使我用手写笔画得和用钢笔一样。

In 2004, after once again doing too much drawing in a compressed time, the dystonia returned. This time, I tried a smarter workaround. I made an educated guess that somewhere in the world a company was probably making a computer tablet or screen on which I could draw my comic. My hypothesis was that drawing on a computer would feel different enough from pen on paper that the dystonia wouldn’t trigger, even though I would be drawing with a stylus just as I would with a pen.

我在谷歌上搜索了一下，发现Wacom正在为艺术家制作一款专用电脑显示器。我当天就订购了。一周后，它就安装好了，可以正常使用了。正如我所希望的那样，在电脑上作画的感觉完全不同，肌张力障碍没有复发。而且，通过不强化触发因素和痉挛，我让肌张力障碍自然消失了。我确信如果我长时间在纸上画画或写字，它肯定会复发，但既然这种情况永远不会发生，它对我来说就不是什么问题了。

I did some Google searches and discovered that Wacom was making a special computer monitor for artists. I ordered it the same day. In a week, it was up and running. As I hoped, drawing on the computer was different enough that the dystonia didn’t reoccur. And by not reinforcing the trigger and the spasm, I allowed the dystonia to simply fade away. I’m sure it would come back if I tried drawing or writing on paper for a long time, but since that will never happen, it’s a non-issue in my life.

顺便说一句，用 Wacom 产品作画让我的总工作时间减少了一半。对于一位漫画家来说，局限性肌张力障碍真是倒霉透顶。但当我彻底解决了肌张力障碍的问题，并彻底解决了它的难题后，我变成了一个效率高得多的漫画家。由于 Wacom 的细微调整非常容易，我的画作质量也得到了显著提升。总的来说，我进步很大。

By the way, drawing on the Wacom product cut my total workday in half. The focal dystonia was a case of extraordinary bad luck for a cartoonist. But when I got done beating the dystonia problem to death and rifling through its pockets, I came out the other end a far more efficient cartoonist. The quality of my drawing improved dramatically on the Wacom because it’s so easy to make small adjustments. On balance, I came out way ahead.

第十五章

Chapter 15

我的演讲生涯

My Speaking Career

哈有个例子可以说明拥有一个聪明的朋友是多么有用。我从事漫画创作几年后，一位加拿大女士打电话问我是否愿意在卡尔加里的一个石油工程师组织发表演讲。我说我不做那种工作，但她坚持说，是组织特别邀请我去的，而且报酬丰厚。我一直犹豫不决，因为我的时间安排非常不灵活。那时，我仍然在太平洋贝尔做全职工作，工作前后以及周末都要创作《呆伯特》 。去加拿大旅行根本不是一个现实的选择。

Here’s an example of how useful it is to have a smart friend. When I was a few years into my cartooning career, a Canadian woman called and asked if I would give a speech to an organization of petroleum engineers in Calgary. I said I didn’t do that sort of work, but she persisted, saying the organization had asked for me, specifically, and that there would be a healthy payment involved. I continued to balk because I had very little flexibility in my schedule. At that point, I was still working my full-time job at Pacific Bell and creating Dilbert before and after work, plus on weekends. Traveling to Canada just wasn’t a practical option.

这位加拿大女士建议我给她报个价，让她觉得我的服务物有所值。如果我的价钱太高，至少她可以把钱退回到她的机构，说她已经尽力了。她这么说，就好像我为了一件我不想做的事情出价，是在帮她一个忙似的。

The Canadian woman suggested I give her a price for my services that would make it worthwhile for me. If my price was too high, at least she could take it back to her organization and say she tried. She made it sound as if I would be doing her a favor to come up with a price for something I didn’t want to do.

但是演讲的价钱该怎么算呢？我完全不知道从何下手。所以我做了任何遇到这种情况的人都会做的事：我找了一位朋友，他可能有这方面的模板。

But how does one come up with a price for giving a speech? I had no idea where to start. So I did what anyone in that situation would do: I sought out a friend who might have a template for this sort of thing.

当时，《呆伯特》由联合传媒（United Media）旗下的一个机构联合发行，这是一家总部位于纽约的大型授权和联合发行公司。我猜想得没错，这个机构里肯定有人有专业演讲的经验。我打电话给一位高级副总裁，他曾是一位畅销书作家，拥有数十年的经验，这让他比我更有资格谈论这类话题。

At the time, Dilbert was syndicated by an organization within United Media, a large licensing and syndication business headquartered in New York City. I figured correctly that someone in that hierarchy would have experience with professional speaking. I called a Senior Vice President who had once been a bestselling author and had decades of experience that made him far more qualified than I was for this sort of topic.

我问他：“我该怎么报这个价？”我告诉他，我很乐意为此付出代价。他说：“开价五千美元吧。如果他们不答应，你就不用去加拿大一趟了。”我笑了笑，因为我知道自己不值这么多钱。但我有自己的计划。我反复练习说“五千美元”，直到我觉得说出来不会让人笑出来。我回拨了电话给我的加拿大联系人。对话是这样的：

I put the question to him: “What should I say is my price for speaking?” I told him that I would be perfectly happy to price myself out of the job. He said, “Ask for five thousand dollars. If they say no, you avoid a trip to Canada.” I laughed at his suggestion, knowing that I wasn’t worth that kind of money. But I had my plan. I practiced saying “five thousand dollars” until I thought I could say it without laughing. I called back my Canadian contact. That conversation went like this:

加拿大人：“你们想好价格了吗？”

Canadian: “Did you come up with a price?”

我：“是的……五千美元。”

Me: “Yes . . . five thousand dollars.”

加拿大人：“好的，我们还会支付您的头等舱旅行和酒店费用。”

Canadian: “Okay, and we’ll also pay for your first-class travel and hotel.”

我飞到加拿大并发表了演讲。

I flew to Canada and gave a speech.

随着时间的推移，呆伯特的名气越来越大，演讲邀请也越来越多，通常一天好几个。我把价格提高到1万美元。邀请源源不断。我尝试了1.5万美元。邀请越来越多。等到我把价格定到2.5万美元的时候，演讲机构开始把我看作能带来更多佣金的来源，建议我把价格提高到3.5万美元，然后是4.5万美元。我因为时间安排冲突而拒绝过的最高报价是10万美元，让我就任何我想谈的话题进行一小时的演讲。

As time went by and Dilbert became more well-known, more speaking requests flowed in, often several per day. I raised my price to $10,000. The requests kept coming. I tried $15,000. The requests accelerated. By the time I got to $25,000, the speakers bureaus started to see me as a source of bigger commissions and advised me to raise my price to $35,000, then $45,000. The largest offer I ever turned down because of a scheduling conflict was $100,000 to speak for an hour on any topic I wanted.

这一切之所以成为可能，是因为我认识一位聪明的朋友，他告诉我如何找到进入演讲圈的简单切入点。我只需要给自己抬高价格，看看会发生什么。回想起来，这听起来很简单，但我怀疑自己是否真的会走上这条路。我想我会礼貌地拒绝这份邀请。

All of this was possible because I had access to a smart friend who told me how to find the simple entry point into the speaking circuit. All I needed to do was overprice myself and see what happened. As simple as that sounds in retrospect, I doubt I would have taken that path on my own. I think I would have politely declined the invitation.

俗话说，成功取决于你认识的人。但不太明显的是，你不需要认识CEO和亿万富翁。有时候，你只需要一个和你了解不同领域的朋友。你总能找到这样的朋友。

It’s a cliché that who you know is helpful for success. What is less obvious is that you don’t need to know CEOs and billionaires. Sometimes you just need a friend who knows different things than you do. And you can always find one of those.

第十六章

Chapter 16

我的声音问题有了名字

My Voice Problem Gets a Name

秒2005年失声六个月后，我仍然不知道问题的根源。这真是令人沮丧。我不介意公平地战斗，但这个看不见、无名的问题却让我苦不堪言，我甚至不知道该如何反击。我需要为我的病情找个名字。我想，如果我知道它的名字，就能找到治愈的方法。

Six months after losing my voice back in 2005, I still didn’t know what the source of the problem was. It was immensely frustrating. I don’t mind a fair fight, but this invisible, nameless problem was kicking my ass, and I didn’t even know which direction to punch back. I needed a name for my condition. I figured if I knew its name, that would lead me down the trail for a cure.

但我该如何找到一个连两位耳鼻喉科医生、两位语音专家、一位心理学家、一位神经科医生以及我的全科医生都陌生的病症的名称呢？只有一个生物比所有这些医生加起来还要聪明：互联网。（没错，它确实是一个生物，懂吗？）

But how could I find the name for a condition that was unfamiliar to two ear-nose-throat doctors, two voice specialists, a psychologist, a neurologist, and my general practitioner? There was only one creature smarter than all those doctors put together: the Internet. (Yes, it’s a creature, okay?)

我打开谷歌搜索框，尝试了各种与声音相关的关键词。结果一无所获。我的搜索范围太广了。然后发生了一件有趣的事情。这种现象在创意行业的人中很常见，但对其他人来说可能并不常见。突然，不知何故，两个毫不相干的想法——它们被话题、时间和距离隔开——在我的脑海里交织在一起。不知何故，我突然想起了几年前我画画时遇到的问题。当时，我的小指无法控制。现在，我又无法控制自己的声音了。这两个问题会不会有什么关联？

I opened a Google search box and tried a variety of voice-related keywords. I found nothing useful. My searches were too broad. Then something interesting happened. It’s a phenomenon that people in creative jobs experience often, but it might sound unfamiliar to everyone else. Suddenly, out of nowhere, two totally unrelated thoughts—separated by topic, time, and distance—came together in my head. For some reason, I had a spontaneous memory of the problem with my drawing hand that I had experienced several years earlier. In that case, I lost control of my pinky. Now I was losing control of my voice. Could the two problems be related?

我输入了“发声障碍”这个关键词，因为我的手部问题被称为局灶性肌张力障碍。结果！搜索结果弹出一段视频，视频中一位病人患有一种叫做痉挛性发声障碍的疾病，这种疾病的症状是声带在发出某些声音时会不由自主地收缩。我播放了视频，识别出视频中病人的发音模式和我一模一样——断断续续的单词和短促的音节。现在我知道了它的名字：痉挛性发声障碍。我发现这种疾病通常与其他类型的肌张力障碍有关。随着进一步研究，我了解到，患有一种类型肌张力障碍的人通常会患上另一种。（幸运的是，这种疾病通常不会进一步发展。）

I entered the search string “voice dystonia” because my hand problem was called a focal dystonia. Bingo. The search popped up a video of a patient who had something called spasmodic dysphonia, a condition in which the vocal cords clench involuntarily when making certain sounds. I played the video and recognized my exact voice pattern—broken words and clipped syllables—coming out of the patient in the video. Now I had its name: spasmodic dysphonia, which I discovered is often associated with other forms of dystonia. As I learned with further research, it’s common for someone who has one type of dystonia to get another. (Luckily, it doesn’t tend to progress beyond that.)

我的秘密杀手有名字了，现在我知道了。这感觉就像一个转折点。

My secret assassin had a name, and now I knew it. It felt like a turning point.

我打印了一份关于痉挛性发声障碍的描述，带给了我的医生。他把我转诊给了我的一位耳鼻喉科医生，这位医生又把我转诊给了一位我之前在凯撒医疗体系里没见过的医生。结果发现，她正是这方面的专家。我刚在她办公室张开嘴，不到十秒钟，医生就确认了我的诊断。我的情况很典型。

I printed out a description of spasmodic dysphonia and took it to my doctor. He referred me back to one of my ear-nose-throat doctors, who in turn referred me to a doctor I hadn’t yet seen in the Kaiser healthcare system. She turned out to be an expert in that exact condition. Within ten seconds of opening my mouth in her office, the doctor confirmed the diagnosis. I had a classic case.

“有什么办法可以治愈吗？”我低声问道。

“What’s the cure?” I whispered.

“没有，”她回答道。

“There is none,” she replied.

但我听到的并非如此。我内心的乐观主义者将这令人沮丧的消息解读为：“斯科特，你将是世界上第一个治愈痉挛性发声障碍的人。” 我决定，等我治愈了自己之后，无论如何，都要把这个消息告诉其他人。我不会满足于仅仅逃离沉默的牢笼；我计划越狱，解救其他囚犯，枪杀典狱长，烧毁监狱。

But that isn’t what I heard. The optimist in me translated the gloomy news as “Scott, you will be the first person in the world to be cured of spasmodic dysphonia.” And I decided that after I cured myself, somehow, someway, I would spread the word to others. I wouldn’t be satisfied simply escaping from my prison of silence; I was planning to escape, free the other inmates, shoot the warden, and burn down the prison.

有时我也会这样。

Sometimes I get that way.

这是一种出人意料地有用的心态。

It’s a surprisingly useful frame of mind.

第十七章

Chapter 17

无效的语音解决方案

The Voice Solution That Didn’t Work

T痉挛性发声障碍的标准治疗方法是，医生将一根装满肉毒杆菌毒素（其商品名 Botox）的针头从患者的颈前推入，希望毒素能够到达喉咙后侧的声带区域。注射毒素的医生会结合经验、猜测和电子设备来确定合适的剂量和注射位置。如果一切顺利，患者的声音可以在几周后恢复正常，并能维持数周直至肉毒杆菌毒素的药效消失。然后重复注射。这个过程令人毛骨悚然，因为针头非常粗，你需要先注射局部麻醉剂，以防止第二根针刺入时疼痛难忍。这可不是愉快的一天。

The standard treatment for spasmodic dysphonia involves a doctor pushing a needle filled with Botulinum toxin (better known by its trade name Botox) through the front of the patient’s neck and hoping it finds the vocal cord region on the back side of the throat. Doctors who give the shot use a mixture of experience, guesswork, and electronics to find the right dose and the right place to put it. If all goes well, a patient’s voice can normalize after a few weeks and stay functional for several weeks until the Botox wears off. Then you repeat. It’s a creepy process because the needle is so thick you need an initial shot of local anesthetics just to keep you from going through the roof when the second needle goes in. It’s not a fun day.

我尝试了几个月的肉毒杆菌注射。效果不错，我和雪莉结婚时说了“我愿意”，这感觉很棒，但几周后药效就消失了。之后的注射效果也差强人意。问题是，两次注射的效果都不一样，一部分原因是你永远不知道体内还有多少肉毒杆菌，另一部分原因是注射两次的部位从来不会完全一样。而且剂量总是在增加或减少的过程中逐渐增大。只有在增加或减少的一周左右的时间里，才会偶然达到合适的剂量。

I tried the Botox treatments for a few months. It worked well enough to say, “I do” when I got married to Shelly, which was great, but it wore off in a few weeks. Subsequent shots were not nearly as effective. The problem is that no two shots were ever the same, in part because you never knew how much Botox was still in your system, and partly because the shot never hits exactly the same place twice. And the dose is always either ramping up or wearing off. It only hits the right dose level by accident for a week or so on the way up or down.

对我来说，更大的问题是肉毒杆菌毒素掩盖了我想尝试的其他任何治疗的效果。我决定停止肉毒杆菌毒素注射，给自己一个机会，找到一个持久的治疗方案。

The bigger issue for me was that the Botox masked the impact of any other type of treatment I might want to experiment with. I made the decision to stop the Botox and give myself a chance to find a lasting fix.

注射了肉毒杆菌后，我知道我有时能找到办法几乎正常地说话。没有它，我几乎与现实生活隔绝了。我就像在用力挥棒击打一个我甚至看不见的球。

With the Botox, I knew I could find a way to talk almost normally some of the time. Without it, I was pretty much shut off from the world of the living. I was taking a big swing at a ball I couldn’t even see.

第十八章

Chapter 18

认识到自己的才能并知道何时放弃

Recognizing Your Talents and Knowing When to Quit

我如果你拥有世界级的天赋——无论在什么领域——你可能已经意识到了。事实上，你小时候，父母可能带着你四处奔波，培养你的技能。但世界级的天赋是个例外，所以我更愿意在本书中忽略它。我将重点关注普通的天赋，以及普通天赋的组合，它们最终成就非凡。就普通天赋而言，你如何知道你的哪些技能可以组合在一起，从而产生有用的东西？这是一个至关重要的问题，因为你想把注意力放在真正能带来改变的地方。

If you have world-class talent—for anything—you probably know it. In fact, your parents probably dragged you from place to place when you were young to develop your skill. But world-class talent is such an exception that I prefer ignoring it for this book. I’m going to focus on ordinary talents and combinations of ordinary talents that sum up to something extraordinary. In the case of ordinary talent, how do you know which of your various skills can be added together to get something useful? It’s a vital question because you want to put your focus where it makes a real difference.

想要知道自己在哪些方面可能拥有额外的天赋，一个有用的经验法则是想想自己十岁之前痴迷于什么。你的兴趣和你擅长的事情之间有着密切的联系。人们自然而然地会被那些让他们感到舒适的事情所吸引，而舒适感正是天赋的标志。

One helpful rule of thumb for knowing where you might have a little extra talent is to consider what you were obsessively doing before you were ten years old. There’s a strong connection between what interests you and what you’re good at. People are naturally drawn to the things they feel comfortable doing, and comfort is a marker for talent.

就我而言，从我拿起蜡笔的时候起，我就痴迷于涂鸦和绘画。我从未成为一名有天赋的艺术家，但我对绘画的浓厚兴趣预示着我几十年后的职业生涯。当然，大多数孩子都喜欢艺术，有些人比其他孩子更喜欢。但我却不同寻常。我在学校上课时一直涂鸦。我用棍子在泥土上画画。我在雪地里画画。对我来说，绘画是一种强迫症，而不是一种选择。童年的强迫症并不能保证未来的天赋。但我的非科学观察是，人们生来就具有某些偏好。这些偏好驱动着行为，而这正是让人愿意练习一项技能的原因。过去几年备受关注的一项研究发现，要成为几乎任何领域的“专家”都需要 10,000 小时的自律练习。1作家马尔科姆·格拉德威尔在他的《异类》一书中写到了这一点。很少有人会为一项技能投入如此多的练习。但早期的痴迷可以预测孩子将来可能擅长哪些技能。

In my case, I was doodling and drawing obsessively from the time I could pick up a crayon. I never became a talented artist, but my high level of interest in drawing foreshadowed my career decades later. Granted, most kids enjoy art, and some enjoy it a lot more than others. But I was off the chart. I doodled all through my classes in school. I drew in the dirt with sticks. I drew in the snow. For me, drawing was more of a compulsion than a choice. Childhood compulsions aren’t a guarantee of future talent. But my unscientific observation is that people are born wired for certain preferences. Those preferences drive behavior, and that’s what can make a person willing to practice a skill. A study that got a lot of attention in the past few years involved the discovery that becoming an “expert” at just about anything requires 10,000 hours of disciplined practice.1 Author Malcolm Gladwell wrote about it in his book Outliers. Few people will put in that kind of practice for one skill. But early obsessions can predict which skills a kid might someday be good at.

天赋的另一个线索是敢于承担风险。小学时，我经常画一些滑稽而不恰当的漫画，内容涉及我的老师和同学。我会把这些漫画展示给同学们，让他们开怀大笑，同时我也知道，如果被权威人士发现，后果不堪设想。为了所谓的艺术，我愿意承担巨大的个人风险，这与我规避风险的生活方式形成了鲜明对比。人们通常只有在预期回报丰厚时才会承担巨大的风险。画不恰当的漫画让我感到快乐。对我来说，这值得冒险。

Another clue to talent involves tolerance for risk. When I was in grade school, I often drew humorously inappropriate comics involving my teachers and fellow students. I would show them to classmates, and I enjoyed making them laugh, all the while knowing that getting caught by an authority figure meant a serious penalty. I was willing to take a significant personal risk for my so-called art, and this was in sharp contrast to my otherwise risk-averse lifestyle. People generally only accept outsized risk when they expect big payoffs. Drawing inappropriate comics made me happy. To me, it was worth the risk.

我十几岁的时候有一辆非常老旧的摩托车。我用自己创业挣的150美元买了它，当时我一边当割草机，一边当铲雪机，还给农场主当了个不称职的助手。当然，这辆摩托车很危险，尤其是在十几岁的青少年手里。我在当地的小路上把它摔了好几次。有好几次，我差点儿撞到鹿、愤怒的狗和其他司机。有一天，我飞驰过一片田野，前轮撞进了一个土拨鼠洞，然后飞了起来，奇迹般地落在了一片散落着大石头的田野里，没有碰到什么坚硬的东西。我喜欢拥有一辆摩托车，但并没有因此而痴迷。最终我得出结论，它不值得我冒这个险。显然，我注定不会成为摩托车冒险家或越野摩托车明星。我不愿意为了骑行的乐趣而承担高风险。但说到漫画，我却甘愿承担被开除的风险，以及侮辱比我大的孩子所带来的巨大身体伤害。我的风险偏好预示了我的未来。

I owned a very used, very old motorcycle when I was a teen. I paid $150 from my earnings as an entrepreneurial mower of lawns, shoveler of show, and a farmer’s incompetent assistant. The motorcycle was dangerous, of course, especially in the hands of a teen. I laid it down a few times on the local back roads. On a number of occasions, I barely missed deer, angry dogs, and other motorists. One day I was barreling across a field and drove the front wheel into a woodchuck hole, thus taking flight and miraculously landing on nothing hard in a field littered with large rocks. I enjoyed having a motorcycle, but it wasn’t an obsession for me. And eventually I concluded that it wasn’t worth the risk. Clearly I was not destined to be a motorcycle daredevil or motocross star. I wasn’t willing to accept a high risk in return for the joy of riding. But when it came to comics, I eagerly accepted the risk of expulsion and great bodily harm that comes with insulting larger kids. My risk profile predicted my future.

当你听到著名演员小时候的故事时，你会注意到一个规律：在他们成为明星之前，他们就在自家的客厅和后院里表演戏剧。这对于一个孩子来说，已经够大胆了。一个敢于在人群面前——哪怕是一群友善的观众——冒着尴尬风险的孩子，很可能拥有一些娱乐天赋。

When you hear stories about famous actors as kids, one of the patterns you notice is that before they were stars, they were staging plays in their living rooms and backyards. That’s gutsy for a kid. A child who eagerly accepts the risk of embarrassment in front of a crowd—even a friendly crowd—probably has some talent for entertaining.

回顾一下比尔·盖茨和史蒂夫·乔布斯的传记。年轻时，两人都在科技领域承担了法律风险。比尔·盖茨最著名的成就是，他通过利用大型机来磨练自己的技术技能。乔布斯和沃兹尼亚克的第一款产品销售的技术可以窃取长途电话通话记录。凡是能容忍风险的人，往往就拥有人才。

Consider the biographies of Bill Gates and Steve Jobs. As young men, both took legal risks in the field of technology. Bill Gates famously found ways to hone his technical skills by stealing time on a mainframe.2. Jobs’ and Wozniak’s first product involved selling technology that allowed people to steal long distance phone calls. Where there is a tolerance for risk, there is often talent.

童年的痴迷和对风险的承受能力充其量只是天赋的粗略参考。随着你的成长和获得更多的天赋，你潜在的成功之路会迅速倍增。这使得你很难知道在众多可能性中，哪种能让你占据竞争优势。你应该选择一份能运用你的摄影和软件知识的职业，还是一份能运用你的公开演讲技巧和写作天赋的职业？你无法完全确定哪条路会最有成果。

Childhood obsessions and tolerance for risk are only rough guides to talent at best. As you grow and acquire more talents, your potential paths for success multiply quickly. That makes it extra hard to know which possibility among many would put you in a position of competitive advantage. Should you pursue a career that uses your knowledge of photography and software, or something that uses your public speaking skills and your gift for writing? There’s no way to be completely sure which path will be most fruitful.

辨别最佳成功之路的最明智方法在于尝试各种不同的事物——如果你愿意，也可以称之为“采样”。对于创业公司来说，如果事情进展不顺利，这可能意味着你很快就会放弃。

The smartest system for discerning your best path to success involves trying lots of different things—sampling, if you will. For entrepreneurial ventures, it might mean quickly bailing out if things don’t come together quickly.

这种方法可能与你一生中听到的建议相矛盾——无论遇到什么障碍，坚持做某事都是成功的关键。事实上，大多数成功人士都曾在某个时刻经历过挫折。克服障碍通常是成功过程中不可避免的一部分。但你也需要知道何时放弃。坚持固然有用，但愚蠢地坚持下去毫无意义。

That approach might conflict with the advice you’ve heard all your life—that sticking with something, no matter the obstacles, is important to success. Indeed, most successful people had to chew through a wall at some point. Overcoming obstacles is normally an unavoidable part of the process. But you also need to know when to quit. Persistence is useful, but there’s no point being an idiot about it.

我决定何时放弃的准则源于我一生尝试过数十个商业创意，其中大多数都失败了。我也仔细观察过其他人在“去留”抉择中挣扎的历程。有时，我会因为错误地认为坚持是一种美德而长期坚持糟糕的想法。我注意到的规律是：终有一天会成功的事情，一开始总是好的。永远行不通的事情，一开始总是坏的，而且一直如此。你很少看到胎死腹中的失败最终蜕变成巨大的成功。小成功可以发展成大成功，但失败很少能转化为成功。

My guideline for deciding when to quit is informed by a lifetime of trying dozens of business ideas, most of them failures. I’ve also carefully observed others struggling with the stay-or-quit decision. There have been times I stuck with bad ideas for far too long out of a misguided sense that persistence is a virtue. The pattern I noticed was this: Things that will someday work out well start out well. Things that will never work start out bad and stay that way. What you rarely see is a stillborn failure that transmogrifies into a stellar success. Small successes can grow into big ones, but failures rarely grow into successes.

为了说明我的观点，不妨回顾一下手机的历史。早期的手机信号一直很差，容易掉线，功能很少，价格昂贵，而且装不下口袋。然而，至少从需求来看，手机在第一天就取得了成功。尽管手机存在诸多缺陷——这些缺陷持续了几十年——但需求一开始就很旺盛，而且一直保持强劲。产品质量差并没有造成任何影响。手机最初只是取得了小小的成功，然后逐渐发展壮大。

To illustrate my point, consider the history of cell phones. Early cell phones had bad reception all the time. They dropped calls. They had few features. They were expensive. They didn’t fit in your pocket. Yet cell phones were successful, at least in terms of demand, on day one. Despite the many flaws with cell phones—flaws that lasted decades—demand started brisk and stayed strong. The poor quality of the product made no difference. Cell phones started as a small success and grew.

传真机也经历了类似的发展历程。早期的传真机速度慢，而且极其不可靠。它们会吞噬你的原件，有时只会向对方机器发送清晰的副本。尽管如此，传真机从一开始就有需求，并且一直持续增长，直到计算机时代的到来，它们变得不再那么重要。

Fax machines followed a similar path. The early fax machines were slow and spectacularly unreliable. They would eat your original and only sometimes deliver a legible copy to the other machine. Still, fax machines had demand from the beginning and grew until the age of computers rendered them less necessary.

第一批个人电脑速度慢、价格昂贵、操作不直观，而且容易崩溃。但需求依然呈爆炸式增长。在每个例子中，早期产品的质量都无法准确预测其成功。真正的原因是，在优质产品问世之前，消费者就已经迫不及待地想要劣质产品了。这就像未来的成功会留下一些痕迹，而这些痕迹在现在依然可见。

The first personal computers were slow, expensive, non-intuitive, and crash-prone. And still the demand was explosive. In each of the examples, the quality of the early products was a poor predictor of success. The predictor is that customers were clamoring for the bad versions of the product before the good versions were even invented. It’s as if a future success leaves bread crumbs that are visible in the present.

1989年，福克斯电视台推出《辛普森一家》，从第一天起就风靡全国。无论我走到哪里，人们都会提起《辛普森一家》：“你看了吗？” 有趣的是，尽管《辛普森一家》经常在联合播出，但你很少看到第一季的重播。根据我看过的片段，我猜想，原因是以今天的标准来看，这部剧的品质低劣得令人尴尬。最初的画面看起来很业余，剧本充满暴力和幼稚的闹剧。与今天相比，《辛普森一家》的第一季简直是烂片。同样，质量并不能预示着成功。更准确的预测是，尽管《辛普森一家》表面上质量不高，但它却一炮走红。它拥有未知因素。随着时间的推移，它逐渐成为有史以来最重要、最具创意、最优秀的电视剧之一。

When FOX launched The Simpsons in 1989, it was a national phenomenon from day one. Everywhere I went, the topic of the Simpsons came up: “Did you see it?” Interestingly, as much as The Simpsons is rebroadcast in syndication, you won’t often see that first season repeated. The reason, I assume, based on clips I’ve seen, is that by today’s standards it would be judged to be embarrassingly bad. The original art looked amateurish, and the writing was violent, sophomoric slapstick. Compared to today, the first Simpsons season was an awful product. Again, the quality didn’t predict success. The better predictor is that The Simpsons was an immediate hit despite its surface quality. It had the X-factor. In time, it grew to be one of the most important, creative, and best shows of all time.

我创作《呆伯特》的经历也遵循着同样的模式。1988年，我向几家漫画联合组织提交了最初的《呆伯特》样本。联合传媒给了我一份合同，并在1989年《呆伯特》创刊时成功地将其卖给了几十家报纸。一年后，报纸销量停滞不前，联合传媒将注意力转向了其他漫画作品。在接下来的五年里，我找到了一种方法，通过写书和利用互联网来激发人们对《呆伯特》的兴趣。 《呆伯特》的转折点出现在1993年，当时我开始在漫画页边空白处印上我的电子邮件地址。那是我第一次能够看到对我作品的未经过滤的评论。在那之前，我一直依赖朋友和商业伙伴的意见，但这些意见的价值有限，因为他们很少提出批评。但哇，公众毫不留情。他们对我的艺术技巧怒不可遏——这并不奇怪——而这只是仇恨山的一角。但我注意到，粉丝和反对者都有一个共同点：他们都更喜欢呆伯特在办公室的漫画。所以我把漫画的焦点转移到了工作场所，结果这成了火花。

My experience with Dilbert followed the same pattern. I submitted my original samples of Dilbert to several comic syndication companies in 1988. United Media offered me a contract and successfully sold it into a few dozen newspapers at its launch in 1989. A year later, sales to newspapers stalled, and United Media turned its attention to other comic properties. Over the next five years, I found a way to generate more interest in Dilbert by writing books and exploiting the Internet. The turning point for Dilbert came in 1993 after I started printing my email address in the margins of the strip. It was the first time I could see unfiltered opinions about my work. Until then, I’d relied on the opinions of friends and business associates, which had limited value because that group of folks rarely offered criticism. But WOW, the general public doesn’t hold back. They were savage about my art skills—no surprise—and that was just the tip of the hateberg. But I noticed a consistent theme that held for both the fans and the haters: They all preferred the comics in which Dilbert was in the office. So I changed the focus of the strip to the workplace, and that turned out to be the spark in the gasoline.

但《呆伯特》第一年就大获成功的一个预兆是，它迅速收获了一小批热情洋溢的追随者。基于一些不甚可靠的传闻，我做出的最佳估计是，98%的报纸读者最初并不喜欢《呆伯特》，但有2%的人认为它是报纸上最好的漫画之一，尽管所有客观证据都表明它并非如此。换句话说，它第一天就拥有了未知因素。这让我想起了我在好莱坞，或者至少是在好莱坞附近学到的一个教训。

But the thing that predicted Dilbert’s success in year one is that it quickly gained a small but enthusiastic following. My best estimate, based on shaky anecdotal evidence, is that 98 percent of newspaper readers initially disliked Dilbert, but 2 percent thought it was one of the best comics in the paper despite all objective evidence to the contrary. In other words, it had the X-factor on day one. And this brings me to a lesson I learned in Hollywood, or at least near Hollywood.

九十年代末，我在洛杉矶地区待了一段时间，试图让一部名为《呆伯特》的电视试播集顺利开播。第一次尝试是用真人演员扮演呆伯特角色，结果惨败。在试播过程中，我观察了试播集的观众，并实时记录他们的感受。屏幕上会显示动态图表，以便我们能够看到观众在节目每个环节的兴衰变化。我和负责这个项目的电视台高管聊天，问他们试播集观众反响的可接受范围是多少。这位高管解释说，对于电视节目来说，最好的预测指标不是平均反响。平均值对娱乐产品来说意义不大。你需要的是一小部分观众异常强烈的反响，即使大多数人讨厌它。《呆伯特》试播集在试播集的观众中反响还不错，但似乎没有人对此充满热情。这个项目最终不了了之。但在这个过程中，我学到了很多制作电视节目的经验，使得下一次尝试的进展更加顺利。动画版《呆伯特》在现已停播的联合电视网（UPN）播出了两个半季，并在这家小型电视网取得了不错的收视率。当这部剧因本书后面会描述的原因被取消时，我积累了足够的新技能、新知识和新人脉，这大大提高了我未来制作一部《呆伯特》电影的几率。大约二十五年来，我一直试图制作一部《呆伯特》电影，但都以失败告终。迄今为止，每一次失败都是因为某种怪异的厄运交织。但厄运不会永远持续下去。除非我先死，否则我一定要完成它。

In the late nineties, I spent some time in the Los Angeles area trying to get a Dilbert TV pilot off the ground. The first attempt, which failed miserably, involved live actors portraying the Dilbert characters. During that process, I got to observe a test audience watch the pilot and register their opinions in real time. Moving graphs appeared on monitors so we could see the ebb and flow of the audience’s enjoyment at each point in the show. I was chatting with the television executive in charge of the project and asked what the cut-off was for an acceptable test audience response. The executive explained that for television shows, the best predictor is not the average response. Averages don’t mean much for entertainment products. What you’re looking for is an unusually strong reaction from a subset of the public, even if the majority hates it. The Dilbert pilot got an okay response from the test audience, but no one seemed enthusiastic. The project went no further. But during the process, I learned enough about making a television show that the next attempt went far better. The animated Dilbert show ran for two half-seasons on the now-defunct UPN and got decent ratings for that tiny network. When that show got cancelled for reasons I describe later in this book, I emerged with just enough new skills, knowledge, and contacts that my odds of someday getting a Dilbert movie made are far higher. I’ve been trying and failing to get a Dilbert movie made for about twenty-five years. Every failure so far has been because of some freakish intersection of bad luck. But bad luck doesn’t have the option of being that consistent forever. I’ll get it done unless I die first.

回到我的观点，热情模型（如果我可以这么称呼它的话）有点像未知因素。它是一种难以捉摸且难以预测的品质，能让一定比例的公众为之疯狂。当未知因素出现时，公众——或者其中的一部分——会立即察觉到它。对于少数兴奋的人来说，构成品质的常规概念并不适用。随着时间的推移，那些激发热情的产品通常也会进化出品质。当市场为你注入大量资金，而你又有时间去改进时，品质是你能够承受的奢侈品之一。

Back to my point, the Enthusiasm Model, if I may call it that, is a bit like the X-factor. It’s the elusive and hard-to-predict quality of a thing that makes some percentage of the public nuts about it. When the X-factor is present, the public—or some subset of it—picks up on it right away. For the excited few, the normal notions of what constitutes quality don’t apply. In time, the products that inspire excitement typically evolve to have quality, too. Quality is one of the luxuries you can afford when the marketplace is spraying money in your direction and you have time to tinker.

想想第一代 iPhone。它的第一个版本一团糟，但却受到了近乎狂热的追捧。这种热情和随之而来的巨大销量为产品改进提供了资金，最终成就了它的卓越。

Consider the first iPhone. The first version was a mess, yet it was greeted with an almost feverish enthusiasm. That enthusiasm and the enormous sales that followed funded improvements until the product became superb.

发现X因素的最佳方法之一是观察顾客对你的想法或产品的反应，而不是他们的言论。人们倾向于说他们认为你想听的话，或者他们认为对你造成最小伤害的话。人们的行动要诚实得多。例如，对于漫画来说，一个很好的测试潜力的方法就是看人们是否会把它贴在冰箱上、张贴出来、通过电子邮件发送给朋友、发布到博客页面上，或者做其他任何积极的事情。

One of the best ways to detect the X-factor is to watch what customers do about your idea or product, not what they say. People tend to say what they think you want to hear, or what they think will cause the least pain. What people do is far more honest. For example, with comics, a good test of potential is whether people stick the comic to the refrigerator, post it, email it to friends, put it on a blog page, or do anything else active.

你可能会觉得，一个没有X因素、也没有热情粉丝的想法，随着时间的推移，也能获得这些特质。我肯定这种情况发生过，但我这辈子想不出一个例子。通常情况下，如果一开始没有人对你的艺术/产品/想法感到兴奋，那么他们就永远不会兴奋。

You might be tempted to think that sometimes an idea with no X-factor and no enthusiastic fans can gain those qualities over time. I’m sure it’s happened, but I can’t think of an example in my life. It’s generally true that if no one is excited about your art/product/idea in the beginning, they never will be.

如果你作品的第一个商业版本没有引起任何人的共鸣，那么是时候换个方向了。不要被朋友和家人的意见所蒙蔽。他们都是骗子。

If the first commercial version of your work excites no one to action, it’s time to move on to something different. Don’t be fooled by the opinions of friends and family. They’re all liars.

如果你的工作激发了顾客的热情并促使他们采取行动，那就准备好迎接挑战吧。你可能拥有一些值得你为之奋斗的东西。
