If your work inspires some excitement and some action from customers, get ready to chew through some walls. You might have something worth fighting for.

第十九章

Chapter 19

练习是你的事吗？

Is Practice Your Thing?

哦有一天，一个朋友的三岁孩子和一群青少年在我们家的网球场上玩耍。一些孩子在篮筐一端投篮，几个孩子在互相扔网球，还有一些孩子在拍排球。但是这个三岁的孩子正在专心练习击球。他会把球拍起来，眼睛盯着球，然后挥动球拍。他击球的次数比你想象的三岁孩子的要多得多，但这并不是最有趣的部分。我观察了几分钟，他独自练习，无视周围年龄较大的孩子。他本来是一个喜欢社交的孩子，但这个击球的简单任务吸引了他的注意力。他一次又一次地击球。

One day, a friend’s three-year-old was playing around on our tennis court¶ along with a bunch of teenagers. Some kids were shooting baskets at the hoop on one end. A few kids were firing tennis balls at each other, and others were slapping volleyballs around. But the three-year-old was intensely practicing the art of hitting a tennis ball. He would bounce it once, lock his eyes on it, and swing the racket. He hit the ball a lot more often than you’d expect for a three-year-old, but that wasn’t the interesting part. I watched for several minutes as he worked alone, ignoring older kids around him. He’s an otherwise social kid, but this simple task of hitting a tennis ball captured his focus. He hit it again and again and again.

然后事情变得更奇怪了。我决定即兴教他如何正确挥拍。别忘了，他才三岁，几乎不懂语言。我要了球拍，说想教他怎么挥拍。令人惊讶的是——对于一个三岁的孩子来说——他把球拍递给了我。他看着我，全神贯注地听着我说的每一个字。我演示了如何握拍和挥拍。他尝试了一下，经过一番指导，差不多模仿了我的挥拍动作。他三岁的时候就完全可以接受指导了。有些成年人——也许是大多数——永远都没有这种能力。我走开后，他又回到了一群青少年中间，独自练习。又一次，又一次，又一次。

Then it got stranger. I decided to give him an impromptu lesson on the proper way to swing a racket. Remember, he’s three. He barely had language skills. I asked for the racket, saying I wanted to show him how to swing, and amazingly—for a three-year-old—he handed it over. He looked at me and absorbed every word I said. I demonstrated how to hold the racket and how to swing. He tried it and with some coaching duplicated my swing, more or less. He was fully coachable at the age of three. Some adults—maybe most—never have that capability. As I walked away, he went back to his solitary practice amid a foaming sea of teenagers. Again. Again. Again.

我很了解这个孩子，网球是他用同样的方式学会的第四或第五项运动。他会在电视上或现场观看比赛，然后模仿并无休止地练习。我从未见过他练习时感到无聊。

I know this kid well, and tennis is the fourth or fifth sport he’s picked up the same way. He watches how it’s done, on television or in person, then he imitates and practices endlessly. I’ve never seen him get bored while practicing.

练习的重要性毋庸置疑。难的是弄清楚练习什么。

There’s no denying the importance of practice. The hard part is figuring out what to practice.

小时候，我曾在冬夜里在卧室里度过无数个无聊的时光，试图用一根手指旋转篮球。最终我掌握了这项技能，却发现它毫无经济价值。同样，我过去的所有老板也从未对我能在十五秒内同时玩三个物体，或者用左手打乒乓球的能力感到满意。我还可以用一只手在空中翻转一支笔，同时在它飞起时用另一只手在它下方划过——这看起来比听起来酷——然后在它旋转一圈后干净利落地接住它。这些以及其他技能对我来说都没什么用。练习什么很重要。

When I was a kid, I spent countless bored hours in my bedroom on winter nights trying to spin a basketball on one finger. Eventually I mastered that skill only to later learn that it has no economic value. In a similar vein, none of my past bosses have ever been impressed with my ability to juggle up to three objects for as long as fifteen seconds, or to play Ping-Pong left-handed. I can also flip a pen in the air with one hand while swiping my other hand under it just as it takes off—which looks cooler than it sounds—then I catch it cleanly after a full rotation. These and other skills have not served me well. It matters what you practice.

我的观察是，有些人天生就有练习的本能，而另一些人则认为，没有即时回报的无意识重复是一种折磨。无论你属于哪一派，这种现象可能都不会改变。指望普通人为了追求长期成功而无休止地练习，未免幼稚。假设你不是食人族，为自己制定一个符合自身天性的生活计划更有意义。大多数天性只要你正确引导，都会产生某种经济价值。

My observation is that some people are born with a natural impulse to practice things while others find mindless repetition without immediate reward to be a form of torture. Whichever camp you’re in, it probably won’t change. It’s naïve to expect the average person to embrace endless practice in pursuit of long-term success. It makes more sense to craft a life plan for yourself that embraces your natural inclinations, assuming you’re not a cannibal. Most natural inclinations have some sort of economic value if you channel them right.

决定将时间花在何处的一个好方法是诚实地评估你的练习能力。如果你不是天生的“练习者”，就不要浪费时间去追求那些需要练习的策略。你知道你不会成为音乐会钢琴家或NBA控球后卫。这未必是坏事。你并非注定平庸。你只需要选择一种鼓励追求新奇而非盲目重复的人生策略。例如，你可能想成为一名建筑师、设计师、房屋建筑商、计算机程序员、企业家、网站设计师，甚至医生。

A good start for deciding where to spend your time is an honest assessment of your ability to practice. If you’re not a natural “practicer,” don’t waste time pursuing a strategy that requires it. You know you won’t be a concert pianist or a point guard in the NBA. That’s not necessarily a bad thing. You’re not doomed to mediocrity. You simply need to pick a life strategy that rewards novelty-seeking more than mindless repetition. For example, you might want to be an architect, designer, home builder, computer programmer, entrepreneur, website designer, or even doctor.

这些职业都需要严谨的学习，但每个职业都有其独特之处。在你的职业生涯后期，你所有的项目都可能独一无二。你的技能会随着经验的积累而提升，经验是实践的更有趣的表亲。实践意味着将你的意识置于假死状态。实践并非生活。但当你通过不断变化的经验序列来构建你的技能时，你才是活着的。

Those professions all require disciplined study, but every class will be different. And later in your career, all your projects are likely to be unique. Your skills will increase with experience, which is the more fun cousin of practice. Practice involves putting your consciousness in suspended animation. Practicing is not living. But when you build your skills through an ever-changing sequence of experiences, you’re alive.

¶是的，我确实意识到提到我家的网球场会让我听起来像个大混蛋，但我不知道如何用一种不那么混蛋的方式来讲述这个故事。

¶Yes, I do realize that mentioning the tennis court at my house makes me sound like a gigantic douchebag, but I couldn’t figure out how to tell the story in a less douchey way.

第二十章

Chapter 20

管理你的成功几率

Managing Your Odds for Success

T学校的首要目的是帮助孩子们为成年后的成功做好准备。正因如此，学校竟然没有开设关于成功人士的体系和实践的必修课程，这让我感到有些奇怪。成功并非魔法；它通常是选择一个好的体系并坚持下去，直到好运降临的结果。可惜的是，学校几乎没有资源来教授基础课程。学生们只能靠自己去摸索出通往成功的最佳体系。

The primary purpose of schools is to prepare kids for success in adulthood. That’s why it seems odd to me that schools don’t have required courses on the systems and practices of successful people. Success isn’t magic; it’s generally the product of picking a good system and following it until luck finds you. Unfortunately, schools barely have the resources to teach basic coursework. Students are on their own to figure out the best systems for success.

如果我们不能指望学校教会孩子们成功的系统，人们还能如何学习这些重要的技能呢？成功人士的孩子或许是通过观察和父母的指导来学习的。但大多数人并非生于非常成功的家庭。普通孩子几乎没有时间与非常成功的人相处，更不用说在那些成功人士运用其方法的工作日了。年轻人被刻意地与成人的职场世界隔绝开来。孩子们最多只能看到电视和电影中关于如何成功的故事，但这并没有多大帮助。

If we can’t count on schools to teach kids the systems of success, how else will people learn those important skills? The children of successful people probably learn by observation and parental coaching. But most people are not born to highly successful parents. The average kid spends almost no time around highly successful people, and certainly not during the workday when those successful people are applying their methods. The young are intentionally insulated from the adult world of work. At best, kids see the television and movie versions of how to succeed, and that isn’t much help.

关于成功的书籍或许有些用处。但出于市场营销的原因，通常一本书会专注于一个主题，以便更容易销售——并且会塞满各种无聊的内容来增加页数。没人有时间去翻阅那么多无聊的内容。

Books about success can be somewhat useful. But for marketing reasons, a typical book is focused on a single topic to make it easier to sell—and packed with filler to get the page count up. No one has time to sort through that much filler.

当我和年轻人谈论成功时，我经常会告诉他们，成功有一个公式。你可以通过选择如何填写公式中的变量来操纵你的成功几率。这个公式粗略地说，就是你掌握的每项技能都会使你的成功几率翻倍。

When I speak to young people on the topic of success, as I often do, I tell them there’s a formula for it. You can manipulate your odds of success by how you choose to fill out the variables in the formula. The formula, roughly speaking, is that every skill you acquire doubles your odds of success.

成功秘诀：你掌握的每项技能都会使你的成功几率加倍。

The Success Formula: Every skill you acquire doubles your odds of success.

请注意，我并没有提到你需要达到每项技能的熟练程度。我也没有提到任何关于卓越或世界级的东西。我的意思是，你只要在多项技能上表现出色（而非非凡），就能提升你的市场价值。

Notice I didn’t say anything about the level of proficiency you need to achieve for each skill. I didn’t mention anything about excellence or being world-class. The idea is that you can raise your market value by being merely good—not extraordinary—at more than one skill.

例如，在加州，拥有一项常见的职业技能加上流利的西班牙语，就能让你在很多类型的工作中脱颖而出。如果你也是一位熟练的公众演讲者（还行，但不算很出色），并且熟悉PowerPoint演示文稿，那么你很有可能胜任管理你的组织。简而言之，成功公式如下：

In California, for example, having one common occupational skill plus fluency in Spanish puts you at the head of the line for many types of jobs. If you’re also a skilled public speaker (good but not great) and you know your way around a PowerPoint presentation, you have a good chance of running your organization. To put the Success Formula into its simplest form:

好 + 好 >优秀

Good + Good > Excellent

从成功的角度来看，精通两项互补的技能比精通一项技能更好。我忽略了你可能在某项技能上是世界上最优秀的人之一这种可能性。这显然也很有价值。但实际上，如果你能以每小时一百英里的速度投掷棒球，或者在脑海里创作出热门歌曲，你就不会读这本书了。

Success-wise, you’re better off being good at two complementary skills than to be excellent at one. I’m ignoring the outlier possibility that you might be one of the best performers in the world at some skill or another. That can obviously be valuable, too. But realistically, you wouldn’t be reading this book if you could throw a baseball a hundred miles per hour or compose hit songs in your head.

当我说你获得的每项技能都会使你的成功几率翻倍时，这是一种有用的简化。显然，有些技能比其他技能更有价值，而你获得的第十二项技能的价值可能比前十一项技能都要低。但如果你把每项技能都看作是让你成功几率翻倍，那么它将比你假设学习一项新技能的好处会在四舍五入中消失更有效地引导你的行动。从逻辑上讲，你可能会认为要么有一个准确的成功公式，要么根本没有更合理。但我们的大脑并非如此。有时，一个完全不准确的公式是一种引导你走向正确方向的便捷方法——如果它能带来简单的好处。我知道这一点并不明显，所以请允许我举个例子。

When I say each skill you acquire will double your odds of success, that’s a useful simplification. Obviously, some skills are more valuable than others, and the twelfth skill you acquire might have less value than each of the first eleven. But if you think of each skill in terms of doubling your chances of success, it will steer your actions more effectively than if you assume the benefit of learning a new skill will get lost in the rounding. Logically, you might think it would make more sense to either have an accurate formula for success or none at all. But that’s not how our brains are wired. Sometimes, an entirely inaccurate formula is a handy way to move you in the right direction—if it offers the benefit of simplicity. I realize that’s not an obvious point, so allow me to give you an example.

您可以从简历写作专家那里学到一个实用技巧，那就是问问自己，你的初稿中是否有任何单词你愿意为了每个100美元而删除。以下是一个简单的公式：

A handy trick you’ll learn from résumé writing experts is to ask yourself if there are any words in your first draft that you would be willing to remove for $100 each. Here’s the simple formula:

删除每个不必要的单词 = 100 美元

Deleting Each Unnecessary Word = $100

当你把这个公式运用到简历中时，你会惊讶地发现，它能如此有效地帮助你精简文字，使其回归最本质的形式。100美元这个数字是随意的，你删除的某些词比其他词更有价值，这些都无关紧要。重要的是，这个公式能引导你的行为朝着正确的方向发展。通常情况下，简洁胜过准确。在这个例子中，100美元不仅不准确，而且完全是虚构的。但它仍然有效。

When you apply the formula to your résumé, you surprise yourself by how well the formula helps you prune your writing to its most essential form. It doesn’t matter that the $100 figure is arbitrary and that some words you remove are more valuable than others. What matters is that the formula steers your behavior in the right direction. As is often the case, simplicity trumps accuracy. The $100 in this case is not only inaccurate, it’s entirely imaginary. And it still works.

同样，我认为重要的是要将你获得的每项新技能都视为使你成功的几率翻倍。从字面意义上讲，这并不比你简历上每删除一个字就会损失100美元的假想更准确，但它仍然有助于引导你的行为朝着富有成效的方向发展。如果我告诉你，晚上上一门网站设计课可能会使你事业成功的几率翻倍，这个想法会增加你采取行动的几率。相反，如果我只是给你一个模糊的观点，认为学习新技能是有益的，你不会感到特别有动力。当你接受但不一定相信每项新技能都会使你的成功几率翻倍时，你实际上是在欺骗你的大脑，让它在追求成功的过程中更加积极主动。以新的方式看待熟悉的事物可以改变你的行为，即使新的观点侧重于想象。

Likewise, I think it’s important to think of each new skill you acquire as doubling your odds of success. In a literal sense, it’s no more accurate than the imaginary $100 per deleted word on your résumé, but it still helps guide your behavior in a productive direction. If I told you that taking a class in website design during your evenings might double your odds of career success, the thought would increase the odds that you will act. If instead I only offer you a vague opinion that acquiring new skills is beneficial, you won’t feel particularly motivated. When you accept without necessarily believing that each new skill doubles your odds of success, you effectively hack (trick) your brain to be more proactive in your pursuit of success. Looking at the familiar in new ways can change your behavior even when the new point of view focuses on the imaginary.

我就是利用多种平庸技能所产生力量的完美例子。我是一个富有而著名的漫画家，但画画并不好。在社交聚会上，我通常不是房间里最有趣的人。我的写作技巧还行，但不是很好。但我拥有大多数艺术家和漫画家所不具备的，那就是多年的企业商业经验，以及伯克利哈斯商学院的 MBA 学位。在Dilbert的早期，我的商业经验直接成为了漫画的素材。最终我发现，我的商业技能对于将Dilbert从邪典漫画变成家喻户晓的名字至关重要。我平庸的技能加在一起的价值远远超过各部分的总和。如果你认为非凡的天赋和对卓越的疯狂追求是成功的必要条件，我认为这只是一种方法，而且可能是最难的一种方法。当谈到技能时，数量往往胜过质量。

I’m a perfect example of the power of leveraging multiple mediocre skills. I’m a rich and famous cartoonist who doesn’t draw well. At social gatherings, I’m usually not the funniest person in the room. My writing skills are good, not great. But what I have that most artists and cartoonists do not have is years of corporate business experience plus an MBA from Berkeley’s Haas School of Business. In the early years of Dilbert, my business experience served as immediate fodder for the comic. Eventually I discovered that my business skills were essential in navigating Dilbert from a cult hit to a household name. My combined mediocre skills are worth far more than the sum of the parts. If you think extraordinary talent and a maniacal pursuit of excellence are necessary for success, I say that’s just one approach and probably the hardest. When it comes to skills, quantity often beats quality.

现在正是时候告诉你，我在伯克利的MBA项目中是怎样的学生。在我的第一个学期，我的成绩经常是班里最低的。我努力学习，却靠着蛮力最终成绩平平。最终，重要的是我学到了能够弥补我其他微薄天赋的技能。

This would be a good time to tell you what kind of student I was in Berkeley’s MBA program. In my first semester, I often had the lowest grades in the class. I worked hard and rose to scholastic mediocrity through brute force. In the end, all that mattered is that I learned skills that complemented my other meager talents.

当我将自己微薄的商业技能、糟糕的艺术技能以及平庸的写作天赋结合起来时，这种组合产生了强大的力量。每掌握一项新技能，我的成功几率就大幅提升。但我在太平洋贝尔公司日常工作中学到的一项技能最终却意义非凡：在大多数人还未听说过互联网之前，我就知道如何使用它了。

When I combined my meager business skills with my bad art skills and my fairly ordinary writing talent, the mixture was powerful. With each new skill, my odds of success increased substantially. But there was still one more skill I acquired in my day job at Pacific Bell that ended up mattering a lot: I knew how to use the Internet before most people had even heard of it.

我在太平洋贝尔的日常工作是向潜在客户演示一种名为万维网（后来被称为互联网）的新事物。我很早就看到了其中的潜力。当《呆伯特》在报纸上的销量停滞不前时，我建议将其转移到互联网上，以提高曝光率，这算是一种幕后营销计划。我希望人们先在线阅读《呆伯特》，然后在当地报纸上点播。事情也确实如此。《呆伯特》是第一部在互联网上免费连载的漫画，尽管一开始它比报纸晚发行一周。如今，很难想象将《呆伯特》免费发布到互联网上会被视为巨大的风险。当时人们担心盗版会泛滥（事实确实如此），也担心报纸会将互联网视为竞争对手而取消发行（但并没有报纸这样做）。在增加曝光率是好事的时代，盗版带来的益处远大于弊端。

My day job at Pacific Bell involved demonstrating a new thing called the World Wide Web, later known as the Internet, to potential customers. I saw the possibilities early, and when Dilbert stalled in newspaper sales, I suggested moving it to the Internet to generate more exposure, as sort of a back-door marketing plan. I wanted people to read Dilbert online, then request it in their local newspapers. And that’s what happened. Dilbert was the first syndicated comic to run for free on the Internet, although in the beginning it ran a week behind newspapers. Today it’s hard to imagine that it ever seemed a huge risk to put Dilbert on the Internet for free. There were concerns that piracy would go through the roof (it did) and that newspapers would see the Internet as competition and cancel (none did). In the days when more exposure was a good thing, the piracy helped far more than it hurt.

我早期对科技的熟悉也在另一个方面帮助了我。我是第一位在每部漫画里都附上自己邮箱地址的漫画家。在九十年代初，电子邮件还是个令人眼花缭乱的新鲜玩意儿，我的一些商业伙伴担心客户报纸会把我的邮箱地址当成一种广告。但我接受的商业培训告诉我，我需要开辟一条直接面向客户的渠道，并根据他们的反馈修改我的产品。我正是这么做的，并根据读者的要求，把它变成了一部以职场为主题的漫画。从此，《呆伯特》开始走红。

My early comfort with technology helped me in another big way, too. I was the first syndicated cartoonist to include my email address in every strip. Email was still a geeky novelty in the early nineties, and some of my business associates worried that client newspapers would consider my email address a form of advertisement. But my business training told me I needed to open a direct channel to my customers and modify my product based on their feedback. That’s exactly what I did,** making it a workplace-focused strip as readers requested. From there, Dilbert took off.

总结一下我的技能：我的艺术造诣很差，商业能力平庸，写作天赋尚可，但算不上优秀，对互联网也了解不多。我的幽默感也不错，但算不上优秀。我就像一锅平庸的大汤。我的技能都不是世界一流的，但当我这些平庸的技能结合在一起时，它们就变成了一股强大的市场力量。

Recapping my skill set: I have poor art skills, mediocre business skills, good but not great writing talent, and an early knowledge of the Internet. And I have a good but not great sense of humor. I’m like one big mediocre soup. None of my skills are world-class, but when my mediocre skills are combined, they become a powerful market force.

我在美国企业界的十六年经历也让我积累了其他六项实用技能。我曾负责人事管理、合同谈判、商业贷款、商业计划书撰写、软件设计、项目管理、绩效追踪系统开发、技术战略制定等等。我参加了公司付费的公共演讲、时间管理、与难相处的人打交道、倾听、商务写作以及许多其他实用主题的课程。在我的企业生涯中，我一边全职工作，一边利用晚上的时间完成MBA课程。我就像一台学习机器。如果我认为某样东西将来可能会有用，我就会努力掌握至少是基础知识。在我的漫画生涯中，我几乎把学到的所有技能都运用到了商业领域。

My sixteen years in corporate America added half-a-dozen other useful skills to the mix as well. I managed people, did contract negotiations, made commercial loans, wrote business plans, designed software, managed projects, developed systems to track performance, contributed to technology strategies, and more. I took company-paid classes in public speaking, time management, managing difficult people, listening, business writing, and lots of other useful topics. During my corporate career, I finished my MBA classes in the evening while working full time. I was a learning machine. If I thought something might someday be useful, I tried to grasp at least the basics. In my cartooning career, I’ve used almost every skill I learned in the business world.

在不同领域尽可能多地学习的另一个巨大优势是，你理解的概念越多，学习新知识就越容易。想象一下，向一位外星访客解释马的概念。这需要一些时间。如果你接下来尝试解释斑马的概念，对话就会更简短。你只需指出斑马很像马，但有黑白条纹即可。你学到的一切都成为理解其他事物的捷径。

Another huge advantage of learning as much as you can in different fields is that the more concepts you understand, the easier it is to learn new ones. Imagine explaining to an extraterrestrial visitor the concept of a horse. It would take some time. If the next thing you tried to explain was the concept of a zebra, the conversation would be shorter. You would simply point out that a zebra is a lot like a horse but with black and white stripes. Everything you learn becomes a shortcut for understanding something else.

我一生的习惯之一就是每天阅读世界时事，有时一天读好几遍。几年前，这意味着上班前读报纸。现在，通常就是一有空闲时间就去看看X。阅读商业、健康、科学、技术、政治等领域的多元视角，好处在于，你会自动发现世界的规律，并在脑海中形成一个个挂钩，让你可以把未来的知识挂在上面。知识的公式大致如下：

One of my lifelong practices involves reading about world events every day, sometimes several times a day. Years ago, that meant reading a newspaper before work. Now it usually involves checking X whenever I have a minute or two of downtime. The great thing about reading diverse perspectives from the fields of business, health, science, technology, politics, and more is that you automatically see patterns in the world and develop mental hooks upon which you can hang future knowledge. The formula for knowledge looks something like this:

知识公式：你知道的越多，你能知道的就越多。

The Knowledge Formula: The More You Know, the More You Can Know.

如果你觉得阅读新闻总是枯燥乏味，那你就错了。养成阅读新闻习惯的简单切入点是只阅读你感兴趣的话题，无论它们多么琐碎。这能有效地训练你享受阅读新闻的时间——即使你只关注名人丑闻和体育新闻。随着时间的推移，你阅读新闻的快乐体验会让你想享受更长时间。你会开始接触以前不感兴趣的话题。一开始，你可能只是浏览一下标题。但随着时间的推移，你会发现自己被吸引住了。这会让人感觉轻松自然——这是一个良好体系的标志。如果我建议每天早上都从阅读《华尔街日报》的硬新闻开始，很多人会觉得望而生畏，而且你不太可能坚持下去。一个更明智的方法是将学习视为一个系统，在这个系统中，你会不断接触新的话题，主要是你感兴趣的话题。

If your experience of reading the news is that it’s always boring, you’re doing it wrong. The simple entry point for developing a news-reading habit is that you only read the topics that interest you, no matter how trivial they might be. That effectively trains you to enjoy the time you spend reading the news—even if the only thing you look at involves celebrity scandals and sports. In time, your happy experience reading the news will make you want to enjoy it longer. You’ll start sampling topics that wouldn’t have interested you before. At first, perhaps you’ll do little more than skim the headlines. But in time, you’ll find yourself drawn in. It will feel easy and natural—the sign of a good system. If I had suggested starting every morning by reading the hard news in The Wall Street Journal, it would feel daunting for many people, and it’s unlikely you would follow through. A smarter approach is to think of learning as a system in which you continuously expose yourself to new topics, primarily the ones you find interesting.

我每天阅读新闻的一个警告是，如果选错了主题，可能会让人非常沮丧。我个人会尽量避免阅读涉及悲剧事件的报道，而专注于那些充满希望的科学、技术和商业主题。我不会忽略坏消息，但不会纠结于此。你花在坏消息上的时间越多，它对你的压力就越大，消耗你的精力。我更喜欢阅读关于绿色技术突破的报道，即使我知道其中99%都是胡扯。我阅读新闻不是为了寻找真相，因为那只是愚蠢地浪费时间。我阅读新闻是为了拓宽我的视野，接触新的主题和模式，从而提高我的大脑整体效率，并享受生活，因为学习有趣的东西能增强我的能量，让我感到乐观。不要把新闻当成信息，而要把它当成能量的来源。

My one caution about reading the news every day is that it can be a huge downer if you pick the wrong topics. Personally, I try to avoid stories involving tragic events and concentrate on the more hopeful topics in science, technology, and business. I don’t ignore bad news, but I don’t dwell on it. The more time you spend exposing yourself to bad news, the more it will weigh on you and sap your energy. I prefer stories about breakthroughs in green technology, even knowing that 99 percent of those stories are pure bullshit. I don’t read the news to find truth, as that would be a foolish waste of time. I read the news to broaden my exposure to new topics and patterns that make my brain more efficient in general and to enjoy myself because learning interesting things increases my energy and makes me feel optimistic. Don’t think of the news as information. Think of it as a source of energy.

**真正的艺术家光是想想就觉得艺术作品要改变，恐怕就觉得不舒服了。我把自己当成企业家，而不是艺术家，所以对我所谓的艺术作品灵活变通一点儿也不成问题。

**Changing art to satisfy customers probably makes real artists ill just thinking about it. I considered myself an entrepreneur, not an artist, so I had no trouble being flexible with my so-called art.

第21章

Chapter 21

成功的数学

The Math of Success

是你无法直接控制运气，但你可以从胜率低的游戏转向胜率更高的游戏。这似乎是一个显而易见的策略，你可能认为自己已经做到了。难的是计算出任何特定游戏的胜率，而这比看起来要难得多。

You can’t directly control luck, but you can move from a game with low odds of success to a game with better odds. That seems like an obvious strategy, and you probably think you already do it. The hard part is figuring out the odds of any given game, and that’s harder than it looks.

几年前，我给五年级的学生们做了一次演讲。我一开始就让他们把我说的话补全。我的句子是：“如果你玩老虎机的时间足够长，最终你会……”全班齐声喊道：“赢！”大多数成年人都知道，这完全是错误的答案。老虎机的设计初衷是让除了赌场之外的所有人最终都输。但孩子们并不知道这一点。我猜他们混淆了从小就被灌输的坚持不懈的好处和成功的实际概率。

Several years ago, I gave a talk to a fifth-grade class. I started by asking them to finish my sentence. The sentence was “If you play a slot machine long enough, eventually you will . . .” The class yelled out in unison “WIN!” As most adults know, that is exactly the wrong answer. Slot machines are engineered to make everyone but the casino a loser in the long run. But kids don’t know that. I presume they confused the benefits of persistence, which is drilled into them as kids, with the actual odds of succeeding.

如果你正在读这本书，你可能已经成年或即将成年，并且了解老虎机的赔率。如果你玩老虎机，你可能会把它当作一种娱乐，而不是一项投资。但你是否同样​​清楚，那些主宰你生活其他领域的赔率呢？

If you’re reading this book, you’re probably an adult or soon to become one, and you understand the odds of slot machines. If you play them, you probably think of it as recreation and not an investment. But are you equally clear about the odds that rule over other areas of your life?

我再用我最喜欢的话题——网球——来举一个关于概率的例子。大约七年的时间里，我每周和同一个朋友打一次网球。他每次都能赢我。早些年，他的胜利合情合理，因为他的球技在各个方面都更强。最终，我的击球技术进步到我觉得我应该赢的地步，但我从未赢过。那些年里，我虽然接近胜利，但每场比赛都输。我并没有觉得自己被心理压力压得喘不过气来，因为我通常在压力环境下表现得更好。我天生的乐观精神总是告诉我，无论落后多少，我都能变出一只兔子，克服一切困难赢得胜利。这种感觉在我心中如此强烈，以至于它之所以没有被归类为精神疾病，唯一的原因是它比你预期的更频繁地奏效。

I’ll give you another example about odds using my favorite topic: tennis. For a period of about seven years, I played tennis once a week with the same friend. He beat me 100 percent of the time. In the early years, his wins made sense because his game was stronger in every way. Eventually, my shot-making improved to the point where I felt I should have been winning, but I never did. I could get close, but I lost every match during those years. I didn’t feel as if I was choking from the psychological pressure because I typically perform better in stressful situations. My natural optimism always tells me I’m going to pull a rabbit out of the hat and win against all odds no matter how far behind I am. That feeling is so strong in me that the only reason it isn’t classified as mental illness is that it works more often than you’d expect.

所以我并没有因为输球记录而感到恐慌，我的击球水平也足够好。为什么我每次都输给这个对手？我经常赢那些看起来和他水平差不多的球员。我的连败记录一直是个谜，困扰了我好几年。显然，我存在某种盲点……什么？我怎么才能看到我看不到的东西？如果我看到了，它能帮助我赢吗？

So I wasn’t getting psyched out by my losing record, and my strokes were good enough. Why did I lose every match against this particular opponent? I would routinely win against players who seemed about the same level as him. My losing streak was a mystery that dogged me for years. Apparently, I had some sort of blind spot about . . . what? How could I learn to see the thing I couldn’t see? And if I saw it, would it help me win?

我和我的网球搭档在场下是好朋友，我们经常聊比赛。我总是留意他是否无意间透露了他的网球秘诀。当我们谈论每天哪些方法有效、哪些方法无效时，我时不时地会得到一些小提示。我们关于网球的对话在我的脑海里盘旋了好几年，直到有一天，这种模式显露出来。

My tennis partner and I were good friends off the court, and we chatted a lot about our matches. I was always on the lookout for him to inadvertently spill his tennis secrets. I got little hints here and there as we talked about what was working and what wasn’t on any given day. Our tennis conversations swirled around in my brain for years until one day the pattern revealed itself.

生活中一些最强大的模式往往非常微妙。这个网球模式尤其如此。简单的解释是，当我在打网球时，我的对手正在做数学题。他是一个拿着网球拍的算牌高手。在几十年的网球生涯中，他已经了解了网球场上几乎所有可能发生事件的概率。

Some of the most powerful patterns in life are subtle. This tennis pattern was extraordinarily so. The quick explanation is that while I was playing tennis, my opponent was doing math. He was a card counter with a tennis racket. Over the course of several decades of tennis, he had learned the odds associated with just about everything that can happen on a tennis court.

了解网球比赛的胜算比看起来要难，因为很多事情都违反直觉。比如，对手打出一记正手对正手的球，让你出界，半个球场无人防守，大多数业余选手都会尝试打出一记强劲的正手制胜球，将球打到空旷的场地上。我几乎总是选择打这个球，但八成都打不中。事实证明，对于业余球手来说，在与目标成直角移动的情况下打出直线球极具挑战性。直线球只有在你有足够的时间准备和向前移动时才能发挥最佳效果。跑动中打直线球只是感觉很容易。这种错觉出奇地强烈。每次我打出直线球却失败，无论我连续多少次都以同样的方式失败，我都会感到惊讶。我以为只要再试几次，就能锁定那个球。结果证明，我错了——多年来一直如此。

Learning the odds with tennis is harder than it looks because so much of it is counter-intuitive. For example, when your opponent hits a forehand-to-forehand shot that takes you wide, leaving half of his court unguarded, most amateurs would try for a blistering forehand winner up the line into the open court. That shot was almost always my choice, and I missed it about 80 percent of the time. It turns out that hitting down the line when you’re moving at a right angle to your target is exceptionally challenging for a weekend player. The down-the-line shot works best when you have time to set up and step toward it. Hitting down the line while on the run only feels like it would be easy. The illusion is surprisingly strong. Every time I missed a down-the-line shot I was surprised, no matter how many times in a row I missed the same way. I assumed I would be able to lock in that shot if I just tried it a few more times. It turns out I was wrong about that—for years.

我可以举出十几个网球例子，这些例子表明，实际的胜率与你在场上的感觉截然相反。我还可以举出十几个例子，说明我的对手总是打出高命中率的球，同时巧妙地引诱我打出一个又一个低命中率的球。关键在于，虽然我们都认为自己了解生活中的胜率，但你很可能存在一些盲点。找到这些盲点至关重要。

I could give a dozen more tennis examples where the odds are exactly opposite of how they feel when you’re on the court. And I could give you a dozen examples of how my opponent always played the high-percentage shots while cleverly goading me into one low-percentage shot after another. The point is that while we all think we know the odds in life, there’s a good chance you have some blind spots. Finding those blind spots is a big deal.

随着时间的推移，我学会了更多地避开那些命中率低的网球击球，而且我大约有一半的比赛胜率，正如我们的击球技巧所预测的那样。我在书中前面提到过，将网球视为一场从对手手中抢时间的游戏，可以让你更上一层楼。这话没错，但只有当你也打出命中率高的击球时，时间管理才有用。

In time, I learned to avoid the low-percentage tennis shots more often, and I won our matches about half the time, exactly as our shot-making skills would predict. I mentioned earlier in the book that seeing tennis as a game of stealing time from your opponent allows you to move to a higher level. That’s true, but managing time only helps if you’re also taking the high-percentage shots.

那么这些对你有什么帮助呢？

So how does any of this help you?

我在这里倡导的理念是，把世界看作数学，而不是魔法。我很容易会认为，我网球连败是因为缺乏求胜的意志。又或许，我以为我的失败是来自宇宙造物主的教训，他意识到我需要帮助，才能保持社交中得体的谦逊。但事实并非如此，这只是数学而已。

The idea I’m promoting here is to see the world as math, not magic. It would’ve been easy for me to assume my tennis losing streak was due to my lacking the will to win. Or perhaps I might have thought my losses were lessons from the Creator of the Universe, who realized I needed help maintaining a socially appropriate level of humility. But no, it was just math.

如果你发现自己在个人生活或事业上不断失败，你可能会将其归咎于命运、因果、动物精神或其他某种魔法——而真正的原因其实很简单。通常情况下，失败是有规律的，但这种规律可能很微妙。不要因为在最初的七年里没有找到规律就停止寻找。

If you find yourself in a state of continuous failure in your personal life or career, you might be blaming it on fate or karma or animal spirits or some other form of magic—when the real reason is simple math. There’s usually a pattern, but it might be subtle. Don’t stop looking just because you don’t see the pattern in the first seven years.

无论是职业还是个人生活，未来都是完全不可预测的。因此，提升成功几率的最佳方法——在别人看来可能像是运气——是系统地掌握那些能够有效协同、几乎对任何工作都非常有用的技能，但并非出类拔萃。这又是一个将世界视为数学（将各种技能相加）而非魔法的例子，它能让你从低成功率的策略转向更优胜的策略。我称之为“人才堆栈”的构建。（注：人才堆栈策略已成为成功领域的标准建议。本书正是该策略的发源地。）

The future is thoroughly unpredictable when it comes to your profession and your personal life. So the best way to increase your odds of success—in a way that might look like luck to others—is to systematically become good but not amazing at the types of skills that work well together and are highly useful for just about any job. This is another example in which viewing the world as math (adding skills together) and not magic allows you to move from a strategy with low odds of success to something better. I call this building a Talent Stack. (Note: The Talent Stack strategy has become standard advice in the success field. This book is where it started.)

我列出了我认为每个成年人都应该掌握的技能。我不指望你精通任何一项，但精通甚至不是必需的。如果你在这些领域中的大多数方面表现优异，那么运气就很有可能降临到你身上。我会逐一列举，但这里只是预览列表。

I made a list of the skills in which I think every adult should gain a working knowledge. I wouldn’t expect you to become a master of any, but mastery isn’t even necessary. Luck has a good chance of finding you if you become merely good in most of these areas. I’ll make a case for each one, but here’s the preview list.

公开演讲

Public speaking

心理学

Psychology

商务写作

Business writing

会计

Accounting

设计（基础）

Design (the basics)

谈话技巧

Conversation skills

克服害羞

Overcoming shyness

第二语言

Second language

高尔夫球

Golf

正确的语法

Proper grammar

劝说

Persuasion

技术（业余水平）

Technology (hobby level)

正确的发声技巧

Proper voice technique

在本章的其余部分，我将阐述每项技能的经济价值。

I’ll defend the economic value of each of these skills in the rest of this chapter.

公开演讲

Public Speaking

我在大学时上过一门公开演讲课，这门课确实有点帮助。在我的公司生涯中，我又上过两门公开演讲课，费用都是公司承担的。这两门课也确实对我有所帮助。后来有一天，我的雇主——当地的电话公司——宣布，他们将为所有利用业余时间参加戴尔·卡耐基课程的员工支付费用。任何想进一步学习的人都可以去大教室听讲座。我很好奇，而且之前听说过戴尔·卡耐基的课程不错，所以我决定去看看到底是怎么回事。

I took one public speaking class in college. It helped a little. I took two more classes in public speaking during my corporate career. The company paid for both. Those classes helped a little, too. Then one day my employer—the local phone company—announced they would pick up the tab for any employee who took the Dale Carnegie class on their own time. Anyone who wanted to learn more could attend a presentation in the big lecture room. I was curious and had heard good things about Dale Carnegie courses, so I decided to go and see what it was all about.

戴尔·卡耐基的区域总监托尼·斯诺——二十年后我莫名其妙地想起了他的名字——做了我见过的最简短却最有说服力的推销。我在这里会进一步精简，但核心内容是：“我没有亲自描述戴尔·卡耐基课程，而是请两位参加过这门课程的同事谈谈他们的感受。” 他介绍完第一个人就走开了。托尼·斯诺的推销工作完成了。

The Regional Director for Dale Carnegie, whose name I inexplicably remember twenty years later—Tony Snow—gave the shortest and most persuasive sales pitch I have ever seen. I’ll condense it further here, but the essence was this: “Instead of describing the Dale Carnegie course myself, I’ve asked two of your fellow employees who took the course to tell you what they think.” He introduced the first guy and walked off. Tony Snow was done selling.

我的同事像中了彩票一样，一跃而上。他的活力和热情极具感染力。他没有讲稿，而是在舞台上漫步，掌控着一切。我们这些观众像尾巴一样紧紧地跟着他，任他摇晃。他风趣幽默，富有表现力，引人入胜，而且非常自然。这是我见过的最精彩的非专业人士演讲。我能感觉到他热爱舞台上的每一秒，同时又能保持简短的演讲。

My fellow employee bounded onto the stage like he had just won the lottery. His energy and enthusiasm were infectious. He had no notes. He prowled the stage and owned it. We, the audience, locked onto him like a tail and let him wag us. He was funny, expressive, engaging, and spontaneous. It was the best speech by a non-professional I had ever seen. I could tell he loved every second on stage, and yet he had the discipline to keep things brief.

演讲结束后，托尼·斯诺向他道谢，并介绍了第二位演讲者。第二位演讲者的风格与第一位截然不同，但同样精彩。他演讲得非常投入，很有预感，思路清晰简洁。他掌控了我们。

When he was done, Tony Snow thanked him and introduced the second speaker. The second guy was completely different in style from the first speaker but every bit as good. He was enjoying himself. He projected. He was clear and concise. He owned us.

讲完后，托尼·斯诺感谢了观众，并告诉我们如何获得有关该课程的更多信息。托尼·斯诺：太棒了，混蛋。

When he was done, Tony Snow thanked the audience and told us how we could get more information about the course. Tony Snow: magnificent bastard.

我当天就报名了。

I signed up that day.

戴尔·卡耐基的课程有很多种。我不记得我上的那门课叫什么了，现在可能已经改名了。这门课的重点是公开演讲，但出于我很久才明白的原因，戴尔·卡耐基并没有把它归类为演讲课程。它的内容更广泛。

There are several flavors of Dale Carnegie courses. I don’t remember what my particular course was called, and it has probably changed names by now. The focus was on public speaking, but for reasons that took a long time for me to understand, Dale Carnegie didn’t classify it as a speaking course. It had a broader agenda.

第一天，我们的老师解释了他将要采用的戴尔·卡耐基学习方法。第一条规则是，任何人都不能受到批评或纠正。只允许老师和其他学生给予积极的鼓励。我立刻就怀疑起来。如果我不知道自己做错了什么，我怎么学习呢？

On day one, our instructor explained the Dale Carnegie method he would be employing. Rule one was that no one would ever be criticized or corrected. Only positive reinforcement would be allowed, from the instructor and from the other students. I was immediately skeptical. How was I supposed to learn if I didn’t know what I was doing wrong?

下一条规则是，每节课每个人都要向全班同学发言，但我们必须自愿下一个发言。这条规则比你最初想象的更重要，因为班上大多数人都非常害怕公开演讲。老师承认，有时全班同学需要安静地坐很长时间，等待下一位志愿者发言。我们确实这样做了。

The next rule was that every person would speak to the rest of the class during each session, but we had to volunteer to go next. This rule is more important than you might first think because most of the people in the class were deathly afraid of public speaking. The instructor acknowledged that sometimes the class would need to sit quietly for long periods waiting for the next volunteer. And wait we did.

课程第一天，我们都像受惊的松鼠一样一动不动地坐在那里，希望有人能先走。不知为何，先走感觉格外糟糕，尽管我们都知道自己最终会走。教练站在僵住的教室前面，耐心地等待着，没有评判，显然他以前也经历过这种情况。

That first day of the course, we all sat there motionless like frightened squirrels, hoping someone else would go first. For some reason, going first seemed extra bad even though we all knew we would go eventually. The instructor stood in front of the frozen class and waited patiently, not judging, clearly having gone through this before.

终于有人自告奋勇，接着又一个。我们的演讲任务很简单，我想我们只需要说说自己的事情就行了。对包括我在内的大多数人来说，这相对容易。但对班上的很多人来说，这几乎是不可能的。一位被雇主强迫上课的年轻女士吓得一句话也说不出来。在凉爽的空调房间里，汗珠从她的额头流到下巴，滴落在地毯上。全场观众都痛苦地看着她与内心的恶魔搏斗，努力开口说话。她勉强挤出几个字，然后回到座位上，感到挫败、羞辱和崩溃。

Eventually someone volunteered, then another. Our speaking assignment was something simple. I think we simply had to say something about ourselves. For most people, including me, this was a relatively easy task. But for many in the class, it was nearly impossible. One young lady who had been forced by her employer to take the class was so frightened that she literally couldn’t form words. In the cool, air-conditioned room, beads of sweat ran from her forehead down to her chin and dropped onto the carpet. The audience watched in shared pain as she battled her own demons and tried to form words. A few words came out, just barely, and she returned to her seat defeated, humiliated, broken.

然后发生了一件有趣的事。我认为这是我见过的最引人入胜的事情之一。教练走到前面，看着那个受伤的学生。房间里一片死寂。我会永远记住他的话。他说：“哇。这太勇敢了。”

Then an interesting thing happened. I rank it as one of the most fascinating things I have ever witnessed. The instructor went to the front and looked at the broken student. The room was dead silent. I’ll always remember his words. He said, “Wow. That was brave.”

我的脑子一片混乱。二十多个学生一直以为这个女人只是以一种极其屈辱的方式摔了下来。她显然也这么想。教练只用四个字就彻底改变了当时的局面。我们每个人都知道教练说得对。我们刚刚见证了一次非凡的个人勇气之举，这种事很少见。这就是教训。就是这样。

My brain spun in my head. Twenty-some students had been thinking this woman just crashed and burned in the most dramatically humiliating way. She clearly thought the same thing. In four words, the instructor completely reinterpreted the situation. Every one of us knew the instructor was right. We had just witnessed an extraordinary act of personal bravery, the likes of which one rarely sees. That was the takeaway. Period.

我看着学生脸上的表情，她对教练的评论做出了反应。她独自承受着痛苦，在进行着一场注定失败的斗争。但不知何故，教练理解了她内心的想法，并且尊重她的感受。我发誓，我看到她眼中闪过一丝光芒。她从地板上抬起头来。她得到了喘息。她仍在战斗。

I looked at the student’s face as she reacted to the instructor’s comment. She had been alone in her misery, fighting a losing fight. But somehow the instructor understood what was happening inside her, and he respected it. I swear I saw a light come on in her eyes. She looked up from the floor. She had a reprieve. She was still in the fight.

第二周，她又主动要求演讲了。（瞧，自愿的力量有多大？她自己决定了。）虽然她表现得不太好，但她没有大汗淋漓，也没有僵住，最终还是完成了演讲。老师也表扬了她的进步。

The next week, she volunteered to speak again. (See how powerful this volunteering thing is? She owned the choice.) She didn’t do well, but she got through it without perspiring or locking up, and the instructor praised her for her progress.

几周后，课程结束，班上每个人都能推销托尼·斯诺的产品。每次我们演讲，都能得到老师的称赞，有时还会得到其他学生的赞赏。我们赢得了掌声。感觉棒极了。如今，当我看到舞台上，上千人等着听我演讲时，我的脑海里就会浮现出一个小小的声音：今天真是美好的一天。我是房间里最快乐的人。观众只是聆听，而我可以演讲，感受，充满活力。我会吸收他们的能量，并将其转化为美好的事物。当我演讲结束后，人们百分之百会称赞我。

By the end of the course some weeks later, every member of the class could have sold Tony Snow’s product. Every time we spoke, we got compliments from the instructor and sometimes other students. We got applause. It felt great. Today when I see a stage and a thousand people waiting to hear me speak, a little recording goes off in my head that says, Today is a good day. I’m the happiest person in the room. The audience only gets to listen, but I get to speak, to feel, to be fully alive. I will absorb their energy and turn it into something good. And when I’m done, there’s a one hundred percent chance people will say good things about me.

这个故事有几个值得思考的地方。最重要的是赞美的转化力量，以及批评的腐蚀性影响。从那时起，我多次尝试去检验赞美的力量，我发现它有着惊人的力量，尤其对成年人而言。孩子们习惯了源源不断的批评和赞美，而成年人却可能连续数周得不到任何赞美，还要忍受工作和家庭中的批评。成年人渴望一句善意的话语。当你理解真诚赞美（而不是胡扯、奉承和谄媚）的力量时，你就会意识到，不去赞美近乎不道德。如果你看到令你印象深刻的事情，出于对人性的尊重，你会坚持说出你的赞美。

There are several takeaways from that story. The most important is the transformative power of praise versus the corrosive impact of criticism. I’ve had a number of occasions since then to test the powers of praise, and I find it an amazing force, especially for adults. Children are accustomed to a continuous stream of criticisms and praise, but adults can go weeks without a compliment while enduring criticism both at work and at home. Adults are starved for a kind word. When you understand the power of honest praise (as opposed to bullshitting, flattering, and sucking up), you realize that withholding it borders on immoral. If you see something that impresses you, a decent respect for humanity insists you voice your praise.

“哇，真勇敢！”这是我听过最清晰、最恰当的例子，换个角度看待问题，一切都会改变。当老师把我们的注意力从学生糟糕的演讲表现转移到她的勇气上时，现实本身就发生了转变。积极性远不止是一种心理偏好。它真的会改变你的大脑，也会改变你周围的人。它是我们最接近魔法的东西。

“Wow. That was brave,” is the best and cleanest example I’ve heard in which looking at something in a different way changed everything. When the instructor switched our focus from the student’s poor speaking performance to her bravery, reality itself shifted. Positivity is far more than a mental preference. It changes your brain, literally, and it changes the people around you. It’s the nearest thing we have to magic.

我从戴尔·卡耐基的经历中学到的另一个教训是，我们并不总是能准确地认识到自己的潜力。我认为大多数害怕公开演讲的人无法想象经过训练后，他们的感受可能会有所不同。不要想当然地认为自己知道自己有多大的潜力。有时，知道自己能做什么的唯一方法就是测试自己。

Another lesson I learned from my Dale Carnegie experience is that we don’t always have an accurate view of our own potential. I think most people who are frightened of public speaking can’t imagine they might feel different as a result of training. Don’t assume you know how much potential you have. Sometimes the only way to know what you can do is to test yourself.

心理学

Psychology

很难想象任何商业或社交活动不需要对人脑如何感知世界有基本的了解。你做的几乎任何决定都与他人对你的看法有关。我们都在推销某种自我。心理学渗透在我们所做的每一件事中。

It’s hard to imagine any business or social activity that doesn’t require a basic understanding of how the human brain perceives the world. Almost any decision you make is in the context of managing what other people will think of you. We’re all in the business of selling some version of ourselves. Psychology is embedded in everything we do.

例如，房地产销售人员可能会先带你看最差的房子，因为他们知道，这样你以后看到更好的房子时，就会更加珍惜——这可能会让你掏空钱包。汽车销售员知道，标价高会让最终的议价看起来比实际价格更划算。销售人员知道，他们可以通过控制比较对象来操纵买家。

For example, a real estate salesperson might show you the worst house first, knowing it will make you appreciate the better home you see later—which might make you reach deeper in your pockets. A car salesman knows that a high sticker price will make the eventual negotiated price look better than it would have otherwise. Salespeople know they can manipulate buyers by controlling what they compare.

建筑承包商知道，在搭建框架阶段，客户看到房子时，房间会显得太小。之后，当房间装修完毕并布置好家具后，它们看起来会更大。聪明的建筑商会提前警告客户，在搭建框架阶段，所有东西看起来都会更小。这样客户就不会抓狂。这就是心理学。

A building contractor knows that when customers see the house during the framing phase, the rooms will look too small. Later, when the rooms are finished and furnished, they look larger. A smart builder warns the customers in advance that everything will look smaller in the framing phase. That way the customer doesn’t flip out. That’s psychology.

即使是主要与物质世界打交道的工程师，也需要了解老板的感受、客户的想法以及用户对产品的认知。你无法逃避基于心理学做出决策的必要性。

Even an engineer who deals mostly with the material world needs to understand how his boss feels, how customers think, and how users will perceive the product. You can’t get away from the need to make decisions based on psychology.

我举的例子很常见，大多数人都能自己理解。但鉴于心理学领域深奥难懂，大多数人只知道一些常识性的东西。如果你对心理学有更深入的了解，你的效率会提高多少呢？答案是：提高很多。

The examples I gave are the common ones that most people figure out on their own. But given that the field of psychology is miles deep, most people only know the stuff that qualifies as common knowledge. How much more effective would you be if you had a greater understanding of psychology? Answer: a lot.

心理学是我最终成功创作《呆伯特》的巨大因素。当联合传媒向我提供《呆伯特》的联合制作合同时，我的自信心受到了直接打击。其他联合制作公司断然拒绝了我。一位编辑建议，或许我可以找一位真正的艺术家来为我画画。哎哟。因此，当联合传媒的编辑莎拉·吉莱斯皮打电话提出要签约时，我为自己糟糕的绘画技巧道了歉，并建议她能否给我配一位可以做插图的人。莎拉显然对心理学很了解，她告诉我，我的绘画技巧很好，不需要改进。这引发了我的实际天赋水平的出乎意料的变化：它提高了。一夜之间，我的绘画技巧从 1 到 10 的等级中的 3 分提高到了 6 分左右。这仍然不算好，但显然已经足够好了。这种突然的进步完全归功于莎拉对我艺术能力的称赞。我成为了一个更自信的艺术家——而且是一个更好的艺术家——因为她改变了我对自己天赋的看法。这是一个绿野仙踪的时刻。

Psychology was a huge factor in my eventual success with Dilbert. By the time United Media offered me a syndication contract for Dilbert, my confidence had taken some direct hits. The other syndication companies had turned me down flat. One editor suggested that perhaps I could find an actual artist to do the drawing for me. Ouch. So when Sarah Gillespie, editor at United Media, called and offered a contract, I apologized for my poor drawing skills and suggested that perhaps she could pair me with someone who could do the artwork. Sarah, who evidently understood a lot about psychology, told me my drawing skill was fine; no improvement necessary. That triggered a highly unexpected change in my actual level of talent: It went up. Overnight, my drawing skill went from about a three on a scale of one-to-ten to about a six. That’s still not good, but apparently it was good enough. The sudden improvement was entirely due to Sarah’s compliment of my artistic ability. I became a more confident artist—and a better one—because she changed what I thought of my own talent. It was a Wizard of Oz moment.

当我回顾我个人的失败和成功时，心理学是其中最引人注目的因素之一。当我正确地运用心理学时，无论是偶然还是机智，事情都会进展得更好。而当我对心理学视而不见时，事情就会变得很糟糕。

When I look at the list of my personal failures and successes, one of the things that stand out is psychology. When I got the psychology right, either by accident or cleverness, things worked out better. When I was blind to the psychology, things went badly.

例如，在Dilbert大获成功后，我曾短暂地考虑过推出第二部漫画。我在Dilbert 的原版网站上发布了一些早期样本，希望这部漫画讲述的是一个格格不入的埃尔波尼亚小男孩的故事。他叫 Plop，是世界上唯一一个没有胡子的埃尔波尼亚人，其中包括女人和婴儿。第一天，Plop 漫画比第一部Dilbert漫画好很多，但远不及当时的Dilbert 漫画。我没有想到——我的盲点——我的新漫画会被拿来与Dilbert比较，而不是与其他新漫画比较。与Dilbert相比，它平淡无奇，缺乏亮点。与同年由不知名漫画家创作的所有新漫画相比，我的漫画竞争力相当强。我收到的大部分电子邮件反馈都是“保住你的日常工作”以及“这不是 Dilbert”。我没想到成为一名成功的漫画家竟然会成为创作新漫画的障碍，但对我来说确实如此。如果我事先明白这一点，就能节省很多时间。

For example, after Dilbert became a hit, I briefly considered launching a second comic. I posted on the original Dilbert website some early samples of what I hoped would be a comic about a young Elbonian boy who didn’t fit in. His name was Plop, and he was the only unbearded Elbonian in the world, and that included the women and babies. On day one, the Plop comic was a lot better than the first Dilbert comics, but not nearly as good as Dilbert had become by that time. What I didn’t count on—my blind spot—was that my new comic would be compared to Dilbert, not to other new comics. Compared to Dilbert, it was flat and lacked an edge. Compared to all the new comics that launched that same year from unknown cartoonists, it was fairly competitive. Most of my feedback by email was of the “Keep your day job” variety along with “It’s no Dilbert.” I wouldn’t have guessed that being a successful cartoonist would be a barrier to launching a new comic, but in my case it was. I could have saved a lot of time if I understood that in advance.

《呆伯特》是第一部以职场为主题的联合漫画。当时，没有什么作品可以与之相比。这让我得以勉强维持糟糕的画风和不成熟的文笔，直到我的技能提升到不那么尴尬的水平。自1989年《呆伯特》问世以来，数十位漫画家尝试进军职场漫画领域，却都因被拿来与成熟的《呆伯特》作比较而遭遇挫败。如果我明天隐瞒身份，推出一部全新的职场漫画，所有角色都是新角色，读者会把它与《呆伯特》作比较，那它就毫无胜算了。

Dilbert was the first syndicated comic that focused primarily on the workplace. At the time, there was nothing to compare it to. That allowed me to get away with bad artwork and immature writing until I could improve my skills to the not-so-embarrassing level. Since the launch of Dilbert in 1989, dozens of cartoonists have tried to enter the workplace-comic space and got clobbered by unfavorable comparisons to a mature Dilbert. If I were to disguise my identity and launch a new workplace comic tomorrow, with all new characters, readers would compare it to Dilbert, and it wouldn’t stand a chance.

在过去二十年左右的时间里，我参加过几十场关于将《呆伯特》改编成故事片的会议。我总是被问到这样一个问题：如何才能让《呆伯特》电影与电视剧《办公室》或邪典电影《上班一条虫》有足够大的区别。这意味着，《呆伯特》电影的质量对其成功的影响，或许不如公众本能地拿来与之比较的事物重要。质量并非宇宙中独立的力量；它取决于你选择的参考标准。

For the past twenty years or so, I have been in a few dozen meetings on the topic of turning Dilbert into a feature film. I always get the question of how we could make a Dilbert movie different enough from the TV show The Office or the cult movie Office Space. The implication is that the quality of a Dilbert movie might be less important to its success than whatever the public reflexively compares it to. Quality is not an independent force in the universe; it depends on what you choose as your frame of reference.

我和合伙人开第二家餐厅时，为了避免抢占生意，决定比第一家更高档，毕竟两家餐厅之间只有五英里远。高档的装潢策略原本看起来很不错，直到我看到一些女士走进餐厅吃午饭，看着高档的装潢，再看看自己的休闲装，就对女主人说自己穿得太随便了。这些自认为穿得太随便的顾客会转身离开。这种情况我亲眼目睹了无数次。在我看来，那些拒绝光顾餐厅的女士们，没有一个穿得太随便。这家餐厅其实不算高档，仍然是一家位于郊区购物中心的社区餐厅。但与附近的其他餐厅相比，它的设计更上一层楼，让人感觉很不舒服。更糟糕的是，我们的菜品质量并没有达到人们对这种装潢风格餐厅的期望。这家餐厅的装潢让我们被拿来与顶级高级餐厅比较。我们的商业模式假设人们更喜欢在格外诱人的环境中享用高档的舒适美食。这想法很糟糕。顾客们感到困惑。这家餐厅究竟应该偏向休闲还是高档？人们将我们的装潢与休闲餐厅进行了比较，认为它过于奢华，无法提供休闲的用餐体验。他们又将我们的菜品与旧金山的顶级餐厅进行了比较，认为我们的菜品不够特别。我们未能预测顾客会如何评价我们的菜品与其他选择。

When my restaurant partner and I built our second restaurant, we decided to make it more upscale than the first so it wouldn’t cannibalize business, given that the two restaurants were only five miles away. The upscale décor strategy seemed like a perfectly good idea until I observed women walk in for lunch, look at the upscale décor, look at their own casual clothes, and proclaim to the hostess that they were underdressed. The self-assessed underdressed customer would turn and leave. I saw that scenario repeat itself over and over. None of the women who rejected themselves from the restaurant looked underdressed to me. The restaurant wasn’t that upscale. It was still a neighborhood restaurant in a suburban strip mall. But compared to other restaurants in the area, it was a step up in design. It made people feel uncomfortable. To make matters worse, our food quality wasn’t up to the level people expected for a place with that type of décor. The restaurant’s appearance caused us to be compared to the very best of fine dining restaurants. Our business model assumed people would prefer eating upscale comfort food in an unusually attractive setting. It was a bad idea. Customers were confused. Was the restaurant supposed to be casual or upscale? People compared our décor to casual restaurants and decided it was too fancy to be a casual eating experience. They compared our food to the top restaurants in San Francisco and decided it wasn’t sufficiently special. We failed to predict how customers would stack us up against alternatives.

这本书本身就提出了一个特别棘手的比较难题。如果我在这本书里加入太多幽默元素，书评人和读者就会把它和其他幽默书籍比较，结果会显得不足，因为很多章节都不适合开笑话。如果我把所有幽默元素都去掉，这本书就会被拿来和自助书籍比较，这本身就有一定的误导性，但我的比较方式可能更胜一筹。换句话说，为了增加你对这本书的享受感，我可能会省略一些你本来会喜欢的幽默元素。

This book itself presents an especially challenging comparison problem. If I add too much humor to this book, reviewers and readers will compare it to other humor books, and it will come up short because many of the chapters don’t lend themselves to jokes. If I leave out all humor, the book will be compared to self-help books, which would be misleading in its own way, but I’d probably come out better in that sort of comparison. In other words, to increase your perceived enjoyment of the book, I might leave out some humor that you would otherwise enjoy.

当我谈到比较问题时，我指的并非简单地将某样事物与其竞争对手进行比较。如果竞争对手比你强，你的问题就不仅仅是顾客感知了。我指的是常识告诉你应该无关紧要的比较，比如将电视节目《呆伯特》与《辛普森一家》进行比较。它们实际上并非竞争对手。它们没有在同一时段播出，也没有以任何有意义的方式耗尽观众有限的可自由支配时间。然而，与《辛普森一家》的比较却阻碍了该节目的成功，因为它将一部成熟的大制作节目与一部资金匮乏、仍在摸索节奏的初创节目进行了对比。动画节目比真人节目需要更长的时间来“调整”，因为动画编剧直到节目完全动画化后才能知道哪些元素有效，而修改为时已晚。任何事情的成功通常意味着多做有效的事情，少做无效的事情。对于动画电视节目来说，这意味着你直到第三季左右才能找到节奏。下半季结束后我们就被取消了。我相信，如果《辛普森一家》从未成为黄金时段动画电视节目的黄金标准，《呆伯特》系列剧应该还有时间更上一层楼。

When I talk of the comparison problem, I don’t mean a simple comparison of one thing to its competition. If the competition is simply better than you, your problem is more than customer perception. I’m talking about comparisons that common sense tells you should be irrelevant, such as comparing Dilbert the TV show to The Simpsons. They weren’t competitors in any real way. They didn’t run during the same slot or exhaust the limited supply of the public’s discretionary time in any meaningful way. And yet the comparison to The Simpsons was a big obstacle to the show’s success because it contrasted a seasoned, big-budget show against a poorly-funded upstart that was still trying to find its rhythm. Animated shows take longer to “tune” than live action because the writers for animation can’t know what worked in a particular show until it is fully animated and too late to change. Success in anything usually means doing more of what works and less of what doesn’t. For animated TV shows, that means you don’t hit your pace until about the third season. We got cancelled after the second half-season. I believe that if The Simpsons had never existed as the gold standard of animated primetime TV shows, the Dilbert show would have had time to reach the next level.

我花了很多时间描述一种心理现象：进行非理性比较的倾向。但一个人究竟需要了解多少心理技巧才能在生活中取得成功呢？

I’ve spent a lot of time describing just one psychological phenomenon: the tendency to make irrational comparisons. But how many psychological tips and tricks does a person really need to understand to be successful in life?

我估计，心理学里应该有几百条规则你应该略知一二。几十年来，我一直在吸收这个领域的知识，但我感觉自己似乎还远远没有达到极限。而且，我学到的关于人类心理学的几乎所有知识最终都派上了用场。

My best guess is that there are a few hundred rules in psychology you should have a passing familiarity with. I’ve been absorbing information in this field for decades, and I don’t feel as if I’m getting anywhere near the end of it. And just about everything I learn about human psychology ends up being helpful.

我查阅了维基百科，快速列出了人类常陷入的心理和认知陷阱。心理学领域广阔，远远超出了本书的讨论范围。我的目的是让你明白，你掌握的信息量之大，而且大多数都是免费的。清单上的每一个心理陷阱都可能被用来操纵你。如果你不熟悉清单上的内容，你就很容易上当受骗。在某些情况下，你会错失提升产品和自身吸引力的机会。

I went to Wikipedia to get a quick list of the psychological and cognitive traps that humans often fall into. Psychology is an immense field and well beyond the scope of this book. My point is to impress upon you how many useful nuggets of information are at your disposal, and most of them are free. Every psychological trap on this list can be used to manipulate you. If there’s something on this list that you’re not familiar with, you’re vulnerable to deception. In some cases, you’re missing opportunities to make your product and yourself more attractive to others.

把心理学作为终身学习的课题是个好主意。作为一名普通公民，你需要知道的大部分知识都可以从互联网上获取。

It’s a good idea to make psychology your lifelong study. Most of what you need to know as a regular citizen can be gleaned from the Internet.

以下是维基百科列出的认知偏差。1看起来有很多东西需要了解，但你用一生的时间去学习这些知识。你可以把它想象成一个系统，你每年都会学习一点。如果你明白心理学对你人生中想要实现的一切目标有多么重要，那么理解心理学的重要性就会更容易理解。如果以1到10为标准，理解心理学的重要性是10分。

Below is Wikipedia’s list of cognitive biases.1 It looks like a lot to know, but you have your entire life to acquire the knowledge. Think of it as a system in which you learn a bit every year. That will be easier if you understand how important psychology is to everything you want to accomplish in life. On a scale of one to ten, the importance of understanding psychology is a solid ten.

清单上的一些条目是常识，你可能已经用其他名称了解它们。我列出完整的清单只是为了让你感受一下这个领域的深度。我甚至想说，清单上任何你不理解的东西都可能在未来让你损失金钱。

Some entries on the list are common sense, and you might already know them by other names. I include the comprehensive list just to give you a feel for how deep the field is. And I would go so far as to say that anything on the list you don’t understand might cost you money in the future.

你一定听过一句老话：知识就是力量。但心理学知识才是这种力量最纯粹的形式。无论你做什么，或者做得多么好，你都能从更深入地理解大脑如何解读世界获益，而这些线索正是通过你头骨上的孔洞进入大脑的。

You’ve heard the old saying that knowledge is power. But knowledge of psychology is the purest form of that power. No matter what you’re doing, or how well you’re doing it, you can benefit from a deeper understanding of how the mind interprets its world using only the clues that somehow find a way into your brain through the holes in your skull.

二十几岁的时候，我参加了一个催眠认证课程。我觉得这门课程会很有趣，而且可能很有用。我甚至考虑过做催眠师赚点外快。但我最终放弃了，因为我不想从事这种出卖时间的行业。但从学习催眠中汲取的技能和洞见，几乎提升了我所有工作的表现，从商业到个人生活。这段时间花得很值。

When I was in my twenties, I took a certification course in hypnosis. I thought it would be fascinating and maybe useful. I even considered making some money on the side as a hypnotist. I decided against it because I didn’t want to be in the business of selling my time. But the skills and insights I gleaned from studying hypnosis have improved my performance in just about everything I’ve done since then, from business to my personal life. It was time well spent.

在催眠中，你不会花太多时间去探究为什么一种技巧有效，而另一种无效。催眠很大程度上是一个反复试验的过程，它运用你自己的经验以及前辈催眠师的经验来减少错误操作的数量。从这个意义上讲，催眠把人当作可以编程的机器。只要你提供正确的输入，就能得到你想要的输出。

In hypnosis, you don’t spend much time asking why one technique works and why another does not. Hypnosis is largely a trial-and-error process that uses your own experience plus that of hypnotists who have gone before to reduce the number of wrong moves. In that sense, hypnosis treats people as if they are machines that can be programmed. If you provide the right inputs, you get the outputs you want.

催眠是一个不精确的过程，因为每个人的大脑中化学成分不同。例如，如果我让你放松，想象一片夏日的森林，你可能会觉得这是一个令人愉悦的画面。除非你害怕熊或害怕在荒野中迷路，否则想到森林你可能会感到不安。催眠师会通过察觉呼吸、姿势、动作和肤色的细微变化来判断所呈现的图像是否按预期发挥作用。并据此进行调整。简而言之，催眠师会尝试多做有效的事，少做无效的事。

Hypnosis is an inexact process because every brain has a different mix of chemistry. For example, if I ask you to relax and imagine a forest in the summer, you might find that a pleasing image. Unless you are afraid of bears or are scared of getting lost in the wilderness, then you might get agitated by the thought of a forest. A hypnotist learns to detect slight changes in breathing, posture, movement, and skin tone to know if the images presented are working as planned. Adjustments are made accordingly. In the simplest terms, a hypnotist tries to do more of whatever works and less of what doesn’t.

我的催眠经历彻底改变了我看待他人以及解读他们选择的方式。我不再将理性视为行为的驱动力。我看到的是简单的因果关系，就像机器的运作方式一样。如果你相信人们会运用理性做出重要决定，那么你一生都会感到困惑和沮丧，因为其他人似乎缺乏理性。事实上，理性只是我们决策的驱动力之一，而且往往是最小的一个。

My experience with hypnosis completely changed the way I view people and how I interpret the choices they make. I no longer see reason as the driver of behavior. I see simple cause and effect, similar to the way machines operate. If you believe people use reason for important decisions, you will go through life feeling confused and frustrated that others seem to have bad reasoning skills. The reality is that reason is just one of the drivers of our decisions, often the smallest one.

最近，我和妻子去买新车。我们在网上和实体店看了很多车型，没有一款能让我们无法抗拒。后来，我们偶然发现了一辆非常“我们”的车，看到它时我忍不住笑了出来。我几乎能感觉到，在我们还没做任何推理、收集数据或讨价还价之前，我的大脑就已经做出了决定。我能感觉到我妻子也有同样的感受。这辆车显然是属于我们的，看到它就像是窥见了未来。

Recently, my wife and I went shopping for a new vehicle. We looked at a lot of models online and in person, and none were irresistible. Then we came upon a vehicle that was so “us” that I laughed when I saw it. I could almost feel my brain make up its mind before we had done one iota of reasoning, data gathering, or negotiating. I could tell that my wife had the same experience. This car was so obviously going to belong to us that seeing it was like peering into the future.

不出所料，之后我们对这辆车的了解似乎都很好，或者说还不错。我们说服自己价格合理。我们说服自己，它的功能正是我们想要的。最终，我们说服自己，我们谈成了一笔好交易。

Predictably, everything we learned about the car after that point seemed either good or good enough. We convinced ourselves that the price was reasonable. We convinced ourselves that the features were just what we wanted. And eventually, we convinced ourselves we had negotiated a good deal.

人们通常看待我们购车经历的方式是，我们看到一款足够吸引我们的车型，然后做了功课，运用我们的推理能力，最终做出了理性的决定。但事实却截然不同。我内心的业余催眠师知道，我们对这辆车的本能反应，是购买过程中“思考”的始末。我们确实做了一些尽职调查，以确保它符合我们的基本要求，但我们已经“知道”它会满足。这次购买是一个非理性的决定，它试图让我相信它是理性的产物，但最终失败了。

The normal way people would look at our car-buying experience is that we saw a model that looked good enough to interest us, then we did our homework, applied our reasoning abilities, and came to a rational decision. The reality is quite different. The amateur hypnotist in me knows that our visceral reaction to the car was the beginning and end of the “thinking” that went into the purchase. We did some due diligence to make sure it met our basic requirements, yes, but we already “knew” it would. The purchase was an irrational decision that tried and failed to sell itself to me as the product of reason.

知道人们何时运用理性，何时将非理性合理化，这非常有用。如果你试图让别人在理性无法影响决策的情况下理解理性，那你就是在浪费时间。如果你曾与一位朋友进行过一场令人沮丧的政治辩论，而他拒绝接受你论点中的逻辑，你就会明白我的意思。但请记住，这位朋友对你的看法完全一样。

It is tremendously useful to know when people are using reason and when they are rationalizing the irrational. You’re wasting your time if you try to make someone see reason when reason is not influencing the decision. If you’ve ever had a frustrating political debate with a friend who refuses to see the logic in your argument, you know what I mean. But keep in mind that the friend sees you exactly the same way.

政客们知道，说谎会被媒体揭穿。他们也知道这无关紧要。政客们明白，理性永远不会对投票决定产生太大影响。一个让选民感觉良好的谎言比一百个理性的论点更有效。即使选民知道谎言是谎言，情况也是如此。如果你对社会如何能容忍如此明目张胆说谎的政客感到困惑，那你就认为人是理性的生物。这种世界观令人沮丧，而且局限性很大。研究催眠的人开始将人类视为潮湿的机器，只是根据程序化的输出对输入做出反应。除了排除最荒谬的选项之外，没有任何推理。你的推理可以阻止你投票给一个彻头彻尾的白痴，但不能阻止你支持一个留着漂亮发型的傻瓜。

When politicians lie, they know the press will call them out. They also know it doesn’t matter. Politicians understand that reason will never have much of an effect on voting decisions. A lie that makes a voter feel good is more effective than a hundred rational arguments. That’s even true when the voter knows the lie is a lie. If you’re perplexed at how society can tolerate politicians who lie so blatantly, you’re thinking of people as rational beings. That worldview is frustrating and limiting. People who study hypnosis start to view humans as moist machines that are simply responding to inputs with programmed outputs. No reasoning is involved beyond eliminating the most absurd options. Your reasoning can prevent you from voting for a total imbecile, but it won’t stop you from supporting a halfwit with a great haircut.

如果你的世界观是人们在重要决策时运用理性，那么你的人生注定充满挫败和困惑。你会发现自己不断地与人争论，却永远无法取得胜利，除了在自己的内心深处。很少有东西比假设人们大多是理性的世界观更具破坏性和局限性。

If your view of the world is that people use reason for their important decisions, you are setting yourself up for a life of frustration and confusion. You’ll find yourself continuously debating people and never winning except in your own mind. Few things are as destructive and limiting as a worldview that assumes people are mostly rational.

在美国广播公司 (ABC) 的单身女郎节目中，其中一名争夺对象的单身男子对他希望娶的年轻女子开了一个恶作剧。这个恶作剧包括带她去他父母家，并让她相信他还住在那里，但事实并非如此。这个恶作剧玩得很精彩，甚至还假装了一个脏乱不堪的卧室。追求者未能理解的是，在真相大白之后很长一段时间，单身女郎仍然会对恶作剧中的场景有感觉。在单身女郎的脑海中 — — 我们所有人都有非理性的一面 — — 这个家伙是个住在家里的失败者的记忆就像一个无法去除的污点。我想单身女郎是真心喜欢这个恶作剧的，并且开怀大笑。但我和妻子互相转过身说：“他完蛋了。” 不久之后，他就被淘汰了。我们无法知道这个笑话对单身女郎的决定有多大影响，但我的催眠训练告诉我，它可能影响很大。

On an episode of The Bachelorette, a show on ABC, one of the contending single men played a practical joke on the young woman he hoped to marry. The joke involved taking her to his parents’ home and convincing her that he still lived there, which he didn’t. The joke was well-executed, complete with a fake bedroom that was a disgusting mess. What the suitor failed to understand is that the bachelorette would still feel the scenario in the joke long after the truth was revealed. In the bachelorette’s mind—the irrational part we all have—the memory of this fellow being a live-at-home loser was like a stain that couldn’t be removed. I think the bachelorette genuinely appreciated the joke and had a good laugh. But my wife and I turned to each other and said, “He’s toast.” He was eliminated soon after. We can’t know how much impact the joke had on the bachelorette’s decision, but my training with hypnosis tells me it was probably huge.

苹果的成功很大程度上归功于史蒂夫·乔布斯的深刻理解：产品带给用户的感受高于其他大多数因素，包括价格。如果史蒂夫·乔布斯认为人是理性的，他或许会走上类似戴尔的道路，以尽可能低的价格销售性能卓越的电脑。戴尔当然也成功了，但如果消费者理性，那么大约一年后就只剩下一家电脑制造商了；消费者总是会购买物有所值的最佳电脑，并在一夜之间赶走劣质产品。对于戴尔和其他几家Windows电脑制造商来说，幸运的是，只要产品雷同，拥有足够多缺乏理性、信息不充分的人，就能维持几家公司的运营。乔布斯的世界观使他找到了一种高利润的商业模式，而Windows电脑如今却成了大众商品。

Apple owes much of its success to Steve Jobs’ understanding that the way a product makes users feel trumps most other considerations, including price. If Steve Jobs saw people as rational beings, he might have followed a path similar to Dell, selling highly capable machines at the lowest possible price. Dell succeeded, too, of course, but if buyers were rational, there would have been only one computer manufacturer left after about a year; consumers would always buy the best computer for the money and drive out the bad players overnight. Luckily for Dell and several other Windows computer manufacturers, there are enough irrational people with poor information to keep several companies afloat so long as their products are confusingly similar. Jobs’ worldview led him to a business model with high margins, whereas Windows computers have become commodities.

如果你觉得我夸大了人们非理性的程度，请允许我为这个想法划定一些界限。人们当然会基于理性的考量做出一些小决定。你可能以审慎的方式投资——或者你自认为如此。但请记住，2009年的金融危机之所以发生，是因为即使是最优秀的投资者也对他们无法理解的金融工具抱有非理性的乐观态度。

If you feel I’m overstating the case that people are irrational, allow me to put some boundaries around that idea. People certainly make small decisions based on rational considerations. You probably invest your money in ways that are prudent—or so you think. But keep in mind that the financial meltdown of 2009 happened because even the best investors were irrationally optimistic about financial instruments they couldn’t hope to understand.

在任何复杂到人类无法理解的情况下，理性行为尤其无用。手机公司利用这一事实，提供过于复杂、难以与竞争对手比较的定价方案。（我创造了“混淆垄断”一词来描述这种策略。）其目的是阻止消费者运用他们所拥有的哪怕是微不足道的推理能力来比较价格和功能。相反，消费者会做出很大程度上不了解情况的决定，并说服自己他们做得不错。我的经验之谈，我最近刚刚从一家无线运营商换到另一家，并计划很快进行第三次更换。我告诉自己，每次更换都是基于价格、覆盖范围和功能。但前两次选择无线运营商时，理性并没有帮助我，下次可能也不会有帮助，因为定价方案故意设计得难以比较。

Rational behavior is especially useless in any situation that is too complex for a human to grasp. Cellphone companies exploit that fact by offering pricing plans too complicated to compare to the competition. (I coined the word “confusopoly” to describe that strategy.) The intent is to prevent consumers from using whatever small reasoning power they possess to compare prices and features. Instead, consumers make largely uninformed decisions and convince themselves they did well. I speak from experience, having recently moved from one wireless carrier to another while planning a third move soon. I tell myself that each of the moves was based on price, coverage, and features. But reason didn’t help me the first two times I chose a wireless carrier, and it probably won’t help the next time because the pricing plans are intentionally hard to compare.

我认为你不需要成为催眠师才能理解人类心理学，尽管这很有帮助。但我确实认为，掌握实用的心理学知识对你的成功至关重要——无论是个人生活还是职业发展。把它看作一个终身学习的过程。你会庆幸自己选择了它。随着时间的推移，掌握心理学基础知识会逐渐感觉像是一种超能力，它能让你理解是什么让你周围的人感到困惑和迷茫。

I don’t think you need to become a hypnotist to understand human psychology, although it helps. But I do think a working knowledge of psychology is essential to your success—both personally and professionally. Consider it a lifelong learning process. You’ll be glad you undertook it. Over time, knowing the psychology basics starts to feel like a superpower that allows you to understand what confuses and confounds those around you.

商务写作

Business Writing

我高中和大学都没上过写作课。我在英语课上学了些基础知识，那些看起来已经足够好了。我能写出别人能理解的句子。我还需要什么呢？

I never took a writing class in high school or in college. I learned the basics in English classes, and those seemed good enough. I could write sentences that people understood. What else did I need?

我确实注意到，商界有些人的文笔非常清晰，说服力也很强。但我认为这只是因为他们特别聪明。我从未想过，这其中蕴含着某种技巧，而我们这些不谙世事的普通民众竟然能轻易学会。

I did notice that some people in the business world wrote with an impressive level of clarity and persuasiveness. But I figured that was just because those people were extra smart. It never occurred to me that there was some technique involved and that we unwashed citizens could easily learn it.

在我的公司生涯中，有一天，我报名参加了公司赞助的商务写作课程。这是我更大战略的一部分，即尽可能多地学习任何将来可能有用的东西，前提是雇主愿意支付费用。我并不指望这门课程能改变我的人生。我只是想学习一些提高写作水平的技巧和窍门。

One day during my corporate career, I signed up for a company-sponsored class in business writing. This was part of my larger strategy of learning as much as I could about whatever might someday be useful while my employer was willing to foot the bill. I didn’t have high hopes that the class would change my life. I was just looking for some tips and tricks for better writing.

我完全误解了这门课的实用性。我记得这门课只有两个下午。但它改变了我的人生。

I was very wrong about how useful the class would be. If I recall, the class was only two afternoons long. And it was life-altering.

事实证明，商务写作的关键在于直奔主题，摒弃所有不必要的赘言。你以为自己在写作中已经做到了这一点，但你可能并没有。

As it turns out, business writing is all about getting to the point and leaving out all the noise. You think you already do that in your writing, but you probably don’t.

思考一下前面的句子。我故意加了一些噪音。你注意到了吗？以“你认为你已经这样做了……”开头的句子包含一个不必要的词“已经”。去掉它，你得到的还是同样的意思：“你认为你已经这样做了……”。“已经”部分是假设的，是不必要的。这种认识是商务写作的基础。

Consider the previous sentence. I intentionally embedded some noise. Did you catch it? The sentence that starts with “You think you already do that . . .” includes the unnecessary word “already.” Remove it, and you get the same meaning: “You think you do that . . .” The “already” part is assumed and unnecessary. That sort of realization is the foundation of business writing.

商务写作还表明，大脑天生就能更好地理解按特定顺序呈现的概念。例如，你的大脑更容易处理“男孩击中了球”，而不是“球被男孩击中”。用编辑的行话来说，第一句话是直接写作，第二句话是被动写作。虽然差别很小，但在整个文档中，被动写作会累积起来，导致读者疲劳。

Business writing also teaches that brains are wired to better understand concepts that are presented in a certain order. For example, your brain processes “The boy hit the ball” more easily than “The ball was hit by the boy.” In editor’s jargon, the first sentence is direct writing and the second is passive. It’s a tiny difference, but over the course of an entire document, passive writing adds up and causes reader fatigue.

最终，我明白了，那些所谓的“说服力”作家，只不过是在运用普通的商务写作技巧而已。简洁的文笔能让作者看起来更聪明，论点也更有说服力。

Eventually, I learned that the so-called persuasive writers were doing little more than using ordinary business writing methods. Clean writing makes a writer seem smarter and makes their arguments more persuasive.

商务写作也是幽默写作的基础。不必要的文字和消极的写作方式会破坏幽默的时机，就像它们会削弱你观点的说服力一样。如果你想让人们觉得你聪明、有说服力、风趣幽默，可以考虑参加为期两天的商务写作课程。很少有技能能在两天内学到，并能让你受益匪浅。

Business writing is also the foundation for humor writing. Unnecessary words and passive writing kill the timing of humor the same way they kill the persuasiveness of your point. If you want people to see you as smart, persuasive, and funny, consider taking a two-day class in business writing. There aren’t many skills you can learn in two days that will serve you this well.

会计

Accounting

我发现会计几乎学不会，因为整个行业都弥漫着无聊的氛围。但即使你从未亲自做过任何会计工作，对会计的基本了解对于在现代社会中成为一个真正有能力的成年人来说也是必要的。

I found accounting nearly impossible to learn because of the bubbling moat of boredom that surrounds the entire field. But a basic understanding of accounting is necessary to be a fully effective adult in a modern society, even if you never do any actual accounting on your own.

会计是商业词汇的一部分，如果你不理解它的概念，世界将会一片混乱。尤其重要的是，能够在电子表格上创建自己的现金流量预测，并确信自己理解税收影响和所谓的货币时间价值，这将大有裨益。††会计与经济学和商业领域有所交叉，在这两个领域，你都需要了解会计实务。

Accounting is part of the vocabulary of business, and if you don’t understand it on a concept level, the world will be a confusing place. In particular, it’s helpful to be able to create your own cash flow projection on a spreadsheet and feel some confidence that you understand the tax impact and the so-called time value of money.†† Accounting overlaps with the fields of economics and business, and in each of those fields, you need to understand accounting practices.

在我所在的小镇，有一家小餐馆几经易主，每次都推出新的理念和菜单。所有这些理念都有一个共同点，那就是它们都无法成功，因为店里没有足够的桌位来支付运营成本。（我很清楚他们的运营成本，因为我曾经在当地拥有两家餐馆。）我猜，新老板拥有丰富的烹饪经验，但缺乏会计知识。任何有会计技能的人都不会涉足一种纸面上行不通的商业模式。

In my town there’s a tiny restaurant that has changed hands several times, always with a new concept and menu. The one thing that all the concepts have in common is that they can’t work because there aren’t enough tables in the place to cover their expenses. (I have a good idea what their expenses are because I once owned two restaurants in the area.) My guess is that the new operator has plenty of culinary expertise but no accounting knowhow. No one with accounting skill would get involved with a business model that can’t work on paper.

你可以花钱请人做会计和现金流量预测，但这只有在你能以有效的方式审核他们的工作的情况下才有效。更明智的做法是学习足够的会计和电子表格知识，掌握基础知识。

You can pay others to do your accounting and cash flow projections, but that only works if you can check their work in a meaningful way. The smarter play is to learn enough about accounting and spreadsheets that you understand the basics.

设计

Design

在当今世界，无论我们是否愿意，我们都是设计师。你可能正在设计PowerPoint演示文稿、为你的初创公司设计网站，或者为孩子的学校活动设计传单。你也在布置你的家，购买你希望别人看起来好看的衣服，等等。设计曾经是艺术家和其他专家的专属领域。现在，我们每个人都应该对设计有一定的了解。

In today’s world, we’re all designers whether we like it or not. You might be designing PowerPoint presentations, a website for your startup, or flyers for your kid’s school event. You’re also furnishing your home, buying clothes you hope look nice to others, and so on. Design used to be the exclusive domain of artists and other experts. Now we’re all expected to have a working understanding of design.

如果你像我一样，天生就没有任何设计技能。直到成年之后，我才惊讶地发现，设计是基于规则的。设计不需要“眼光”；对于普通人来说，了解规则就足够了。

If you’re like me, you were born with no design skills whatsoever. I was amazed to learn, well into my adult years, that design is rules-based. One need not have an “eye” for design; knowing the rules is good enough for civilians.

例如，景观设计师会告诉你，最好在院子里种三棵同种灌木，而不是两棵或四棵。在这种情况下，奇数看起来更好。你不需要设计眼光就能数到三，而且至少在这个有限的例子中，你得到的结果和专家一样。

For example, landscape designers will tell you that it’s better to put three of the same kind of bush in your yard, not two and not four. Odd numbers just look better in that context. You don’t need an eye for design to count to three, and you get the same result as the expert, at least in that limited example.

我还了解到，从杂志封面到油画，再到 PowerPoint 幻灯片，任何艺术作品的构图都应该遵循一些基本模板。最常见的是L形布局。想象页面上有一个巨大的字母L，沿着字母 L 的形状填充密集的内容，在四个开放象限中的一个象限中留出较少的杂乱。艺术家将这部分整洁的部分称为负空间。以油画为例，你可能在一侧画一棵树，在底部画一些风景，在左上角画一片开阔的天空。你可以通过旋转L来改变布局，留出一个比其他象限更简洁的象限，但这仍然是 L 的概念。

I also learned that art composition for anything from a magazine cover to an oil painting to a PowerPoint slide should conform to a few basic templates. The most common is the L-shaped layout. You imagine a giant letter L on the page and fill in the dense stuff along its shape, leaving less clutter in one of the four open quadrants. Artists call the uncluttered part negative space. In the case of an oil painting, you might have a tree going up one side, some landscape on the bottom, and the open sky in the top left. You can change it up by rotating the L and leaving a different quadrant less busy than the rest, but it’s still the L concept.

拍照时，你可以运用同样的方法。不要把人物放在照片的中心，而是调整视野，让人物位于L形的一侧，地面位于下方。不那么显眼的象限可能是一些风景或日落。

When you take a photograph, you can use the same concept. Instead of centering the person in the pictures, adjust your field until the person is one side of the L and the ground is the bottom. The less busy quadrant might be some landscape or the sunset.

设计 PowerPoint 幻灯片或网页时，思路是一样的。你留出一个象限，让其他象限显得简洁一些。翻阅任何一本设计精良的杂志，你会发现80% 的艺术作品和摄影作品都采用了L 形设计。剩下的 20% 是一些特殊情况，我就不赘述了。我只是想让你明白设计的重要性，以及它能让你轻松掌握主要思想。只需学习一些设计技巧，人们就会觉得你更聪明，而你却不知道具体原因。

When you design a PowerPoint slide or a web page, it’s the same idea. You leave one quadrant less busy than the rest. Skim through any well-designed magazine and you’ll see the L design in 80 percent of the art and photography. The other 20 percent will be some special cases that I won’t go into here. I’m only trying to convince you of the importance of design and the ease with which you can pick up the main idea. Learn just a few design tricks, and people will think you’re smarter without knowing exactly why.

会话技巧

Conversation Skills

很少有人是熟练的谈话者。大多数人只是在说话，这两者是两码事。区别在于，熟练的谈话者掌握了一些对很多人来说出奇地不为人知的技巧。我人生的前半段对谈话技巧一无所知。十几岁的时候，我觉得谈话完全是浪费时间，应该避免。我知道谈话有很多所谓的理由，但我看不出它们有什么价值。我当时觉得很无聊。

Few people are skilled conversationalists. Most people are just talking, which is not the same thing. The difference is that skilled conversationalists have learned techniques that are surprisingly non-obvious to a lot of people. I was among the clueless about conversation skills for the first half of my life. When I was a teen, I thought conversation was a complete waste of time and something to be avoided. I was aware that there were several alleged reasons for conversation, but I didn’t see much value in them. I was a bore.

进行对话的理由可能有十几个甚至更多，这取决于你如何看待它。你可能开始一段对话是为了……

There are probably a dozen or more reasons to have a conversation, depending on how you slice it. You might start a conversation to . . .

交换信息

Exchange information

计划

Plan

抱怨

Complain

招待

Entertain

感受联系

Feel connected

成为朋友

Befriend

勾引

Seduce

说服

Persuade

要有礼貌

Be polite

避免尴尬的沉默

Avoid awkward silence

吹牛

Brag

不善言辞的人会专注于清单上那些贫乏的部分，大肆吹嘘、抱怨和交换信息。可以说，这样的人根本不懂得什么是对话，也不懂得如何进行对话。我人生的最初几十年就属于这类人。

A bad conversationalist will focus on the impoverished part of the list, doing a lot of bragging, complaining, and exchanging information. It’s fair to say that such a person doesn’t understand what conversation is and how to do it. I fell into that category for the first few decades of my life.

我第一次意识到，对话是一项可以学习的技能，而且它的好处比我想象的要大，是在我上之前提到的戴尔·卡耐基课程的时候。这门课的重点是公开演讲，但我们也学习了与陌生人交谈的技巧，比如在聚会或商务场合。这个技巧简单得可笑，却百分百有效。你只需要自我介绍，然后提问，直到找到共同感兴趣的话题。

My first inkling that conversation was a learnable skill and that the benefits of conversation were larger than I imagined happened while I was taking the Dale Carnegie course I mentioned earlier. The focus of the class was on public speaking, but we also learned techniques for making conversation with strangers, such as one might in a party or business situation. The technique is laughably simple and 100 percent effective. All you do is introduce yourself and ask questions until you find a point of mutual interest.

我尽量把我记得的戴尔·卡耐基的问题表述一下。大致如下：

I’ll paraphrase the Dale Carnegie question stack as best I remember it. It goes something like this:

  1. 你叫什么名字？
  2. What’s your name?
  3. 你住在哪里？
  4. Where do you live?
  5. 你有家人吗？
  6. Do you have a family?
  7. 你靠什么谋生？
  8. What do you do for a living?
  9. 你有什么爱好/运动吗？
  10. Do you have any hobbies/sports?
  11. 您有任何旅行计划吗？
  12. Do you have any travel plans?

如果你和我一样，这些问题对于刚认识的人而言似乎有点过于尴尬和私密。在参加戴尔·卡耐基课程之前，我遇到新朋友时会立刻进入玩笑模式，因为我不知道还能聊些什么。我发现，大概只有5%的人愿意和陌生人开玩笑。而在这5%的人中，可能只有一半的人会欣赏你觉得好笑的话语。其他人都会希望你走开。虽然大多数人都喜欢幽默，但一般情况下，人们在了解彼此之前不会直接进入玩笑模式。

If you’re like me, the questions seem a bit too awkward and personal for someone you just met. Prior to experiencing the Dale Carnegie course, I would meet someone new and immediately go into joking mode because I didn’t know what else to talk about. I discovered that perhaps only 5 percent of the general population wants to get into joking mode with a stranger. And of that 5 percent, maybe only half of them will appreciate whatever you think is funny. Everyone else will want you to go away. While most people enjoy humor, the typical person doesn’t go directly there before getting to know someone.

让这五个问题有效且不显得尴尬的秘诀在于，你要明白你遇到的人和你一样会感到尴尬。对方想聊一些有趣的话题，并且听起来很有见识。你的工作就是让这变得容易。没有什么比谈论自己更容易的了。我甚至可以说，99% 的人都喜欢谈论自己。当你问陌生人一个私人问题时，你会让对方感到高兴。你的问题可以缓解尴尬沉默的压力，让谈话继续下去。最重要的是，它表明你对陌生人感兴趣，大多数人会将这理解为友好和社交自信，即使你是假装的。而假装的社交自信会随着时间的推移转化为真正的自信。

The secret to making the list of five questions work without seeming awkward is in understanding that the person you meet will feel every bit as awkward as you. That person wants to talk about something interesting and sound knowledgeable. Your job is to make that easy. Nothing is easier than talking about oneself. I would go so far as to say that 99 percent of the general public LOVE talking about themselves. When you ask a stranger a personal question, you make that person happy. Your question relieves the stress of awkward silence and gets the conversation moving. Best of all, it signals that you have interest in the stranger, which most people interpret as friendliness and social confidence, even if you’re faking it. And faking social confidence leads to the real thing over time.

作为一名谈话者，你的职责就是不断提问，不断寻找你和陌生人的共同点，或者一些足够让你感兴趣、足以深入探讨的话题。我这辈子遇到的陌生人，每一位都有着引人入胜的人生经历，只要你问对了问题，就能倾诉衷肠。如果你营造出一种安全感，每个人都会对你感兴趣。以下是一些良好谈话技巧的总结：

Your job as a conversationalist is to keep asking questions and keep looking for something you have in common with the stranger or something that interests you enough to wade into the topic. In my entire life, I have never met a stranger who didn’t have some fascinating life experiences that spill out—if you ask the right questions.
