Everyone is interesting if you make the situation feel safe. Here’s a summary of good conversation technique:

  1. 提出问题。
  2. Ask questions.
  3. 不要（过多）抱怨。
  4. Don’t complain (much).
  5. 不要谈论无聊的经历（电视节目、饭菜、梦想等）。
  6. Don’t talk about boring experiences (TV show, meal, dream, etc.).
  7. 不要主导谈话。让其他人说话。
  8. Don’t dominate the conversation. Let others talk.
  9. 不要纠结于一个话题。继续讨论。
  10. Don’t get stuck on a topic. Keep moving.
  11. 计划很有用，但它不是对话。
  12. Planning is useful, but it isn’t conversation.
  13. 尽量简短地讲述悲伤的故事，尤其是医疗故事。
  14. Keep the sad stories SHORT, especially medical stories.

对话的意义在于让对方感觉良好。如果你正确地做到了这一点，其他好处也会随之而来。例如，一个喜欢你的人更有可能被说服，向你推荐好的机会，分享信息，并希望与你建立关系。如果你因为难以忍住而不得不抱怨，那么最好向已经喜欢你的人抱怨；这样，你就能获得你想要的同理心。

The point of conversation is to make the other person feel good. If you do that one simple thing correctly, the other benefits come along with the deal. For example, a person who likes you is more likely to be persuaded, to recommend you for good opportunities, to share information, and to want a relationship with you. And if you must complain because it’s just too hard to keep it in, you’re better off complaining to someone who already likes you; that way, you’ll get the empathy you want.

那么，如何让陌生人喜欢你呢？其实很简单。首先要面带微笑，并保持肢体语言的开放。之后，只需提问，并像关心一样倾听，同时寻找共同的兴趣爱好。每个人都喜欢谈论自己的生活，也都喜欢有同理心的倾听者。最终，如果你发现了一些共同的兴趣爱好，你就会毫不费力地感受到彼此的联系。

So how do you get a stranger to like you? It’s simple. It starts by smiling and keeping your body language open. After that, just ask questions and listen as if you care, all the while looking for common interests. Everyone likes to talk about their own life, and everyone appreciates a sympathetic listener. Eventually, if you discover some common interests, you’ll feel a connection without any effort.

如果你外表魅力十足，可能不太好说话。人们天生就喜欢有魅力的人。多说话只会让情况更糟。如果你本身就很有魅力，在谈论你收集幼年动物头骨的爱好，或者其他你感兴趣的事之前，一定要先建立牢固的联系。话越少越好，至少在认识某人的初期是这样。

If you’re physically attractive, it probably isn’t a good idea to talk too much. People are predisposed to liking attractive people. Talking can only make it worse. If you’re attractive, be sure you’ve created a solid connection before discussing your hobby of collecting baby animal skulls or whatever-the-hell you’re into. The less you say, the better, at least in the early stages of getting to know someone.

如果你缺乏吸引力——而这正是我的专长——你的谈话技巧就显得尤为重要。除非你拥有世界级的成就，否则这些可能就是你推销自己的全部资本。所以你需要提升你的谈话技巧。这意味着你要成为讲短小精悍、引人入胜故事的高手。

If you’re unattractive—and this is my area of expertise—your conversation skills will be especially important. Those might be all you have to sell yourself unless you’re accomplished in some world-class way. So you’ll need to take your conversation skills up a notch. And that means becoming the master of short but interesting stories.

作为一名作家，我会本能地将观察到的一切转化为故事，并设置背景、转折（如果有的话），以及一些妙语或想法来收尾。你也可以这样做。试着养成习惯，问问自己如何将有趣的经历转化为故事。我发现，想象一下把故事讲给某个特定的人听，比如配偶、朋友或亲戚，会很有帮助。在脑海中尝试几个版本，讲述这个故事，感受它的进展。故事简短吗？你是否把惊喜留到了恰当的时机？你是否找到了用妙语或有趣的观察来结束故事的方法？

As a writer, I reflexively translate whatever I observe into a story form with a setup, a twist if there is one, and some sort of punch line or thought that ties it in a bow. You can do the same thing. Try to get in the habit of asking yourself how you can turn your interesting experiences into story form. I find it helps to imagine telling the story to someone in particular, such as a spouse, friend, or relative. Try a few versions in your head, telling the story and feeling how it goes. Was it brief? Did you save the surprise for just the right moment? Did you have a way to end the story with a punch line or interesting observation?

积压一些故事，随时可以拿出来读，是个好主意。而且，你也要不断用新素材更新你的内部故事数据库。比如，如果我知道几天后要见朋友，我会特别提醒自己，把最近的经历写成故事，因为我知道以后会有理由拿出来写。最受欢迎的故事类型是……搞笑故事。

It’s a good idea to always have a backlog of stories you can pull out at a moment’s notice. And you’ll want to continually update your internal story database with new material. For example, if I know I’ll be seeing friends in a few days, I make a special note to myself to turn my recent experiences into story form because I know I’ll have a reason to bust one out. The most popular type of stories are . . . funny stories.

我认为每个人都应该学习如何讲一个有趣的故事。我认为人们没有意识到讲故事是一项可以学习的技能，而不是遗传的天赋。一旦你了解了构成一个好故事的要素，你就拥有了从日常经验中雕琢出属于自己的故事的一切所需的一切。

I think everyone should learn how to tell a funny story. I don’t think people realize that storytelling is a learnable skill and not a genetic gift. Once you know the parts that comprise any good story, you have all you need to sculpt your own out of your everyday experiences.

讲好故事最重要的关键在于准备。你肯定不想边讲边琢磨故事情节。如果你遇到了值得写成故事的事情，那就花点时间在脑子里构思故事结构——我一会儿会解释这个结构——然后在脑子里练习讲故事，直到你完全理解为止。

The most important key to good storytelling is preparation. You don’t want to figure out your story as you tell it. If something story-worthy happens to you, spend some time developing the story structure in your head—a structure I will explain in a minute—and practice telling the story in your head until you have it down.

一个好的派对故事的基本组成部分是：

The basic parts of a good party story are:

设置

Setup

故事的铺垫只有一条重要规则：简洁。我的意思是非常简洁，就像“所以，我把车送去修刹车……”这样就够了。不要告诉我们刹车出了什么问题。也不要告诉我们是什么让你觉得刹车出了问题，除非它与故事本身相关。尽量将故事铺垫控制在一句话，最多两句话。

There’s only one important rule for a story setup: Keep it BRIEF. And I mean really brief, as in “So, I took my car in for a brake job . . .” That’s it. Don’t tell us the problem with the brakes. Don’t tell us what made you think you had a brake problem, unless for some reason it is relevant. Try to keep your setup to one sentence, two at most.

图案

Pattern

建立一个你的故事会打破的模式。例如，你可以说：“每当我把车送去做任何保养，我总是惊讶于它有多贵。” 这就建立了模式。现在我们知道接下来的内容将会违反这个模式。我们把这种暗示称为……

Establish a pattern that your story will violate. For example, you could say, “Whenever I take my car for any kind of service, I’m always amazed how expensive it is.” That establishes the pattern. Now we know that what follows will be a violation of the pattern. And we call that hint of things to come . . .

铺垫

Foreshadowing

伏笔意味着你留下一些线索来预示故事的发展方向。伏笔可以在故事的开场阶段就出现，比如说：“我阿肯色州的姻亲家有个叫做‘恐惧洞’的地方，万一龙卷风来袭，大家都会爬进去。它最多只能容纳四个人。” 这就是预先设定好的伏笔。

Foreshadowing means you leave some clues where the story is going. The foreshadowing can happen as early as the setup, as in, “My in-laws in Arkansas have something they call the ‘fraidy hole’ that everyone climbs into in case of tornadoes. It’s meant to hold no more than four people.” That’s the setup with the foreshadowing built in.

角色

The Characters

每个故事都包含人物，你或许就是其中之一。对于那些了解你所有缺点、缺陷和喜好的人来说，无需赘述。但如果你是在和陌生人交谈，或者谈论不熟悉的人，不妨在故事中融入一些相关的人物特征。例如，“我们的朋友鲍勃多年来一直借用我们的电动工具，因为他太抠门，买不起自己的。”这种简短的人物刻画对任何涉及人物的故事都至关重要。所有好的故事都围绕着人物展开。

Every story involves characters, and you might be one of them. For people who know all your foibles, defects, and preferences, no elaboration is required. But if you are talking to strangers or talking about unfamiliar others, fill in the story with some character traits that will be relevant. For example, “Our friend Bob has been borrowing our power tools for years because he’s too cheap to buy his own.” That sort of brief caricature profile is essential to any story that involves people. All good stories are about personalities.

相关性

Relatability

有一个话题是人们最关心的——他们自己。选择一些听众能产生共鸣的故事主题。如果你的故事是关于如何应对一个固执的官僚，那么无论涉及什么样的官僚机构，大多数成年人都能产生共鸣。但如果你的故事是关于拼布比赛的内在运作，你最好简短而诙谐。当你停止谈论与他们无关的事情时，人们就会渐渐走神。

There is one topic that people care more about than any other—themselves. Pick story topics that your listeners will relate to. If your story is about dealing with a stubborn bureaucrat, most adults can relate to it no matter the bureaucracy involved. But if your story is about the inner working of competitive quilting, you’d better make it short and extra witty. People drift off when you stop talking about stuff that isn’t, well, them.

转折

The Twist

你的故事如果没有出乎意料或不寻常的事情发生，就不能称之为故事。这就是情节转折。如果没有转折，那就不能称之为故事。它只是你一天经历的翻版。跟配偶叙叙旧还行，但不会成为派对上的焦点。

Your story isn’t a story unless something unexpected or unusual happens. That’s the plot twist. If you don’t have a twist, it’s not a story. It’s just a regurgitation of your day. That’s fine for catching up with a spouse, but it won’t make you the life of a party.

要避免的话题

Topics to Avoid

讲述有趣的故事很重要。更重要的是，要避免讲述极其无聊或令人沮丧的场景。以下是一些你应该避免的话题​​：

It’s important to tell stories about interesting events. It’s even more important to avoid telling stories about deadly boring or downer situations. Here are a few topics you should avoid:

美食：除非他们计划很快再去同一家餐厅吃饭，否则人们不会在意你的餐点有多好吃。我同意，一些极端的美食家确实能从听到美食故事中获得乐趣。但即使如此，你也应该保持简短。

Food: People don’t care how good your meal was unless they plan to eat at the same place soon. I will agree that some extreme foodies can get pleasure from hearing about food. But even in that case, you want to keep it short.

电视节目情节：谈论你和对话对象都喜欢的电视节目可能很有趣也很有意思。但没有人愿意听你看过而他们没看过的电视节目的完整情节。

Television Show Plots: Talking about TV shows that you and your conversation partner both enjoy can be fun and entertaining. But no one wants to hear the entire plot of a television show that you watched and they didn’t.

梦：没人会在意你梦到的细节。如果你一定要谈论你的梦，那就用一句话来表达，比如：“我梦见一只长得像温斯顿·丘吉尔的花栗鼠在我的麦片碗里游泳。”

Dreams: No one cares about the details of your dream. If you must discuss your dreams, keep it to one sentence, as in, “I dreamed that a chipmunk with a face that looked like Winston Churchill was swimming in my cereal bowl.”

医疗故事：如果你身体正常，或者接近正常，无论我多么有说服力地告诉你这是不好的，你都会滔滔不绝地谈论你的健康问题。如果人们知道你身体不好，他们也会询问你的健康状况。所以你无法完全避免谈论你的健康问题。只要保持你的故事轻松、尽可能幽默、简短即可。最重要的是，要意识到你有责任尽快转移话题。其他人会觉得转移话题很尴尬，因为没有办法做得得体。这是你的职责所在。

Medical Stories: If you are normal or anywhere near it, you will talk too much about your health issues no matter how persuasively I tell you that it’s a bad idea. And people will ask about your health if they know there’s something wrong with you. So you can’t entirely avoid talking about your medical problems. Just keep your stories light, funny if possible, and short. Most importantly, recognize that it’s your responsibility to change the subject as soon as you can. Other people will feel awkward changing the subject from your health problems because there’s no way to do it gracefully. That’s your job.

是的，我知道这本书里有很多与健康相关的故事。但我是个专业人士。如果我做得对，你肯定会好奇我的声音问题最后会如何发展。

And yes, I realize this book has a lot of health-related stories in it. But I’m a professional. And if I did my job right, you’re curious how my voice problem turned out.

微笑，提问，避免抱怨和悲伤的话题，准备好一些有趣的故事。这样你就能跻身所有对话高手的前10%。

Smile, ask questions, avoid complaining and sad topics, and have some entertaining stories ready to go. It’s all you need to be in the top 10 percent of all conversationalists.

克服害羞

Overcoming Shyness

如果你把一个来自偏远部落、从未有人听说过游泳的人扔进海里，他很可能会惊慌失措地溺水身亡。游泳对人类来说并非天生如此。我们需要学习。幸运的是，我们人类只需稍加练习就能轻松学会游泳。

If you take a human from a remote tribe where no one has ever heard of a thing called swimming, and you throw him in the ocean, he’ll probably panic and drown. Swimming isn’t entirely natural to humans. We need to learn it. Luckily, we humans learn to swim easily with a little practice.

害羞就像游泳一样，我们并非生来就拥有克服害羞的本领。有些人天生就比其他人更害羞。但就像游泳一样，我们可以通过一些练习来克服害羞。而且这值得付出努力。否则，你会发现自己在每次聚会或公开演讲中都显得力不从心。

Shyness is analogous to swimming in the sense that we aren’t born with the tools to overcome our own shyness. Some of us have more natural shyness than others. But like swimming, we can learn to overcome shyness with a little practice. And it’s worth the effort. Otherwise, you’ll find yourself socially drowning at every gathering or public talk.

我二十多岁的时候非常害羞，以至于我会开车去参加聚会，停好车后就大汗淋漓，然后开车回家，甚至都不打招呼。

I was so shy when I was in my twenties that I would drive to a party, park my car, break into a full sweat, then drive home without even saying hello.

我很感谢我的一位大学朋友，他教给我一个克服害羞的秘诀：想象自己在表演，而不是在互动。我指的是真正的表演。

I credit one of my college friends for teaching me the secret of overcoming shyness by imagining you are acting instead of interacting. And by that, I mean literally acting.

事实证明，害羞的人更容易装作别人，而不是装作自己。这很有道理，因为害羞源于内心觉得自己不配参与对话。装作别人能让你摆脱这种想法。

It turns out that a shy person can act like someone else more easily than he can act like himself. That makes some sense because shyness is caused by an internal feeling that you are not worthy to be in the conversation. Acting like someone else gets you out of that way of thinking.

当我假装克服天生害羞时，我喜欢想象一个我熟悉的自信的人。我会对这个人留下不好的印象，但这比我习惯性的大汗淋漓、被自己的笑话逗得大笑不止，然后找个借口躲到角落里流汗要好得多。

When I fake my way past my natural shyness, I like to imagine a specific confident person I know well. I do my bad impression of that person, but it comes off much better than my default routine of breaking into a sweat, laughing too hard at my own jokes, and excusing myself to go sit in a corner and perspire.

当我感到害羞时，我也会记住一些事情。首先，我记得大多数人在社交场合至少都会在某些时候感到尴尬。很可能你正在交谈的人也同样害羞。这让我知道，我可能和他们处在一个公平的竞争环境中。对方只是假装自己很擅长社交，就像我一样。

I also like to keep a few things in mind when I feel shyness coming on. First, I remember that most people feel awkward in social situations at least some of the time. Chances are that the person you are talking to is feeling just as shy. It helps me to know I’m probably on a level playing field. The other person is only pretending to be socially talented, just as I am.

避免害羞的最佳秘诀就是学会表现出对别人的兴趣。你当然不想让自己变得爱管闲事，但当你表现出兴趣时，每个人都会很感激。

The single best tip for avoiding shyness involves harnessing the power of acting interested in other people. You don’t want to cross into nosiness, but everyone appreciates it when you show interest.

你还应该弄清楚哪些人是“物”人，哪些人是“人”。“物”人喜欢听新技术、新工具和新奇事物。他们也喜欢讨论流程和系统，包括政治。

You should also try to figure out which people are thing people and which ones are people people. Thing people enjoy hearing about new technology and other clever tools and possessions. They also enjoy discussions of processes and systems, including politics.

人人都喜欢聊一些有趣的事情。一旦话题转到“事”上，他们很快就会感到无聊。一旦你清楚自己是在和“事人”打交道，还是在和“人”打交道，你就能巧妙地调整谈话方式，找到他们最合适的切入点。这会极大地影响人们对你的反应，从而让你更加自信，不再害羞。

People people only enjoy conversations that involve humans doing interesting things. They get bored in a second when the conversation turns to things. Once you know whether you are dealing with a thing person or a people person, you can craft your conversation to their sweet spot. It makes a big difference in how people react to you, and that in turn will make you more confident and less shy.

那些看起来外向的人通常会运用一种你以为天生就很自然的社交技巧。其实不然，至少并非完全如此。外向的人通常来自至少有一位父母外向的家庭。他们会观察并模仿。外向的性格部分源于遗传，但你仍然需要知道什么时候该说什么。这部分是后天习得的。好消息是，你也可以学会。观察外向的人，如果可以的话，学习他们的小技巧。我已经这样做很多年了，效果非常好。

People who appear outgoing are usually employing a learned social skill that you think is somehow natural. It probably isn’t, at least not entirely. Outgoing people usually come from families with at least one outgoing parent. They observe and imitate. Being outgoing is partly genetic, but you still need to know what to say when. That part is learned. And the good news is that you can learn it, too. Observe outgoing people and steal their little tricks if you can. I’ve been doing that for years. It works great.

我也发现提醒自己每个人内心都是一团糟也很有帮助。你很容易以为你面前那个长得好看、谈吐得体的人一切都好，因此比你优秀。但事实上，每个人内心都是一团糟。有些人只是藏得比较好。找个正常人，我就能告诉你一个你不太了解的人。提醒自己，你的缺点和别人相比，其实没那么糟糕，这很有帮助。

I also find it helpful to remind myself that every human is a mess on the inside. It’s easy to assume the good-looking and well-spoken person in front of you has it all together and is therefore your superior. The reality is that everyone is a basket case on the inside. Some people just hide it better. Find me a normal person, and I’ll show you someone you don’t know that well. It helps to remind yourself that your own flaws aren’t that bad compared to everyone else.

我还建议你像锻炼其他肌肉一样锻炼你的自尊心。试着让自己置身于一些一旦出问题就一定会让你尴尬的境地——或者即使没有出问题，你也会感到尴尬。就像任何其他技能一样，抑制害羞需要练习。你把自己置于可能尴尬的境地越多，你就越容易克服它们。

I also recommend exercising your ego the way you’d exercise any other muscle. Try putting yourself in situations that will surely embarrass you if things go wrong—or maybe even if they don’t. Like any other skill, suppressing shyness takes practice. The more you put yourself in potentially embarrassing situations, the easier they all become.

坦白说，当我意识到自己小有名气，并且从事着一份有趣的职业时，我的害羞感就消失了。成功能建立自信，而自信能抑制害羞。如果你不能直接用我列出的这些技巧来控制你的害羞，那就等到你变得富有和出名的时候吧；害羞或许会自然而然地消失。

In the interest of full disclosure, my own shyness dissipated when I realized I was semi-famous and had an interesting profession. Success builds confidence, and confidence suppresses shyness. If you can’t control your shyness directly through the tricks I outlined, wait until you’re rich and famous; the shyness might leave on its own.

第二语言

Second Language

尽管我努力了好几年，却始终没能学会第二语言。语言课上我的笔试成绩不错，但听到别人说另一种语言，我感觉就像烘干机里塞满了嘟囔的小丑。显然，我的大脑不具备学习其他语言的正确机制。

I never learned a second language despite years of trying. I can ace written tests in language classes, but when I hear another language spoken, it sounds like a clothes-dryer full of mumbling clowns. Apparently, my brain doesn’t have the right wiring for learning additional languages.

与只会说一种语言的同龄人相比，掌握第二语言可以让你获得更多的工作机会。在我居住的加州，西班牙语是第二语言的不二之选。我遇到过不少用西班牙语管理员工的小企业主。如果你打算找一份与公众打交道的工作，西班牙语是必不可少的，至少在加州是这样。每个人的情况可能有所不同，但掌握一门额外的语言总是有益的。这会带来巨大的竞争优势。

A second language can qualify you for a greater range of jobs and opportunities compared to your mono-lingual peers. Where I live, in California, Spanish is the obvious choice for a second language. I’ve met quite a few small business owners who use Spanish to manage their employees. And if you plan to get a job that involves working with the public, Spanish is essential, at least in California. Your situation will differ, but it always makes sense to know an extra language. It’s a huge competitive advantage.

如果本章任何内容听起来过于显而易见，请记住，许多人都会读这样的书。我还记得自己年轻时对宇宙的无知。常识竟然如此罕见，真是令人惊讶。另外，请记住，加州的学校仍然因为某些荒谬的原因教授法语，所以显然有人没有理解常识。

If any of this chapter sounds painfully obvious, keep in mind that many different folks will read a book like this. And I remember my own galactic ignorance as a young man. It’s surprising how uncommon common sense is. Also, keep in mind that California schools still teach French for some ridiculous reason, so clearly someone hasn’t gotten the common sense memo.

高尔夫球

Golf

俗话说，生意都是在高尔夫球场上谈的。我是个新手，但据我所知，没人会在高尔夫球场上谈生意。高尔夫最大的好处在于，它尤其能让男性增进感情。男人之间通过共同的活动建立联系。对于成年男性来说，高尔夫几乎可以说是一项全民运动。过了一定年龄，它可能是男性最常见的类似体育运动。

It’s an old cliché that business gets done on the golf course. I’m new to the game, but as far as I can tell, no one ever talks business on a golf course. The thing that golf does well is that it allows males, especially, to bond. Men bond with other men through common activities. And for adult men, golf is as close as you can get to a universal activity. After a certain age, it’s probably the most common sport-like activity for men.

如果你因为高尔夫看起来无趣而拒绝它，那你可能错了。一年前，在学习高尔夫之前，我以为即使这项运动好玩，也只是低级趣味，绝对不值得投入时间和金钱。但我错了。事实证明，在球场上挥杆的几个小时里，高尔夫会让你的大脑进入另一个维度，就像是一次心灵假期。虽然我不会说高尔夫能让人放松，尤其是如果你打得像我一样糟糕，但这种简单的举动能让你把思绪带到一个全新而引人入胜的地方，帮助你摆脱日常的烦恼。这就像一次大脑假期。真的非常棒。

If you’re resisting golf because it doesn’t look fun, you’re likely mistaken. Prior to learning how to golf just one year ago, I assumed that if the game was fun at all, it was a low-grade fun and certainly not worth the time and expense. I was wrong. It turns out that golf transports your brain to another dimension for the hours you are on the course. It’s like a vacation for the mind. And while I wouldn’t call golf relaxing, especially if you play as poorly as I do, the simple act of putting your mind in a completely new and absorbing place can help you escape your daily worries. It’s like a brain vacation. It’s extraordinary, really.

商界女性应该学习高尔夫，原因和男性一样，而且还有一个额外的原因：如果你有约会对象，高尔夫能为你带来绝佳的约会机会。我不知道有多少心仪的男士会更喜欢打高尔夫的普通女性，而不是不打高尔夫的超模，但我敢打赌，这个数字肯定很大。如果你是一位女性，希望提升自己在约会中的购买力，高尔夫将是你巨大的竞争优势。而且你或许也会喜欢它。

Women in the business world should learn golf for the same reasons as men, plus the extra reason that it opens up some tremendous dating opportunities if you’re in the market. I don’t know how many desirable men would prefer an average woman who golfs over a supermodel who doesn’t, but I’ll bet it’s a substantial number. If you’re a woman looking to increase your buying power in the dating pool, golf is a great competitive advantage. And you might enjoy it, too.

还有一件事：如果你在鸡尾酒会上和一位三十多岁的男士聊天，想找个共同感兴趣的话题，高尔夫是个不错的选择。我都数不清有多少次被问到“你会打高尔夫吗？”这个问题让我烦透了，直到我学会了打高尔夫。现在我很高兴能这么轻松地找到共同话题，聊到一些让人感觉愉悦的话题。

One more thing: If you find yourself in cocktail conversation with a male over the age of thirty, and you’re looking for a topic of common interest, golf is a great go-to topic. I can’t tell you how many times I’ve been asked “Do you golf?” It annoyed the hell out of me until I learned the game. Now I’m happy that I can so easily find common ground on a feel-good topic.

正确的语法

Proper Grammar

无论你多么聪明，如果你的语法不够好，受过教育的人都会认为你是个白痴。我不是这方面的专家，但让我告诉你几个让我感到尴尬的常见语法错误。这些错误就像你刚从厕所出来，鞋子上粘着卫生纸一样。人们会注意到的。

No matter how smart you are, educated people will think you’re a moron if your grammar is lacking. I’m not an expert in this category, but let me tell you the few common grammar errors that make me cringe. Each of these is like leaving the restroom with toilet paper stuck to your shoe. People notice.

“如果我是……”

“If I Were . . .”

当你谈论假设将来时，用“were ”而不是“was”。不要说“如果我和你一起去，我会玩得很开心。” 要说“如果我和你一起去，我会玩得很开心。” 这条语法规则很重要。如果你把“were”/“was”的语法弄错了，对那些知道区别的人来说，这是一个危险信号。

When you talk about the hypothetical future, use “were” instead of “was.” Don’t say, “If I was to go with you, I would enjoy myself.” Say, “If I were to go with you, I would enjoy myself.” This rule of grammar is a big one. If you get “were”/”was” grammar wrong, it’s a red flag to people who know the difference.

非文字

Non-Words

使用字典里的单词是个好主意。我一生中的大部分时间都以为“brang”是个词，比如“他给我带了个球”。在我长大的小镇里，这很常见。二十多岁的时候，我惊恐地发现，我这辈子大部分时间都在说一种乡巴佬的语言。“Brang”不在字典里。“Br ought ”在。

It’s a good idea to use words that are in the dictionary. For most of my life, I believed “brang” was a word, as in, “He brang me the ball.” It was common usage in the small town where I grew up. In my late twenties, I was mortified to learn that I had been speaking a hillbilly language for most of my life. “Brang” is not in the dictionary. “Brought” is.

Supposably 也不是一个词。试试“su pposedly”。

Supposably isn’t a word either. Try “supposedly.”

“沮丧”不是一个词，“沮丧至极”才是。

Fustrated isn’t a word. “Frustrated” is.

Libary 不是一个词。“Lib rary ”才是。

Libary isn’t a word. “Library” is .

Nucular 不是一个词。“Nu clear” 才是。

Nucular isn’t a word. “Nuclear” is.

“希望如此”

“Hopefully”

大多数人误用了“hopefully”这个词。“希望她能带甜点来”这种说法语法错误。“hopefully”应该是副词。应该这样说：“我们满怀希望地等着甜点。” 在后一种情况下，“hopefully”正确地修饰了动词“waited”。在第一个例子中，“hopefully”就像一个错误的用词一样被放在那里。

Most people misuse the word “hopefully.” It’s bad grammar to say, “Hopefully, she will bring the dessert.” Hopefully should be an adverb. Say instead, “We waited hopefully for dessert.” In the latter case, hopefully is correctly modifying the verb “waited.” In the first example, “hopefully” just sits there like the wrong word choice.

“我”与“我”

“I” and “Me”

要掌握的最重要的语法规则就是何时使用“我” ，何时使用“我”。我敢打赌，只有不到20%的普通民众能正确掌握这一点。通常情况下，20%的民众评判你并无大碍。但仍然有绝大多数人不会评判你，在大多数情况下，这样做也无妨。问题在于，这20%的人往往是受教育程度最高、最成功的人。这些人正是你在求职、为初创公司融资或求婚时想要打动的人。

The single most important grammar rule to master is when to use “I” and when to use “me”. I’ll bet less than 20 percent of the general public gets that right. Normally, it wouldn’t matter that 20 percent of the public is judging you. That still leaves a strong majority that doesn’t, and for most purposes that would be fine. The problem is that the 20 percent in this case tend to be the most well-educated and successful folks. Those are the same people you might someday want to impress if you’re asking for a job, trying to get venture funding for your startup, or proposing marriage.

“我”与“我”的简单规则是，即使你删除句子中提到的另一个人，句子也必须有意义。例如，如果你说“鲍勃和我去看电影”，那么即使你删除“鲍勃和”，而说“我去看电影”，句子仍然有意义。

The simple rule for “I” versus “me” is that the sentence must make sense if you remove the other person mentioned in the sentence. For example, if you say, “Bob and I went to a movie,” it would still make sense if you removed “Bob and” and said, “I went to a movie.”

如果句子是“请将文件交给鲍勃和我”，你可以删除“鲍勃和”，它仍然可以理解为“请将文件交给我”。你经常会听到聪明人弄错这个规则，所以不要被你听到的正确次数所迷惑。

If the sentence is “Please give the documents to Bob and me,” you can remove “Bob and” and it still makes sense as “Please give the documents to me.” You’ll often hear smart people get this rule wrong, so don’t be fooled by how many times you hear it incorrectly.

“更少”还是“更少”

“Less” or “Fewer”

人们经常在应该说“fewer”的时候说“less”。例如，说“我的朋友比以前少了”就是语法错误。当主语是复数时，比如“friends”，你就用“fewer”——“我的朋友比以前少了”。

People often say “less” when they should say “fewer.” For example, it’s bad grammar to say, “I have less friends than before.” When the subject is plural, as in “friends,” you use “fewer”—“I have fewer friends than before.”

你可以说你的头发比以前少了，但是如果你谈论的是你自己的头发，你会说“我的头发少了”。

It’s okay to say you have less hair than before, but if you were talking about your individual strands of hair you would say, “I have fewer strands of hair.”

“理论”与“假设”

“Theory” Versus “Hypothesis”

非科学家在表达“假设”时经常使用“理论”一词。简单来说，理论是对现实的科学解释，经过充分检验，足以与事实媲美。

Non-scientists often use the word “theory” when they mean “hypothesis.” Without getting too technical, a theory is a scientific explanation of reality that is so well tested it is as good as fact.

未经证实和检验的解释的正确术语是假设。例如，我认为人类可能是外星人在地球上播撒生命种子，这些生命经过数百万年进化而来。我没有证据支持这个想法，所以它只是一个假设。在与朋友交谈时，我可能会称之为理论。如果我发布关于它的帖子，我会谨慎行事，尽量记住称之为假设。我因不当使用“理论”一词而收到的投诉可能比我几乎所有激怒公众的事情都要多，而且这个清单很长。

The correct term for an unproven and untested explanation is a hypothesis. For example, I think it is possible that humans are the result of aliens seeding the earth with life that evolved over millions of years. I have no evidence for that idea, so it’s merely a hypothesis. In conversations with friends, I might call it a theory. If I post about it, I’ll play it safe and try to remember to call it a hypothesis. I’ve probably had more complaints about my inappropriate use of the word “theory” than almost every other thing I’ve done to anger the public, and that’s a long list.

我犯过我提到的大多数语法错误，也经常听到别人犯同样的错误。语法错误并非最糟糕的缺陷，但考虑到改正起来如此轻松，投入的回报比可谓是极高的。学习如何避免最常见的语法错误绝对值得你付出努力。

I’ve made most of the grammar mistakes I mentioned, and I often hear them from others. Bad grammar isn’t the worst flaw you could have, but when you consider how easily you can fix it, the effort-to-reward ratio is excellent. It’s well worth your effort to learn how to avoid the most common grammatical errors.

劝说

Persuasion

无论你的人生使命是什么，你都会花费大量时间试图说服别人。你可能是一位努力达成交易的销售人员，一位努力拯救灵魂的牧师，或者任何有老板、家人或朋友的人。几乎每一次与他人的互动都涉及某种形式的说服，即使这种说服方式很微妙。学习如何更有效地说服别人，难道不是更有意义吗？

No matter your calling in life, you’ll spend a great deal of time trying to persuade people of one thing or another. You might be a salesperson trying to close deals, a minister trying to save souls, or anyone with a boss, a family, or friends. Nearly every interaction with others involves some form of persuasion, even if it’s subtle. Wouldn’t it make sense to learn how to persuade more effectively?

学习说服艺术的一个好起点是去你喜欢的网上书店搜索“说服”。你会看到很多关于这个主题的书籍。继续阅读这些书，直到它们看起来似乎在重复同样的技巧。你会惊讶地发现说服这个话题有多么深奥。而且，你将在余生的几乎每一次商业或个人互动中运用你所学到的知识。成为一名优秀的说服者就像拥有神奇的力量。

A good starting point in learning the art of persuasion is to go to your preferred online bookstore and search for “persuasion.” You’ll see a number of books on the topic. Keep reading those books until they seem to be repeating the same tricks. You’ll be amazed how deep the topic of persuasion is. And you’ll use what you’ve learned in just about every business or personal interaction you have for the rest of your life. Being a good persuader is like having magical power.

当然，这其中也涉及道德方面的考量。你肯定不想说服别人去做那些不符合他们最佳利益的事情。如果你发现自己太擅长说服别人，这可能会让人觉得毛骨悚然，像是在操纵别人。我在说服方面学到了很多，所以当我感觉自己在和一个没有棍棒的人打架时，我会刻意地收敛一下。有时候，比起被别人操纵，我更乐意不按自己的想法行事。说服是一项强大的技能，应该谨慎使用。

There is an ethical consideration, of course. You don’t want to persuade people to do things that are not in their best interest. And it might feel creepy and manipulative if you find yourself too skilled at persuasion. I’ve learned so much on the topic of persuasion that I intentionally dial it back when I feel like I’m in a stick fight with someone who has no stick. I’m sometimes happier not getting my way than I would be if I felt manipulative. It’s a powerful skill that should be used judiciously.

为了让你们明白我在说什么，我先简单介绍一下这个话题。首先，有些词语和短语确实比其他的更有说服力，这已经在受控研究中得到了证实。根据我的亲身经历，我列出了一些我最喜欢的说服词汇。

I’ll give you a taste of the topic just so you know what I’m talking about. For starters, some words and phrases are simply more persuasive than others, and that has been demonstrated in controlled studies. I’ve included a few of my own favorite persuasion words based on my own experiences.

有说服力的词语和短语

Persuasive Words and Phrases

  • “因为。 。 。”
  • “Because . . .”
  • “你会介意的 。 。 。 ？”
  • “Would you mind . . . ?”
  • “我对此不感兴趣。”
  • “I’m not interested.”
  • “我不会这么做。”
  • “I don’t do that.”
  • “我有一条规则...”
  • “I have a rule . . .”
  • “我只是想澄清一下……
  • “I just wanted to clarify . . .
  • “你能为我做些什么吗？”
  • “Is there anything you can do for me?”
  • “谢谢。”
  • “Thank you.”
  • “这只是你我之间的事。”
  • “This is just between you and me.”

请允许我详细说明。

Allow me to elaborate.

“因为 。 。 。”

“Because . . .”

心理学家罗伯特·西奥迪尼 (Robert Cialdini) 的研究表明，当你用包含“因为”这个词的句子请求帮助时，人们会更愿意合作，即使你给出的理由没有什么意义。3显然，“因为”这个词表示合理性，而合理性可以让人们放下防备，放弃反对意见。

Studies by psychologist Robert Cialdini show that people are more cooperative when you ask for a favor using a sentence that includes the word “because,” even if the reason you offer makes little or no sense.3 Apparently, the word “because” signals reasonableness, and reasonableness allows people to let down their defenses and drop their objections.

如果科学准确的话，一个有效的借钱方式可能是这样的：“我可以借一百美元吗？因为我下周才发工资。” 这根本算不上什么借钱的理由；根本没有给出真正的理由。借钱的人甚至都没说他为什么需要钱。感觉就像是因为“因为”才给出理由一样。

If the science is accurate, an effective way to ask for money might look something like this: “May I borrow a hundred dollars because I don’t get paid until next week?” That’s not much of a justification for borrowing money; no real reason is given. The person asking for money hasn’t even said why he needs it. It just feels as if a reason was offered because of “because.”

我已经测试过这种技术，并且效果出奇地好。

I’ve tested this technique, and it works surprisingly well.

“你会介意的 。 。 。 ？”

“Would You Mind . . . ?”

我发现任何以“你介意吗……”开头的问题往往很受欢迎。我猜，问一个人是否介意，其实是在暗示你有一个合理的请求，但可能会带来不便。对于任何以“你介意吗？”开头的请求，你很难拒绝。这个问题既能体现真诚，又能体现对对方的关心。这是一个强有力的组合。

I’ve found that any question beginning with “Would you mind . . .” tends to be well-received. My best guess is that asking a person if he minds is signaling that you have a reasonable request that might be inconvenient. It’s hard to be a jerk and say no to any request that starts with “Would you mind?” The question comes across as honest while also showing concern for the other person. It’s a powerful combination.

“我对此不感兴趣。”

“I’m Not Interested.”

有时候你需要说服别人不要再试图说服你。每次接到电话推销员的电话，或者有人试图向你推销你不想要的东西时，你都会遇到这种情况。在这种情况下，最糟糕的做法就是编造一些看似合乎逻辑的理由，解释你为什么不喜欢正在出售的东西。以推销为生的人会试图用他们自己的理由来说服你放弃你的理由。事实上，他们通常对每个常见的反对意见都有充分的论据。同样，如果你只给出一些合理的理由来拒绝他们的想法，你的朋友也会一直纠缠你。

Sometimes you need to persuade someone to stop trying to persuade you. You are in that situation every time a telemarketer calls or someone tries to sell you something you don’t want. The worst thing you can do in that sort of situation is give some logical-sounding reason why you don’t want whatever is being sold. People who sell for a living will try to talk you out of your reason with reasons of their own. In fact, they are usually equipped with arguments against every common objection. Likewise, your friends will badger you forever if you offer nothing but good reasons for rejecting their ideas.

我发现阻止别人说服我的最有效方法就是说“我不感兴趣”。你应该试试。不要解释你不感兴趣的原因。没人能解释为什么某些人对某件事感兴趣，而另一些人却不感兴趣。缺乏兴趣是无可辩驳的。尽可能多地重复你不感兴趣的说辞，直到结束谈话。你可能会惊讶于这种方法的有效性。我已经用了很多年了。这绝对是个致命的话题。

I’ve found that the most effective way to stop people from trying to persuade me is to say, “I’m not interested.” You should try it. Don’t offer a reason why you aren’t interested. No one can say why a thing holds interest for some and not for others. There’s no argument against a lack of interest. Repeat your claim of disinterest as often as it takes to end the conversation. You might be surprised how effective this method is. I’ve been using it for years. It’s a total conversation-killer.

“我不会那样做。”

“I Don’t Do That.”

另一个很好的说服句是“我不做那件事”。这算不上什么理由，也几乎算不上什么理由。但这听起来像是一个硬性规定。如果有人邀请你参加一年一度的芦笋节，不要说“听起来没意思”；这只会让你们群里的芦笋爱好者们无休止地描述如果你去尝试一下会多么快乐。相反，你应该这样说：“我不参加美食节。”如果有人问为什么，就说：“我只是不感兴趣。”有些这样的说服句搭配起来效果很好。

Another good persuasion sentence is “I don’t do that.” It’s not a reason, and barely tries to be. But it sounds like a hard-and-fast rule. If someone asks you to attend the annual asparagus festival, don’t say it doesn’t sound fun; that’s just begging the asparagus lovers in your group to endlessly describe just how joyous it could be if only you would try it. Instead, say something like, “I don’t do food festivals.” And if anyone asks why, say, “I’m just not interested.” Some of these persuasive sentences work well in tandem.

“我有一条规矩……”

“I Have a Rule . . .”

类似地，另一个有效的说服方法是说你有个“规矩”。比如，假设你和一位潜在客户约好了午餐，你那讨厌的同事问他能不能一起去。坦诚相告是行不通的，因为你必须和你的同事和平共处。你可以这样说：“我有个规矩，就是只和客户单独吃午餐。” 这样说既有说服力，又不失礼貌，而且完全不需要解释任何理由。

In a similar vein, another persuasive deterrent is to say you have a “rule.” For example, let’s say you have a lunch scheduled with a potential client, and your obnoxious co-worker asks if he can join you. Honesty won’t work because you must coexist with your co-worker. Instead, say something along the lines of, “I have a rule of only doing one-on-one lunches with clients.” It will sound convincing and somewhat polite while offering no reason whatsoever.

“我只是想澄清一下……”

“I Just Wanted to Clarify . . .”

有时你会听到一些愚蠢、邪恶或刻薄的言论，让你觉得直接正面攻击只会引发争吵。人们在受到质疑时往往会变本加厉，无论他们错得多么离谱。处理危险的社交或商业场合，更有效的方法是换个角度，以“我只是想澄清一下……”开头提问。

Sometimes you hear statements that are so mind-numbingly stupid, evil, or mean that you know a direct frontal assault would only start a fight. People tend to double-down when challenged, no matter how wrong they are. A more effective way to approach a dangerous social or business situation is sideways, by asking a question that starts with “I just wanted to clarify . . .”

这种方法可能是这样的：“我只是想澄清一下。你是说你愿意接受百分之八十的牢狱之灾，还是我听错了你的意思？”

That approach might look like this: “I just wanted to clarify. Are you saying you’re okay with an eighty percent chance of going to jail, or did I hear your plan wrong?”

如果你正确地措辞澄清问题，它就能间接地揭示问题，并提供一条挽回面子的出路。很多情况下，你收到的澄清会是一个全新的、更合理的计划。没有人喜欢被证明是错的，但大多数人都乐于“澄清”，即使这个澄清完全颠覆了之前的立场。只是当你把某件事称为“澄清”时，感觉会有所不同。

If you phrase your clarification question correctly, it will shine an indirect light on the problem and provide a face-saving escape path. In many cases, the clarification you receive will be an entirely new and more rational plan. No one likes to be proven wrong, but most people will be happy to “clarify,” even if the clarification is a complete reversal of an earlier position. It just feels different when you call something a clarification.

“你能帮我什么忙吗？”

“Is There Anything You Can Do for Me?”

我们总会遇到这样的情况：某个组织或个人阻碍我们实现我们认为公正公平的目标。也许零售店拒绝退款，而你正试图退货；又或者你买错了型号，而你想要的型号却缺货了。你需要说服某个人，让他/她不惜一切代价，让你满意。

We all find ourselves in situations where an organization or person is thwarting us from achieving whatever it is that we perceive as just and fair. Perhaps a retail store is refusing to refund you for an item you’re trying to return, or you purchased the wrong model but the one you want is out of stock. You need to persuade someone to go above and beyond the rules to make you happy.

你知道，如果你生气又要求苛刻，对方可能会墨守成规，试图把你打发走。处理这种情况最有效的方法就是问：“你能帮我什么忙吗？”你会发现，这是一个极具说服力的问题。

You know that if you get angry and demanding, the person you’re dealing with might stick to the rules and try to brush you off. The most powerful way to approach a situation like this is to ask, “Is there anything you can do for me?” You will discover it to be an extraordinarily persuasive question.

这个问题将情境定义为：你扮演无助的受害者，而你试图说服的人则扮演解决问题的英雄。人们一有机会就喜欢强化这种自我形象。你所做的就是创造这种机会。当你委托某人成为你的问题解决者时，你创造了一种让他们获得明确回报的情境：帮助好人总是让人感觉良好。你只需要礼貌地直接提问。“你能帮我什么忙吗？”你会惊讶地发现它的效果有多么好。

The question frames the situation as you being the helpless victim and the person you are trying to persuade as the problem-solving hero. That’s a self-image people like to reinforce when they have the chance. All you’re doing is creating that opportunity. When you deputize someone to be your problem-solver, you create a situation in which they have a clear payoff: Helping nice people always feels good. All you need to do is be polite and ask a direct question. “Is there anything you can do for me?” You’ll be amazed how well it works.

“谢谢。”

“Thank You.”

“谢谢”的表达方式多种多样，从一句随意的“谢谢”，到充满细节的夸张表达，不一而足。每种表达方式的效果可能存在很大差异。

“Thank you” can range from a casual “thanks” to an over-the-top expression of appreciation complete with details. There’s a big difference in how effective each approach is likely to be.

我上了一堂训狗课，学到的第一件事就是，狗零食的质量对狗狗的配合度影响巨大。训练师的零食质量很好，我相信只要她愿意，她能让狗狗弹钢琴。我们那些中等质量的零食勉强够让狗狗不反抗我们。训练师承认，她训练狗狗取得优异成绩的关键部分在于零食的质量。

When I took a class on how to train our dog, one of the first things we learned is that the quality of the dog treats made a big difference in how cooperative the dog would be. The trainer had the good stuff, and I believe she could make those dogs play the piano if she wanted. Our medium-quality treats were just barely good enough to keep the dogs from turning on us. The trainer admitted that the key to her superior results with dogs was partly because of snack quality.

感谢就像是款待人类一样。当你慷慨或善意地做了一些事情时，你希望得到感激。感谢的质量对人类来说至关重要，就像款待对狗一样重要。如果你想让人们喜欢你，就必须特别注意你感谢的质量。

A thank-you is like a treat for a human. When you do something generous or nice, you like to know it’s appreciated. The quality of the thank you matters as much to humans as the good treats matter to dogs. If you want people to like you, pay special attention to the quality of your thanks.

通过平信寄送感谢信总是会受到欢迎，在重要场合也依然必不可少。但如今，一封写得好的电子邮件在大多数普通场合也已被社会接受。无论你如何表达感谢，务必包含一些让你感激的细节。是惊喜、体贴，还是对方的帮助或礼物有多有用？务必具体。

Thank you notes sent by snail mail are always appreciated and still a must for the bigger occasions. But a well-written email is now socially acceptable for most common situations. No matter how you deliver a thank you, make sure it includes a little detail of what makes you thankful. Was it the surprise, the thoughtfulness, or how helpful the favor or gift was? Be specific.

例如，“非常感谢你的载送。我整天都在担心我的车在维修期间该如何完成所有事情。你真的救了我一命。”

For example, “Thank you so much for the ride. I was worried all day about how I would get everything done while my car is in the shop. You really saved me.”

这与一句简单的“谢谢载我一程”相比，任何感谢都比没有好，但如果做得不好，就会错失良机。人们在决定与谁共事、挑选团队或邀请他人参加聚会时，都会记住这一点。表达感激看似微不足道，实则不然。

Compare that to a simple “Thank you for the ride.” Any thank you is better than none, but you’re missing an opportunity if you do a poor job of it. It’s the sort of thing people remember when they decide who they want to work with, pick a team, or invite people to a party. Expressing gratitude seems like a small thing, but it isn’t.

“这只是你我之间的事。”

“This Is Just between You and Me.”

研究表明，如果你分享秘密，人们会自动将你标记为朋友。3分享秘密是快速赢得他人好感和信任的捷径。诀窍在于，要透露一个不危险的秘密。

Research shows that people will automatically label you a friend if you share a secret.3 Sharing a confidence is a fast-track way to cause people to like and trust you. The trick is to reveal a secret that isn’t a dangerous one.

错误： “我把我的老板埋在后院了。”

Wrong: “I buried my boss in the backyard.”

正确： “我可能不应该承认这一点，但每次简端上她的蘸酱时，我只是假装喜欢它，因为其他人都说它好吃得要命。”

Right: “I probably shouldn’t admit this, but every time Jane serves her dip, I only pretend to like it because everyone else says it’s to die for.”

分享秘密的正确方法是从小事做起。在尝试任何更冒险的事情之前，确保这些小秘密是保密的。判断风险的一个方法是警惕别人向你透露的秘密。不善于保守某种秘密的人，很可能不善于保守所有秘密。你也不例外。

The right approach to sharing a secret is to start small. Make sure the small secrets stay secret before you try anything riskier. One way to judge your risk is to be alert for other peoples’ secrets that are being relayed to you. Someone who is bad at keeping one kind of secret is probably bad at keeping all secrets. You won’t be exempt.

果断

Decisiveness

没有人能始终果断果断。世界错综复杂，我们常常只是在猜测哪条路才是最佳选择。任何在极其复杂的境况下依然自信满满的人都是疯子。

No one is decisive all the time. The world is a complicated place, and often we’re only guessing which path will be best. Anyone who is confident in the face of great complexity is insane.

然而，有些人比其他人更果断。这种果断既具有说服力，又很实用。果断看起来像是领导力。请记住，大多数普通人在面对陌生而复杂的情况时，至少都会有些不确定。在这种环境下，人们渴望的是任何看起来像确定的东西。如果你能展现出果断的形象，无论多么不真诚，别人都会认为这是领导力。

However, some people act much more decisively than others. And that act can be both persuasive and useful. Decisiveness looks like leadership. Keep in mind that most normal people are at least a little bit uncertain when facing unfamiliar and complicated situations. What people crave in that sort of environment is anything that looks like certainty. If you can deliver an image of decisiveness, no matter how disingenuous, others will see it as leadership.

别把你那人为的果断感和总是想做对的欲望混为一谈。生活纷乱，你只会偶尔做对。然而，即使你内心有所怀疑，果断行事也会对你生命中的每个人都有好处。

Don’t confuse your artificial sense of decisiveness with a need to be right all the time. Life is messy, and you’re only going to be right sometimes. You’ll do everyone in your life a favor by acting decisively though, even if you have doubts on the inside.

活力

Energy

人们会对他人的活力做出回应。如果你展现出你对某种娱乐方式的热爱，就更容易说服他人尝试。活力是会传染的。人们喜欢这种感觉。如果你展现出热情，其他人也会想要体验同样的激情。

People respond to energy in others. If you show how much you love a particular form of entertainment, it will be easier to persuade others to try it. Energy is contagious. People like how it feels. If you show enthusiasm, others will want to experience the same rush.

疯狂

Insanity

在大多数群体中，最疯狂的人总是掌控着局面。这始于没人想惹恼一个疯子而惹出麻烦。有时候，让疯子随心所欲更聪明、更容易。

In most groups, the craziest person is in control. It starts because no one wants the problems that come from pissing off a crazy person. It’s just smarter and easier sometimes to let the crazy person have their way.

疯子也会承担更多风险，行事也比事实更自信。这是一个强大的组合。疯狂加上自信，或许比任何其他性格特征的组合更能杀死人，但当它恰到好处时，却能产生非凡的说服力。邪教就是一个将疯狂视为领导力的典型例子。

Crazy people also take more risks and act more confidently than the facts would warrant. That’s a potent combination. Crazy-plus-confident probably kills more people than any other combination of personality traits, but when it works just right, it’s a recipe for extraordinary persuasion. Cults are a good example of insanity perceived as leadership.

假设你没有疯。疯癫能帮你吗？答案是肯定的，但你需要运用一种经过深思熟虑、情绪化的疯狂。在任何谈判中，最糟糕的做法就是表现得理智。理智的人通常会屈服于非理性的人，因为这似乎是阻力最小的途径。

Suppose you’re not insane. Can insanity help you? The answer is yes, but you want to use a calculated, emotional type of insanity. In any kind of negotiation, the worst thing you can do is act reasonable. Reasonable people generally cave in to irrational people because it seems like the path of least resistance.

谈判中假装疯狂的运作方式是，你赋予交易中某些要素比客观观察者认为合理的价值更高的价值。例如，你可能要求在假期前完成一笔交易，这样你就可以把它作为节日礼物向家人宣布。当你带入情感层面时，人们知道他们无法说服你。情感不会屈服于理性。所以，用你能想到的任何情感来包裹你的论点，以影响他人。一点点非理性的力量是巨大的。

The way fake insanity works in a negotiation is that you assign a greater value to some element of a deal than an objective observer would consider reasonable. For example, you might demand that a deal be closed before the holidays so you can announce it to your family as a holiday present. When you bring in an emotional dimension, people know they can’t talk you out of it. Emotions don’t bend to reason. So wrap your arguments in whatever emotional blankets you can think of to influence others. A little bit of irrationality is a powerful thing.

说服和操纵一样吗？

Is Persuasion the Same as Manipulation?

如果你认为说服是一种操纵，而操纵又是一种邪恶，那么这种世界观将阻碍你发挥应有的说服力。我认为大多数人之所以不愿充分发挥说服力，是因为操纵他人的感觉并不好。说出自己的想法和偏好是一回事，但你希望别人因为你的论点无比正确而认同你的观点。可悲的是，我们生活的世界并非总是好的论点能够获胜。有时，你需要引导人们走上正确的道路，即使他们坚信这条道路是错误的。在某些情况下，你有道德义务去操纵他人——如果你知道这样做会给所有相关人员带来好的结果。例如，操纵同事让他们更好地完成工作通常对每个人都有好处。

If you see persuasion as a form of manipulation and manipulation as a form of evil, that worldview will keep you from being as persuasive as you might be. I think most people hold back their full powers of persuasion because it doesn’t feel good to be manipulative. It’s one thing to speak your mind and voice your preferences, but you hope that other people agree with you because of the thundering rightness of your arguments. Sadly, we do not live in a world where good arguments always win. Sometimes you need to nudge people onto the right path, even if they firmly believe it to be wrong. In some cases, you have a moral obligation to be manipulative—if you know it will create a good result for all involved. For example, manipulating coworkers to do better work is usually good for everyone.

技术（业余爱好水平）

Technology (Hobby Level)

科技曾经是孤独极客的专属领域。那样的日子已经一去不复返了。每个成年人都应该对互联网的运作方式、网站搭建的步骤、“云”的概念，当然还有如何使用个人电脑、智能手机、平板电脑等等有基本的了解。很难想象任何职业或初创公司不需要这些技能，即使你只是负责监督供应商、外包和管理其他人。掌握技术到我所谓的“业余爱好”水平是个好主意。你不需要亲自为棘手的问题提供技术支持，但你也不想成为房间里唯一一个不懂这些技术的人。

Technology once was the exclusive domain of lonely geeks. Those days are over. Every adult should have a basic understanding of how the Internet works, the steps involved in building a website, what the “cloud” is, and of course how to use personal computers, smartphones, tablets, etc. It’s hard to imagine any profession or startup that wouldn’t require those skills, even if you’re doing nothing more than supervising vendors, outsourcing, and managing others. It’s a good idea to master technology at what I would call a hobby level. You don’t need to be your own tech support for the hard stuff, but you also don’t want to be the only person in the room who doesn’t understand the topic.

这又是一个可以用个人能量来指引方向的例子。想象一下，当你陷入一场你不懂的技术讨论时，你会是什么感觉。这既无趣，也提不起精神。你会感觉自己的灵魂快要从袜子里抽干了。另一方面，如果你觉得自己有话可说，参与讨论总是能让你充满活力。科技是文明结构的一部分，如果你还没有融入其中，就需要尽快融入。学习基础知识，你会更加快乐。

This is another case in which your personal energy can be your guide. Imagine how you feel when you find yourself in a technology discussion that you don’t understand. It’s not fun, and it’s not energizing. You can feel your soul draining out through your socks. On the other hand, being part of the conversation is always energizing if you feel you have something to add. Technology is part of the fabric of civilization, and you need to weave yourself into it if you haven’t already. Learn the basics, and you’ll be a lot happier.

正确的发声技巧

Proper Voice Technique

针对不同情况，制定不同的语调策略会很有帮助。你幽默的语调可能更高，节奏更快，而你严肃的语调可能更深沉，更有分寸。务必在幽默的语调和说服性的语调之间保持一定的距离。对于认识你的人来说，严肃的语调会发出一个明确的信号，表明这个话题很重要，而且你可能不愿意进行谈判。

It’s helpful to have different vocal strategies for different situations. Your fun voice might be higher pitched and more rapid paced whereas your serious voice might be deeper and more measured. It’s important to keep a lot of distance between your fun voice and your persuasive voice. For people who know you, the serious voice will send an unambiguous signal that the topic is important and that you might be closed to negotiation.

我估计，只有不到20%的普通民众能够用正确的发声技巧说话。我指的是正确的呼吸控制、语调和口型技巧。你可能认为任何对声音质量的改进都是无用的。毕竟，与你交谈的人完全听得懂你的意思。但研究表明，声音质量对你的整体健康和幸福感的重要性远超乎人们的想象。4-9研究表明，具有威严的声音与成功密切相关。其他研究表明，声音优美的男性和女性比声音平庸的人更快找到伴侣。6虽然我们大多数人无论多么努力地训练自己的声音，都永远无法像摩根·弗里曼那样说话，但我们都能够改善自己的说话方式，而这或许值得我们付出努力。

My guess is that 20 percent or less of the general public speaks with proper voice mechanics. And by that I mean proper breath control, tone, and mouth strategies. You probably think any improvement to your voice quality would be wasted. After all, the people that you speak with understand you perfectly. But research says that voice quality is far more important to your overall health and happiness than one might imagine.4-9 Studies say a commanding voice is highly correlated with success. Other studies suggest that both men and women with attractive voices find partners more quickly than those with less attractive voices.6 While most of us will never be able to speak like Morgan Freeman no matter how diligently we train our voices, we’re all capable of improving how we speak, and that’s probably worth the effort.

在我的企业生涯中，我注意到一个最奇怪的现象：许多高层管理人员的声音似乎都独具特色、引人入胜，引人注​​目，并且赋予他们所说的每一句话一种难以言喻的分量。我敢打赌，你可以给一群志愿者播放员工的录音，受试者可以准确预测——至少比随机预测更准确——谁会掌权，谁会继续默默工作。一项研究表明，护士经理的声音往往更有力，这与人们感知到的更高的护理质量和管理能力相关。10

One of the strangest patterns I noticed during my corporate career is that many of the higher-level managers seemed to have distinctive, interesting voices that commanded attention and gave an inexplicable weight to everything they said. I’m willing to bet that you could play voice recordings of employees to a group of volunteers and the subjects could accurately predict—at least better than chance—who will ascend to power and who will remain a worker bee. One study showed that nurse managers tended to have stronger voices, and this was correlated with a perceived higher quality of care and greater management abilities.10

在职场生涯中，每当我处于“专业”状态时，我都会使用一种听起来很严肃的语气。我实际上是在演戏，但这并不让人觉得不真诚，因为商业世界就像戏剧一样。每个人都努力融入自己的角色。当我做银行出纳员时，我对顾客毕恭毕敬。当我管理员工时，我的说话方式自认为既权威又通情达理。在与上级会面时，我会压低语气，流露出一种只有疯子才会坦诚表达的自信。我相当确信，我那低沉的、故作自信的假嗓音让我看起来比实际更有能力，而这并不难，因为我在公司担任的每一份工作中基本上都能力不足。尽管我明显能力不足，但几乎每一位老板——而且有很多——都认定我是未来的公司高管。

Throughout my corporate years, I used a serious-sounding tone of voice whenever I was in “professional” mode. I was literally acting but it didn’t feel disingenuous because the business world is a lot like theater. Everyone tries to get into character for the job they have. When I was a bank teller, I was obsequious to customers. When I managed people, I spoke in a way that I thought sounded authoritarian and reasonable. In meetings with higher-ups, I lowered my tone and spoke with the sort of self-assurance that only the insane come by honestly. I’m reasonably sure that my fake voice with its low notes and artificial confidence made me appear more capable than I was, and that wasn’t difficult because I was largely incompetent at every corporate job I held. Despite my obvious lack of ability, nearly every boss I had—and there were many—identified me as a future corporate executive.

别忘了，我当时衣着简陋，身高只有5英尺8英寸（约1.73米），二十多岁就过早秃顶了。我看起来绝对不像个CEO的料。虽然我愿意相信我内心的才华有时会流露出来，但我怀疑事实并非如此。我觉得我那虚假的专业嗓音和虚假的肢体语言至少是我被看好有管理潜力的一半原因。

Keep in mind that I was poorly dressed, 5’8” tall, and prematurely balding in my twenties. I certainly didn’t look like CEO material, and while I’d like to think my interior brilliance sometimes shined through, I doubt that was the case. I think my fake professional voice and fake body language was at least half the reason I was seen as management potential.

我在公司工作期间也注意到，那些从未见过我本人的女性，只要我用假装专业的嗓音，就会在电话里疯狂地跟我调情。我猜，那些表明领导潜力的声音特质，也会影响潜在的伴侣。6我假装自信，还有我那仿佛在喊“睾丸激素”的低沉嗓音，对女士们就像猫薄荷一样有效。可惜的是，一旦有人见到我本人，调情就停止了。所以，我猜我的假嗓音才是我的秘密武器。

I also noticed during my corporate years that women who had never met me in person flirted like crazy on the phone whenever I used my fake professional voice. I assume the same voice qualities that indicate a potential for leadership also influences potential mates.6 My fake confidence along with my fake low voice that screamed “TESTOSTERONE” worked like catnip on the ladies. Unfortunately, the flirting stopped as soon as anyone saw me in person. That’s why I assume my fake voice was the secret sauce.

至少有一位语音专家认为，我那低沉的假嗓音是导致我后来出现痉挛性发声障碍的原因。我不确定这是否属实，但值得一提。

At least one voice expert believes that my fake voice with its artificially low tone was a cause of my later voice problems with spasmodic dysphonia. I don’t know that to be true, but it’s worth mentioning.

本书的目的不是教你发声，而是介绍一些培养你最佳“成功声音”的常用方法。

This book isn’t designed to give you voice lessons, but I’ll include a few common methods for developing your best “success voice.”

首先，用肺底呼吸，而不是用上胸部。正确的呼吸还有很多其他好处，包括减轻压力、促进新陈代谢并使其更高效，以及增强体力，所以值得学习。11-15如果你把手放在肚脐上，并正确呼吸，那么肚脐就是你躯干唯一应该起伏的部位。如果你正常呼吸时上胸部也在扩张，那你就做错了。当你呼吸正确时，你说话会听起来更自信。

For starters, breathe from the bottom of your lungs, not from the upper chest area. Proper breathing has lots of other benefits including stress reduction, increased and more efficient metabolism, and better physical stamina, so it’s worth learning.11-15 If you put your hand on your belly button and breathe correctly, that’s the only part of your torso that should be rising and falling. If your upper chest is expanding when you breathe normally, you’re doing it wrong. When you get your breathing right, your words will come out sounding more confident.

接下来，你需要选择一个语调。一些语音专家会告诉你，你最好、最自然的语调可能比你平时说话的语调要高。例如，很多人天生倾向于对别人说话比对宠物说话时声音低。在某种程度上，我们都明白，较低的声音会给我们所说的话增添一些分量。

Next, you need to pick a tone. Some voice experts will tell you that your best and most natural tone is probably higher than the way you normally speak. Many people have a natural tendency to speak lower to other humans than they might to a pet, for example. On some level, we all understand that lower voices confer some weight to what we say.

低沉嗓音的缺点是，很难听清与背景噪音相符的词语。在我使用假嗓的年代，人群喧闹声太大，根本没人能听清我说话。在嘈杂的环境中，点饮料或交谈都很困难。后来，我学会了用高音来穿透背景噪音。这在沟通方面很有效，但我并不指望能得到任何CEO的邀请。这真是个代价。

The downside of a lower voice is that it’s difficult to hear words that match background noise. In my fake voice era, no one could hear me above crowd noises. It was hard to order a drink or make conversation in any noisy situation. I’ve since learned to penetrate background noise by using a higher-pitched voice. It’s great for communicating, but I don’t expect to get any CEO offers. It’s a real trade-off.

另一个常见的说话技巧是哼唱“生日快乐歌”的前半部分，然后立即用正常的声音说话。你会注意到，哼唱之后的声音出奇地流畅完美。虽然这种效果不会持续太久，但它能让你通过练习达到目标音调。

Another common speaking trick is to hum the first part of the “Happy Birthday” song and then speak in your normal voice right after. You’ll notice your post-humming voice is strangely smooth and perfect. It won’t last, but it gives you a target voice you can achieve with practice.

姿势对良好的说话能力也至关重要。如果你坐姿或站姿不正，你的发声器官就会听起来很紧——即使你自己没有注意到。

Posture is also important for good speech. If you don’t sit up or stand straight, your vocal equipment will sound pinched—even if you don’t notice it yourself.

当你试图表现出一种虚假的自信时——这通常很管用——你需要告诉自己你在演戏。只要像你想象中自信的人那样说话，你就能一次成功。

When you’re trying to convey a fake sense of confidence—which is often handy—you need to tell yourself you’re acting. Simply speak the way you imagine a confident person would speak, and you’ll nail it on the first try.

所以，别再吞吞吐吐、“嗯”、“呃”之类的支吾了，别再说任何打断你思路的话了。自信的人不会这样说话。但要做到正确，确实需要练习。最快的解决办法就是用沉默代替你之前说的“嗯”、“呃”。一开始可能会觉得不舒服，但你会习惯的。我也喜欢在开始说话之前，尽可能在脑子里构思完整的句子。当我知道某个话题很可能在不久的将来出现时，我会在脑子里练习整段对话，直到我能流利地说出自己的想法。

So get rid of the hemming and hawing, the “ums” and “uhs,” and anything that disrupts your flow. Confident people don’t speak that way. But it does take practice to get right. The quickest fix is simply to substitute silence where you once had “ums” and “uhs.” It will feel uncomfortable at first, but you get used to it. I also like to form full sentences in my head before I start them, whenever that’s an option. And when I know a topic is likely to come up in the near future, I practice entire conversations in my head until I can speak my thoughts fluently.

我列出的可组合技能并非面面俱到。每个人的情况都不同。对你来说，或许摄影和植物学才是合适的技能。既然你的思维已经适应了这两种思维方式，你一眼就能认出它们。

My list of combinable skills isn’t meant to be comprehensive. And every person is in a unique situation. For you, maybe the right skills are photography and botany. You’ll recognize them when you see them now that your mind is tuned to think in that way.

††简而言之，今天的一美元比明天的一美元更值钱，因为你今天拥有的这美元可以用来投资。这其中的数学计算要复杂得多。

††Simply put, a dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow because the dollar you have today can be invested. The math of it is more complicated.

第22章

Chapter 22

模式识别

Pattern Recognition

哦我的一个系统就是不断寻找生活中的规律。最近，我注意到，我作为继父参加的高中排球比赛几乎总是由先得17分的球队获胜——即使最终的获胜比分是25分，而且必须赢2分。在排球比赛中，领先优势经常发生变化是很常见的，而先得17分的球队在获胜之前可能会再落后几次，这使得这种规律显得格外奇怪。

One of my systems involves continuously looking for patterns in life. Recently, I noticed that the high school volleyball games I attended in my role as stepdad were almost always won by the team that reached seventeen first—even though the winning score is twenty-five and you have to win by two. It’s common for the lead to change often during a volleyball match, and the team that first reaches seventeen might fall behind a few more times before winning, which makes the pattern extra strange.

如果排球比赛的规律是真实存在的——而且这远未得到解决——我会假设它有一个正常的解释。也许17分感觉离25分太近了，以至于落后的球队感到泄气，而领先的球队则感到格外自信。也许在高中阶段，落后球队的教练觉得有必要在比赛结束前给替补球员一些时间。无论原因是什么，这种规律似乎一直存在。也许这本书付印后，它会有所改变。我会继续追踪。

If the volleyball pattern is real—and that is far from settled—I would assume there is a normal explanation for it. Perhaps seventeen just feels so close to twenty-five that the team behind feels deflated and the team ahead feels extra confident. Perhaps at the high school level, the coach whose team is behind feels the need to give the bench players some time before the end of the game. Whatever the reason, the pattern seems to hold. Perhaps it will change after this book goes to print. I’ll keep tracking it.

在业余网球中，最奇怪的规律之一被称为“五二魔咒”。在网球比赛中，率先至少赢两局六局的选手将赢得该盘，因此，你通常会认为率先拿到五局的选手大多数时候都会获胜。然而，实际情况却远超常识的预测：领先的业余选手感觉自己可以轻松取胜，而落后的选手则觉得可以放松打，因为结果似乎在意料之中。这种想法会给落后的选手带来心理优势，他们通常不费吹灰之力就能将比分追近到五比三。现在，领先的选手开始觉得领先优势并不稳固。他们或许觉得势头已经发生了变化。下一局对手只要打出几个漂亮的球，就能强化这种印象。率先在与水平相当的业余选手对战中拿到五局的选手，仍然会大多数时候获胜，但胜率远低于你的预期。如果你是一名业余选手，只赢了两局，而对手赢了五局，那么知道自己有大约40%的胜率将大有裨益。了解模式会改变你对机会的看法，而这种思维的改变可以提高你的表现。

In amateur tennis, one of the oddest patterns is called the five-two curse. In tennis, the first player to win six games by at least two wins the set, so you would expect the player who first reaches five to win most of the time. What happens instead—far more often than common sense would predict—is that the weekend player who is ahead feels they can coast while the player who is behind feels they can play relaxed because the outcome seems predictable. That sort of thinking leads to a psychological advantage for the player who is behind, who often closes the gap to five-three3 without much effort. Now the player who is ahead starts to think the lead isn’t so secure. Perhaps they feel the momentum has shifted. It only takes a few good shots from the opponent in the next game to reinforce that impression. The player who first gets to five games against a similarly skilled amateur will still win most of the time but not nearly as often as you would predict. If you’re an amateur player with only two games compared to your opponent’s five, it helps a great deal to know you have something like a 40 percent chance of prevailing. Knowing the pattern changes how you think about your chances, and that change in thinking can then improve your performance.

成功人士

Successful People

无数的自助书籍和商业书籍都试图寻找人们成功的行为模式。人们认为，如果我们能找到成功人士的做法，我们就能效仿他们，最终获得成功。

Countless self-help and business books have tried to find the patterns of behavior that make people successful. If we can find out what successful people do, so the thinking goes, we can imitate them and become successful ourselves.

史蒂芬·柯维或许是最著名的“模式成功大师”。他的著作《高效人士的七个习惯》销量超过2500万册。柯维描述了一套值得人们效仿的优秀模式，但这仅仅是个开始。我将总结他的七个习惯，如果你想了解更多，建议你读读他的书。

Stephen Covey was probably the most famous of the success-by-pattern gurus. His book Seven Habits of Highly Effective People sold more than 25 million copies. Covey described a good set of patterns for people to follow, but they‘re only a start. I’ll summarize his seven habits and suggest you read his books if you want more.

  1. 积极主动
  2. Be Proactive
  3. 以终为始。（想象一个好的结果。）
  4. Begin with the End in Mind. (Imagine a good outcome.)
  5. 要事第一。（设定优先次序。）
  6. Put first things first. (Set priorities.)
  7. 考虑双赢。（不要贪心。）
  8. Think win-win. (Don’t be greedy.)
  9. 先去理解，然后被理解。
  10. Seek first to understand then be understood.
  11. 协同增效。（利用团队合作。）
  12. Synergize. (Use teamwork.)
  13. 磨利锯子。（不断学习。）
  14. Sharpen the saw. (Keep learning.)

文明的圣杯在于，我们希望有一天能够发现成功人士的秘诀，并将其普及到所有人，从而使所有人都能获得成功。据我所知，史蒂芬·柯维的七个习惯并没有降低贫困率，所以其中可能存在更深层次的模式。

The holy grail of civilization is the hope that we can someday make all people successful by discovering the formula used by successful people and making it available to all. As far as I know, Stephen Covey’s seven habits didn’t budge the poverty rate, so there are probably deeper patterns at play.

以下是我多年来观察到的一些重要成功模式的清单。这些模式纯属轶事。我排除了那些完全由基因决定的模式。

Here’s my own list of the important patterns for success that I’ve noticed over the years. This is purely anecdotal. I excluded the ones that are 100 percent genetic.

  1. 不惧怕尴尬。
  2. Lack of fear of embarrassment.
  3. 教育（正确的教育）。
  4. Education (the right kind).
  5. 锻炼。
  6. Exercise.

不惧怕尴尬，才能让你积极主动。正因如此，人们才会勇于接受别人认为风险过大的挑战。正因如此，你才会在还没想好下一步该怎么做之前，就迈出第一步。我不喜欢身体上的风险，但如果你无法应对尴尬、拒绝和失败的风险，你就需要学习如何应对，研究表明，这确实是一项可以学习的技能。1

Lacking the fear of embarrassment allows you to be proactive. It’s what makes a person take on challenges that others write off as too risky. It’s what makes you take the first step before you know what the second step is. I’m not a fan of physical risks, but if you can’t handle the risk of embarrassment, rejection, and failure, you need to learn how, and studies suggest that is indeed a learnable skill.1

至于身体上的勇气，我一无所知。但我很高兴有些人拥有这种勇气，这样他们就可以在那些拥有勇气的人射杀我之前射杀他们。我建议你提升你的心理勇气，但要对任何可能致命的事情说“不” 。

As far as physical bravery goes, I don’t know anything about it. But I’m glad some people have it so they can shoot the other people who have it before those people shoot me. I recommend that you improve your psychological bravery but say no to anything that has a strong chance of killing you.

然后是教育。你知道工程师的失业率是多少吗？几乎为零。你知道有多少工程师喜欢他们的工作吗？尽管你在呆伯特漫画里读到过，但大多数工程师确实喜欢。而那些对工作不满意的人可以很容易地换工作。一般来说，受过良好教育的人几乎没有失业的风险。

Then there’s education. Do you know what the unemployment rate is for engineers? It’s nearly zero. Do you know how many engineers like their jobs? Most of them do, despite what you read in Dilbert comics. And the ones who are unhappy with work can change jobs fairly easily. Generally speaking, the people who have the right kind of education have almost no risk of unemployment.

教育和心理勇气在某种程度上是可以互换的。如果你缺乏其中之一，你可以用另一个来弥补。当你看到一个没有大学学历的成功人士时，你通常会看到一个异常无所畏惧的人。

Education and psychological bravery are somewhat interchangeable. If you don’t have much of one, you can compensate with a lot of the other. When you see a successful person who lacks a college education, you’re usually looking at someone with an unusual lack of fear.

我注意到的下一个规律是锻炼。良好的健康是成功的基本要求。但我指的并非病人无法完成很多工作这一显而易见的事实。我指的是健康带来的额外能量和活力。我可能理解错了这种关联，也许激励一个人成功的因素也会激励他坚持锻炼。但我认为它是双向的。我相信锻炼能让人更聪明、更勇敢、更有创造力、更有活力、更有影响力。在一篇关于成功人士的二十个习惯的在线文章中，第二项是每周锻炼五到七天。2其他研究也支持这一观点——总体身体健康，尤其是日常锻炼，与事业和生活中的成功息息相关。3,4

The next pattern I’ve noticed is exercise. Good health is a baseline requirement for success. But I’m not talking about the obvious fact that sick people can’t get much done. I’m talking about the extra energy and vitality that good health brings. I might be getting the correlation wrong, and perhaps whatever motivates a person to succeed also motivates that person to maintain an exercise schedule. But I think it works both ways. I believe exercise makes people smarter, psychologically braver, more creative, more energetic, and more influential. In an online article about twenty habits of successful people, the second item on the list is exercise five to seven days a week.2 Other studies back this notion—physical fitness in general and daily exercise in particular are correlated with success in business and in life.3,4

我在成功人士身上还发现了一个共同点：他们把成功视为一种可学习的技能。这意味着他们会弄清楚自己需要什么，然后去获取它。如果你读到这里，你就是其中之一。你读这本书是因为它提供了一些可能对你有帮助的信息。

There’s one more pattern I see in successful people: They treat success as a learnable skill. That means they figure out what they need then go get it. If you’ve read this far, you’re one of those people. You’re reading this book because it offers a non-zero chance of telling you something that might be helpful.

第23章

Chapter 23

幽默

Humor

我如果你把幽默视为一种可有可无的娱乐方式，那你就错过了它的一些最大优点：喜欢幽默的人比不喜欢的人更有吸引力。想和那些能欣赏欢笑，或者更好的是，能让人开怀大笑的人共度时光，这是人的天性。

If you see humor as an optional form of entertainment, you’re missing some of its biggest benefits: People who enjoy humor are simply more attractive than people who don’t. It’s human nature to want to spend time with people who can appreciate a good laugh or, better yet, cause one.

相信我，良好的幽默感可以弥补一个人外貌和性格上的许多其他缺陷。幽默能让相貌平平的人看起来可爱，让无趣的人看起来有趣。研究表明，良好的幽默感甚至能让你看起来更聪明。1-3一项研究表明，女性会寻找幽默感更强的男性，因为这可能表明他们可能“风趣、善良、善解人意、值得信赖……” 4

Take it from me when I say a good sense of humor can compensate for a lot of other shortcomings in one’s looks and personality. Humor makes average-looking people look cute and uninteresting people seem entertaining. Studies show that a good sense of humor even makes you look smarter.1-3 One study showed that women seek out men with a better sense of humor because it can signal that they may be “amusing, kind, understanding, dependable . . .”4

最棒的是，也是本书主题的核心：幽默能提升你的能量，并能影响你在学校、工作或个人生活中所做的一切。能量的提升甚至会让你更愿意去锻炼，从而进一步提升你的整体能量。

Best of all and central to the theme of this book, humor raises your energy, and that can reverberate into everything you do at school, at work, or in your personal life. The boost of energy will even make you more willing to exercise, and that will raise your overall energy even more.

幽默还能让你忘却日常烦恼。幽默能让你以更客观的角度看待生活，有时甚至能让你一笑置之，即使是最糟糕的问题。

Humor also transports your mind away from your daily troubles. Humor puts life in perspective and sometimes helps you laugh at even the worst of your problems.

因为幽默直接影响你的能量，它触及你生活中每一个需要专注和意志力的部分。而且在大多数情况下，幽默是免费的，很容易获得。互联网上充满了幽默。如果你没有幽默的朋友，那就去找一些。如果你喜欢读书，那就选择有趣的书籍。如果你去看电影，优先选择有趣的电影，避免任何你知道结局会很悲伤的电影。

Because humor directly influences your energy, it touches every part of your life that requires concentration and willpower. And for the most part, humor is free and easily accessible. The Internet is full of humor. If you don’t have funny friends, find some. If you’re a reader, choose funny books. If you go to movies, choose the funny ones first and avoid anything you know will end on a sad note.

有时你会想展现一点自己的幽默感。有些人天生就具备这种能力，但大多数人并非如此。根据我的经验，大多数人都认为自己有幽默感，某种程度上确实如此。但并非所有人的幽默感都生来平等。所以，我觉得分享一些日常生活中的幽默小贴士会很有帮助。

Sometimes you want to dispense a bit of your own humor. That comes naturally to some people but not most. In my experience, most people think they have a sense of humor, and to some extent that’s true. But not all senses of humor are created equal. So I thought it would be useful to include some humor tips for everyday life.

你不必非得在小组里说笑话才能展现你的幽默感。你可以引导大家讨论一些有趣的话题，让其他人也能加入幽默。每个聚会都需要一个正直的人。通过与人交往，你会显得风趣幽默。

You don’t have to be the joke-teller in the group to demonstrate your sense of humor. You can be the one who steers the conversation to fun topics that are ripe for others to add humor. Every party needs a straight person. You’ll appear fun and funny by association.

说到当面幽默，努力至关重要。当人们看到你试图幽默时，你就会让他们也尝试一下。所以，即使你自己的幽默努力不够，你也可能释放了别人压抑的幽默。在社交或商业场合，人们需要获得允许才能幽默，因为幽默总是伴随着风险。如果你能先发制人，消除一些风险，那对别人来说就大有裨益。对于当面幽默来说，质量并不像你想象的那么重要。你的态度和努力才至关重要。

When it comes to in-person humor, effort counts a lot. When people see you trying to be funny, you free them to try it themselves. So even if your own efforts at humor fall short, you might be unleashing the pent-up humor in others. People need permission to be funny in social or business settings because there’s always a risk that comes with humor. You will do people a big favor when you remove some of that risk by going first. For in-person humor, quality isn’t as important as you might think. Your attitude and effort count for a lot.

显然，在幽默方面，要避免“用力过猛”。如果你对自己或他人的笑话笑得太过激烈，就会出现这种情况。如果你想追求数量，所谓的“冷幽默”才是最佳策略。

Obviously you want to avoid “trying too hard” when it comes to humor. That happens if you laugh too vigorously at your own jokes or other people’s jokes. So-called dry humor is the best strategy if you plan to go for quantity.

我认为，说到幽默，质量总是被高估，但你确实需要达到一个最低标准。这通常意味着要避开一些陷阱。避开这些陷阱，你就成功了。所以，请允许我为你列出这些陷阱。我会先总结一下，然后再解释。

I say quality is overrated when it comes to humor, but you do need to achieve a minimum threshold. And that usually means avoiding a handful of traps. Avoid these and you’re golden. So allow me to map the traps for you. I’ll start with a summary, then explain.

  • 过度抱怨从来都不是件好事。
  • Over-complaining is never funny.
  • 不要过度自贬。
  • Don’t overdo self-deprecation.
  • 不要嘲笑别人。
  • Don’t mock people.
  • 避免使用双关语和文字游戏。
  • Avoid puns and wordplay.

有些人——包括我——认为幽默地抱怨生活中的小烦恼就能构成幽默。有时确实如此。但当你开始用太多抱怨来幽默时，问题就来了。对生活中的问题说一句有趣的评论或许很有趣，但说五句就只是抱怨了，无论你自认为多么机智。幽默的抱怨会让人精疲力竭。

Some people—and I was one of them—believe that humorous complaints about the little aggravations of life constitute humor. Sometimes that’s the case. The problem comes when you start doing too much gripe-based humor. One funny observation about a problem in your life can be funny, but five is just complaining, no matter how witty you think you are. Funny complaints wear people out.

自嘲式的幽默通常是最安全的，但同样，你也不应该过度。一句自嘲式的话语是一种慷慨甚至自信的幽默。你必须至少有点自信才能在别人面前自嘲。但如果你经常这样做，在别人眼里，你就会从一个自信的玩笑者变成一只吉娃娃。

Self-deprecating humor is usually the safest type, but here again you don’t want to overshoot the target. One self-deprecating comment is a generous and even confident form of humor. You must be at least a bit self-assured to mock yourself in front of others. But if you do it too often, you can transform in the eyes of others from a confident jokester into a Chihuahua.

不要经常取笑别人。如果这种情况逐渐成为一种习惯，人们会认为你也在背后说他们的坏话。

Don’t make fun of other people too often either. If that starts to look like a pattern, people will assume you’re talking behind their backs as well.

小心双关语和其他巧妙的文字游戏。只有会用双关语的人才能欣赏它。这就像水球，除非你玩过，否则很难欣赏这项运动。如果你不确定对方是不是双关语的铁杆爱好者，那就完全避免使用双关语。否则，你只会被对方礼貌地嗤之以鼻或翻白眼。

Beware of puns and other clever wordplay. The only people who appreciate puns are the people who can do them. It’s like water polo; it’s hard to appreciate the sport unless you’ve played it. If you don’t know for sure that you’re dealing with hardcore pun lovers, avoid puns completely. Otherwise, you’re just begging for a courtesy snort or an eye roll.

避开陷阱，人们就会觉得你真的很有趣。而且他们说得没错。但赢得他人的喜爱并非幽默的唯一好处。幽默还能让你更有创造力，至少在短期内如此。5,6我认为这与幽默违背直线思维有关。幽默会暂时关闭你潮湿的机器人大脑中的常识程序，启动随机灵感生成器。至少对我来说，打个比方，是这样。或许这一切只是因为幽默让你感到精力充沛，同时又放松身心。这必然有助于激发创造力。

Avoid the traps, and people will think you are genuinely fun. And they’ll be right. But endearing yourself to others isn’t the last of humor’s benefits. Humor also makes you more creative, at least in the short run.5,6 I think it has something to do with the fact that humor is a violation of straight-line thinking. Humor temporarily shuts down the common sense program in your moist robot brain and boots the random idea generator. At least it feels that way to me, figuratively speaking. Perhaps all that is happening is that humor makes you feel energized and relaxed at the same time. That is bound to help creativity.

量身定制你的幽默

Tailor Your Humor

多年来，我注意到一个最可靠但带有性别歧视的概括：女性往往会对发生在别人身上的坏事发笑，比如一个漂亮女孩在去舞会的路上一头栽进泥坑。男性也喜欢这种幽默，但我的观察是，男性更有可能喜欢那些精心设计而非自然发生的传统笑话式故事。

One of the most reliable albeit sexist generalizations I’ve noticed over the years is that women tend to laugh at stories involving bad things happening to people, such as an attractive girl taking a face plant into a mud puddle on the way to the prom. Guys like that sort of humor, too, but my observation is that men are far more likely to enjoy traditional joke-like stories that are more engineered than organic.

了解你的听众。有些人认为厕所幽默和涉及生殖器的幽默是唯一有效的幽默形式。另一些人则追求巧妙的幽默。你不会赢得任何人对你偏爱的幽默风格的兴趣。所以，假设你的目标是赢得别人的喜欢，最好根据别人想听的内容进行调整。

Know your audience. Some people believe that bathroom humor and references to genitalia are the only valid forms of humor. Others look for cleverness. You won’t win anyone over to your preferred brand of humor. So it’s better to adapt to what others want to hear, assuming your goal is to be liked.

人们通常从见面的那一刻起就展现出他们的幽默感。你可以观察他们笑什么，讲什么样的故事，以及他们是否有尖锐的个性。如果我听到有人说“天哪”或“我的天哪”，我就会把脏话从故事里删掉。如果我说了一些略带机智的话，并得到了回应，我知道我可以尽情发挥我的机智了。在承诺之前，先测试一下方法是个好主意。

People generally broadcast their sense of humor from the moment you meet. You can observe what people laugh at, what sort of stories they tell, and whether they have an edgy personality. If I hear someone say, “Gosh” or “Holy mackerel,” I leave out the profanity from my stories. If I say something mildly clever and get a reaction, I know I can turn the cleverness spigot on full. It’s a good idea to test an approach before committing.

吉姆的结肠镜检查故事

Jim’s Colonoscopy Story

我的朋友吉姆讲了一个关于他结肠镜检查预约的趣事。按照医生的指示，他在预约前一天喝了一种强效泻药，并在当天的大部分时间里泡在厕所里，以此来净化自己。正如吉姆所说，到他去看医生的时候，他的后门区域已经“干干净净”了。

My friend Jim tells a funny story about his colonoscopy appointment. Per his doctor’s instructions, he purged himself the day before the appointment by drinking a powerful laxative and spending the better part of the day in the bathroom. As Jim tells it, he was “squeaky clean” in his backdoor region by the time he visited the doctor.

故事讲到这里，你就能看出故事的结构在发展。作为观众，你已经知道吉姆身上会发生一些不好的事情，而且会涉及到他的肛门部位。这是一个好故事的标志。现在，回到正题……

By this point in his story, you can see the structure developing. As the audience, you already know something bad is going to happen to Jim somehow involving his anal area. That’s the sign of a good story. Now, back to it . . .

正如吉姆所说，清理肠道的过程漫长而痛苦。但因为他大约每年只需要做一次，所以这些痛苦也值得。吉姆走进医生的办公室，自豪地宣布自己已经准备好接受结肠镜检查。接待员看了看日历，说：“您的预约时间是……明天。”

As Jim tells the story, the cleansing process was a long and unpleasant one. But since he only needs to do it once every year or so, it’s worth the unpleasantness. Jim walked into the doctor’s office and proudly announced his readiness for the colonoscopy. The receptionist checked her calendar and said, “Your appointment is . . . tomorrow.”

这就是妙语。它体现了讲故事的两个有趣之处。首先，你或许能感觉到，这个故事如果当面讲出来会更有趣。你会发现，有些类型的幽默在书面形式下效果最佳，而有些则更适合当面讲。吉姆的故事就属于当面讲的类型。当你读到这里时，你可能只会露出一个微笑，或者说，笑一笑。但如果当面讲出来，每次都会引来阵阵大笑。

That’s the punch line. It illustrates two interesting points about storytelling. First, you can probably sense that the story would be far funnier in person. You will discover that some types of humor work best in written form and others work best in person. Jim’s story is an in-person type. As you read it here, you probably managed little more than a smile, if that. Told in person, it gets a huge laugh every time.

第二个有趣的点是，吉姆的故事把“糟糕的部分”留给了你的想象。他第二天的净化显然会很不愉快，但这个笑话的结尾却简单地暗示了不愉快的时光即将到来。通常，你希望你的妙语能够激发听众在自己的脑海中完成这个故事——包括糟糕的部分。这样每个人都能以自己觉得最有趣的方式想象结局。

The second interesting point is that Jim’s story saves the “bad part” for your imagination. His second day of cleansing will obviously be unpleasant, but the joke ends with the simple knowledge that unpleasant times are ahead. In general, you want your punch line to inspire listeners to complete the story—including the bad part—in their own minds. That allows every person to imagine the ending in the way that is most amusing to them.

精心设计的幽默

Engineered Humor

精心设计的笑话包含一个不太可能或令人惊讶的问题解决方案，就像工程师发现一种修复损坏物体的新方法一样。

An engineered joke is one that includes an unlikely or surprising solution to a problem, much like the way an engineer discovers a novel way to fix something that is broken.

例如，2010年，全世界见证了智利煤矿工人被困地下数日的悲剧。从地面到他们狭小地下空间的一个小洞是他们唯一的氧气、食物和水来源。全世界都与这些矿工心心相印，祈祷他们获救。

For example, in 2010, the world watched the drama of the Chilean coal miners trapped underground for days. A small hole from the surface to their tiny underground space was their only source of oxygen, food, and water. The world was emotionally connected to these miners, praying for their rescue.

与此同时，一些矿工既有妻子，又有情妇的故事开始流传。我的朋友劳拉听到这些情妇的故事后，打趣道：“如果我是他们妻子中的一个，我早就把泥土铲到那个通风口里去了。”

Meanwhile, stories started emerging that some of the miners had both wives and mistresses. My friend Laura heard the stories of the mistresses and quipped, “If I were one of those wives, I’d be shoveling dirt down that air hole.”

这真是一个工程学的解决方案，解决了一个通常无法用工程学解决的问题。你可以想象一下，愤怒的妻子听到丈夫有情妇的消息，一边咒骂一边把泥土铲进洞里。这画面很滑稽，至少对那些幽默感有点儿扭曲的人来说是这样。（我笑了大概一个星期。）

That’s an engineering solution to a problem not normally solved by engineering. You can visualize the angry wife hearing the news of her husband’s mistress and shoveling dirt down the hole while cursing. It’s a funny image, at least for people who have a warped sense of humor. (I laughed for about a week.)

我意识到，我对女性和男性喜欢的幽默类型的刻板印象并不适用于所有人。例如，劳拉创造了一个我听过的最精彩的精心设计的笑话。但我认为你会发现，关于幽默的性别概括大约有80%是正确的。

I realize that my stereotypes about the type of humor women enjoy versus men won’t hold for all people. For example, Laura created one of the best engineered jokes I’ve heard. But I think you’ll find the gender generalization about humor to be about 80 percent true.

第24章

Chapter 24

肯定句

Affirmations

我在我的书《呆伯特的未来》（The Dilbert Future）中，我描述了我与一种叫做“肯定句”的奇特经历。你需要了解一些背景故事，才能理解我面对各种困境（包括我的声音问题）时始终保持的坚定乐观。

In my book The Dilbert Future, I described my odd experience with something called affirmations. You’ll need to know a little back story here to understand my unwavering optimism against long odds, including my voice problem.

肯定句其实就是在想象结果的同时，不断重复自己想要实现的目标。你可以写下来，说出来，或者直接用句子的形式思考。典型的肯定句形式是“我，斯科特·亚当斯，将成为一名宇航员”。肯定句的细节可能并不重要，因为这个过程是为了提升你的专注力，而不是召唤魔法。

Affirmations are simply the practice of repeating to yourself what you want to achieve while imagining the outcome you want. You can write it, speak it, or just think it in sentence form. The typical form of an affirmation would be “I, Scott Adams, will become an astronaut.” The details of affirmations probably don’t matter much because the process is about improving your focus, not summoning magic.

显然，我第一次尝试在《呆伯特的未来》中写关于肯定句的文章，失败了。我原本想探讨人类感知的局限性，以及这种局限性如何阻碍我们前进。根据我收到的愤怒邮件和互联网上的热议，显然大多数人把我的观点理解为我相信魔法。全世界的怀疑论者都对我的言行勃然大怒，他们认为我向缺乏理性且轻信的公众宣扬魔法思维。

Apparently, I failed badly at my first attempt to write about affirmations in The Dilbert Future. I had intended to make a point about the limits of human perception and how that might be holding us back. Based on angry emails I got and the buzz on the Internet, apparently most people interpreted my point to mean I believe in magic. The skeptics of the world were apoplectic about what they perceived as my promotion of magical thinking to an irrational and gullible public.

所以，首先我要明确声明，我不相信魔法。但和大多数人一样，我一生中经历过一些与魔法难以区分的事情，就像穴居人可能会觉得你的手机是魔法一样。‡‡我当时和现在的观点是，你不需要知道某样东西的工作原理才能利用它。一个穴居人可以成功地使用手机，假设有人教他如何使用，同时仍然相信手机的内部运作是超自然的。他的错误认知不会影响手机的实用性，至少在手机坏了，他开始对着手机祈祷之前是这样。

So let me start by clearly stating that I don’t believe in magic. But like most people, I have experienced several events in my life that are indistinguishable from magic in the same way a caveman might perceive that your phone is magic.‡‡ My point then and now is that you don’t need to know why something works to take advantage of it. A caveman could successfully use a phone, assuming someone taught him how, while continuing to believe its inner workings were supernatural. His faulty perception would have no impact on the usefulness of the phone, at least until it broke and he started praying to it.

肯定句或许有点像穴居人与电话。你可以自行判断，我接下来的故事究竟是巧合、选择性记忆、纯粹的运气、努力工作、更专注、思维调节、隐藏的天赋，还是其他任何你喜欢的。我的看法（为了保持一致性，我假设这种看法是有缺陷的）是肯定句很有用，但我不知道为什么。

Affirmations might be a bit like the caveman and the phone. You can make your own judgment about whether my story that follows is a case of coincidence, selective memory, simple luck, hard work, greater focus, mind-tuning, hidden talent, or whatever you like. My perception (which I assume for the sake of consistency is flawed) is that affirmations are useful, and I have no idea why.

我先简单说说我尝试肯定句时发生了什么，你自己判断吧。不过，我们先排除魔法作为解释之一。

Let me simply tell you what happened when I tried affirmations, and you can decide for yourself. But let’s agree to rule out magic as one of the explanations.

起源

How It Started

正如我之前提到的，二十五六岁时，我参加了一些催眠课程。课外，我认识了一些学生。其中一位打电话到我家，说她读了一本关于肯定疗法的书，也尝试了一下，并获得了一些意想不到的效果，至少根据她自己的估计是如此。她强烈推荐我也试试肯定疗法。这对我来说没什么用，只是时间问题，而那几年我时间充裕，所以我说我会试试。我真正的目的是要揭穿她的说法。我当时觉得肯定疗法完全是胡扯。但我倾向于尽可能保持开放的心态，所以我决定尝试一下，希望能够公平地尝试一下肯定疗法。

As I mentioned earlier, in my mid-twenties, I took classes to learn hypnosis. I got to know some of the students outside of class. One of them called me at home to say she had read a book about affirmations, tried them, and experienced some hugely unlikely results, at least according to her own estimate of the odds. She strongly recommended I try affirmations, too. It would cost me nothing but time, which I had in abundance during those years, so I said I’d give them a try. My real agenda was to debunk her claims. I assumed affirmations were complete bullshit. But it’s my preference to be open-minded when I can, so I went into it with the intention of giving affirmations a fair try.

我的第一个肯定句是“我，斯科特，会变得富有”。这个故事的长篇版本讲述了两只极其幸运的股票，它们不知从何而来，分别像直觉一样闪现在我眼前。但我对肯定句的信任程度不足以让我对那些通过某种非理性过程注意到的股票进行大举投资。由于文书工作上的失误，我对第一只股票一分钱都没投资，结果它却一路飙升。我买入并迅速卖出第二只股票，获得了可观的收益，并在场外看着它也一路飙升。这两只股票在那一年都成了热门话题，在大约1万只可能的股票中名列前茅。那段时间我没有再买其他股票。
