My first affirmation was “I, Scott, will become rich.” The long version of the story involves two ridiculously lucky stock picks that came to me out of nowhere in separate flashes of something that felt like intuition. But I didn’t trust affirmations enough to invest heavily in stocks that came to my attention through some sort of irrational process. I invested nothing in the first stock because of a paperwork snafu, and it subsequently went to the moon. I bought and quickly sold the second stock for a respectable gain and watched from the sidelines as it, too, zoomed up. Both stocks were big stories that year and among the top gainers out of a field of perhaps 10,000 possible stocks. I didn’t pick any other stocks during that time.

我的肯定没能让我致富，至少没能立刻。但我心想：零基础就能连续选出今年两只最佳股票的概率有多大？显然，这可能纯粹是运气。猴子至少有时也能连续选出两只盈利股票。但这足以让我再次尝试，再次确认我的肯定。

My affirmation failed to make me rich, at least right away. But I wondered: What were the odds I could pick two of the best stocks of the year back-to-back with zero research? Obviously, it could be pure luck. A monkey could pick two winning stocks in a row at least some of the time. But it was enough of a tease to encourage me to try again with another affirmation.

我第二次尝试的对象是一位我认为远非我所能配得上的女孩。我简化一下，说是一系列巧合让不可能的事情发生了，虽然只是短暂的。但再次强调，这并不能证明肯定句有效。也许我只是个选股高手，而且比我那面撒谎的镜子愿意承认的要帅得多。无论我成功的真正原因是什么，我得到的回报足以鼓励我继续尝试肯定句，希望它能有所裨益。

My second attempt involved a girl I perceived to be far out of my league. I’ll shortcut that story by saying a series of coincidences lined up to make the unlikely happen, albeit briefly. But again, that wasn’t proof affirmations work. Maybe I’m just a good stock-picker and far more handsome than my lying mirror is willing to admit. Whatever the real reason for my success, I got enough of a payoff to encourage me to keep trying affirmations just in case there was something to them.

我的下一个肯定比我在这里描述的更私人。但它恰好是那种我可以相当肯定地计算概率的事情，就像你如何知道彩票中奖者的概率能超过千万分之一一样。就我而言，我战胜了自己计算出的万分之一左右的概率，而且这一切都不需要努力、技巧或人脉。

My next affirmation was more personal than I can describe here. But it happened to be the type of thing for which I could calculate the odds with some degree of certainty, like how you might know a lottery winner beat odds of ten-million-to-one. In my case, I beat odds that I calculated to be somewhere in the ten-thousand-to-one range, and none of it required hard work, skill, or connections.

我在此停顿一下，承认选择性记忆可能是我感知背后的原因。也许我尝试了很多肯定句，但只记得那些看起来有效的。我不能排除这种可能性。也许我是个优秀的选股高手，一个完全没意识到这一点的帅哥，而且像彩票中奖者一样幸运。又或许我非常不擅长估计特定事件发生的概率。以上任何一种解释都有可能。

I pause here to acknowledge the possibility that selective memory is behind my perceptions. Perhaps I tried lots of affirmations and only remember the ones that seemed to work. I can’t rule that out. Maybe I was a good stock-picker, a total stud who didn’t realize it, and lucky like a lottery winner. Or perhaps I’m terrible at estimating the odds of particular events happening. Any one of those explanations is possible.

我又尝试了一次肯定式的练习。这次是为了打赌。我那位银行同事报名参加了一个提高GMAT考试成绩的课程。GMAT是申请商科硕士学位（也就是MBA）的资格考试。我大学四年级时参加了GMAT考试，成绩平平，只拿到了77%的百分位，也就是说只有23%的人比我考得好。这分数根本进不了顶尖大学，所以我放弃了这个梦想。但不知何故，事后想想，我竟然跟同事打赌，说我可以重考，下次再赢她，不管她下次的分数是多少。我大胆地（愚蠢地）宣称，我不用参加预备班也能赢。考虑到她第一次考试的成绩是86%，而且她还指望这门课能让她表现更好，这个赌注真是太蠢了。

I tried affirmations again. This time was in service of a bet. My coworker at the bank had signed up for a class to help raise her GMAT test scores. That’s the test you take to qualify for a master’s degree program in business, better known as an MBA. I had taken the test in my senior year of college and scored a mediocre seventy-seventh percentile, meaning 23 percent of people who took the test did better. It wasn’t good enough to get into a top school, and so I had abandoned that dream. But for some reason that I don’t even understand in hindsight, I bet my coworker that I could retake the test and beat her next score, whatever that might be. And I boldly (stupidly) proclaimed I would do it without a prep class. It was a dumb bet, given that she had scored in the eighty-sixth percentile her first try and expected to do better because of the class.

我在家做了一些练习测试，分数从未比我最初的77%高出多少。我决定测试一下我的肯定句。我想想象一个具体的结果，所以我选了94%的百分位，因为我觉得这个分数足够高，足以赢得赌注。我想象着打开邮件，看到考试成绩单上写着“94” 。

I took some practice tests at home and never scored much better than my original seventy-seventh percentile. I decided to put my affirmations to the test. I wanted to visualize a specific result, so I picked the ninety-fourth percentile because I thought that would be high enough to win the bet. I visualized opening the mail and seeing “94” on my test result form.

考试当天，我感觉自己的成绩并不比练习题好，但我坚持94分，并等待着邮寄的成绩。几周后，成绩到了。我打开信，看了看总分。上面写着94分。

On test day, I felt I did no better than my practice tests, but I kept up my affirmations on the score of 94 and waited for the results in the mail. A few weeks later, the results arrived. I opened the letter and looked in the box with my overall score. It said 94.

也许我只是考试成绩好，和同事的打赌启发了我。又或许，我考到94分只是巧合。我唯一确定的是，如果肯定句有任何价值，我应该把目标定得更高一些。但接下来的几年里，我专注于日常工作，没有使用肯定句，因为事情似乎进展顺利，无需任何帮助。我从加州大学伯克利分校哈斯商学院毕业，以为自己有朝一日会成为某个重要企业的CEO。我并不认为我需要任何帮助就能实现这个目标。

Perhaps I’m just a good test-taker and my bet with a coworker inspired me. And perhaps hitting the exact score of 94 was nothing but a coincidence. All I knew for sure is that if affirmations had any kind of value, I should set my sights higher. But for the next few years, I focused on my day job and didn’t use affirmations because things seemed to be going generally well without any help. I graduated from the Haas School of Business at the University of California at Berkeley and assumed I was on my way to becoming a CEO of something important someday. I didn’t think I needed any help to get there.

该计划没有成功。

That plan did not work out.

我下一次使用肯定句是为了追求一份我想象中最稀有、最令人向往的工作。肯定句是这样的：“我，斯科特·亚当斯，将成为一名著名的汽车漫画家。”

The next time I used affirmations was in pursuit of the rarest, most desirable job I have ever imagined. The affirmation went like this: “I, Scott Adams, will be a famous cartoonist.”

效果更好。

That worked out better.

‡‡我套用阿瑟·克拉克 (Arthur C. Clarke) 的观察：任何足够复杂的技术都与魔法无异。

‡‡I’m paraphrasing Arthur C. Clarke’s observation that any sufficiently complex technology is indistinguishable from magic.

第25章

Chapter 25

时机也是运气

Timing Is Luck, Too

西当你练习肯定句，然后恰好在你专注的领域取得成功时，你会感觉自己很幸运。反正你就是这么认为的。迪尔伯特的成功故事充满了听起来很幸运的事件。我会描述我故事中一些最幸运的部分，这样你就能体会到，有时运气需要多么深厚才能获得成功。

When you practice affirmations and then happen to succeed in your area of focus, it feels like extraordinary luck. That’s how you perceive it, anyway. The Dilbert success story is engorged with lucky-sounding events. I’ll describe some of the luckiest parts of my story so you can get a sense for how deep luck sometimes needs to run before you find success.

运气最重要的组成部分是时机。当宇宙和我的时间安排完全契合时——纯属偶然——事情就会进展得非常顺利。而当我的时间安排不对时，无论多么努力或多么有天赋都无济于事。迪尔伯特就是你所能见到的运气时机的最佳例证。运气降临我并非完全偶然；我把自己置于一个更容易发生运气的位置。我就像一个猎人，聪明地选择森林中的地点，在隐蔽处等待雄鹿经过。猎人仍然需要运气，但他会掌控自己的处境，以增加获胜的几率。

The biggest component of luck is timing. When the universe and I have been on a compatible schedule—entirely by chance—things worked out swimmingly. When my timing was off, no amount of hard work or talent mattered. Dilbert was the best example of lucky timing you will ever see. It wasn’t a complete accident that luck found me; I put myself in a position where luck was more likely to happen. I was like a hunter who picks his forest location intelligently and waits in his blind for a buck to stroll by. The hunter still must be lucky, but he manages his situation to increase his odds.

我也做过类似的事情。我尝试了很多不同的冒险，保持乐观，投入精力，尽可能多地学习，做好准备，并在游戏中坚持足够长的时间，直到好运降临。我希望最终能有一只雄鹿出现，而“呆伯特”真的来了。

I did something similar. I tried a lot of different ventures, stayed optimistic, put in the energy, prepared myself by learning as much as I could, and stayed in the game long enough for luck to find me. I hoped a buck would eventually walk by, and with Dilbert it did.

让我给你简要介绍一下迪尔伯特成功所需的运气（时机）。

Let me give you a snapshot of the luck (timing) that needed to happen for Dilbert to succeed.

首先，我必须出生在报纸盛行、漫画盛行的时代。我必须拥有适合这份工作的基因和良好的成长环境。而我出生在美国，这对我帮助很大。

For starters, I had to be born in a time in which newspapers existed and comics mattered. And I had to have the right genetic makeup for the work and the right upbringing. And it helped a great deal that I was born in the United States.

我的第一位漫画编辑莎拉·吉莱斯皮 (Sarah Gillespie) 在看过我提交给联合媒体的样本后，立即发现了呆伯特的潜力。莎拉的丈夫是 IBM 的一名工程师。他上班时会穿一件白色短袖纽扣衬衫，口袋里插着笔，就像呆伯特一样。其他漫画联合公司看到呆伯特后并不认同，于是便礼貌地给我发了拒绝信。莎拉看到呆伯特后，对内容和文笔都产生了共鸣。尽管公司内部存在强烈反对，她还是坚持创作这部漫画。如果莎拉的工作是别人做，我相信呆伯特也会被拒绝。业内只有少数人是新漫画的守门人。他们中的一个嫁给现实生活中的呆伯特的几率有多大？

My first comics editor, Sarah Gillespie, immediately saw the potential in Dilbert when she looked over the samples I submitted to United Media. Sarah was married to an engineer who worked at IBM. When he dressed for work, he wore a white short-sleeved button-up shirt with pens in his pocket, just like Dilbert. When the other syndication companies saw Dilbert and didn’t relate to him, they sent me polite rejection letters. When Sarah saw Dilbert, she related both to the content and to the writing. She championed the strip against some heavy objections within her company. Had someone else been in Sarah’s job, I believe Dilbert would have been rejected. There was only a handful of people in the industry who were gatekeepers for new comics. What were the odds that one of them would be married to a real-life Dilbert?

《呆伯特》推出后的头几年，我们很难找到任何一家大型都市报纸来刊登它。你需要第一家大型报纸来跟进，其他人才会觉得值得冒险。

For the first few years after Dilbert’s launch, we had trouble getting any large metropolitan newspaper to pick it up. You need the first big paper to get onboard before others see it as a worthy risk.

一天，《波士顿环球报》的一位员工——她的工作包括审核联合投稿并向高层推荐新漫画——和丈夫一起去度假。她开车，丈夫正无聊着呢。《呆伯特》的促销册子恰好在车里。这位丈夫——碰巧是一位工程师——捡到后哈哈大笑。他的妻子对《呆伯特》的感受并不一样，但她相信丈夫的反应，并推荐它刊登在《波士顿环球报》上。随着这笔生意的顺利完成，美国东北部的许多报纸也纷纷效仿。

One day, a Boston Globe employee—whose job included looking at syndication submissions and recommending new comics to senior management—went on a vacation with her husband. She was driving; he was bored. The Dilbert sales packet happened to be in the car. The husband, who was—as luck would have it—an engineer, picked it up and started laughing. His wife didn’t relate to Dilbert the same way, but she trusted her husband’s reaction and recommended it for inclusion in The Boston Globe. With that sale in the bag, many of the newspapers in the Northeast followed suit.

但美国西部的销售却一片萧条。我很快就知道了原因——那个地区的销售员并不是《呆伯特》的粉丝。所以当他出去推销时，他把《呆伯特》的销售包放在公文包里，并展示其他漫画。然后宇宙介入了。这位销售员心脏病发作，死在了路上的一家酒店房间里。他的继任者约翰·马修斯认为《呆伯特》是联合媒体公司最畅销的漫画。他确实把它卖给了他走访的每一家报纸。约翰是我所认识的最好的销售员。如果他没有得到这份工作，或者原来的销售员还活着，《呆伯特》可能只是一本小漫画，在东北部连载几年，然后就销声匿迹了。

But sales in the western United States were comatose. I soon learned why—the salesperson for that region wasn’t a fan of Dilbert. So when he went on sales calls, he kept the Dilbert sales packet in his briefcase and showed other comics. Then the universe got involved. The salesman had a heart attack and died in a hotel room on the road. His replacement, John Matthews, identified Dilbert as the most sellable comic in United Media’s stable. And sell it he did to every newspaper he visited. John is the best salesman I’ve ever known. Had he not been available for the job or had the original salesman lived, Dilbert might have been a small comic that ran in the northeast for a few years before fading to obscurity.

呆伯特的诞生恰逢其时。九十年代中期，媒体聚焦令人不安的企业裁员趋势，呆伯特则被推到了风口浪尖，成为世界各地苦不堪言的办公室白领的象征。呆伯特登上了《时代》杂志、 《人物》杂志、《新闻周刊》杂志、《财富》杂志、《公司》杂志等众多杂志的封面。我修改了呆伯特，使其比原版更加关注职场，这部漫画也因此成为了一个与时代完美契合的漫画。

The good timing for Dilbert was relentless. In the mid-nineties, the media was focusing on the disturbing trend of corporate downsizing, and Dilbert got pushed to the front of the conversation as the symbol of hapless office workers everywhere. Dilbert was on the covers of TIME, People, Newsweek, Fortune, Inc., and more. I modified Dilbert to be more workplace-focused than it had originally been, and it became a perfect match of a comic to an era.

大约在同一时期，科技本身也成了名人。互联网爆炸式增长，互联网时代到来，所有与科技相关的事物突然间甚至吸引了普通大众的目光。在八十年代，呆伯特不过是又一个书呆子漫画人物。到了九十年代，呆伯特象征着那些正在改变地球生活的科技天才。出人意料且颇具讽刺意味的是，呆伯特“性感”。

At about the same time, technology itself became a celebrity. The Internet exploded, the dot-com era happened, and all-things technical were suddenly fascinating even to the general public. In the eighties, Dilbert would have been nothing but another nerd comic. In the nineties, Dilbert symbolized the type of technology geniuses who were transforming life on planet Earth. Dilbert was unexpectedly and ironically “sexy.”

当伯克·布雷斯德（Berke Breathed）退休他的热门漫画《布鲁姆县》（Bloom County）时，我的运气更加好，这为报纸腾出了数百个版面。后来，《卡尔文和霍布斯》（Calvin and Hobbes）的创作者比尔·沃特森（Bill Watterson）退休，也为报纸腾出了更多版面。对于正处于事业巅峰、如此年轻就退休的漫画家来说，这可是史无前例的。而且，时机恰逢《呆伯特》（Dilbert）日益受到关注，这使其成为最显而易见的替代选择。报纸像抢糖果一样抢购了它。

I had even more luck when Berke Breathed retired his popular comic strip Bloom County, which opened hundreds of spaces in newspapers. Later, Bill Watterson, creator of Calvin and Hobbes, retired and opened even more space. It was unprecedented for cartoonists at the top of their game and so young to retire. And the timing coincided with the growing spotlight on Dilbert, making it the most obvious replacement choice. Newspapers snapped it up like candy.

我在之前的章节中提到过我的手部问题——局限性肌张力障碍。如果不是当时同时开发的Wacom Cintiq产品，让我能够直接在电脑上无忧无虑地作画，我的职业生涯早就结束了。问题和解决方案同时出现的概率有多大？如果我的手部问题早五年发生，我可能就从漫画界退休了。

I mentioned my hand problem—the focal dystonia—in an earlier chapter. My career would have been over if not for the simultaneous development of Wacom’s Cintiq product, which allowed me to draw directly to the computer with no worries. What were the odds that the problem and the solution existed at the same time? If my hand problem had happened five years earlier, I might have retired from cartooning.

总而言之，《呆伯特》的成功很大程度上是运气的结晶。但我确实让运气更容易地降临到我身上，而且当它降临时，我已经做好了充分的准备。运气不会给你策略或体系——你必须自己去争取。

To sum it up, the success of Dilbert is mostly a story of luck. But I did make it easier for luck to find me, and I was thoroughly prepared when it did. Luck won’t give you a strategy or a system—you have to get that yourself.

我发现把世界看作一台老虎机很有帮助，它不需要你投入金钱。它只需要你的时间、专注和精力——一遍又一遍地拉动手柄。一台普通的老虎机需要投入金钱，从长远来看会让任何玩家破产。但如果你有能力持续拉动手柄，一台回报稀少但确定可靠、无需预先投入资金的机器就能保证你赢。在这种环境下，即使你99%的时间都失败，你也知道成功是必然的。你只需要在游戏中坚持足够长的时间。

I find it helpful to see the world as a slot machine that doesn’t ask you to put money in. All it asks is for your time, focus, and energy—to pull the handle over and over. A normal slot machine that requires money will bankrupt any player in the long run. But the machine that has rare yet certain payoffs and asks for no money up front is a guaranteed winner if you have what it takes to keep yanking until you get lucky. In that environment, you can fail 99 percent of the time while knowing success is guaranteed. All you need to do is stay in the game long enough.

第26章

Chapter 26

几次肯定句都有效

A Few Times Affirmations Worked

一个在我漫画创作的几年里，《华尔街日报》邀请我撰写一篇关于职场的客座评论。那篇文章的标题是《呆伯特法则》，读者反响热烈。《哈珀商业周刊》的一位编辑联系我，问我是否愿意就同一主题写一本书。我同意了，并开始写作。在那段时间里，以及通常在健身房跑步机上跑步时，我都会在脑海里反复念叨我的新誓言：“我，斯科特·亚当斯，将成为排名第一的畅销书作家。”

A few years into my cartooning career, The Wall Street Journal asked me to write a guest editorial about the workplace. That article was titled “The Dilbert Principle,” and it got a great response from readers. An editor for Harper Business contacted me and asked if I would be willing to write a book around the same topic. I agreed and started writing. During that time, and usually while running on the treadmill at the gym, I repeated my new affirmation in my head: “I, Scott Adams, will be a number-one bestselling author.”

《呆伯特法则》一炮打响，几周内就荣登《纽约时报》非虚构类畅销书排行榜榜首。几个月后，我的后续作品《呆伯特的生意经》也跻身第二名。这两本书的成功为我带来了大量关注，也极大地促进了《呆伯特》在报纸上的销量。以当时的标准来看，《呆伯特》网站的流量非常大，而我的演讲事业也蒸蒸日上。《呆伯特》的授权业务也随之腾飞。突然之间，我接触的一切都似乎开始奏效了。

The Dilbert Principle started strong and within a few weeks hit number one on The New York Times nonfiction bestseller list. In a matter of months, my follow-up book, Dogbert’s Big Book of Business, joined it in the number two slot. The success of the two books brought me a lot of attention and put a turbo boost on sales of Dilbert to newspapers. The Dilbert website was getting huge traffic by the standards of the day, and I had a booming speaking career on the side. The licensing business for Dilbert took off, too. Suddenly, it seemed as if everything I touched was working.

看到这么多美好的事情发生，我确信只要下定决心，我几乎可以做到任何事。我不再相信那些自我肯定只是一种集中注意力的方法，我觉得自己不再需要它了。

With so many good things happening, I convinced myself that I could do just about anything that I set my mind to. I discounted the affirmations as being nothing more than a way to focus, and I figured I no longer needed that crutch.

所以，当我担任动画电视剧《呆伯特》的联合执行制片人时，我没有使用肯定句。这部电视剧在现已停播的联合电视网（UPN）播出了两个半季。前半季反响不错，但由于一个简单的沟通问题，我们失去了下一季的档期，导致节目被转移到了新的时段。观众很难找到这部剧，收视率也因此暴跌。与此同时，联合电视网决定转型为一个专注于非裔美国观众的频道。《呆伯特》在播出后半季就被取消了。我对这部剧的过早停播感到很矛盾，因为它需要大量的制作，而且并不好玩。

So I didn’t use affirmations when I worked as co-executive producer of the animated Dilbert TV show that ran for two half-seasons on the now-defunct UPN network. The first half-season did well, but we lost our time slot the following season because of a simple communication problem that resulted in the show getting moved to a new time slot. Viewers had trouble finding the show, and the ratings tanked. At the same time, the network decided to remake itself as a channel focusing on African-American viewers. Dilbert was cancelled after the second half-season. I had mixed feelings about the show’s premature death because it was a lot of work, and not the fun kind.

当我投资第一家或第二家餐馆时，我也没有使用肯定句，从长远来看，这些都没有成功。

I also didn’t use affirmations when I invested in my first or second restaurant, and in the long run, neither of those worked out.

当我创办素食卷饼公司时，我并没有使用肯定句，因为这家公司从未成功过。

I didn’t use affirmations when I started my vegetarian burrito company, which never took off.

我无法告诉你，我之所以能取得少数成功，是肯定句的运用，也无法告诉你，没有运用肯定句的运用注定了其他项目的失败。我只能告诉你我做了什么以及何时做的。正如我之前解释过的，这种模式有几种非常合理的解释。我脑海中浮现的最突出的解释是，我真的不喜欢电视节目、《傻瓜先生》或餐厅的工作。而当每件事结束时，我都感到如释重负。我注意到的规律是，只有当我百分之百地渴望成功时，肯定句才会起作用。如果我能打个响指，让电视节目、《傻瓜先生》和餐厅都成功，我早就这么做了。但我知道，我不会喜欢持续管理其中任何一个项目。我的复杂感受重要吗？我永远不会知道。

I can’t tell you I believe affirmations caused my few successes or that not using affirmations doomed other projects to failure. I can only tell you what I did and when. As I’ve explained, there are several perfectly reasonable explanations for the pattern. The one that stands out in my mind is that I really had no love for the work involved in the TV show, the Dilberito, or the restaurants. And I felt relief when each ended. The pattern I noticed is that the affirmations only worked when I had a 100 percent unambiguous desire for success. If I could have snapped my fingers and made the TV show, the Dilberito, and the restaurants successful, I would have done it. But I knew I wouldn’t have enjoyed ongoing management of any one of them. Did my mixed feelings matter? I’ll never know.

我只用了一次肯定句。那次，我的心情很平和。我渴望得到的东西，就像一个人渴望得到的东西一样。

I only used affirmations one more time. And in that case, I had no mixed feelings. I wanted something as much as a person can want.

“我，斯科特，将会讲得非常完美。”

“I, Scott, will speak perfectly.”

第27章

Chapter 27

语音更新 I

Voice Update I

米自从我上次注射肉毒杆菌到声带，已经过去好几个月了。我的声音非常虚弱，而且难以预测，即使是最简单的人际交流也变得非常困难。我天生乐观，但现实是，痉挛性发声障碍无法治愈，我很可能这辈子都无法再进行任何对话了。

Months had passed since my last Botox shot to my vocal cords. My voice was so weak and unpredictable that it was a struggle to accomplish the simplest human interactions. I’m a natural optimist, but the reality was that spasmodic dysphonia had no cure, and I was likely to spend the rest of my life without ever again experiencing a conversation.

我无法打电话，除非是和那些了解我的情况，并且愿意用简短的“是”或“否”来回答的人。我无法在餐厅自己点餐，无法在社交聚会上与人交谈，无法继续我的巡回演讲，总的来说，我无法享受生活。我经常感到沮丧，我知道大多数患有这种疾病的人都会有这种感觉。孤独感让我身心俱疲。

I couldn’t speak on the phone except to people who knew my situation and were willing to keep conversations to short yes or no answers. I couldn’t order my own food at restaurants, couldn’t talk to people at social gatherings, couldn’t continue my speaking tour, and generally couldn’t enjoy life. I was often depressed, which I understand happens to most people with this condition. The loneliness was debilitating.

博客让我活了下来。当我写博文时，我就是交流。大多数人都能理解我，并留下了精彩的评论和回复。博客让我感觉不那么孤独。它让我保持理智，但也仅此而已。

Blogging kept me alive. When I wrote a blog post, I was communicating. People understood me, mostly, and left fascinating comments and responses. Blogging made me feel less lonely. It kept me sane but only barely.

我并不期待接下来几十年过着沉默寡言的生活。这感觉就像我的地狱。但我没有放弃。我不知道该如何放弃。

I wasn’t looking forward to the next several decades of life as a non-talker. It felt like my personal hell. But I hadn’t given up. I didn’t know how to give up.

无法治愈的健康问题常常会引来庸医的治疗。我尝试了大多数不危险的疗法。喝某个牌子的止咳糖浆没用。针灸没用。矿物质补充剂没用。口吃疗法也没用。三种不同的嗓音疗法都没用。亚历山大技巧§§也没用。补铁剂也没用。改变饮食也没用。

Incurable health problems often attract quack cures. I tried most of the ones that weren’t dangerous. Drinking a certain brand of cough syrup didn’t work. Acupuncture didn’t work. Mineral supplements didn’t work. Stutter cures didn’t work. Three different approaches to voice therapy didn’t work. The Alexander Technique§§ didn’t work. Iron supplements didn’t work. Changing my diet didn’t work.

我已经有一年多没能正常说话了。这正在慢慢地折磨着我。

I hadn’t spoken normally for over a year. It was slowly killing me.

但我当时确实有一个由两部分组成的系统。为了找出导致我声音变得糟糕的模式，我创建了一个电子表格，记录了我猜测的所有可能起作用的因素，包括饮食、睡眠时间、运动、练习说话，甚至喝健怡可乐的数量。如果我能找到我声音最糟糕的日子背后的模式，我就能知道我需要改变什么。但是，并没有出现任何模式。

But what I did have was a two-part system. To identify the pattern that caused my voice to be its worst, I created a spreadsheet and recorded every factor I guessed might be at work, including diet, hours of sleep, exercise, practice talking, and even the number of Diet Cokes consumed. If I could find the pattern behind my worst voice days, I would know what I needed to change. But no pattern emerged.

我的系统的第二部分是在全球范围内搜寻任何在医学背景下提及“痉挛性发声障碍”一词的资料。幸运的是，我生逢其时，所以这项搜寻工作由谷歌的“谷歌快讯”功能完成。我只需输入关键词即可。任何在互联网上提及我的病情的信息都会生成一条电子邮件，发送到我放在左前裤兜里的手机上。我每周都会收到几条快讯，但看起来都没有什么希望。通常情况下，互联网上的文章都在讨论这种疾病的不可治愈性——这并不奇怪，因为医学界一致认为我的病情是由脑部异常引起的。而脑部异常很难治愈。

The second part of my system involved scouring the planet for any mention of the words “spasmodic dysphonia” in a medical context. Luckily, I was born in the right era, so the scouring was done by Google using their Google Alerts function. I just plugged in the keywords. Any mention of my condition anywhere on the Internet generated an email message that went to my phone that lives in my left-front pants pocket. I got several alerts per week, but none looked promising. Usually, the articles on the Internet discussed the incurability of the condition—no surprise given that the medical consensus was that my condition was caused by a brain abnormality. Those are hard to fix.

没人想感到孤独和沮丧。但从好的方面来说，痛苦会改变你对风险的偏好。如果有人提出一个修复我嗓音的方案，而这个方案有50%的几率会让我丧命，我会毫不犹豫地接受。

No one wants to feel lonely and depressed. But on the plus side, misery alters your appetite for risk. If someone had suggested a plan for fixing my voice that had a 50 percent chance of killing me, I would have taken it in a heartbeat.

我频繁查看手机，看看有没有谷歌提醒邮件。然后我等待着。智人已经存在了15万年。我最大的希望是，在我有生之年，在地球上的某个地方，我们之中的某个人能找到治愈这个问题的方法，趁着它吞噬掉我仅存的乐观之前。我的希望渺茫。但我绝不会放弃。事实上，我气疯了，对我来说，有时愤怒就足够了。我的态度始终如一：逃出牢房，救出其他囚犯，射杀典狱长，烧毁监狱。

I checked my phone often to see if any Google alert emails had come in. And I waited. Homo sapiens have been around for 150,000 years. My best hope was that one of us, somewhere on Earth, would figure out a cure for this problem within my lifetime, before the condition devoured what was left of my optimism. My odds were not good. But I was far from giving up. In fact, I was mad as hell, and for me, anger is sometimes enough. My attitude was always the same: Escape from my cell, free the other inmates, shoot the warden, and burn down the prison.

每天，我坐在车里一遍又一遍地重复：“我，斯科特·亚当斯，会说一口完美的英语。”我相信这会发生，因为我需要相信它。

In my car, every day, I repeated over and over, “I, Scott Adams, will speak perfectly.” I believed it would happen because I needed to believe it.

§§亚历山大技巧是一种有意识地运动的方法，目的是消除身体的紧张。

§§The Alexander Technique is a method for moving in a conscious way with the goal of removing tension from your body.

第28章

Chapter 28

专家

Experts

米几年前，我快三十岁的时候，请医生检查一下我脖子上长了一个奇怪的肿块，大概有半个乒乓球那么大。我问他是什么，他说：“嗯，两种可能。要么是癌症，要么……我不知道还有什么别的可能。我会给你安排X光检查。”

Many years ago, in my late twenties, I asked a doctor to look at a strange lump that formed on my neck, about half the size of a Ping-Pong ball. I asked what it might be, and he said, “Well, two possibilities. It’s either cancer or . . . I don’t know what else it could be. I’ll schedule you for X-rays.”

我清楚地记得，我和其他病人坐在候诊室里，他们来这里的原因都一样：可能是癌症。医生会拿着X光片走进房间，喊出一个病人的名字，如果好消息是真的，他会在病人起身之前宣布。“冈萨雷斯先生？好消息。您的X光片没问题。”几分钟后，医生又说：“约翰逊太太，X光片看起来很棒。一切都好。”

I have a vivid memory of sitting in the doctor’s waiting room with the other patients who were there for the same reason: maybe cancer. The doctor would enter the room with some X-rays in hand, call out a name, and if the news was good, he would announce it before the patient even rose from his chair. “Mr. Gonzales? Good news. Your X-rays are clean.” A few minutes later, “Mrs. Johnson, the X-rays look great. It’s all good.”

然后轮到我了。“亚当斯先生？请进我的办公室。”

Then it was my turn. “Mr. Adams? Please step into my office.”

哎呀。

Yikes.

医生给我看了X光片，说从检查结果来看，可能是某种颈部癌症。我瘫坐在椅子上。

The doctor showed me the X-rays and said that from the looks of it, it was probably some sort of neck cancer. I slumped in my chair.

医生解释说，这可能是无害的。他解释说，有时候肿块在X光片上看起来像癌症，但结果发现只是“一种癌症”，没什么大不了的。他安排我去做活检，一劳永逸地解决这个问题。

The doctor explained that it might be something harmless. He explained that sometimes a lump looks just like cancer on an X-ray, but it turns out to be just “one of those things” and no big deal. He scheduled me for a biopsy to settle it once and for all.

预约时间定在下周。接下来的七天里，我就像薛定谔的猫一样，可能死了，也可能没死。我独自一人住在旧金山，几乎没有社会支持。只有我和我的一居室公寓。我的床也是我的沙发。这真是漫长的一周。

The appointment was set for the following week. For seven days, I was like Schrőedinger’s Cat, maybe dead and maybe not. I lived alone in San Francisco and didn’t have much of a social support structure. It was just me and my one room apartment. My bed was also my couch. It was a long week.

预约时，护士技师描述了活检流程。时间仿佛慢了下来，我甚至能听到自己的心跳。技师解释说，他会把针头插进肿块里，抽出一些液体。如果是血，那我可能得了癌症。如果液体是清澈的，那只是“某种疾病”，没什么大不了的。

At the appointment, the nurse technician described the biopsy procedure. Time slowed to a crawl, and I could hear my own heartbeat. The technician explained that he would put a needle into the lump and draw out some fluid. If it was blood, I probably had cancer. If the fluid was clear, it was just “one of those things,” and no big deal.

针头扎了进去，时间再次慢了下来，技师在我余光之外吸出了液体。快说，你这混蛋！他第一秒就知道结果了。他让我等他做完。

The needle went in, and time slowed again as the technician sucked out the liquid just beyond my peripheral vision. Say something, you bastard! He knew the result in the first second. He made me wait until he was done.

针头里全是清澈的液体。“我想就是那种东西，”他说。“让我把剩下的液体取出来。”

The needle was full of clear fluid. “I guess it was just one of those things,” he said. “Let me get the rest of it.”

几分钟后，我离开了医院，身上缠着一块小绷带，对生活有了新的认识。接下来的几个星期里，食物的味道都变好了。烦人的人也不再烦人了。树木变成了毛茸茸的、充满惊奇的球体。冷空气不再令人讨厌，反而令人神清气爽。我还意识到，有时专家们第一次尝试就会出错。

I left the hospital a few minutes later with a tiny bandage and a new outlook on life. Food tasted better for weeks. Annoying people were no longer annoying. Trees were fuzzy balls of wonder. Cold air was refreshing instead of annoying. And I learned that sometimes experts get it wrong on the first try.

与专家打交道总是很棘手。他们诚实吗？他们能力强吗？他们有多少次说对？我的观察和猜测是，专家在简单的事情上大约98%的时间是正确的，但在任何异常复杂、神秘甚至新颖的事情上，只有50%的时间是正确的。

Dealing with experts is always tricky. Are they honest? Are they competent? How often are they right? My observation and best guess is that experts are right about 98 percent of the time on the easy stuff but only right 50 percent of the time on anything that is unusually complicated, mysterious, or even new.

多年后，当一位心理学家建议我服用安定（Valium）来治疗我的声音问题时，我意识到这种情况属于专家一半时间都错的情况。这让我很容易拒绝安定，并继续寻找一种不那么“药物化”的解决方案。当我做出这个决定时，感觉就像是直觉，不管它是什么。但我认为更准确的说法是，这是模式识别加上乐观主义的结果​​。

Years later, when a psychologist offered me Valium to fix my voice problem, I recognized the situation as the type in which experts are wrong half of the time. That made it easy for me to say no to the Valium and keep searching for a less-druggy solution. When I made the decision, it felt like intuition, whatever that is. But I think it would be more accurate to say it was the result of pattern recognition plus optimism.

如果你的直觉与专家的判断不一致，那就认真对待吧。你可能正在经历一些你还无法用语言表达的模式识别。

If your gut feeling (intuition) disagrees with the experts, take that seriously. You might be experiencing some pattern recognition that you can’t yet verbalize.

第29章

Chapter 29

关联编程

Association Programming

西我在克罗克国民银行工作时，同事们都对一位暑期实习生大笑不已。他信奉一个古怪的理论，认为成功取决于你选择的社区。他的计划是，无论需要多少室友，都要在高档社区里住进他能负担得起的最好的公寓。剩下的就交给某种神秘的魔法吧。他愿意努力工作、上学、遵守法律，并采取所有其他正常的成功步骤。但他认为这些也只能让他走这么远。真正让人吃惊的是，他那绝妙的计划是，先和富人生活在一起，直到通过交往成为富人。

When I worked for Crocker National Bank, my coworkers and I had a good laugh at a summer intern who espoused a whacky theory about success being a function of the neighborhood you choose to live in. His plan was to get into the best apartment he could afford in an upscale neighborhood no matter how many roommates that might require him to have. He’d let some sort of vague magic do the rest. He was willing to work hard, go to school, obey the law, and take all the other normal steps to success. But he figured that could only take him so far. The real kicker was his brilliant plan to live among rich people until he could become one by association.

我记得我巧妙地嘲讽了他一番，让所有听到的人都乐开了怀。在其他方面，他看起来都很理性。但这种“结交富人”的计划简直蠢透了。经过盘问，我才知道他并没有打算与富裕的邻居建立联系，建立重要的人脉。没有明确的机制可以解释接近富人如何让他成功。他所能提供的最好的解释就是，生活有规律可循，而这就是其中之一：你会变得像你周围的人一样。

I recall cleverly mocking him to the delight of all who were within earshot. He seemed like such a rational guy in every other way. But this rich-by-association scheme was just plain stupid. Upon interrogation, I learned he wasn’t suggesting he would network and make important contacts with his well-to-do neighbors. There was no defined mechanism to explain how proximity to rich people would make him successful. The best he could offer was his observation that life had patterns, and this was one of them: You become like the people around you.

几年后，我对匿名戒酒会的运作方式了解得比我想要的还要多。我的前女友需要他们的服务，而我发现，对于有酗酒问题的人来说，匿名戒酒会比大多数其他选择都更有效。1,2匿名戒酒会的规则之一是远离那些对你有不良影响的人。考虑到同伴压力之类的力量，仔细想想，这似乎显而易见。在这种情况下，你与谁交往会产生很大的影响。但这是一个特例，与“交往致富”假说截然不同。尽管如此，这两个案例之间仍然有足够多的相似之处，我开始意识到这是一种潜在的模式。

A few years later, I learned more than I wanted to know about the workings of Alcoholics Anonymous. My ex-girlfriend had a need for their services, and I learned that it works better than most alternatives for people with drinking problems.1,2 One of Alcoholics Anonymous’ rules involves keeping away from people who are bad influences. That seems obvious when you think about it, given the power of peer pressure and that sort of thing. In this situation, who you associate with makes a big difference. But this is a special case and quite different from the rich-by-association hypothesis. Still, there was enough similarity between the two cases that it began to register with me as a potential pattern.

最近，我看到一项研究表明，与超重的人相处会导致体重增加。3-9我无法想象这是真的。但我可以想象出几种可以解释这一现象的机制。如果你的每个朋友都超重五十磅，而你只重了十磅，你可能不会感到太大的压力去改变。而如果你们在一起时，肥胖的朋友一直带你去快餐店，那也会很有害。因此，与超重的人相处会影响你的腰围似乎完全有道理。尽管如此，这与没有明显机制的交往致富理论截然不同。

More recently, I saw a study that said hanging around with overweight people can cause you to gain weight.3-9 I would not have imagined that to be true. But I can imagine several mechanisms that would explain it. If each of your friends are fifty pounds overweight and you’re only sporting an extra ten, you probably don’t feel much pressure to change. And if your corpulent friends keep steering you toward fast-food joints when you’re together, that can hurt, too. So it seems entirely plausible that hanging around with overweight people can influence your own waistline. Still, that’s very different from the rich-by-association theory that has no obvious mechanism.

《呆伯特》推出后，我继续在太平洋贝尔公司（Pacific Bell）做了几年正职。之后，我的前任老板迈克·古德温（也是他为《呆伯特》起名）写了一本关于他父亲在日本战俘营经历的书并出版了。（剧透：这本书不太顺利。）这本名为《翔文》（Shobun）的书是他作为作家的首次尝试。太平洋贝尔公司的两位“格子鼠”都成为了出版作家，我并不觉得这是什么天大的巧合。世界上有很多这样平凡的巧合。

After Dilbert launched, I continued working my day job at Pacific Bell for several years. Since then, my old boss, Mike Goodwin (who was also the guy who named Dilbert), wrote and published a book about his father’s experience in a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp. (Spoiler alert: It didn’t go well.) The book, Shobun, was his first attempt as a writer. It didn’t strike me as a huge coincidence that two cubicle rats from Pacific Bell both became published writers. The world is full of such ordinary coincidences.

离开太平洋贝尔公司后，我得知坐在我对面隔间墙的另一位同事后来写了一本关于他因谋杀入狱经历的书。他现在出狱了，因为我对用皮带勒死熟人的人很仁慈，所以我想说他是个好人，他的书也很棒。这本书的名字是《你一事无成：狱中鱼的笔记》，作者是吉米·勒纳。太平洋贝尔公司一个小角落里的三个人同时成为出版作家的几率有多大？我知道巧合通常只是巧合，但它们看起来很特别，因为我们看不到所有没有发生的事情。尽管如此，我的模式探测器还是活跃起来了。这两个人和我关系很近，最终也采取了类似的模式。他们和我关系密切是否在某种程度上很重要，也许是作为榜样或灵感？或者他们本来就写书吗？无从知晓。

After I left Pacific Bell, I learned that another fellow who sat across the cubicle wall from me subsequently wrote a book about his stint in prison for murder. He’s out of jail now, and because I have a policy of being kind to people who strangle acquaintances with belts, I’d like to say he’s a fine fellow and his book is excellent. It’s called You Got Nothing Coming: Notes from a Prison Fish, by Jimmy Lerner. What are the odds that three people in one little corner of Pacific Bell could all become published authors? I understand that coincidences are normally just that, but they seem special because we don’t get to see all the things that don’t happen. Still, my pattern detector perked up. Here were two guys who shared my proximity and ended up following a similar model. Did their proximity to me matter in some way, perhaps by example or inspiration? Or would they have written books anyway? There’s no way to know.

但故事远不止于此。几年前，我在克罗克国家银行技术部门担任主管，那时“呆伯特”甚至都还未成形。有一天，我手下的一名员工来找我，说他计划写一篇关于他发现的电子表格技巧的文章。他计划投稿给一家行业杂志，看看他们是否会付费。他之前没有写作经验，但他的想法很聪明，值得分享。我鼓励他投稿，令我惊讶的是，杂志社接受了，并支付了他1500美元（当时）的高额稿费。他们甚至重写了文章的大部分内容，他们称之为“编辑”，而他称之为“修改”。尽管如此，他证明了一个办公室小隔间里的人也能成为出版作家，并以此赚钱。他后来又写了好几篇文章，也都发表了。我和他合作是否增加了我以后从事漫画事业的可能性？我想是的。这让我觉得在专业领域之外取得成功似乎唾手可得。这真的成了现实。

But there’s more to the story. Back up several years to my time as a supervisor in the technology wing of Crocker National Bank, before Dilbert was even an idea. One of the employees I managed came to me one day and announced his plan to write an article about a spreadsheet trick he discovered. His plan was to submit it to a trade magazine and see if they would pay. He had no experience as a writer, but his idea was clever and worthy of sharing. I encouraged him to submit his work, and to my surprise, the magazine accepted it and paid him a hefty (at the time) fee of $1,500. They even rewrote most of the article, which they called “editing” and he called “butchering.” Still, he proved that a guy in a cubicle can become a published writer and make money at it. He went on to write several more articles that also got published. Did my association with him make it more likely I would later pursue a career in cartooning? I think it did. It made success outside my field seem accessible. It made it real.

人类是社会动物。我们从周围的人身上汲取能量、灵感、技能和性格特质的方式可能有很多。有时，我们通过榜样学习。有时，成功看起来更容易接近、更普通，因为我们看到普通人取得了成功，这或许会激励我们去追求回报更高的目标。有时，我们周围的人会给我们提供所需的信息、鼓励、人脉，甚至是有益的批评。我们无法总是了解他人改变我们未来行为的机制，但很明显，这种情况确实会发生，而且非常重要。

Humans are social animals. There are probably dozens of ways we absorb energy, inspiration, skills, and character traits from those around us. Sometimes we learn by example. Sometimes success appears more approachable and ordinary because we see normal people achieve it, and perhaps that encourages us to pursue schemes with higher payoffs. Sometimes the people around us give us information we need, or encouragement, or contacts, or even useful criticism. We can’t always know the mechanism by which others change our future actions, but it’s clear it happens, and it’s important.

几年前，我曾嘲笑过一位实习生，因为他认为邻居的选择会影响他的职业生涯。如果他正在读这篇文章，我深表歉意。我很容易理解，你的居住地可能会影响你对事业的投入。住在乐观的赢家附近肯定会在某种程度上产生影响。我建议你把这一点作为编程你湿润机器人自我的主要工具。编程界面就是你的位置。要改变自己，解决方案的一部分可能是花更多时间与那些代表你所寻求的改变的人相处。

Years ago, I mocked an intern for thinking his choice of neighbors would influence his career. If he’s reading this, I’d like to offer my apology. I can easily see that where you live might influence the energy you put into your career. Living near optimistic winners is sure to rub off to some extent. And I advise you to consider this fact a primary tool for programming your moist robot self. The programming interface is your location. To change yourself, part of the solution might involve spending more time with the people who represent the change you seek.

例如，你会发现在别人锻炼的环境中锻炼起来更容易。当你看着别人锻炼时，你会激活自己大脑中的锻炼子程序。同样，当其他人在同一个房间里工作时，通常更容易工作，只要他们不会太烦你。

For example, you’ll find it much easier to exercise in an environment where others are exercising. When you watch others exercise, you activate the exercise subroutine in your own brain. Likewise, it’s often easier to work when others are working in the same room, so long as they don’t bug you too much.

鉴于我们人类本能地会习得他人的习惯和能量，你可以利用这种知识，按照你想要的方式编程你的大脑。只需找到最能代表你理想状态的人，尽可能多地与他们相处，但不要擅自闯入、绑架或跟踪。他们的良好习惯和正能量会感染你。

Given our human impulse to pick up the habits and energy of others, you can use that knowledge to literally program your brain the way you want. Simply find the people who most represent what you would like to become and spend as much time with them as you can without trespassing, kidnapping, or stalking. Their good habits and good energy will rub off on you.

第三十章

Chapter 30

幸福

Happiness

T人生中唯一合理的目标，就是最大限度地提升你一生中所谓的幸福体验。这听起来可能很自私，但其实不然。只有反社会人格者或隐士才能通过极端自私获得幸福。正常人需要善待他人才能享受生活。为了便于讨论，我们假设你并非正常人。

The only reasonable goal in life is to maximize your total lifetime experience of something called happiness. That might sound selfish, but it’s not. Only a sociopath or a hermit can find happiness through extreme selfishness. A normal person needs to treat others well to enjoy life. For the sake of argument, let’s assume you’re normal(ish).

如果你想提升幸福感，就必须理解幸福的本质以及它是如何运作的。你可能认为幸福的科学原理显而易见，但事实并非如此。追求幸福却不了解其背后的机制，就像种植花园却不懂施肥、病虫害防治、浇水和防霜冻的基本知识。把种子种在地里很容易，但要想种出一株美丽的植物，却需要对园艺艺术有更深入的理解。幸福就像园艺一样，看似简单。如果你不相信，看看我花园里的那株番茄苗。我给了它水和阳光。它还需要什么呢？

If you want to boost your happiness, understand what happiness is and how it works. You might think the science of happiness is obvious, but it’s not. Pursuing happiness without understanding the mechanisms behind it is like planting a garden without knowing the basics of fertilization, pest control, watering, and frost. It’s easy to pop a seed in the ground, but it takes a deeper understanding of the gardening arts to grow something wonderful. Happiness, like gardening, only seems simple. If you don’t believe me, look at the tomato plant in my garden. I gave it water and sunlight. What more could it need?

让我们先来定义幸福，并就其成因达成共识。我对幸福的定义是，当你的身体化学反应在你的大脑中产生愉悦感时，你就会感受到这种感觉。这个定义与幸福的科学原理相符。1-6

Let’s start by defining happiness and agreeing on what causes it. My definition of happiness is that it’s a feeling you get when your body chemistry is producing pleasant sensations in your mind. That definition is compatible with the science of happiness.1-6

人们很容易把幸福想象成一种由生活中发生的一切所引发的心理状态。按照这种思维方式，我们很大程度上成了这个冷酷世界的受害者，这个世界有时会奖励我们的努力，有时会无缘无故地惩罚我们。这种无助的世界观会蒙蔽你，让你看不到一个让你更快乐的简单系统。

It’s tempting to imagine happiness as a state of mind caused by whatever is happening in your life. By that way of thinking, we’re largely victims to the cold, cold world that sometimes rewards our good work and sometimes punishes us for no reason. That’s a helpless worldview that can blind you to a simple system for being happier.

近年来，科学已卓有成效地证明，幸福并不像人们想象的那样取决于环境。例如，截肢者通常能恢复到失去肢体之前的幸福水平。7-9 并且，你从自身经历中也知道，有些人似乎无论生活中发生什么都能感到快乐，而另一些人无论多么顺利都无法找到幸福。我们生来就拥有有限的幸福范围，而生活环境只能在这个范围内左右摇摆。

Science has done a good job in recent years of demonstrating that happiness isn’t as dependent on your circumstances as one might think. For example, amputees often return to whatever level of happiness they enjoyed before losing a limb.7-9 And you know from your own experience that some people seem to be happy no matter what is going on in their lives while others can’t find happiness no matter how many things are going right. We’re all born with a limited range of happiness, and the circumstances of life can only jiggle us around within the range.

好消息是，任何体验过幸福的人，或许都能在自身幸福感的上限停留更长时间，而在下限停留更短时间。就我而言，我的幸福感底线介于快乐与不快乐之间，因此，保持在我那狭窄幸福感上限附近至关重要。为了做到这一点，我把自己当成一个湿润的机器人，并根据需要调节身体的化学反应。我也尽力改善自身处境和环境，但我认为这只是解决方案的20%。最重要的部分——80%的幸福——不过是一个化学实验。这样思考会非常有帮助。你无法总是快速修复环境中的任何问题，也无法阻止负面想法涌入你的脑海。但你可以通过改变生活方式，轻松地控制身体的化学反应，这反过来会让你的想法变得积极，同时让你感觉前进道路上的坎坷不那么令人沮丧。

The good news is that anyone who has experienced happiness probably has the capacity to spend more time at the top of their personal range and less time near the bottom. In my case, my baseline is on the fence between happy and unhappy, so staying near the top of my narrow range makes all the difference. To do that, I treat myself like the moist robot I am and manipulate my body chemistry as needed. I also try to improve my situation and circumstances wherever I can, but I see that as 20 percent of the solution. The big part—the 80 percent of happiness—is nothing but a chemistry experiment. And it’s hugely helpful to think of it that way. You can’t always quickly fix whatever is wrong in your environment, and you can’t prevent negative thoughts from drifting into your head. But you can easily control your body chemistry through lifestyle, and that in turn will cause your thoughts to turn positive while making the bumps in your path feel less disruptive.

让我们来谈谈操控身体化学反应的机制。显然，你的医生可以给你开药来改变你的情绪。抗抑郁药生意很大。你也可以通过饮酒或使用娱乐性药物来改变你的化学反应。这些方法的问题在于，它们都伴随着你宁愿避免的风险和副作用。我提倡更自然的方法。

Let’s get to the mechanics of manipulating your body chemistry. Obviously, your doctor can give you a pill to change your mood. Antidepressants are big business. And you can change your chemistry by drinking alcohol or using recreational drugs. The problem with each of those methods is that they come with risks and side effects you’d rather avoid. I advocate a more natural approach.

首先，掌控幸福化学反应的最大诀窍就是能够在你想做的时候做你想做的事。相比之下，更常见的情况是，你或许可以做所有你想做的事，但却常常无法在你想做的时候做到。

For starters, the single biggest trick for manipulating your happiness chemistry is being able to do what you want when you want. Contrast that with the more common situation in which you might be able to do all the things you want, but you can’t often do them when you want.

例如，你可能喜欢吃一顿美味的饭菜。但如果只有在你肚子里塞满了垃圾食品之后才允许你吃美味的食物，那么这顿美味的饭菜就不会让你感到快乐。饥饿时吃一顿平庸的饭菜，比不饿时吃一顿丰盛的饭菜更能让你感到快乐。事情发生的时机可能比事物本身的价值更重要。

For example, you might enjoy eating a delicious meal. But if the only time you were allowed to eat delicious food was right after you already filled your stomach with junk food, the delicious meal would not make you happy. A mediocre meal when you’re starving will contribute more to your happiness than an extraordinary meal when you’re not hungry. The timing of things can be more important than the intrinsic value of the things.

午睡是另一个完美地体现时间重要性的例子。好好睡一觉固然美妙，但如果唯一可用的时间是睡前一小时，那么午睡对你来说就没什么意义了。你需要掌控事情的顺序和时间才能获得快乐。从时间的角度看待幸福很重要，因为时间比资源更容易掌控。想要拥有足够的财富来购买自己的私人岛屿并非易事，但相对而言，找到一份工作时间灵活的工作却更容易。一个拥有灵活时间安排和中等资源的人会比一个什么都有却没有灵活时间安排的富人更幸福。寻找幸福的第一步就是不断努力掌控自己的时间安排。

Napping is another perfect example of the importance of timing. A good nap can be a wonderful thing, but if the only available time to nap is an hour before bedtime, a nap would do you little good. You need to control the order and timing of things to be happy. It’s important to look at happiness in terms of timing because timing is easier to control than resources. It’s hard to become rich enough to buy your own private island, but, relatively speaking, it’s easier to find a job with flexible hours. A person with a flexible schedule and average resources will be happier than a rich person who has everything except a flexible schedule. Step one in your search for happiness is to continually work toward having control of your schedule.

父母们明白我的意思。大多数父母都爱自己的孩子，并庆幸自己拥有他们。与此同时，孩子几乎剥夺了你日程安排中的所有灵活性，尤其是如果你是全职家庭主妇。难怪那些看似拥有一切的父母——漂亮的房子、优秀的孩子、好的朋友——在孩子年幼的时候仍然会感到痛苦。这些父母可能拥有他们想要的一切“东西”，但他们却无法灵活地在他们想要的时候享受自己想要的东西。

Parents understand what I’m talking about. Most parents love their kids and are glad they had them. At the same time, kids remove almost all flexibility from your schedule, especially if you’re the stay-at-home parent. It’s no wonder that parents who seem to have everything—nice house, great kids, good friends—still find themselves in misery during the years their kids are young. Those parents might have all the “stuff” they could ask for, but they have no flexibility to enjoy what they want when they want.

写这一章的时候，我正坐在舒适的椅子上，和我那只值得信赖的狗狗士力架一起，一边享用着一杯热咖啡。我刚刚锻炼完，感觉很放松，有心情写作。无论从哪个角度来看，我所做的都是工作，但因为我可以掌控这一天的时间，所以感觉不像工作。我把工作变成了乐趣，仅仅是因为我可以掌控工作的时间。

As I write this chapter, I’m sitting in a comfortable chair with my trusty dog, Snickers, while enjoying a warm cup of coffee. I just came from a good workout, so I’m feeling relaxed and in the mood to write. By any definition, what I’m doing is work, but because I can control the timing of it on this particular day, it doesn’t feel like work. I transformed work into pleasure simply by having control over when I do it.

在你的个人生活和职业生涯中，做任何重大决定时，都要考虑时间安排的灵活性。现实地说，有时你确实需要忍受，长时间工作，照顾孩子，并履行你的职责。记住，要留意如何长期最大限度地提高你的时间安排自由。这是你想要努力实现的目标。并非所有读过这本书的人都会成为在家工作的漫画家，但你肯定能找到一个重视你的工作效率而不是出勤率的老板。

In your personal life and your career, consider schedule flexibility when making any big decision. Realistically, sometimes you do need to suck it up, work long hours, watch the kids, and do your duty. Just remember to keep your eye out for ways to maximize your schedule freedom in the long term. It’s something you want to work toward. Not everyone reading this book will become work-from-home cartoonists, but you can certainly find a boss who values your productivity over your attendance.

这让我想到了幸福的下一个重要机制。幸福更多地取决于你前进的方向，而不是你现在所处的位置。一个身价20亿美元的人，如果因为方向错误而突然损失10亿美元，即使这种变化对他购买所需物品的能力没有影响，也会感到难过。但一个流浪汉会庆祝在一家高档餐厅后面发现一个新的垃圾箱，因为这意味着接下来会有丰盛的美食。当事情朝着正确的方向发展时，我们往往会感到快乐，而当事情朝着糟糕的方向发展时，我们则会感到不快乐。

That brings me to the next important mechanism for happiness. Happiness has more to do with where you’re heading than where you are. A person who is worth $2 billion will feel sad if he suddenly loses $1 billion because he’s moving in the wrong direction, even if the change has no impact on his ability to buy what he wants. But a street person will celebrate discovering a new dumpster behind an upscale restaurant because it means good eating ahead. We tend to feel happy when things are moving in the right direction and unhappy when things are trending bad.

幸福感的方向性，使得拥有一项每年都留有足够进步空间的运动或爱好成为明智之举。网球和高尔夫就是两个完美的例子。无论是哪一项运动，普通运动员都能在六十岁之后继续进步。任何运动，缓慢而稳定的进步都会让你感觉自己走在正确的轨道上。进步的感觉会刺激你的身体产生让你感到快乐的化学物质。

The directional nature of happiness is one reason it’s a good idea to have a sport or hobby that leaves you plenty of room to improve every year. Tennis and golf are two perfect examples. With either sport, an average player can continue improving well past the age of sixty. Slow and steady improvement at anything makes you feel as if you are on the right track. The feeling of progress stimulates your body to create the chemicals that make you feel happy.

选择职业时，要考虑它会让你的技能持续提升、停滞不前或持续下降。作为一名漫画家，我的绘画技巧在职业生涯的大部分时间里都在缓慢提升，这对我来说是一种快乐的源泉。如果你足够幸运，拥有众多职业选择，但只有一种职业能够让你持续进步，那么在其他条件相同的情况下，选择它吧。

When you choose a career, consider whether it will lead to a lifetime of ever-improved performance, a plateau, or a steady decline in your skills. As a cartoonist, my drawing skills have slowly improved over most of my career, and that is a source of happiness for me. If you are lucky enough to have career options but only one of them affords a path of continuous improvement, choose that one, all else being equal.

你需要掌握的下一个幸福要素是想象力。我之前在提升能量的背景下写过这个话题，能量与幸福密切相关，但在本章中值得再次强调。悲观主义通常是想象力的缺失。如果你能想象未来更加光明，这些想法就会提升你的能量，刺激你体内的化学反应，产生幸福感。如果你连更美好的未来都无法想象，你就不会快乐——无论你现在的生活多么美好。

The next element of happiness you need to master is imagination. I wrote about this in the context of raising your energy, which is closely related to happiness, but it bears repeating in this chapter. Pessimism is often a failure of imagination. If you can imagine the future being brighter, those thoughts lift your energy and goose the chemistry in your body to produce a sensation of happiness. If you can’t even imagine an improved future, you won’t be happy—no matter how well your life is going right now.

我发现幻想未来会比现在更好，甚至比现在好得多是很有用的。我喜欢想象一个精彩绝伦、令人叹为观止的未来。这些幻想不必准确预测未来。仅仅想象一个更美好的未来就能改变你的大脑化学反应，让你感受到当下的幸福。快乐能提升你的能量水平，让你更容易迈向现实世界的幸福。这又是一个想象力影响现实世界的例子。不要让现实控制你的想象力。让你的想象力成为你选择自己现实的用户界面。

I find it useful to daydream that the future will be better than today and by far. I like to imagine a future that is spectacular and breathtaking. The daydreams need not be accurate in terms of predicting the future. Simply imagining a better future hacks your brain chemistry and provides you with the sensation of happiness today. Being happy raises your energy level and makes it easier to take steps toward real-world happiness. This is another case in which your imagination can influence the real world. Don’t let reality control your imagination. Let your imagination be the user interface to choose your own reality.

关于幸福，还有一点需要记住：它并非心灵的奥秘，也不是魔法。对大多数人来说，只要身体健康、时间安排灵活、对未来充满期待，幸福就是自然状态。

The next important thing to remember about happiness is that it’s not a mystery of the mind, nor is it magic. Happiness is the natural state for most people whenever they feel healthy, have flexible schedules, and expect the future to be good.

当我写下一段文字时，已经过去了几天，现在我正坐在健身俱乐部的桌旁。我锻炼了身体，吃了健康的奖励零食，现在我非常开心，尽管我正在重写和修改这一章。照顾好自己的身体总是比我从事的任何工作都更能影响我的幸福感。这一点很重要，因为通常当你感到不开心时，你会把自己的情绪归咎于环境的影响。责怪环境很容易，因为你知道你几乎可以把任何事情解读成坏消息或潜在的坏消息。只要在任何观察中加入悲观和愤世嫉俗的情绪，你就能凭空捏造出坏消息。如果你认识任何经常把好消息解读成坏消息的人，你就知道这是多么容易。我想告诉你，你坏情绪的罪魁祸首是缺乏五大因素之一：弹性作息时间、想象力、睡眠、饮食或运动。

As I write this next paragraph, a few days have passed, and now I’m sitting at a table in my health club. I exercised, I had my healthy reward snack, and now I’m thoroughly happy even though I’m working at rewriting and tweaking this chapter. Taking care of my body always influences my happiness more than whatever task I’m involved in. That’s an important point because normally when you feel unhappy, you blame your mood on whatever your environment is serving up to you. It’s easy to blame your environment because you know you can interpret almost anything as bad news or potential bad news. Just add pessimism and cynicism to any observation, and you can manufacture bad news out of thin air. If you know anyone who routinely interprets good news as bad, you know how easily it can be done. I’m here to tell you that the primary culprit in your bad moods is a deficit in one of the big five: flexible schedule, imagination, sleep, diet, or exercise.

我曾向很多人解释过我的观察：运动、饮食和睡眠会影响情绪。通常的反应是面无表情，然后转移话题。没有人愿意相信幸福的秘诀就这么简单：做做白日梦、控制日程、小憩、合理饮食，每天保持活跃。你会觉得自己像个傻瓜，竟然经历了那么多不开心的日子，却不知道治愈方法如此简单。根据我的经验，你可能会接受这样一种观点：日常生活方式的选择或许只是导致你情绪低落的一小部分原因。但你可能认为，你的大部分暴躁情绪都是由你生活中的那些傻瓜和反社会人格者，以及你某一天莫名其妙的霉运造成的。根据我一生的观察，我估计，你80%的情绪取决于你的身体感受，只有20%取决于你的基因和环境，尤其是你的健康状况。

I’ve explained to a number of people my observation that exercise, diet, and sleep influence mood. The usual reaction is a blank expression followed by a change of topic. No one wants to believe that the formula for happiness is as simple as daydreaming, controlling your schedule, napping, eating right, and being active every day. You’d feel like an idiot for suffering so many unhappy days while not knowing the cure was so accessible. I know from experience that you might accept the idea that daily lifestyle choices are perhaps a small part of what causes your bad moods. But you probably think most of your crabbiness is caused by the idiots and sociopaths in your life, plus your inexplicable bad luck on any given day. Based on a lifetime of observation, my best estimate is that 80 percent of your mood is based on how your body feels, and only 20 percent is based on your genes and your circumstances, particularly your health.

问问自己这个问题：当你早上锻炼身体、吃得好、补充水分、睡眠充足时，你心情好的比例是多少？我敢打赌你不知道这个问题的答案，因为这不是人们会关注的事情。但现在我把这个想法灌输到你脑子里，你自然会注意到日常身体保养和你那并不神秘的幸福感之间的联系。我估计你会发现，你的好心情与运动、饮食和睡眠高度相关。

Ask yourself this question: At times when you’ve exercised earlier in the day, eaten well, hydrated, and had enough sleep, what percentage of those times would you find yourself in a good mood? I’ll bet you don’t know the answer to that question because it’s not the sort of thing anyone pays attention to. But now that I’ve put the idea in your head, you’ll automatically find yourself noticing the link between daily body maintenance and your not-so-mysterious happiness. I predict you’ll observe that your good moods are highly correlated with exercise, diet, and sleep.

运动有两个截然不同的好处，很难区分开来。运动本身会释放天然的止痛物质——内啡肽，这会让你直接感受到幸福感。10-15但运动也能让你从穿上运动鞋之前的压力中解脱出来，从而获得精神上的放松。这就是为什么我推荐一些既能锻炼肌肉，又能让你大脑活跃起来的运动形式。

Exercise has two very different benefits that are hard to untangle. The exercise itself releases natural pain-relieving substances, endorphins, and that gives you a direct feeling of well-being.10-15 But exercise is also a mental escape from whatever was stressing you before you laced your athletic shoes. That’s why I recommend forms of exercises that occupy your mind at the same time as your muscles.

运动还能改善睡眠，所以这是一举两得。16在影响幸福的五大因素——灵活的时间安排、想象力、饮食、运动和睡眠——中，我认为最重要的是运动。如果运动听起来很费劲，那就等着看我关于如何最轻松地变得活跃起来的章节吧。

Exercise also helps you sleep better, so that’s a double benefit.16 Of the big five factors in happiness—flexible schedule, imagination, diet, exercise, and sleep—my pick for the most important is exercise. If exercise sounds like a lot of work, wait for my chapter on the easiest way to become active.

如果幸福的五大要素看起来不完整，那是故意的。我知道你可能还想要性、灵魂伴侣、名望、认可、被重视的感觉、事业成功等等。我的观点是，你对幸福的这五个要素会像磁铁一样吸引你所需的其他幸福要素。当你身体健康、快乐、精力充沛时，人们更有可能和你发生性关系、成为你的朋友并雇佣你，有时所有这些事情都会在同一天发生。

If the five elements for happiness seem incomplete, that’s intentional. I know you might also want sex, a soul mate, fame, recognition, a feeling of importance, career success, and lots more. My contention is that your five-pronged pursuit of happiness will act as a magnet for the other components of happiness you need. When you’re fit, happy, and full of energy, people are far more likely to have sex with you, be your friend, and hire you, sometimes all in the same day.

如果你肥胖、疲惫、性欲旺盛、又不快乐，那么你最好的长期解决方案可能不是 Match.com。我支持在线约会服务，因为有证据表明它们有效。但更明智的做法是先照顾好自己，然后利用成功的契机来获得你所需的一切。

If you’re chubby, tired, horny, and unhappy, then your best long-term solution probably isn’t Match.com. I’m a proponent of online dating services because the evidence shows they work. But a smarter approach is to take care of yourself first and use that success as leverage to get everything else you need.

最后，我想讲讲我漫画生涯巅峰时期的感受。那是九十年代末，我刚刚收到人生中最大的一笔钱，这主要归功于我签下的多本书的出版合同。我得到了儿时梦寐以求的工作，正式发了财，名声也如我所愿。然而，我突然感到一阵深深的悲伤。这到底是怎么回事？

I’ll cap this discussion by telling you the story of how I felt when my cartooning career reached its high point. It was the late nineties, and I had just deposited the biggest check of my life, thanks largely to a multi-book publishing deal. I had the precise job I had wanted since childhood. I was officially rich. I was as famous as I wanted to be. And I was suddenly and profoundly sad. What the hell was going on?

经过一番自我反省，我意识到自己感觉飘忽不定。我不再拥有人生的主要目标，因为我已经实现了它。这种感觉怪异、不真实、令人不安。当时我还没有孩子，所以没有理由再去追求任何目标。我的幸福感远远低于基准线，而且没有反弹。

After some self-reflection, I realized that I was feeling adrift. I no longer had a primary purpose in life because I already achieved it. It was an eerie feeling, unreal and unsettling. I had no kids at the time, so I had no reason to achieve anything more. I dipped well below my baseline happiness, and I wasn’t rebounding.

我摆脱低落情绪的方法是意识到我新获得的资源可以帮助我以一些微小但积极的方式改变世界。这就是我创建“迪尔贝里托”（Dilberito）的动机，我希望它能让饮食更加便捷，甚至可能引领一股潮流。从长远来看，“迪尔贝里托”并没有成功。但它百分之百地成功地给了我一个有意义的目标，让我重新找回了乐观和活力。

The way I climbed out of my funk was by realizing that my newly acquired resources could help me change the world in some small but positive ways. That was the motivation for creating the Dilberito, which I hoped would make nutrition convenient and perhaps contribute to a trend. In the long run, the Dilberito didn’t work out. But it was 100 percent successful in giving me a meaningful purpose, which allowed my optimism and energy to return.

过度成功带来的不快乐是高级问题。这种不快乐是人们毕生努力追求的。如果你发现自己处于这种境地——我希望你如此——你会发现你的注意力自然而然地转向外部世界。你会通过服务他人来寻求快乐。我保证那种感觉一定很棒。

Unhappiness caused by too much success is a high-class problem. That’s the sort of unhappiness people work all their lives to get. If you find yourself there—and I hope you do—you’ll find your attentions naturally turning outward. You’ll seek happiness through service to others. I promise it will feel wonderful.

常规

Routine

《幸福悖论》的作者巴里·施瓦茨告诉我们，如果生活中有太多选择，人们就会变得不快乐。选择的问题在于，选择任何一条路都会让你陷入自我怀疑。你会很理性地认为，其中一条你没选的路可能会更好。这可能会让你感到沮丧。

Barry Schwartz, author of The Paradox of Happiness, tells us that people become unhappy if they have too many options in life. The problem with options is that choosing any path can plague you with self-doubt. You quite rationally think that one of the paths not chosen might have worked out better. That can eat at you.

在众多诱人的方案中做出选择也会让人精疲力尽。你希望感觉自己已经研究并考虑了所有选项。这就是为什么我能在规律的生活中感到无比安心。如果你今天问我，2033年星期六早上6:20我会在哪里，我会告诉你，我会坐在办公桌前准备我的每日直播。这就是我上周六那个时候正在做的事情，也是我计划在本周六做的事情。我已经记不清上次醒来后查看选项，决定先做什么是什么时候了。这总是一样，至少在我一天的最初几个小时里是如此。

Choosing among attractive alternatives can also be exhausting. You want to feel as if you researched and considered all your options. That’s why I find great comfort in routine. If you ask me today where I will be at 6:20 AM on Saturday morning in the year 2033, I’ll tell you I will be at my desk preparing for my daily live stream. That’s what I was doing last Saturday at that time and what I plan to do this Saturday as well. I can’t recall the last time I woke up and looked at my options for what to do first. It’s always the same, at least for the first few hours of my day.

同样，我总是在早上5:10左右喝第一口咖啡，然后吃一根蛋白棒，这样直到下午晚些时候我才会再次感到饥饿。我早上从来不会浪费一个脑细胞去思考什么时候该做什么。相比之下，你认识的有些人，他们每完成一个小时的任务，都要花两个小时去计划和决定。我比这些人快乐得多。

Likewise, I always have my first sip of coffee at about 5:10 AM, and a protein bar to keep me from getting hungry again until late afternoon. I never waste a brain cell in the morning trying to figure out what to do when. Compare that to some people you know who spend two hours planning and deciding for every task that takes one hour to complete. I’m happier than those people.

回顾幸福公式：

Recapping the happiness formula:

吃得正确。

Eat right.

锻炼。

Exercise.

睡个好觉。

Get enough sleep.

想象一个不可思议的未来（即使你不相信）。

Imagine an incredible future (even if you don’t believe it).

制定灵活的时间安排。

Work toward a flexible schedule.

做一些你可以稳步提高的事情。

Do things you can steadily improve at.

帮助别人（如果你已经帮助过自己）。

Help others (if you’ve already helped yourself).

将日常决策简化为例行事务。

Reduce daily decisions to routine.

如果你做到了这八件事，那么你大脑中激发幸福化学反应所需的其他物质就会更容易找到。事实上，如果你让自己成为一个有吸引力的目标，你所追求的幸福的其他要素——比如职业机会、爱情和朋友——或许就能找到你。

If you do those eight things, the rest of what you need to stimulate the chemistry of happiness in your brain will be a lot easier to find. In fact, the other components of happiness that you seek—such as career opportunities, love, and friends—might find their way to you if you make yourself an attractive target.

第31章

Chapter 31

健康

Health

T现在是时候提醒你了，本书中的任何内容都不应被视为建议。听取漫画家的建议永远不是一个好主意，如果主题与健康有关，这一点就更加重要了。我不知道有多少人因为听从漫画家的健康建议而死亡，但这个数字可能不为零。

This is a good time to remind you that nothing in this book should be seen as advice. It’s never a good idea to take advice from cartoonists, and that’s a hundred times more important if the topic is health-related. I don’t know how many people have died from following the health advice of cartoonists, but the number probably isn’t zero.

所以，不要把本章或我写的任何其他内容当作建议。在接下来的几页中，我会参考一些关于饮食的有趣且实用的研究。我也会分享我自己的经历。这将解决你“胡扯过滤器”的两个维度——科学研究和一位聪明朋友的经历——但为了安全起见，在接受本书中的任何观点之前，请先咨询你的医生。

So don’t view this chapter or anything else I write as advice. In the coming pages, I’ll make reference to some interesting and useful studies about diet. And I’ll describe my own experiences. That will address two dimensions of your bullshit filter—scientific studies and the experience of a smart friend—but just to be on the safe side, talk to your doctor before embracing any ideas in this book.

如果说我在饮食方面有什么价值的话，那就是简化。对我而言，最有效的简单饮食计划是：想吃多少就吃多少，想吃什么就吃什么，想什么时候吃就什么时候吃。我的体重是155磅（约75公斤），感觉从未如此健康。我的健康体重并非遗传。过去几年，我的体重最高曾达到168磅（约84公斤），这在我5英尺8英寸（约175厘米）的身高上显得有些臃肿。

My value on the topic of diet, if any, is in simplification. The simple diet plan that works for me is this: I eat as much as I want, of anything I want, whenever I want. I weigh a trim 155 pounds and have never felt better. My healthy weight is not a genetic gift. In years past, I have weighed as much as 168 pounds, which looks portly on my 5’8” frame.

显然，我的这个看似简单却难以置信的饮食计划里有一些小技巧。这些技巧很简单，但需要解释一下。我们先从“想吃什么就吃什么”说起。这个技巧就是改变你的饮食习惯。是的，这是可能的，而且可能比你想象的要容易。一旦你为了享受而选择合适的食物，并且不再渴望不合适的食物，其他一切都会水到渠成。

Obviously, there are some tricks involved with my too-easy-to-be-true diet plan. The tricks are simple, but they will take some explaining. Let’s start with the part about eating “anything I want.” The trick there is to change what you want. Yes, that’s possible, and it’s probably easier than you imagine. Once you want to eat the right kinds of food for enjoyment, and you don’t crave the wrong kind of food, everything else comes somewhat easily.

你可能需要一些说服力才能相信人们可以改变自己的饮食偏好。但想想饥饿和饱腹时食物的味道有多么不同。同样的食物，但你的享受程度却截然不同。我吃过的最好的一顿饭是在牙科手术一周后，因为我已经好几天没吃固体食物了。一盘普通的天使细面尝起来就像是神灵送来的，并精心匹配了我的DNA。一个月后，同样的一顿饭就变得索然无味了。

You probably need some convincing that people can reprogram their food preferences. But consider how differently food tastes when you are famished versus when you have a full stomach. It’s the same food, but your enjoyment level is radically different. The best meal I’ve ever tasted was a week after dental surgery because I hadn’t had solid food for days. An ordinary dish of angel hair pasta tasted as if it had been delivered by a deity and carefully paired to my DNA. A month later, the same meal was boring.

我相信你肯定有过类似的经历：当你饿的时候，平淡无味甚至糟糕的食物也会变得美味。你的味觉偏好更像是大脑发出的暗示，而非硬核神经的产物。

I’m sure you’ve had similar experiences in which bland or even bad food tastes great when you’re hungry. Your taste preferences are more like a suggestion from your brain than a result of hard-wiring.

你也注意到，随着年龄的增长，你的食物口味也在变化。小时候只能忍受通心粉和奶酪，长大后却对寿司欲罢不能。我想你也经历过这样的经历：吃了某种食物后不久就生病了，后来却发现这种巧合彻底改变了你对这种食物的偏好。

You have also observed that your tastes in food evolve as you age. A kid who can tolerate nothing but mac and cheese matures into an adult who can’t get enough sushi. And I imagine you’ve had the experience of getting sick soon after eating a specific type of food and finding that the coincidental association completely alters your preference for the food later.

你或许还会发现，一些你原本觉得难吃的食物，如果按照自己的喜好烹制和调味，其实也能变得美味。烹饪技巧也必须纳入你的口味偏好中。

You also might have discovered that some foods you thought were awful-tasting can be delightful if prepared and seasoned to your liking. Technique must be factored into your taste preferences as well.

你的饮食偏好终其一生都在变化，但你可能从未真正努力去改变自己的偏好。我会分享一些技巧来帮助你改变。如果这些技巧奏效，你也可以“想吃什么就吃什么”，因为最终你只会吃对你有益的食物。

Your food preferences change continuously throughout your life, but you probably never put much effort into deliberately changing your preferences. I’ll describe some tricks for doing just that. If the tricks work, you, too, can eat “whatever you want” because eventually you’ll only want food that is good for you.

我以前特别想吃冰淇淋。有段时间，我一天能吃掉两大碗香草冰淇淋。那时候，西兰花似乎是狱卒强迫囚犯吃的惩罚性食物。渐渐地，我训练自己克服这种渴望。现在，冰淇淋很容易抗拒，但我却无法忍受两天不吃西兰花。这种渴望的转变，源于我刻意改变自己偏好的努力。我开始像破解电脑一样破解我的大脑，重新连接渴望的电路。

I used to crave ice cream in a big way. At one point in my life, I consumed up to two heaping bowls of vanilla bean ice cream per day. During those years, broccoli seemed like the sort of thing that jailers forced prisoners to eat as punishment. Over time, I trained myself to reverse my cravings. Now ice cream is easy to resist, but I’m not comfortable going two days without a hit of broccoli. This transformation in cravings was the result of a deliberate effort to change my preferences. I set out to hack my brain like a computer and rewire the cravings circuitry.

如果不再渴望自己喜欢的食物听起来像是一种牺牲，其实不然。这是一种错觉，因为几乎不可能想象自己会失去任何一种渴望。渴望感觉就像直接从我们的内心深处生长出来，感觉就像是我们身体的一部分。我的经验是，渴望是可以控制的。我已经成功地消除了对各种不太健康食物的渴望。我一次只消除一种，这比你想象的要容易得多。

If the thought of no longer craving your favorite food sounds like a sacrifice, it isn’t. That’s an illusion caused by the fact that it’s nearly impossible to imagine losing a craving of any kind. Cravings feel like they grow directly from our core. They feel a part of us. My experience is that cravings can be manipulated. I’ve successfully erased cravings for a wide variety of less-healthy foods. I do them one at a time, and it’s a lot easier than you might think.

反过来也一样；我可以激发我对健康食品的渴望，而我以前根本没这种渴望。这个技巧也有局限性，因为你可能无法忍受真正难吃的味道。但大多数健康食品与其说是“有害”，不如说是“平淡无味”。

It also works the other way; I can instill cravings for healthy foods where I previously had no such desires. There’s a limit to this trick in the sense that you probably can’t get past a truly nasty taste. But most healthy food is closer to bland than obnoxious.

在大多数正常饮食者眼中，健康食品的名声并不好，因为我们总是把健康食品与同类食物中味道最差、口感最差的联系起来。如果健康食品让你联想到豆腐、年糕或任何尝起来像肥皂的东西，你可能不太想对健康饮食产生渴望。想想美味的咸坚果、黄油玉米棒或香蕉，你就更接近健康食品的本质了。（我稍后会讨论食用盐和黄油的利弊。）

Healthy food has a bad reputation with most normal eaters because we associate healthy food with the worst tastes and textures in the category. If healthy food makes you think of tofu, rice cakes, or anything that tastes like soap, you’re probably not too keen on developing a craving for healthy eating. Think instead of delicious, salted nuts, a buttery ear of corn, or a banana, and you’re closer to the mark. (I’ll talk later about the tradeoffs of consuming salt and butter.)

改变你的饮食偏好是一个简单的过程，它和所有改变一样，始于不同的视角。我的工作就是做最难的部分，并向你展示如何以不同的方式看待我们熟悉的饮食话题。你的部分也会自然而然地发生，因为你的思维过程会沿着可预测、可控的因果关系路径轻轻地引导你的行为。

Changing your food preferences is a straightforward process, and it starts the way all change starts: by looking at things differently. It’s my job to do the hard part and show you a different way to look at the familiar topic of diet. Your part will happen naturally as your own thought process gently nudges your behavior along a predictable and controlled pathway of cause and effect.

我的经历听起来可能有点奇怪，但我可以改变自己的饮食偏好，只要把自己的身体想象成一个可编程的机器人，而不是一个充满魔力的肉体袋子。这种细微的视角转变，其威力远超乎想象。大多数人认为，吃什么和感觉之间并没有很强的联系。我把这种看法称为“肉体魔袋”的世界观。当你把自己想象成一个充满魔力的肉体袋子时，你要么会认为吃什么和感觉之间没有直接联系，要么会认为饮食确实有影响，但这种影响是无法预测的，因为生活很复杂，有太多因素在起作用。

My experience, as odd as it sounds, is that I can change my food preferences by thinking of my body as a programmable robot as opposed to a fleshy bag full of magic. This minor change in perspective is more powerful than it seems. Most people believe there is no strong connection between what they eat and how they feel. I call that perception the Fleshy Bag of Magic worldview. When you think of yourself as a fleshy bag of magic, you assume there is either no direct connection between what you eat and how you feel, or you think your diet has some impact, but it’s unpredictable because life is complicated and there are too many factors in play.

大多数成年人都了解饮食选择的基本因果关系。他们知道暴饮暴食会腹胀，豆类食物会胀气，辛辣食物会流鼻涕。这些因果关系显而易见，很难被忽视。但你有没有追踪过自己的情绪、解决问题能力和能量水平与最近吃的食物之间的关系？对大多数人来说，答案是否定的。你可能认为你的情绪是由生活中发生的事情引起的，而不是你午餐吃的淀粉类食物。

Most adults understand the basic cause-and-effect of their diet choices. They know that overeating makes them feel bloated, beans make them gassy, and spicy food might make their noses run. Those causes and effects are so obvious that they’re hard to miss. But have you ever tracked your mood, problem-solving ability, and energy level in relation to what you recently ate? For most people, the answer is no. You probably think your mood is caused by what’s happening in your life, not the starchy food you ate for lunch.

如果你从远处审视自己的生活，你会发现今天和昨天没什么两样，明天也不会有太大不同。我们的生活大致保持不变，但情绪却可能剧烈波动。我的观点是，决定你的能量水平，进而影响你情绪的主要因素之一是你最近吃了什么，这一点请你保持怀疑态度。¶¶

If you look at your life from some distance, you can see that today is a lot like yesterday Tomorrow won’t be that different either. Our lives stay roughly the same while our moods can swing wildly. My proposition, which I invite you to be skeptical about, is that one of the primary factors in determining your energy level and therefore your mood is what you’ve eaten recently.¶¶

寻找模式

Look for the Pattern

别轻信我的话。“食物就是情绪”的假说可能不符合你的常识。这种事需要你亲身体验。你天生就相信，你的情绪是由你最近生活中发生的好坏事以及你的基因构成决定的。我的观察，有科学依据，是饮食合理的人不会被生活中的小坎坷所困扰。他们也会更加乐观。

Don’t take my word for it. The food is mood hypothesis probably doesn’t pass your common sense filter. It’s the sort of thing you need to experience for yourself. You’re wired to believe that your mood is determined by whatever good or bad events have happened in your life recently plus your genetic makeup. My observation, backed by the science, is that the person who eats right won’t be bothered as much by the little bumps in life’s road. They will have greater optimism, too.

当厄运来临时，你的反应取决于运气的糟糕程度以及身体对压力的准备程度。你无法阻止所有厄运降临，但你可以强化自己，让小事也能迎刃而解。你的情绪是由体内的化学反应决定的，而食物对你体内化学反应的影响可能远大于你周围发生的事情，至少在平常的一天里是如此。

When bad luck comes around, your reaction to it is a combination of how bad the luck is plus how prepared your body is for the stress. You can’t prevent all bad luck from finding you, but you can fortify yourself to the point where the smaller stuff bounces off. Your mood is a function of chemistry in your body, and food may be a far more dominant contribution to your chemistry than what is happening around you, at least during a normal day.

还记得第一次有人告诉你，揉肚子和拍头很难吗？你可能不信，除非你亲身尝试。有些知识只有通过经验才能获得。饮食与情绪的关系就是其中一类必须亲身体验的知识。如果你一生中从未注意到某些食物会让你昏昏欲睡，甚至可能让你暴躁易怒，那么无论我在书里告诉你什么，都无法让你相信食物是情绪的主要决定因素。你唯一能相信食物影响情绪的方法就是在日常生活中亲身体验。我的意思是，简单地问问自己，在某个特定时刻你的感受，然后在心里记下你最近吃了什么。寻找其中的规律。

Remember the first time someone told you it would be hard to rub your stomach and pat your head at the same time? You probably didn’t believe it until you tried it yourself. Some types of knowledge can only be acquired by experience. The diet connection to mood is one of those categories of knowledge that must be experienced. Nothing I can tell you in a book will convince you that food is the dominant determinant of mood if you’ve lived your entire life without noticing that some types of food make you sleepy and probably cranky as a result. The only way you’ll believe that food drives your mood is by testing it in your daily life. By that I mean simply asking yourself how you feel at any given moment and then making a mental note of what you ate recently. Look for the pattern.

你可能会想，如果食物能控制情绪，为什么你之前还没注意到呢？最大的原因是，你可能吃的食物是由多种不同食材混合而成的。你很少会为了感受一下某种食物的滋味而单独挑一种来吃。你可能认为，大餐后感到困倦仅仅是因为你吃得太多，身体把能量从大脑和肌肉转移到了消化系统。你认为自己下午困倦，是因为有人告诉你午餐就是这样。你不是那种会单独挑出一种食物进行严格分析的科学家。饿的时候你会吃，累的时候你会想睡觉。饮食的深层真相被巧妙地隐藏了起来。

You might wonder why, if food controls mood, you haven’t noticed it already. The biggest reason is that you probably eat meals that are a combination of lots of different ingredients. You rarely isolate one kind of food just to see how it feels. You probably believe the reason you’re sleepy after a big meal is simply because you ate a lot and so your body is diverting its energy from your brain and muscles to your digestive system. You think you’re sleepy in the afternoon because someone told you that’s what lunch does to people. You’re not a scientist who isolates one kind of food and does rigorous analysis. You eat when you’re hungry and try to sleep when you’re tired. The deeper truths about diet do a good job of hiding.

检验“食物决定情绪”假说的最佳方法是去一家墨西哥餐厅——那里简直就是碳水化合物的天堂——享用一顿丰盛的午餐，并监测几个小时后你的感觉。下午2点左右检查你的能量水平。你觉得你更想运动还是小睡一会儿？我提前告诉你答案：你肯定不想小睡一会儿。

The best way to test the food-is-mood hypothesis is to enjoy a hearty lunch at a Mexican restaurant—a virtual paradise of carbs—and monitor how you feel in a few hours. Check your energy level at about 2:00 PM. Do you feel as if you would prefer exercising or napping? I’ll tell you the answer in advance: You’ll want the nap.

你觉得你下午的困倦可能只是时间的简单函数吗？这很容易验证。等几天，用早餐代替午餐，做同样的实验。点煎饼和薯饼。看看你能不能保持清醒到午餐时间。这可不容易。这个实验会告诉你，时间是否比你吃什么更重要。

Do you think your sleepiness in the afternoon might be a simple function of the time of day? That’s easy to test. Wait a few days and try the same experiment with breakfast instead of lunch. Order pancakes and hashbrown potatoes. See if you can stay awake until lunchtime. It won’t be easy. That experiment will tell you whether the time of day is more important than what you eat.

如果你觉得饭菜的“油腻”或份量是导致你困倦的原因，不妨改天再试试墨西哥菜，但只吃一半的量。你会发现，份量并没有你想象的那么重要。

If you’re thinking the “heaviness” of the meal or the quantity is the cause of your sleepiness, try your Mexican food experiment again another day but only eat half as much. You’ll discover that quantity doesn’t matter as much as you thought.

为了比较，你可以尝试几天不吃面包、土豆、白米饭和其他简单的碳水化合物。吃蔬菜、坚果、沙拉、鱼或鸡肉。然后看看吃完几小时后你的感觉如何。我敢打赌，吃完这些食物后，运动的想法会比你尝试墨西哥食物那天更有吸引力。

For the sake of comparison, experiment for a few days by skipping bread, potatoes, white rice, and other simple carbs. Eat veggies, nuts, salad, fish, or chicken. Now see how you feel a few hours after eating. I’ll bet the idea of exercising sounds more appealing after eating those types of foods compared to the day of your Mexican food experiment.

关于饮食，别轻信我的任何说法。人与人不同，而且我们似乎每周都能学到一些新的营养知识。你也应该对饮食研究保持合理的怀疑态度，因为它们在区分相关性和因果关系方面出了名的糟糕。吃鱼子酱的人可能活得更长，但维持他们生命的并非鱼子酱；收入和预期寿命之间存在已知的相关性。饮食研究很难令人信服，因为其中有很多相互矛盾的研究，而且它们通常研究的是特定人群，而不是普通人。

Don’t take my word for anything on the topic of diet. People are different, and it seems we learn something new about nutrition every week. You should also have a healthy skepticism about diet studies because they’re notoriously bad at sorting out correlation from causation. People who eat caviar probably live longer, but it’s not the caviar keeping them alive; there’s a known correlation between income and life expectancy. Diet studies are hard to trust because there are so many contradictory ones, and often they look at specific populations, not the average person.

只要切实可行且安全，就把你的身体当作一个实验室，用来测试不同的健康方法。吃一些特定食物，比如一碗白米饭，然后看看之后的感觉。或者吃大量的碳水化合物，然后在周末称一下体重。寻找规律。哪些食物能让你精力充沛，哪些食物会让你昏昏欲睡？哪些食物吃起来不会发胖，哪些食物会让你像梅西百货游行气球一样膨胀？当你掌握了自己的饮食因果模式后，你可能会发现它们与我的经历不同。例如，你可能对小麦或麸质过敏，或者有乳糖不耐症，又或者无论吃什么，你下午都不会感到疲倦。找到适合自己的饮食方式很重要。而这需要不断尝试。

Whenever it’s practical and safe, consider your body a laboratory in which you can test different approaches to health. Eat something specific, such as a bowl of white rice, and see how you feel later. Or eat lots of carbs and weigh yourself at the end of the week. Look for the patterns. Which foods make you energetic, and which make you sleepy? Which ones can you eat without gaining weight, and which ones make you expand like a Macy’s parade balloon? When you get a handle on your own diet cause-and-effect patterns, you might discover they differ from my experience. For example, you might have wheat or gluten sensitivity or a lactose intolerance, or maybe you never get tired in the afternoon no matter what you eat. It’s important to figure out what works for you. And that will require experimenting.

就我而言，吃简单的碳水化合物会彻底消耗我的能量，以至于吃完几个小时后，我闭上眼睛三十秒内就能睡着。我喝太多咖啡的晚上，真的会把白米饭当安眠药吃。但你的身体对咖啡和白米饭的反应可能不同，或者没那么剧烈。你需要亲身体验才能确定。记住，控制你能量的是化学反应，而不是魔法。

In my case, eating simple carbs depletes my energy so thoroughly that a few hours after consuming them I can fall asleep within thirty seconds of closing my eyes. I literally use white rice like a sleeping pill on evenings I’ve had too much coffee. But your body might respond differently or less dramatically to both coffee and white rice. You need to experiment to know for sure. Just remember that it is chemistry, not magic, controlling your energy.

我特意没有把意大利面列入要避免的简单碳水化合物清单中。根据我的经验，意大利面不会像其他简单碳水化合物那样让我昏昏欲睡、烦躁不安。我最初发现意大利面对情绪无影响，是因为多年来我大量食用意大利面，并留意过后的感觉。土豆会让我直接躺到午睡椅上，而意大利面则是完美的运动前零食。后来研究证实意大利面的血糖指数并不特别高，这与我的经验相符，也通过了我的“胡扯”过滤。说到饮食，你既要遵循科学，也要从个人经验中寻找佐证。

I haven’t mentioned pasta in my list of simple carbs to avoid, and that’s intentional. In my experience, pasta doesn’t make me sleepy and cranky like other simple carbs. I first discovered that pasta was mood-neutral by eating a lot of it over the years and paying attention to how I felt later. While potatoes send me straight to my napping chair, pasta is a perfect pre-workout snack. When studies later confirmed that pasta isn’t especially high on the glycemic index, it matched my own experience and passed my personal bullshit filter. When it comes to diet, you want to stay consistent with science but also look for confirmation in your personal experience.

花生是另一个科学与我自身经验相符的例子。科学研究​​表明，由于花生富含脂肪，它们能有效满足食欲并提供能量。12-18在饮食中添加富含脂肪的花生，其意想不到的结果是，它能提高你的减肥能力。我的经验与科学完全吻合。花生确实能满足我的食欲，而且我注意到，在吃花生的日子里，我的饮食习惯是少食多餐。

Peanuts are another example in which science and my own experience lined up. The science says that because peanuts have a high concentration of fat, they satisfy your appetite efficiently and provide fuel.12-18 The unpredicted outcome of adding fat-laden peanuts to your diet is that they improve your ability to lose weight. My experience matches the science exactly. Peanuts do satisfy my appetite, and the pattern I notice is that I eat smaller meals on days I eat peanuts.

同样，我发现我可以随心所欲地吃奶酪——大多数日子里我都吃得很多——它既能很好地满足我的饥饿感，又不会让我感到疲倦。如果我能很好地控制其他饮食，我的体重就不会增加。我不相信科学能证明奶酪的益处，如果我的胆固醇很高，我就会避开它。我对奶酪有些疑虑，但目前我喜欢它的味道，也欣赏它抑制饥饿的功效。我会持续关注科学的发展。在跟随我吃奶酪之前，请先咨询你的医生。我提到奶酪只是因为它体现了我选择食物的方法，而不是因为我的选择一定是正确的。我试图为饮食选择提供一个合理的模板，而不是为每个人提供具体的处方。

Likewise, I find I can eat as much cheese as I want—I eat a lot of it on most days—and it does a great job of satisfying my hunger without making me tired. And if I do a good job with the rest of my diet, I don’t gain weight. I don’t believe science backs me up on the benefits of cheese, and if my cholesterol were high, I would steer clear. I have some doubts about cheese, but for now I enjoy the taste and appreciate the hunger-squashing utility of it. I’ll keep looking at the science as it evolves. Ask your doctor before you follow my lead on cheese. I only mention cheese because it illustrates my approach to choosing foods, not because I necessarily choose right. I’m trying to provide a rational template for diet choices, not a specific prescription for everyone.

在阅读本书之前，你看待食物的方式很可能是好与坏、高热量与低热量、碳水化合物与蛋白质，或者这些概念的某种组合。所有这些看待食物的方式都能帮助你避免不良的饮食选择。这种普遍的食物观的问题在于，它总是会让你感觉自己在与自己作斗争。你会渴望糟糕的食物，因为它们实在太美味了。你难以抗拒。

Prior to reading this book, the way you probably looked at food was in terms of good versus bad, fattening versus low-calorie, carbs versus protein, or some combination of those. All those ways of looking at food have power to help you steer away from bad diet choices. The problem with the common view of food is that it will always make you feel as if you’re in a battle with yourself. You crave bad foods because they are so darned tasty. You struggle to resist.

科学证明，人类的意志力是有限的。19-21如果你为了抵制一种诱惑而耗尽了意志力，那么你抵抗其他诱惑的能力也就受到了限制。努力做任何事情都会付出高昂的代价，因为你不想把你的意志力和精力耗费在像远离糖果抽屉这样无关紧要的事情上。你以后可能需要用到你的意志力去做一些更重要的事情。所以你需要的是一个不依赖意志力的饮食系统。这意味着重新规划你的饮食偏好，这样意志力就变得不那么重要了。我稍后会解释如何做到这一点。

Science has demonstrated that humans have a limited supply of willpower.19-21 If you use up your supply resisting one temptation, you limit your ability to resist others. Struggling to do anything has a steep price because you don’t want to use up your willpower and energy on something as unimportant as staying away from the candy drawer. You might need your willpower later for something more substantial. So what you need is a diet system that doesn’t rely on willpower. And that means reprogramming your food preferences so willpower is less necessary. I’ll explain how to do that in a minute.

有些人会把重新编程大脑的想法比作自我催眠，这可能让人觉得毛骨悚然，或者不太可能奏效。正如我提到的，一个更好的方法是把你的身体想象成一个湿润的、可编程的机器人，它的输出取决于输入，而不是魔法。想象一下，你是一位工程师，正在努力为你的湿润机器人身体找到用户界面，以便进行一些有用的调整。这就像你有一个菜单选项，标签是“催眠”，另一个标签是“补充能量”。你只需吃一些简单的碳水化合物就可以选择“催眠”。
