Some people reading will compare the idea of reprogramming your brain to self-hypnosis, and that might feel creepy or unlikely to work. A better approach, as I mentioned, is to think of your body as a moist, programmable robot whose outputs depend on its inputs, not magic. Imagine you’re an engineer who is trying to find the user interface for your moist robot body so you can make some useful adjustments. It’s as if you have one menu choice labeled “Make Sleepy” and another labeled “Energize.” You can choose “Make Sleepy” simply by eating simple carbs.

如果说重塑思维的想法听起来像L·罗恩·哈伯德的戴尼提和“听析”（山达基的核心）的过程，那大概说对了一半。说对了一半的是，戴尼提也试图通过改变你看待自己的方式以及促使你做事的动机来改变行为。有趣的是，正如我在本书前面指出的那样，即使出于错误的理由做正确的事情，你也能获得良好的结果。例如，如果你相信酒精是魔鬼的尿液，这或许能消除你酒后驾车的风险。错误的世界观通常也能带来良好的结果。一些著名的哲学家、一些科学家，以及至少一位漫画家会推测，错误的世界观是唯一存在的世界观。

If the idea of reprogramming your mind sounds like L. Ron Hubbard’s Dianetics and the process of “auditing,” which is at the core of Scientology, that’s about half right. The part that’s right is that Dianetics also attempts to change behavior by changing the way you look at yourself and what makes you do what you do. Interestingly, as I pointed out earlier in this book, you can get good results by doing the right thing for the wrong reasons. For example, if you believe alcohol is the Devil’s urine, that might eliminate your risk of drinking and driving. You can often get good results from inaccurate worldviews. Some famous philosophers, some scientists, and at least one cartoonist would speculate that inaccurate worldviews are the only kind there are.

戴尼提真的能给信徒带来好结果吗？我没有数据来回答这个问题。但如果听析对某些人有效，我也不会感到惊讶。根据我的经验，我认为你可以用通灵板代替山达基的听析过程，仍然能给某些人带来好结果。

Does Dianetics work in terms of creating good outcomes for its followers? I have no data to answer that question. But I wouldn’t be surprised if auditing does work for some people. Based on my experience, I think you could replace the auditing process in Scientology with an Ouija board and still have good outcomes for some people.

食物与运动的关系

The Food–Exercise Connection

传统的体重维持观点认为，要想达到良好的效果，你需要锻炼并注意饮食。这在很大程度上是正确的，但更实用的方法是将食物和运动视为平等的伙伴。更实际的观点是，食物是运动所需的能量。当你午餐吃简单的碳水化合物时，你会发现自己更想小睡一会儿，而不是在跑步机上锻炼一个小时。如果你晚餐吃得太饱，你可能会取消跑步计划。如果你管理好自己的饮食，你就会想要更多锻炼，这也会转化为你的实际行动。健康的起点是饮食。一旦你的饮食合理，你的能量水平就会提高，你会发现自己更有运动的心情。

The traditional view of weight maintenance is that you need to exercise and watch your diet to get good results. That’s mostly true, but a more useful way to look at the connection between food and exercise is not as equal partners. A more practical view is that food is the fuel that makes exercise possible. When you eat simple carbs for lunch, you find yourself wanting a nap more than you want to spend an hour on the treadmill. If you stuff yourself for dinner, you might cancel your plans to go for a run. If you manage your diet right, you’ll want to exercise more, and that will translate into doing so. The starting point for good health is diet. Once you get your diet right, your energy level will increase, and you’ll find yourself more in the mood for exercise.

同时改变饮食和开始锻炼计划可能会更加困难，至少以人们通常的做法来说是这样，因为这两个目标都需要意志力。更明智的方法是使用一个系统，将意志力从你的饮食选择中移除——我稍后会解释——让你增加的能量引导你自然地更积极地运动。关于锻炼，我稍后也会详细介绍。饮食和锻炼的要点在于，你需要减少所需的意志力。任何其他方法都是不可持续的。

It can be doubly hard to change your diet and start an exercise program at the same time, at least in the usual way people do these things because both objectives require willpower. A smarter approach is to use a system to remove willpower from your diet choices—as I’ll explain in a bit—and let your increased energy guide you toward a natural preference for being more active. I’ll have more to say about exercise later as well. The main point for both diet and exercise is that you want to reduce the amount of willpower required. Any other approach is unsustainable.

打破简单碳水化合物成瘾

Breaking the Simple-Carb Addiction

抵制诸如白土豆、白面包和白米饭等简单碳水化合物所需的意志力肯定来自某个地方。正如我之前提到的，研究表明，用意志力做任何事情都会减少你抵御其他诱惑的储备。对我而言，有效的方法是从大脑中试图避免暴饮暴食的部分窃取意志力。你或许可以试试我的方法。几个月内，想吃多少就吃多少，任何非简单碳水化合物的食物。这能释放你的意志力，让你用它来避免那些美味又方便的简单碳水化合物。

The willpower you need to resist simple carbs such as white potatoes, white bread, and white rice must come from somewhere, and as I mentioned earlier, studies show that using willpower for anything reduces how much you have in reserve for other temptations. The approach that works for me involves stealing willpower from the part of my brain that tries to avoid overeating. You might want to give my method a try. For a few months, eat as much as you want of anything that is not a simple carb. That frees up your willpower so you can use it to avoid those delicious and convenient simple carbs.

如果你饿了，我告诉你不能吃你面前面包篮里的美味面包，那你需要强大的意志力才能抗拒。但如果我说你不能吃美味的面包，但可以吃任何你现在想吃的东西，突然间，面包就很容易被你抗拒了。一个有吸引力的替代方案会让意志力变得不那么必要。它能释放你储存的意志力用于其他用途。在我的体系中，你只需要想吃多少就吃多少，任何不是简单碳水化合物的食物，并坚持几个月。

If you were hungry and I said you couldn’t eat the delicious bread in the breadbasket in front of you, that would take great willpower to resist. But if I said you couldn’t have the delicious bread but could have anything else you wanted right now, suddenly the bread would be easy to resist. An attractive alternative makes willpower less necessary. It frees up your stockpile of willpower for other uses. In my system, all you need to do is eat as much as you want of anything that isn’t a simple carb and keep to that for a few months.

这个计划会让你在几个月内增重吗？对某些人来说，可能会。但短期效果并不重要；你的目标是长期坚持。这是一个系统，而不是一个设定特定体重目标的饮食计划。记住，目标是个陷阱。你需要的是系统，而不是目标。这个系统的第一步是戒掉你对简单碳水化合物的依赖。

Would this plan make you gain weight for a few months? For some people, it might. But the short term doesn’t matter; you’re in this for the long haul. It’s a system, not a diet with a specific weight goal. Remember, goals are a trap. You want systems, not goals. The first part of the system is to break your addiction to simple carbs.

我的经验是，戒掉碳水化合物上瘾后，偶尔狂吃炸薯条的习惯就不难恢复了。食物不像酒，一杯酒就能让酒鬼再次跌入深渊。对于已经戒掉碳水化合物上瘾的人来说，吃一块面包只不过是路上的一块小石子。

My experience is that after you break the addiction, it isn’t hard to recover from the occasional french fry binge. Food isn’t like alcohol, where one drink can send an alcoholic back to the bottom. Eating a piece of bread is only a pebble in the road for someone who has broken the carb addiction.

如果你允许自己连续几个月想吃多少就吃多少，那些不含容易上瘾的简单碳水化合物的食物，你会发现一些变化。首先，不吃简单碳水化合物，你的能量会更足。这会让你更加活跃，从而燃烧卡路里。

If for several months you give yourself permission to eat as much as you want of the foods that don’t include addictive simple carbs, you’ll discover several things. For starters, you’ll have more energy without the simple carbs. And that will translate into keeping you more active, which in turn burns calories.

几个月不吃简单碳水化合物后，你会注意到的另一个变化是，你的食欲会开始减弱。你对某些食物的偏爱实际上可能更像是一种上瘾，而不是真正的偏爱。例如，我生命中有很长一段时间，如果不吃一大块士力架就无法一整天。第一口就让我感到欣快，我全身心地享受着这种感觉。但是，几个月后，我可以随心所欲地吃更健康的食物，我就不再想吃士力架了。我原以为这是对巧克力的某种深层遗传倾向，但实际上更像是一种上瘾。几个月不吃巧克力后，我不再想吃了。后来，当我只是为了试试会发生什么而吃了一块士力架时，我几乎没有享受到它带来的快感。感觉它只是增加了不必要的卡路里。

Another change you’ll notice after a few months without simple carbs is that your cravings will start to diminish. The sensation you feel as a preference for certain foods can be in reality more of an addiction than a true preference. For example, there was a long period in my life in which I couldn’t go a whole day without eating a giant Snickers candy bar. The first bite gave me a feeling of euphoria I enjoyed in every particle of my being. But after a few months of eating as much as I wanted of healthier food, I lost the craving for Snickers bars. What I thought was some sort of deep genetic disposition to chocolate was actually more of an addiction. After a few months of staying off the chocolate, I lost the craving. Later, when I ate a Snickers bar just to test what would happen, I barely enjoyed it. It felt like nothing but unnecessary calories.

需要说明的是，我不把士力架归类为消耗能量的简单碳水化合物。我的经验是，巧克力和花生的组合通常能让我精神抖擞，正如他们的广告宣传的那样。我唯一不喜欢士力架的地方就是我经常狂吃。

Just to be clear, I don’t include Snickers in the category of simple carbs that sap your energy. My experience was that the combination of chocolate and peanuts generally pepped me up, exactly as their commercials suggest. My only problem with Snickers is that I binged on them.

我戒掉对白米饭和土豆的渴望就没那么成功了。显然我的确偏爱这些口味。但这种渴望并没有强烈到我会为了吃得不好而放弃一个苹果。今天，当我看到一堆土豆泥时，我就会不由自主地联想到一个小时后感觉糟糕透顶。如果这还不足以让我戒掉它们，我就允许自己想吃多少就吃多少。这种转移注意力的方法通常很有效。

I’ve had less success losing my desire for white rice and potatoes. Apparently I have a genuine preference for those tastes. But the desires aren’t so strong that I would pass up an apple to eat poorly. Today, when I look at a pile of mashed potatoes, I automatically associate them with feeling crappy in an hour. And if that isn’t enough to keep them off my plate, I give myself permission to eat as much as I want of good food instead. The diversion usually works.

健怡可乐

Diet Coke

为了全面披露，我这辈子喝了太多健怡可乐。我每天最多喝十二瓶健怡可乐。而几乎所有医学和营养专家都警告我不要喝健怡可乐。我的问题是，我真的很享受喝的每一瓶健怡可乐，当我查找关于其健康风险的科学依据时，我发现两者之间存在很多关联，但没有明确的因果关系。但我一直密切关注，以防科学结论最终偏向某一方。

In the interest of full disclosure, I have over the course of my life consumed far too much Diet Coke. I have routinely consumed as many as twelve Diet Cokes per day. This was in the context of nearly every medical and nutritional expert warning against it. My problem was that I truly enjoyed each Diet Coke I drank, and when I looked for the science about the health risks, I saw a lot of correlation but no clear causation. But I kept an eye on it just in case the science became settled on one side or the other.

几个月前，为了写这本书，我把我的食欲管理理念进行了终极测试：我彻底戒掉了健怡可乐，在四十多年异常规律的饮用之后。我承认，第一周很艰难。但每当我想喝健怡可乐时，我就用咖啡（我也很喜欢咖啡）来代替，这大大减少了我使用意志力的需要。第一周对我来说是个挑战。到了第四周，抵制健怡可乐就变得轻而易举了。八周后，我把健怡可乐看作一小杯充满我不需要的化学物质的、奇怪的彩色水。我的食欲完全消失了。除了最初的几天，戒掉健怡可乐并不需要太多的意志力。我甚至很享受喝更多咖啡的时光，因为我感觉一整天都更加警觉。科学界高度评价适量饮用咖啡对健康有益。27-32

A few months ago, as part of my process for writing this book, I put my concept of cravings management to the ultimate test: I quit Diet Coke, cold turkey, after forty-plus years of extraordinarily regular consumption. The first week was hard, I admit. But I substituted coffee, which I also love, whenever I craved Diet Coke, and that greatly reduced my need to use willpower. Week one was a challenge. By week four, it was easy to resist Diet Coke. Eight weeks later, I see Diet Coke as a weird little colored water full of chemicals I don’t need. My cravings are completely gone. Giving up Diet Coke didn’t require much willpower beyond the first several days. I’m even enjoying my greater coffee consumption because I feel more alert all day. And coffee in moderation gets high marks from science for promoting good health.27-32

我之所以选择健怡可乐进行我的食欲消除测试，是因为虽然我不认为健怡汽水对偶尔饮用者来说特别不健康，但我也不确定每天喝十二罐是否有助于健康生活。虽然关于健怡汽水危害的研究尚无定论——至少对我来说是这样——但在某种程度上，其对健康的负面影响已经达到了我个人风险承受能力的临界点。所以需要说明的是，我个人并未发现偶尔饮用健怡汽水会造成任何已证实的健康问题。我只是不喜欢这种可能性。33-35

The reason I picked Diet Coke for my cravings elimination test is that while I’m not convinced that diet soda is especially unhealthy for the occasional consumer, I wasn’t so sure that drinking twelve cans a day was contributing to a healthy life. And while the studies on the dangers of diet sodas stop short of being convincing—at least to me—at some point, the sheer tonnage of negative health correlations reached a tipping point for my personal risk profile. So just to be clear, I am not personally aware of any proven health problems from an occasional diet soda. I just don’t like the odds.33-35

如何知道吃什么

How to Know What to Eat

健康饮食的最大障碍之一是不方便。对我们大多数人来说，生活如此忙碌，以至于便捷性压倒了其他大多数考虑因素。即使我们知道这会缩短寿命，我们也会选择最容易的选择。你真正想要的是健康食品比不健康食品更方便。我会给你一些建议，希望能对你有所帮助。但首先，让我来描述一下，即使是知道什么是健康的，更不用说找到它了，是多么困难。

One of the biggest barriers to healthy eating is the inconvenience factor. Life is so busy for most of us that convenience trumps most other considerations. We do what’s easiest even if we know it shortens our lives. What you want is for healthy food to be more convenient than unhealthy food. I’ll give you a few tips that can help. But first let me describe just how hard it is to even know what is healthy, much less find it.

我的观察是，大多数人都认为自己已经知道哪些食物健康。人们知道蔬菜有益健康，芝士汉堡则不然。但你无需深入研究饮食选择的细节，即使是知识渊博的人也会感到疑惑。这周鸡蛋健康吗？黑麦面包怎么样？黄油呢？火鸡呢？你很快就会陷入连专家都意见不一的灰色地带。

My observation is that most people think they already know which foods are healthy. People know vegetables are good for you and cheeseburgers are not. But you don’t have to drill far down into the details of diet options before even well-informed people become unsure. Are eggs healthy this week? How about rye bread? What about butter? Turkey? You quickly get into grey areas in which even experts disagree.

假设你博学多识，能够准确地将食物分为好食物和坏食物，并且每次都能得到正确的答案。但这仅仅是你需要了解的一小部分。在健康食品类别中，你能进一步对它们进行排序吗？如果可以，那么坚持选择最好的，避免选择那些所谓的“健康食品”中排名较低的，就显得明智了。苹果比西兰花好吗？牛油果比香蕉差吗？如果你吃最好的健康食品，避免那些“不太好但还可以”的食物，你的健康状况会好多少？差别很大还是很小？

Suppose you are so well-informed that you could accurately sort food into categories of good and bad and get the right answer every time. That’s only a fraction of what you need to know. Within the category of healthy foods, can you further rank them? If you can, it would make sense to stick with the best of the best and avoid the lower quadrant of the so-called healthy foods. Is an apple better than broccoli? Is an avocado worse than a banana? How much healthier would you be if you ate the best of the healthy foods and avoided the less-good-but-still-okay foods? Is it a big difference or a small one?

饮食多样化有多难？吃各种名称和外观各异的食物或许很容易，但它们的营养成分真的有那么大差异吗？吃一个苹果配一个橙子，还是一个苹果配一个西红柿，哪个更有益？哪种营养补充更全面？

How hard is it to get variety in your diet? It might be easy to eat a variety of foods that have different names and appearances, but are they that different nutritionally? Would you be better off eating an apple and an orange or an apple and a tomato? Which one gives you a more complete nutritional boost?

任何医生或营养专家都会告诉你，均衡饮食能提供你所需的所有维生素和矿物质。这个观点几乎被所有聪明人百分之百地接受。问题是，这在数学上是不可能的。你可以自己证明这一点，只要你确信自己在食物种类和健康选择方面都做得很好，就用谷歌搜索你吃的所有食物的营养信息。我做过这个实验，发现你摄入的维生素和矿物质根本无法接近美国政府的每日推荐摄入量。你得吃掉满满一手推车的食物才能接近这个数字。

Any doctor or nutrition expert will tell you that eating a balanced diet will get you all the vitamins and minerals you need. That opinion is nearly 100 percent accepted by all smart people. The problem is that it’s mathematically impossible. You can prove that to yourself by googling the nutritional information for everything you eat on any given day in which you’re sure you did a good job with both your food variety and healthy choices. I’ve done this experiment and found that you can’t get anywhere near the US government’s Daily Recommended Intake of vitamins and minerals. You would have to eat a wheelbarrow full of food to come close.

普通食物的营养不足促使我将“呆伯特卷饼”推向市场。我认为它能为这个世界带来一些好处，因为这个世界给了我创作《呆伯特》的丰厚回报。强化墨西哥卷饼的生意和我尝试过的大多数东西一样失败了。但在这个过程中，我学到了很多关于维生素和矿物质的知识。主要的收获是，营养学看似科学，但实际上可能有60%是胡扯、猜测和错误的假设。剩下的就是营销。

The nutritional shortfall of normal food is what prompted me to bring the Dilberito to market. I thought it would do some good for the world that had rewarded me so handsomely for Dilbert. The fortified burrito business failed like most of the things I’ve tried. But during the process, I learned a lot about vitamins and minerals. The main takeaway is that nutrition presents itself as science but is perhaps 60 percent bullshit, guesswork, and bad assumptions. The rest is marketing.

在强化墨西哥卷饼生意失败的过程中，我学到了本章中你将读到的大部分内容。这就是我所说的“不断失败，不断前进”。任何时候，只要你学到一些有用的东西，你就会领先一步。就我而言，我对健康饮食的关注可能延长了我的寿命。

In the process of failing at the fortified burrito business, I learned most of what you’ll read in this chapter. That’s what I call failing forward. Any time you learn something useful, you come out ahead. In this case, my focus on a healthy diet has probably lengthened my lifespan.

在某些特定领域，营养科学相当扎实。研究人员知道孕妇需要维生素E。我们知道维生素C有助于预防坏血病。数据也表明维生素D有益。还有其他一些维生素也明显有益。但如果你看看商店货架上的维生素和矿物质，你会发现大多数维生素和矿物质的研究程度都远不及你对健康相关产品的研究程度。

In some narrow areas, nutrition science is reasonably solid. Researchers know that pregnant women need vitamin E. We know that vitamin C is needed to avoid scurvy. And the data suggests good things about vitamin D. There are other clearly beneficial vitamins as well. But if you look at any store shelf of vitamins and minerals, most of them haven’t been researched to the extent you would want for health-related products.

让营养科学更加复杂的是，没有两个人是完全相同的。一个体重120磅、准备怀孕的素食女性，需要的维生素和矿物质，真的和一个患有痛风的肥胖煤矿工人一样吗？没有两个人的生活方式、健康状况和基因是完全相同的。

Further complicating nutrition science is the inconvenient fact that no two humans are alike. Does a 120-pound vegetarian woman who is trying to get pregnant need the same vitamins and minerals as an obese coal miner with gout? No two people have the same lifestyle, health, and genetics.

虽然我的强化墨西哥卷饼公司因为普通的商业原因倒闭了，但我最终还是会选择退出，因为我不再相信每日推荐摄入量的维生素和矿物质足够可靠。在迪尔贝里托的那些年里，似乎每周都会有新的研究出来，挑战我自以为的认知。这真的让我深感不安。

While my fortified burrito company failed for ordinary business reasons, I would have bowed out eventually as I lost my faith in the Daily Recommended Intake levels of vitamins and minerals as sufficiently credible. During the Dilberito years, it seemed as if every week a new study would come out that challenged what I thought I knew. It was deeply unsettling.

你不可能精确地知道你应该吃什么以及应该多久吃一次。营养科学极其不完善。充其量，你只能避免一些显而易见的饮食错误。然而，当科学给我们带来不确定性时，有时你可以通过个人观察和模式识别来逐渐找到真相。如果你认识任何一位在没有私人厨师或私人教练的帮助下也能保持理想成年体重的人，你难道不想知道他们是如何做到的吗？问问任何体重健康的人他们吃什么，然后留意其中的规律。

It’s impossible to know with any precision what you should be eating and how often you should eat it. Nutrition science is shockingly incomplete. At best, you can avoid the obvious diet mistakes. But where science gives us uncertainty, sometimes you can creep up on the truth through personal observation and pattern recognition. If you know anyone who maintains an ideal adult weight without the services of a personal chef or a personal trainer, wouldn’t you like to know how? Ask anyone who has a healthy weight what they eat, then be on the lookout for the pattern.

知道你为什么吃东西

Know Why You’re Eating

我们吃东西的原因不止一个。我发现了解自己吃东西的原因很有帮助，这样我就能相应地调整自己的食物选择。

We eat for more than one reason. I find it useful to understand what is making me eat so I can adjust my food choices accordingly.

例如，科学家知道，当你睡眠不足时，大脑会触发饥饿感，并分泌瘦素和生长素释放肽等饥饿激素。22-26下次当你有一天吃不饱时，问问自己前一天晚上睡了多久。你会惊讶地发现，睡眠不好常常会导致你不停地进食。

For example, scientists know that your brain triggers the hunger sensation and hunger hormones like leptin and ghrelin when you don’t get enough sleep.22-26 The next time you have one of those days when you can’t eat enough to satisfy your hunger, ask yourself how much sleep you got the night before. You’ll surprise yourself at how often a bad night of sleep leads to non-stop eating.

当疲倦引发饥饿感，而你又已经摄入了一段时间所需的所有热量时，可以尝试吃花生或混合坚果来抑制食欲。奶酪也有效，至少在这方面是如此。这些食物中的脂肪可以满足食欲。坚果和奶酪含有大量热量，但你会发现，如果选择吃到厨房里所有食物都吃完，那么以额外摄入一些热量来抑制食欲仍然是有益的。

When tiredness sparks your hunger and you’ve had all the calories you need for a while, try eating peanuts or mixed nuts to suppress your appetite. Cheese also works, at least for that specific purpose. The fat in those foods acts as an appetite satisfier. Nuts and cheese have lots of calories, but you’ll find that suppressing your appetite at the expense of some extra calories is still a net gain if the alternative is to eat until everything in your kitchen is gone.

我经常发现自己在社交场合进餐，只是因为家里有人碰巧在厨房吃零食。我走进去，开始聊天，然后就发现一些不必要的东西正冲向我的胃。这几乎是自动的，不假思索的。我有足够的意识引导自己选择最低热量的食物。我不需要坚果或奶酪，因为我其实不饿。我只是需要在闲逛的时候做点什么。所以我会选择冰箱里准备好的芹菜、胡萝卜或黄瓜。当你因为社交原因进食时，尽量选择最低热量的食物。如果你吃东西的原因不是饥饿，就不需要抑制食欲。

I often find myself doing social eating just because someone else in the family happens to be snacking in the kitchen. I wander in, start a conversation, and the next thing I know something unnecessary is heading for my stomach. It’s almost automatic and mindless. I have just enough awareness to steer myself toward the lowest-calorie items. I don’t need nuts or cheese because I’m not actually hungry. I just need something to do while I hang out. So I go for the celery or carrots or cucumbers in my fridge that are prepped and waiting. When you eat for social reasons, aim for the lowest-calorie options. You don’t need to suppress your appetite if the reason you’re eating isn’t hunger.

如何让健康食品变得美味

How to Make Healthy Food Taste Good

健康饮食的最大障碍或许就是味道。你可能喜欢所有对身体有害的食物，却对所谓的健康食品却不太感兴趣。作为你这个吃素偶尔吃鱼的朋友，我会告诉你如何从原本乏味的食物中获得你想要的味道。

Perhaps the biggest obstacle to healthy eating is flavor. You might love the taste of everything that’s bad for you while being less enthusiastic about so-called healthy foods. As your friend who eats a vegetarian diet plus an occasional fish, I’ll tell you how to get the flavor you need from otherwise boring food.

正确饮食的首要原则是避免那些让你感觉像在受惩罚的食物。没有人会因为吞下一大碗无聊的食物而颁发奖章。如果健康饮食让你感觉不舒服，那你就做错了。而且你正在浪费你有限的意志力。你可能有一份自己列出的糟糕但健康的食物清单。只要你还有许多其他选择，就可以随意避免它们。

The first rule of eating right is avoiding foods that feel like punishment. No one gives out medals for choking down a big bowl of boredom. If eating a healthy diet feels unpleasant, you’re doing it wrong. And you’re wasting your limited stockpile of willpower. You might have your own list of awful-yet-healthy foods. Feel free to avoid them so long as that leaves you plenty of other options.

我发现大多数饮食不良的人都认为健康食品味道寡淡或难吃。如果你在素食中首先想到的是豆腐，这种印象就更加明显了，而且我发现这种情况经常发生。为了公益，我列出了以下调味品、佐料和配料，它们可以为大多数原本寡淡的食物增添风味。这些都是我赖以生存的味觉体验，却从未感到丝毫的味觉缺失。每个人的口味都会有所不同，所以这只是一个模板，用来说明健康饮食中你可以享受多少种风味。

I find that most people who have poor diets believe healthy food has bland or unpleasant flavor. That impression is double-true if the first thing you think of in a vegetarian diet is tofu, and I find that is often the case. As a public service, I’ve listed below the condiments, seasonings, and ingredients that can add flavor to most foods that would be otherwise bland. These are the taste sensations I live on while never feeling the slightest twinge of flavor deprivation. Your tastes will differ, so this is just a template to make the point about how many flavors you can enjoy in a healthy diet.

素食口味：

Vegetarian flavors:

  • 酱油
  • Soy sauce
  • 香菜
  • Cilantro
  • 柠檬
  • Lemon
  • 盐
  • Salt
  • 胡椒
  • Pepper
  • 黄油（或黄油替代品）
  • Butter (or butter substitute)
  • 蒜
  • Garlic
  • 洋葱
  • Onion
  • 咖喱
  • Curry
  • 奶酪
  • Cheese
  • 番茄酱
  • Tomato sauce
  • 萨尔萨舞
  • Salsa
  • 蔬菜汤
  • Vegetable broth
  • 蜂蜜
  • Honey
  • 沙拉酱
  • Salad dressings
  • 香醋​
  • Balsamic vinegar
  • 黑豆酱
  • Black bean sauce
  • 辣酱
  • Hot sauce

你会注意到我的清单上有盐和黄油，你可能觉得这两种食物都和不良饮食有关。我想提一个建议，建议在饮食中加入大量的盐和黄油，前提是要把它们添加到其他健康食品中。

You’ll notice that salt and butter are on my list, and you probably associate both of those with a bad diet. I’d like to make an argument in favor of including copious amounts of both salt and butter in your diet, so long as you’re adding them to otherwise healthy food.

在这里我再提醒你一次——因为我再怎么强调也不为过——要警惕漫画家们的健康观念。在客厅里放一块盐块，或者开始吃黄油之前，一定要先咨询医生。

Here I’ll remind you again—because I can’t say it too often—be wary of health ideas from cartoonists. Check with your doctor before you install a salt lick in your living room or start eating butter by the stick.

先从盐说起。多年来，科学界对盐对没有心脏病特殊风险人群的健康风险的报告一直存在争议。鉴于目前已开展了大量研究来揭示盐的潜在风险，我本以为现在已经能找到明确的答案。然而，科学界尚未给出答案。

Let’s start with salt. For years, science has produced conflicting reports about the health risks of salt for people who have no special risk for heart disease. Given the number of studies undertaken to uncover the hidden risks of salt, I would expect a clear answer by now. Science has not provided it.

生活中的一切都是经过深思熟虑的风险，而我决定，想用多少盐就用多少盐，这样我就能尽情享受一些原本不会吃的健康食物。比如，腌胡萝卜很美味，但不加盐的胡萝卜就像嚼一根棍子。蒸咸抱子甘蓝是我的最爱之一，但原味抱子甘蓝却毫无吸引力。

Everything in life is a calculated risk, and I’ve decided that using salt as much as I want allows me to thoroughly enjoy some healthy foods that I wouldn’t otherwise eat. For example, a salted carrot is delicious, but an unsalted carrot is like chewing on a stick. Steamed and salted brussels sprouts are one of my favorite foods, but plain brussels sprouts hold no appeal.

享受盐而不担心心脏病发作的关键在于你需要总体健康饮食、规律运动并保持健康的体脂比例。如果你没有高血压，这也会有所帮助。如果你体格健壮，早餐吃猪肉，而且所有叔叔都因心脏病去世，你的医生可能会建议你从饮食中去除盐，以确保安全。请记住，你的医生可能不是盐专家，所以谨慎永远是医生的第一反应。你可以在互联网上找到大量关于盐研究的信息。你可以自己做决定，但也要保持关注，因为新的盐研究会定期发布。

The key to enjoying salt without worrying about a heart attack is that you need to have a healthy diet in general, exercise regularly, and keep a healthy body fat composition. It also helps if you don’t have high blood pressure. If you’re built like a barrel, eat pork for breakfast, and have lost all your uncles to heart disease, your doctor will probably advise you to take salt out of your diet just to be on the safe side. Keep in mind that your doctor probably isn’t a salt expert, so caution will always be a doctor’s first instinct. You can find plenty of information on salt studies on the Internet. Make up your own mind but keep your eyes open because new salt studies come out on a regular basis.

我支持黄油的理由和盐类似。黄油能有效抑制食欲。和盐一样，它能帮助我享受健康食品。蒸西兰花加点黄油和胡椒粉很美味。光吃西兰花就没意思了。如果黄油能帮你吃更多蔬菜，而且你的体重也控制在可接受的范围内，那么黄油的风险或许是可以接受的。建议咨询医生，确认一下。

My argument in favor of butter is similar to salt. Butter is a good appetite suppressant. As with salt, it helps me enjoy healthy foods. Steamed broccoli with some butter and pepper is delicious. Plain broccoli is boring. If butter helps you eat more vegetables and your weight is under control, butter is probably an acceptable risk. Check with your doctor to be sure.

你可以自己测试一下奶酪和黄油的抑制食欲效果。比如，有一天试试用黄油和帕玛森奶酪蒸蔬菜，然后回忆一下之后的感觉。第二天，试试只用酱油蒸蔬菜。酱油的味道很棒，但你还没咽下最后一口就饿了。在社交聚餐或以其他方式摄入健康脂肪以保持饱腹感时，酱油的效果最佳。

You can do your own test on the appetite-suppressing quality of cheese and butter. Try steamed vegetables with butter and parmesan cheese one day and remember how you felt after. The next day, try steamed vegetables with just soy sauce. The soy sauce is a great flavor, but you’ll find yourself hungry before you swallow the last bite. Soy sauce works best when you’re doing social eating or you are eating healthy fat in some other form to keep you feeling satisfied.

把健康饮食想象成一个系统，在这个系统中，你会不断尝试不同的调味料和酱汁，直到找到真正适合自己的方法。你希望看到一种蔬菜，就能立刻知道五种让它变得美味的方法，其中至少两种不需要费力。当你改变了对食物调味的认知时，你的行为也会随之改变。你将不再需要太多的意志力来抵制不健康的食物，因为你仍然会被健康的食物所吸引。

Think of healthy eating as a system in which you continually experiment with different seasonings and sauces until you know exactly what works for you. You want to be able to look at a vegetable and instantly know five ways to make it delicious, at least two of which don’t require much effort. When you change what you know about adding flavor to food, that alone will change your behavior. You’ll no longer need much willpower to resist bad food because you will be just as attracted to the healthy stuff.

调整生活方式，健康饮食

Adjusting Your Lifestyle for Healthy Eating

正如我之前提到的，研究表明，拥有超重的朋友也会导致你自身超重。36-39我不会轻易相信那些在不了解其背后机制的情况下发现相关性的研究，但我注意到我的体重确实会随着我交往的人而波动。目前，我的副业伙伴是一位铁人三项运动员。在我写这段话的时候，我正坐在一位朋友旁边，他看起来就像是从健身杂志封面走出来的一样。在过去一年左右的时间里，我与体格健壮的人相处的时间比我生命中的任何其他时期都多。这很可能是巧合。但正如研究表明的那样，不知何故，我设法达到了成年后的最佳体型。而且我并不觉得自己用了什么额外的意志力来达到这个目标。感觉好像是社会的影响让这一切变得更容易。我不知道这是因为我有竞争意识，还是因为人们会自然而然地模仿周围的人，就像我们搬到其他地方后会模仿口音一样。不管原因是什么，科学、常识和我的个人经验都一致：和健康的人一起出去玩会让你变得更像他们。这完全符合我的“胡说八道”原则。

As I mentioned earlier, studies show that having overweight friends can make you overweight yourself.36-39 I don’t automatically trust studies that uncover correlations without knowing the mechanism behind them, but I have noticed that my weight does fluctuate depending on the company I keep. At the moment, my business partner in a side venture is an Ironman athlete. And as I write this paragraph, I am sitting next to a friend who looks like he stepped off the cover of a fitness magazine. For the past year or so, I’ve spent more time with unusually fit people than at any other time in my life. That’s mostly a coincidence. But just as the studies suggest, I’ve somehow managed to drift into the best physical shape of my adult life. And I don’t feel that I used any extra willpower to get there. It feels as if the social influence makes it easier. I don’t know if the reason is that I feel competitive or that people naturally imitate the people around them in the same way we adopt accents when we move to other parts of the country. Whatever the reason, science, common sense, and my personal experience are in agreement: Hanging out with fit people can cause you to become more like them. And that passes my bullshit filter.

我并不是建议你停止接受超重朋友的邀请。但在接下来关于健身的章节中，我建议你如果可以的话加入一些有组织的运动队。这会扩大你的社交圈，让你接触到热爱运动的人。假以时日，你的运动伙伴会在你的社交生活中扮演更重要的角色。这绝对是件好事。

I’m not suggesting you should stop accepting invitations from your overweight friends. But in the upcoming fitness chapter, I’ll suggest joining some organized sport teams if you can. That will expand your social circle to include people who enjoy exercise. In time, your sport friends will play a bigger role in your social life. That can only be good.

咖啡

Coffee

如果您不喝咖啡，那么每天应该喝两到四杯。咖啡可以让你更警觉、更快乐、更高效，甚至可能让你长寿。咖啡还能让你更倾向于运动，它还含有有益的抗氧化剂和其他与降低中风（尤其是女性）、帕金森病和痴呆症风险相关的物质。咖啡还能降低心律失常、2 型糖尿病和某些癌症的风险。27-32,62-67咖啡的这些益处中，任何一个都可能令人信服，但综合起来，就变得显而易见了。

If you don’t drink coffee, you should think about two to four cups a day. Coffee can make you more alert, happier, and more productive. It might even make you live longer. Coffee can also make you more likely to exercise, and it contains beneficial antioxidants and other substances associated with decreased risk of stroke (especially in women), Parkinson’s disease, and dementia. Coffee is also associated with decreased risk of abnormal heart rhythms, Type 2 diabetes, and certain cancers.27-32,62-67 Any one of these benefits of coffee would be persuasive, but cumulatively, they make it a no-brainer.

一个小时前，我考虑过为这本书写点东西，但没有足够的精力和专注力坐下来开始工作。不过，我倒是有足够的精力给自己泡了一杯咖啡。抿几口，我感觉工作比做任何懒惰的事情都更快乐。咖啡真的让我享受工作，不需要意志力。

An hour ago, I considered doing some writing for this book, but I didn’t have the necessary energy or focus to sit down and start working. I did, however, have enough energy to fix myself a cup of coffee. A few sips in, I was happier to be working than I would have been doing whatever lazy thing was my alternative. Coffee literally makes me enjoy work. No willpower needed.

咖啡还能让你管理能量，在需要的时候拥有最大的能量。我的经验是，喝咖啡的人比不喝咖啡的人能量高点更高，低点更低，但这种平衡是有效的。我可以保证，我的最佳想法都会投入到工作中。同时，我会把大脑的空闲时间留给家务和其他简单的任务。

Coffee also allows you to manage your energy so you have the most when you need it. My experience is that coffee drinkers have higher highs and lower lows energy-wise than non-coffee-drinkers, but that tradeoff works. I can guarantee that my best thinking goes into my job. Meanwhile, I save my dull-brain hours for household chores and other simple tasks.

咖啡最大的缺点是，一旦你对咖啡因上瘾，长时间不喝咖啡就会得“咖啡头痛”。幸运的是，咖啡是地球上最丰富的饮料之一，所以你几乎不需要担心没有咖啡。

The biggest downside of coffee is that once you get addicted to caffeine, you can get a “coffee headache” if you go too long without a cup. Luckily, coffee is one of the most abundant beverages on earth, so you rarely need to worry about being without.

咖啡花钱、费时间，还会留下口臭，还会让你尿频。喝太多还会让你神经紧张。但如果你梦想成功，并且希望保持最佳精神状态，那么咖啡是个不错的选择。我强烈推荐它。事实上，我强烈推荐它，甚至为那些还没有养成习惯的人感到惋惜。

Coffee costs money, takes time, gives you coffee breath, and makes you pee too often. It can also make you jittery and nervous if you have too much. But if success is your dream, and you want to operate at peak mental performance, coffee is a good bet. I highly recommend it. In fact, I recommend it so strongly that I feel sorry for anyone who hasn’t developed the habit.

快乐单元假说

Pleasure Unit Hypothesis

我认为明星们保持苗条身材并非巧合。显然，他们有空闲时间和资源来做到这一点。而且对他们来说，健身还能带来巨大的经济效益。但我认为明星们还有另一个王牌，因为他们的生活总体来说非常精彩。你在生活的某个方面越快乐，你就越不会在其他方面寻找快乐。这可以转化为对食物味道的更少关注。

I don’t think it’s a coincidence that celebrities do a good job of staying thin. Obviously, they have the free time and resources to do it right. And for them, fitness has an enormous financial upside. But I think celebrities have another ace in the hole, too, because their lives are fabulous in general. The happier you are in one area of your life, the less effort you’ll put into searching for happiness elsewhere. And that can translate into caring less about the taste quality of your meal.

例如，如果我让你选择吃你最喜欢的食物还是看无聊的电视节目，你可能会选择美味的食物。但如果让我让你选择吃你最喜欢的食物，或者去你梦想的目的地旅行，那里有你想要的一切，除了美食，你肯定会选择梦想的目的地。健康的饮食很大程度上取决于你的非食物替代品。如果你的生活井然有序，那么拥有理想体重就会容易得多。

For example, if I gave you a choice of eating your favorite food or watching a boring television show, you’d probably choose the tasty food. But if I gave you a choice of your favorite food or a trip to your dream destination that has everything you want except great food, you’d choose the dream destination. Eating right depends a great deal on your non-food alternatives. If you get your entire life in order, it will be much easier to have an ideal weight.

当然，这是一个循环问题，因为达到健康的体重可以改善你的职业、健康和社交生活质量。你需要吃得好才能享受余生，而你需要在余生中保持良好的体形才能更容易地抵制不良的饮食选择。一切都是相互关联的。这就是为什么我在一本关于成功的书中加入了饮食和健身的内容。如果你保持健康，成功就会更容易到来。但如果你没有健康的身体就获得了成功，你就无法享受它。

This is a circular problem, of course, because reaching a healthy weight can improve the quality of your career, health, and social life. You need to eat well to enjoy the rest of your life, and you need the rest of your life to be in good shape to more easily resist bad food choices. Everything is connected. That’s why I include diet and fitness in a book about success. If you get your health in order, success will come more easily. But if you get success without good health, you won’t be able to enjoy it.

健康饮食总结

The Healthy Eating Summary

简单、无需意志力的饮食系统

The Simple, No-Willpower Diet System

  1. 注意吃完某些食物后你的能量水平。找到你的规律。
  2. Pay attention to your energy level after eating certain foods. Find your pattern.
  3. 将不健康、消耗能量的食物从家中清除。
  4. Remove unhealthy, energy-draining food from your home.
  5. 储备方便的健康食品（例如苹果、坚果、香蕉等），让懒惰成为您健康饮食的副驾驶。
  6. Stock up on convenient healthy food (e.g., apples, nuts, bananas, etc.) and let laziness be your copilot in eating right.
  7. 停止食用容易让人上瘾的食物：白米饭、白土豆、甜点、白面包、油炸食品。
  8. Stop eating foods that create feelings of addiction: white rice, white potatoes, desserts, white bread, fried foods.
  9. 随时随地，想吃多少就吃多少健康食品。
  10. Eat as much healthy food as you want, whenever you want.
  11. 保证充足的睡眠，因为疲劳会让人产生饥饿的错觉。
  12. Get enough sleep because tiredness creates the illusion of hunger.
  13. 如果您因疲劳而感到饥饿，请尝试食用含有脂肪的健康食品，例如坚果、鳄梨、蛋白质棒和奶酪，以抑制饥饿感。
  14. If your hunger is caused by tiredness, try healthy foods with fat such as nuts, avocados, protein bars, and cheese to suppress the hungry feeling.
  15. 如果您只是出于社交原因而进食，请选择热量最少的最健康的食物。
  16. If you’re eating for social reasons only, choose the healthiest options with with the fewest calories.
  17. 学习如何调味既健康又美味的食物。
  18. Learn how to season healthy-yet-bland foods.
  19. 随着时间的推移，您将不再渴望吃垃圾食品，而且不会感觉自己做出了牺牲。
  20. In time, you will lose your cravings for bad food without feeling like you’re making a sacrifice.

这是一个长期有效饮食的系统。识别减肥失败者最可靠的方法是，他们往往会说“我的目标是减掉10磅”。设定体重目标通常在短期内有效。但如果你需要意志力来维持体重，那么从长远来看，你注定会失败。长期成功的唯一方法是使用一个不需要意志力的系统。

That’s a system for eating right over the long term. The surest way to identify someone who won’t succeed at weight loss is that they tend to say things like, “My goal is to lose ten pounds.” Weight targets often work in the short run. But if you need willpower to keep the weight off, you’re doomed in the long run. The only way to succeed long term is by using a system that bypasses your need for willpower.

¶¶ *在接下来的健身章节中，我将讨论运动如何影响情绪。饮食通过影响你的能量水平和大脑化学反应来影响情绪。运动通过控制你的压力来影响情绪。务必做好这两点。1-11

¶¶*In the fitness chapter that follows, I’ll talk about how exercise influences mood. Diet affects mood by influencing your energy levels and your brain’s chemistry. Exercise influences mood by keeping your stress under control. Get both of those right.1-11

第32章

Chapter 32

健康

Fitness

一个作为一个在小镇长大的孩子，我一天要玩四五种运动，骑几英里的自行车，游泳，晚上还要在家具上做体操。积极的游戏、运动和其他锻炼是我生活中很重要的一部分。很难想象没有它们的日子会是什么样子。小时候健身很有趣，所以看起来很容易。

As a boy growing up in a small town, I played four or five sports in a day, rode my bike for miles, went for a swim, and finished the evening doing gymnastics on the furniture. Active play, sports, and other exercise were a huge part of my life. It was hard to imagine a day without them. Fitness as a kid was fun, so it seemed easy.

成年后，生活总是让我无法锻炼。我发现很难抽出时间健身，更难找到享受健身的方式。如果我周日在公园里踢一场足球赛，我就会浑身淤青、酸痛难忍，直到周四才能恢复体力。当我试图把自己变成一个休闲跑步者时，我的大脑和身体却另有打算。事实证明，只有当我追着某个球跑，或者被什么长着獠牙的东西追的时候，跑步才对我有用。

When I became an adult, life kept getting in the way of exercise. I found it hard to carve out the time for fitness and even harder to find a way to enjoy it. If I played a pickup soccer game in the park on a Sunday, I would be so bruised and sore that I wouldn’t feel good enough to exercise again until Thursday. When I tried to turn myself into a recreational runner, the rest of my brain and body had other plans. It turns out that running only works for me if I’m chasing some sort of ball or if something with fangs is chasing me.

我尝试过打网球，也取得了一些成功，但找到一个水平相当的搭档、安排好我们的时间安排，以及找到可用的公共球场，都是一件苦差事。我很幸运，每周能打一次球。我当然理解为什么这么多成年人会疏于健身。锻炼从各个方面来说都是一件很辛苦的事。再加上婚姻和孩子，锻炼对很多人来说就变得完全不切实际了。我理解这一点。那么，考虑到生活中所有阻碍保持健康的自然因素，有没有一种有效的方法呢？

I tried tennis with some success, but finding a partner of equal ability, matching our schedules, and finding available public courts was all a chore. I was lucky to play once a week. I certainly understand why so many adults let their fitness slide. Exercise is hard work in every imaginable sense. When you add marriage and kids into the mix, exercise can become completely impractical for many people. I get that. So considering all of life’s natural barriers to remaining fit, is there any system that can work?

我想是的。我尝试了几乎每一种运动技巧、窍门、潮流，甚至有时是经过科学验证的技巧，最终把所有健身建议都浓缩成了一句话：

I think so. After a lifetime of trying nearly every exercise tip, trick, fad, and sometimes scientifically proven techniques, I have condensed the entire field of fitness advice into one sentence:

每天都要活跃起来

Be Active Every Day

请允许我承认，这听起来简直毫无用处。我相信你已经知道，积极运动是件好事。你可能觉得漫画家在健身方面没什么可说的。我承认你可能是对的。但如果你再坚持读一两页，我可能会让你大吃一惊。我绝对算不上健康和健身专家，但我的确有漫画家那种简化的本领。而这种简化或许正是你所需要的。

Allow me to acknowledge how spectacularly useless that sounds. I’m sure you already knew that being active is a good thing. You’re probably thinking that a cartoonist has nothing to offer on the topic of fitness. I’ll be the first to admit that you might be right. But stick with me for a page or two and I might surprise you. I’m not a health and fitness expert by any stretch of the imagination, but I do have a cartoonist’s knack for simplification. And simplification might be just what you need.

简化往往决定了你该做的事情是去做还是拖延。你不介意刷牙，因为很简单。但你可能却拖延着去查阁楼里为什么会飘来一股怪味。这可能会让事情变得复杂。

Simplification is often the difference between doing something you know you should do and putting it off. You don’t mind brushing your teeth because it’s simple. But you probably put off finding out why there’s a strange smell coming from the attic. That could get complicated.

正确的简化还能帮助将运动、饮食、事业、财务和社交生活等重要部分联系起来。如果其中任何一个环节变得过于复杂，你就不得不从其他你同样在意的事情中借用时间、意志力和资源。我不会费力地向你推销简化的好处，因为你每天都在自己的生活中看到它们。

Simplification done right also helps connect the important parts of exercise, diet, career, finance, and your social life. If any of those becomes too complicated, you’re forced to borrow time, willpower, and resources from something else you also care about. I won’t try too hard to sell you on the benefits of simplicity because you see them in your own life every day.

如果你还年轻，没有繁重的责任，你可能已经具备了定期锻炼的一切条件。但过了一定年龄，生活就会把锻炼从你的首要任务之一变成忙碌时你首先要放弃的事情。这实际上可能是一个死亡陷阱。

If you are young and don’t have crushing responsibilities, you probably have everything you need to exercise regularly. But after a certain age, life transforms exercise from one of your highest priorities to the thing you give up first when things get busy. That can literally be a death trap.

我在本章中提出的挑战是让你相信，如果你能正确完成一件简单的事情——每天保持活跃——那么健身的所有其他要素都会自然而然地结合在一起，而无需耗尽你有限的意志力。

My challenge in this chapter is to convince you that if you get one simple thing right—being active every day—all other elements of fitness will come together naturally without the need to use up your limited supply of willpower.

最后一点才是关键。根据我的经验，任何需要意志力的锻炼都是不可持续的。为了长期保持健康，你需要像孩子们一样，把锻炼限制在不让你感觉吃力的水平。当你不再依赖意志力，并达到稳定的日常体育锻炼基础时，你自然会倾向于逐渐增加锻炼量。你会这样做，因为你想做，因为感觉很轻松——而且感觉很好。不需要意志力。

That last part is the key. In my experience, any form of exercise that requires willpower is unsustainable. To stay fit in the long run, you need to limit your exercise to whatever level doesn’t feel like work, just as kids do. When you take willpower out of the equation and achieve a solid baseline of daily physical activity, your natural inclination will be to gradually increase your workout. You’ll do it because you want to and because it feels easy—and because it feels good. No willpower needed.

如果你坚持一个月每天步行两英里，并享受这种悠闲的节奏，你的大脑会自动开始认为多走一英里可能会更有趣，或者跑一半路程，走剩下的路程可能会很有趣。这就是你把无聊变成工具的方法。当你每天都活动量大，身体感觉良好时，你会发现多锻炼比少锻炼更容易。问问任何一位专注的跑步者、骑行者或游泳者，他们在偶尔的休息日感觉如何。他们不喜欢这样。那就是你想要的。而实现这一目标的唯一方法就是让健身——任何形式的健身——成为一种日常习惯。一旦锻炼成为日常，你就不需要意志力来坚持下去，因为你的身体和大脑会更喜欢体力活动，而不是窝在沙发上。而你对多样性的自然偏好会驱使你随着时间的推移做更多的事情。

If you walk two miles every day for a month and enjoy the leisurely pace, your brain will automatically start to think that walking an extra mile might be even more fun—or that running half the way and walking the rest might be interesting. That’s how you turn boredom into a tool. When you are active every day and your body feels good about it, you’ll find it easier to exercise more rather than less. Ask any dedicated runner, biker, or swimmer how they feel on the occasional off day. They don’t like it. That’s where you want to be. And the only way that happens is if you make fitness—of any kind—a daily habit. Once exercise becomes routine, you won’t need willpower to keep going because your body and brain will simply prefer physical activity to being a couch spud. And your natural inclination for variety will drive you to do more stuff over time.

你可能认识一些长跑运动员，每天跑五到十英里。如果你自己体格不那么健壮，你可能会认为这些跑步者拥有非凡的意志力。但这很可能只是一种错觉，而非现实。长跑运动员天生就拥有某种基因，让他们在跑步时感觉良好。没有人需要意志力来做自己喜欢的事情。

You probably know someone who is a long-distance runner, putting in five to ten miles every day. If you’re not that fit yourself, you might think those runners have extraordinary willpower. That’s probably more of an illusion than reality. Long-distance runners are born with a certain genetic gift that allows them to feel good when running. No one needs willpower to do the things they enjoy.

包括我在内的大多数普通成年人，都觉得跑步不过是消磨无聊和不适的最经济实惠的方式。在我的一生中，我曾十几次试图强迫自己享受跑步，或者至少为了健康而坚持跑步。但每次，我的意志力都在几周后就崩溃了。

Most normal adults, including me, find running to be little more than the most cost-effective way to be bored and uncomfortable. A dozen times over the course of my life, I have tried to force myself to enjoy running, or at least to do it anyway for the health benefits. Each time, my willpower crapped out a few weeks into it.

你不会仅仅因为看到鸟儿的飞行效果就挥动手臂尝试飞翔。同样，我也不建议仅仅因为体型和大脑完全不同的人似乎喜欢某个锻炼计划就采用它。无论YouTube上的健身大师听起来多么有魅力，都不要相信别人的特定健身计划对你有效。没有人和你一样。

You wouldn’t flap your arms and try to fly just because you saw how well it worked for a bird. Likewise, I don’t recommend adopting an exercise plan just because people who have completely different bodies and brains seem to enjoy it. No matter how charismatic that exercise guru on YouTube sounds, don’t believe that someone else’s specific fitness plan will work for you. No one is like you.

你需要的是一种自然而简单的方法来制定适合你大脑和身体状况的健身计划。而且你希望做到这一点，而不是依赖意志力。这段旅程的起点无非就是每天进行体力活动，无论具体情况如何。

What you need is a natural and easy way to evolve a fitness routine that works for your specific brain and body. And you want to do that without relying on willpower. The starting point for that journey is nothing more than physically activity every day regardless of the specifics.

我在亚马逊网站上搜索了关键词“锻炼”，得到了125,508条推荐书籍。我并非想成为第125,509个关于那些内容大同小异的书籍的推荐者。我读过的书不多，但我认为大多数都需要你运用一定程度的意志力。无论你如何粉饰，无论作者如何鼓舞人心，这都是一个失败的策略。从长远来看，任何依赖于意志力的系统都会失败。或者更糟的是，当你把有限的意志力储备消耗在健身上时，你生活的其他部分也会受到影响。

I did an Amazon.com search on the keyword “exercise” and got 125,508 book suggestions. I’m not trying to be the 125,509th variation on largely familiar material. I haven’t read many of those books, but I assume most of them require you to use a degree of willpower. That’s a losing strategy no matter how you dress it up or how inspirational the author might be. In the long run, any system that depends on your willpower will fail. Or worse, some other part of your life will suffer as you deplete your limited stockpile of willpower on fitness.

我喜欢的健身方法与常规方法不同，它不仅简单易行，而且在任何阶段都不需要意志力。事实上，如果你坚持每天活动，你会感觉更有活力，这可以补充你的意志力。

The fitness approach I prefer differs from the norm both in its simplicity and because it doesn’t require willpower at any stage. In fact, if you follow the system of being active every day, you’ll feel more energetic, and that can replenish your willpower.

我故意用“积极”这个词，语气比较含糊。正因如此，这条规则才是一个体系，而不是一个目标。众所周知，目标是为失败者准备的。如果这条规则是“每天跑十英里”，那它就是一个目标。而且，由于大多数人无法每天都做某件具体的事情，它很可能会让你走向失败。但几乎每个人都可以每天以某种方式保持活跃。这可以是任何事情，从打篮球到打扫车库，再到散步。在我的体系下，任何体力活动都算数，没有优劣之分。在本章中，我将解释，如果你遵循一些简单的意志力控制规则，所有途径都能让你达到最佳体能。

I use the word “active” in an intentionally ambiguous way. That’s what makes the rule a system and not a goal. As you know, goals are for losers. If the rule were “Run ten miles every day,” that would be a goal. And it would probably set you up for failure since most people can’t do something specific every day. But almost everyone can be active in some way every day. That could mean anything from playing basketball to cleaning the garage to taking a walk. Under my system, any physical exertion counts, and none is better than the other. I’ll explain in this chapter how all paths can lead to optimal fitness if you follow a few simple rules for manipulating your willpower.

“每日运动”体系中最重要、最强大的部分是“每日”部分。一切都由此自然而然地展开。如果你像大多数成年人一样，难以在繁忙的日程中抽出时间锻炼，我也会为你提供一些建议。

The most important and powerful part of the “Be active every day” system is the “every day” part. Everything springs naturally from that. And if you have trouble fitting exercise into your busy schedule as most adults do, I’ll give you some suggested fixes for that, too.

健身本是一个简单的体验，却因市场力量而变得异常复杂。如果你想成为一名健身专家并赚钱，你必须对你的产品或服务的价值提出新颖的主张。每一个新想法都层层叠加，直到整个领域变得错综复杂，令人望而生畏。

Fitness is a simple experience made absurdly complicated by market forces. If you want to make money as a fitness expert, you must make a novel claim about the value of your product or service. Each new idea is layered on top of old ideas until the entire field is so complicated it becomes intimidating.

你应该多久锻炼一次？锻炼前后应该吃什么？有氧运动和举重训练的饮食应该有所不同吗？你应该根据年龄、性别和自身情况定制多少锻炼计划？腹部锻炼会损伤背部还是有益？举重训练之间应该休息多久？长跑对你的整体健康有益吗？值得你为此承受膝盖的磨损吗？诸如此类的问题和复杂性层出不穷。以下是一些你经常听到的关于“必须”锻炼的建议。

How often should you work out? What should you eat before and after working out? Should you have a different diet for cardio workouts versus weightlifting? How much should you customize your workouts for your age, gender, and situation? Will an abdominal exercise hurt your back or help it? How much rest should you get between days of weightlifting? Is long-distance running beneficial enough to your overall health to justify the wear and tear on your knees? The questions and complexity are endless. Here are a few of the exercise “musts” you hear all the time.

  1. 每天进行三十分钟的有氧运动。
  2. Thirty minutes of aerobic exercise daily.
  3. 拉紧。
  4. Stretch.
  5. 补充水分。
  6. Hydrate.
  7. 力量训练后三十分钟内吃蛋白质。
  8. Eat protein within thirty minutes of strength training.
  9. 在高强度锻炼的前一天晚上补充碳水化合物。
  10. Carb-load the night before a big exercise day.
  11. 每隔一天进行阻力训练和重量训练。
  12. Do resistance and weight training every other day.
  13. 做三组，每组十到十五次。
  14. Do three sets of ten to fifteen reps.
  15. 多休息。
  16. Get lots of rest.
  17. 改变你的锻炼方式来创造“肌肉混乱”。
  18. Vary your workout to create “muscle confusion.”
  19. 采用适当的方式进行举升。
  20. Use proper form for lifting.

这只是部分情况。能做到这一切的人只有专业运动员、私人教练、失业者以及社会上不受欢迎的人。对于其他人来说，这根本不切实际。

That’s just a partial list. The only people who can do all that right are serious athletes, personal trainers, the unemployed, and the socially unpopular. For everyone else, it’s simply not practical.

对于已婚人士来说，锻炼失败的一个典型例子是这样的：

For married people, an excellent way to fail at exercise starts like this:

你： “嘿，亲爱的，你愿意一小时后和我一起散步吗？

YOU: “Hey, honey, would you like to take a walk with me in an hour?

配偶： “这得看情况。也许吧。”

SPOUSE: “It depends. Maybe.”

（然后生活就变得如此艰难。）

(And then life gets in the way.)

这是另一种失败的方式。

Here’s another way to fail.

你： “我两点钟要去健身房。”

YOU: “I’m going to the gym at two o’clock.”

配偶： “但这正是蒂米需要被带去参加他的生日派对的时候。”

SPOUSE: “But that’s exactly when Timmy needs to be taken to his birthday party.”

还有另外...

And another . . .

你： “克里斯约我今晚七点打网球。”

YOU: “Chris asked me to play tennis at seven tonight.”

配偶： “我本来想和你一起看电影，但如果你喜欢克里斯胜过喜欢我，那好吧。”

SPOUSE: “I was hoping to see a movie with you then, but if you like Chris more than you like me, fine.”

顺便说一句，如果你把这些例子中的“配偶”理解为“妻子”，你可能就是个性别歧视者。性别歧视是双向的。一旦你试图同时满足两个而不是一个日程安排，所有看似可有可无的活动，比如锻炼，都会被推到“以后”去做。那么，该如何解决呢？

By the way, if you assumed “spouse” means “wife” in those examples, you might be a sexist jerk. It works both ways. As soon as you try to satisfy two schedules instead of one, all your seemingly optional activities such as exercise get pushed to “later.” So what’s the fix?

在婚姻或类似婚姻的情况下安排锻炼有三种实用的方法：

There are three practical ways to schedule exercise in a marriage or marriage-like situation:

  1. 加入一个有组织的团队。
  2. Join an organized team.
  3. 每天始终在同一时间锻炼。
  4. Always exercise at the same time every day.
  5. 一起锻炼（如果你们俩都真心这么做的话）。
  6. Exercise together (if you both really mean it).

当我妻子雪莉告诉我她周四晚上有一场网球联赛时，她缺席从来不会让我感到被抛弃。首先，我总是能提前收到通知，可以自己安排比赛，这很棒。但更重要的是，我知道雪莉并没有选择比赛的具体日期和时间。比赛是由某个不知名的第三方安排的，这让我觉得没问题，因为我知道雪莉并不是故意选择在那个特定时间缺席的。当然，在某种程度上，这和雪莉事先知道比赛会在周四晚上进行，然后她选择加入球队是一样的。但感觉不一样。这才是最重要的。只要有机会，就参加一个有固定时间表的团队运动项目。你的配偶仍然会感到不便，但不会觉得不方便。

When my wife, Shelly, tells me she has a tennis league match scheduled on a Thursday night, her absence never makes me feel abandoned. For starters, I always have advance notice and can make my own plans, which is great. But even more important, I know Shelly didn’t pick the specific date and time of the match. The fact that the game is scheduled by some unknown third party makes it okay with me because I know that Shelly didn’t make a conscious choice to be away at that specific time. Sure, sure, on some level, it’s the same thing because Shelly knew in advance that matches would be on Thursday nights, and she chose to join the team. But it feels different. And that’s what matters. Whenever you can, join a team sport that has a set schedule. Your spouse will still be inconvenienced, but it won’t feel personal.

如果你不喜欢团队运动，那么次优方案就是每天安排同一时间锻炼。Shelly 可以告诉你我每周二下午 12:40 会在哪里。我会在健身房，刚刚完成阻力训练，准备在有氧运动前做一些拉伸。Shelly 有时会觉得我的常规锻炼安排不方便，但这对我来说并不是什么私人问题，因为这是我的锻炼系统。我不会为了和妻子共进浪漫午餐而放弃锻炼；我只是有一套锻炼系统而已。某种程度上来说，它们是一样的，但感觉却截然不同。而这正是它的美妙之处。

If team sports aren’t your thing, the next best solution is to schedule your exercise for the same time every day. Shelly can tell you where I will be on any given Tuesday at 12:40 PM. I will be at the gym, just finishing my resistance training and heading for some stretching before cardio. Shelly finds my regular exercise schedule inconvenient at times, but it doesn’t feel personal because it’s my system. I don’t decide to be unavailable for a romantic lunch with my wife; I simply have an exercise system. On some level it’s the same, but it sure feels different. And that’s the beauty.

我选择午餐时间锻炼，因为早上更利于我的创意工作，而下午的工作和家庭时间安排则难以预测。其他成功的锻炼者会在太阳升起前很早就起床锻炼。还有一些人下班后直接去健身房。对于每种情况，关键在于要有一个可预测的锻炼计划。永远不会成功的方法是一有空闲时间就锻炼。如果你和大多数成年人一样，那你已经好几年没有空闲时间了。

I exercise at lunchtime because mornings are better for my creative work and afternoons are unpredictable in terms of work and family time. Other successful exercisers get up long before the sun to do their workouts. Still others go straight from work to the gym. In each case, the key is to have a predictable system. The method that never succeeds is exercising whenever you have some spare time. If you’re like most adults, you haven’t seen spare time in years.

锻炼的动力

Motivation to Exercise

我保持每天活力充沛的体系包含几个部分。我已经解释过饮食对保持精力充沛的重要性。此外，最重要的规则是，你一天的运动量不要太大，以免第二天不想活动。换句话说，今天的合适运动量就是让我期待明天能继续运动的量。

My system for staying in the mood to be active every day has several parts. I already explained the importance of diet in keeping your energy up. After that, the most important rule is that you should never exercise so much in one day that you won’t feel like being active the next day. To put that another way, the right amount of exercise today is whatever amount makes me look forward to being active tomorrow.

我以前的锻炼方式就是拼命锻炼，第二天几乎动弹不得。我心想，没有付出就没有收获。我以为我越努力，效果就越好。但坚持需要意志力，如果我在健身房耗尽了意志力，我开车经过甜甜圈店的时候几乎都会被它吸引过去。

My old exercise system involved working out so hard I could barely move the next day. No pain, no gain, I thought. I figured the harder I pushed myself, the better. But pushing takes willpower, and if I use up my willpower at the gym, I can barely drive past the donut shop without being sucked in there.

酸痛就像是对锻炼的惩罚。人类和狗没什么不同：如果每次我做某事都受到惩罚，最终我会找到一个理由停止做这件事。这个理由大概就是“太忙了”。

And the soreness is like a penalty for exercising. Humans aren’t that different from dogs: If you give me a penalty every time I do something, eventually I’ll find a reason to stop doing it. And that reason will be something along the lines of “too busy.”

你想要的是每天的锻炼都能给你带来回报。轻度运动就能做到这一点；它能减轻你的压力，增强你的能量。随着时间的推移，随着你变得更健康，你自然会提高运动量，但到那时，你的身体已经能够承受了。

What you want is for your daily exercise to give you a reward every time. Light exercise does just that; it reduces your stress and boosts your energy. Over time, as you become fitter, you will naturally increase your exercise level, but by then your body will be equipped to handle it.

如果你想养成习惯，最糟糕的做法就是挑三拣四地选择一周中哪几天做，哪几天不做。只有每天坚持锻炼，才能养成习惯。在锻炼日之间安排休息日，会破坏养成习惯的模式。这也会让你很容易就把今天定为不锻炼日——也许明天也不例外。

If you want to make a habit of something, the worst thing you can do is pick and choose which days of the week you do it and which you don’t. Exercise becomes a habit when you do it every day without fail. Taking rest days between exercise days breaks up the pattern that creates habits. It also makes it too easy to say today is one of your non-exercise days—and maybe tomorrow, too.

报酬

Reward

我发现运动后犒劳自己很重要，比如吃点自己喜欢的健康零食，或者在手机上读读有趣的文章，或者喝杯好咖啡。把这些乐趣放在运动结束后，我就能把运动和美好的感觉紧密联系起来。这就能养成习惯。

I find it important to reward myself after exercise with a healthy snack I enjoy, some downtime that involves reading interesting articles on my phone, or a nice cup of coffee. By putting those pleasures at the immediate end of my exercise, I develop a strong association between the exercise and the good feelings. That’s habit-forming.

正如我之前提到的——值得再次强调——咖啡是我锻炼动力的很大一部分。咖啡能提升运动表现，但更重要的是，它能让你更愿意付出努力。68-70如果你不是每天都锻炼，也不喝咖啡，也许你应该试试。我都数不清有多少次因为太累而放弃了锻炼，但一杯咖啡之后，我却彻底改变了主意。

As I’ve mentioned—and it’s worth repeating—a big part of my exercise motivation is coffee. Coffee boosts athletic performance but more importantly makes you willing to put in the effort. 68-70 If you’re not exercising every day and don’t drink coffee, maybe you should give it a try. I can’t tell you how many times I ruled out exercise because I was too tired, only to completely change my mind after a cup of coffee.

我还发现，布洛芬（Advil 和其他品牌的成分）有助于减轻我运动过量时的酸痛。如果我在肌肉僵硬的日子服用布洛芬，第二天就很有可能恢复运动。不服用布洛芬，我感觉就像《绿野仙踪》里的铁皮人——我只想要我的油罐。我不推荐你服用布洛芬，因为我不是医生，而且过量服用会有风险。请咨询你的医生。

I also find that ibuprofen (as found in Advil and other brands) helps reduce my soreness on those days I overdo it. If I take the ibuprofen on days I’m stiff, there’s a good chance I’ll feel up to exercising the next day. Without the ibuprofen, I feel like the Tin Man on The Wizard of Oz—all I want is my oil can. I can’t recommend ibuprofen for you because I’m not a doctor and because there are risks if you overdo it. Ask your doctor.

那么，当你只想窝在沙发上吃冰淇淋、心情不好的时候，该如何锻炼呢？当你大脑的一部分知道锻炼是个好主意，而另一部分却在行使否决权时，你还能重新激活你的身体吗？

So how do you exercise on those days when all you want to do is sit on the couch, eat ice cream, and feel bad? Can you jump-start your body when one part of your brain knows that exercise is a good idea but another part of your brain is using its veto power?

我发现最有效的技巧是利用你生活中的某些线索，或者催眠师喜欢称之为“钥匙”。例如，如果你小时候被一只德国牧羊犬咬过，那么每次看到这种狗，你可能会感到一阵恐惧。这就是线索——一把钥匙。你的生活中充满了这些可以控制你态度的小线索和钥匙。诀窍在于以一种编程你的思维的方式来操纵你自己的线索。

The trick I’ve found that works best takes advantage of certain cues in your life, or “keys,” as hypnotists like to call them. For example, if you were bitten by a German Shepherd dog as a child, every time you see that type of dog you might get a little burst of fear. That’s a cue—a key. Your life is full of these little cues and keys that can control your attitude. The trick is manipulating your own cues in a way that programs your mind.

当我知道我应该锻炼，但又感到疲惫不堪、无精打采，无法想象进行剧烈运动时，我会这样做。我不会去做那些我感觉做不到的事，而是去做我能做的事——穿上运动服，系好运动鞋。（在你居住的地方，你可能会把它们叫做网球鞋或跑鞋。）我的方法的核心是，即使已经穿好运动服，我也完全允许自己不去锻炼。这一点很重要，因为我知道，如果我执着于一件在我现在的心态下看似不可能完成的事情，我就不会迈出穿上运动服的第一步。

Here’s what I do when I know I should exercise but I feel too tired and droopy to imagine doing a vigorous workout. Instead of doing what I feel I can’t do, I do what I can do—which is put on my exercise clothes and lace my sneakers. (You might call them tennis shoes or running shoes where you live.) Central to my method is that I grant myself 100 percent permission to NOT exercise, even after getting suited up for it. This is important because I know I won’t take the first step of donning my exercise clothes if I feel committed to something that just seems impossible in my current frame of mind.

但一旦穿上运动鞋和短裤，一件奇妙的事情就发生了，而且发生得很快。运动服给我带来的身体感觉触发了我大脑中“去健身房”的子程序，我的精力一下子提升了一个档次。就像巴甫洛夫的“流口水狗”一样。运动服让我对锻炼产生积极的想法，这提升了我的能量。

But once the sneakers and shorts are on, a funny thing happens, and it happens quickly. The physical feeling I get from my exercise clothes triggers my going-to-the-gym subroutine in my brain, and my energy kicks up a notch. It’s like Pavlov’s salivating dogs. The exercise clothes cause me to think positive thoughts about exercising, and that boosts my energy.

突然间，锻炼的想法似乎变得可行，即便并非那么诱人。还有一步，同样需要允许自己随时放弃。我开车去附近的健身房，走进去，环顾四周，看看感觉如何。大约95%的情况下，这些提示能让我保持良好的心情去锻炼，进而提升我的情绪。但有时——今年大概发生过五次，这种情况很常见——我到了健身房，环顾四周，转身离开。开车回家的路上，我并没有觉得自己失败了。事实上，我的感觉恰恰相反。失败是属于有目标的人的。如果我的目标是锻炼，那么不费吹灰之力就离开健身房，看起来和感觉起来都像是失败。但我拥有的不是目标，而是一个系统。而这个系统允许漏洞百出。它就是这样设计的。当我开车从健身房回家——这趟看似白跑一趟——我从未感到挫败。相反，我感觉自己在运用一个我知道总体上行之有效的系统。锻炼身体就是赢家；如果坚持锻炼，决定不锻炼，那也是赢家（尽管赢面小）。不管怎样，我的态度都变好了。至少我可以走出家门，理清思绪。一切都很好。

Suddenly, the idea of exercising seems possible if not desirable. There’s one more step, and this, too, requires granting yourself permission to back out at any time. I drive to my local gym, walk in, look around, and see how I feel. About 95 percent of the time, this set of cues puts me in a sufficient mood to go ahead and exercise, and that in turn boosts my mood. But sometimes—and this happened perhaps five times this year, which is typical—I get to the gym, look around, turn, and leave. As I drive home, I’m not thinking I failed. In fact, I feel exactly the opposite. Failure is for people who have goals. If my goal is to exercise, leaving the gym without breaking a sweat looks and feels like failure. But what I have is not a goal; it is a system. And the system allows leakage. It’s designed that way. As I drive home from the gym—a seemingly wasted trip—I never feel defeated. Instead, I feel I’m using a system that I know works overall. I win if I exercise, and I win (albeit less) if I use my system and decide not to work out. Either way, my attitude improves. And at least I get out of the house and clear my head. It’s all good.

不必在意运动量。长远来看，重要的是养成日常锻炼的习惯。研究表明，适度的运动对长寿最有益。71-75

Don’t be concerned about how much or how little you exercise. All that matters in the long run is that you make exercise a daily habit. Studies indicate that moderate levels of exercise are optimal for longevity.71-75

随着时间的推移，您自然会倾向于增加您的身体可以承受的多样性和挑战。

Over time, you’ll naturally gravitate toward adding the variety and challenge that your body can handle.

护发死亡螺旋

Hair-Care Death-Spiral

2011年，美国卫生局局长雷吉娜·M·本杰明博士因声称太多女性因为头发问题而放弃锻炼而登上头条新闻。在她看来，这是一个重要的健康问题。《纽约时报》援引本杰明的话说：“经常会听到女性说，‘我今天不能锻炼了，因为我不想把头发弄得汗流浃背，或者把头发弄湿。’当你开始锻炼的时候，你会找各种理由不去锻炼，有时头发就是其中一个原因。” 76

In 2011,United States surgeon general Dr. Regina M. Benjamin made headlines by saying that too many women were skipping exercise because of hair-related issues. In her view, this qualified as an important health issue. The New York Times quoted Benjamin as saying, ”’Often times you get women saying, ’I can’t exercise today because I don’t want to sweat my hair back or get my hair wet.’ When you’re starting to exercise, you look for reasons not to, and sometimes the hair is one of those reasons.”76

本杰明博士的观察结果与我自己的观察结果相符——而且很可能也与你的观察结果相符，我认为我不需要解释为什么从长远来看将头发置于健康之上是一种失败的策略。

Dr. Benjamin’s observations match my own—and yours, too, most likely, I don’t think I need to explain why putting your hair above your health is a loser strategy in the long run.

如果你是一位深陷护发泥潭的女性，除非你能摆脱困境，否则本书里说的一切都帮不了你。请允许我提供一个可行的解决方案。

If you’re a woman caught in the hair-care death-spiral, nothing I’ve said in this book will be much help unless you escape. Allow me to offer a possible solution.

首先，我假设女性想要拥有一头秀发主要有三个原因：1）吸引性伴侣，2）提升职业潜力，3）自我感觉良好。每个人都不一样，但这三个原因大概涵盖了85%的原因。

I’m going to start with the assumption that there are three main reasons a woman wants great-looking hair: 1) attract sexual partners, 2) improve career potential, and 3) feel good about herself. Everyone is different, but those three causes probably cover 85 percent of the reasons.

前两个原因（性伴侣和职业选择）是为了影响别人对你的看法。我认为，只有当你知道自己正在影响他人，让他们也产生同样的感受时，自我感觉良好才有意义。所以，护发其实就是为了影响别人对你的看法。我们都是社会动物，所以这本身并没有错。只有当我们在意别人的想法时，世界才会运转。

The first two reasons (sexual partners and career options) are about influencing how others view you. And I would argue that feeling good about yourself only has meaning because you know you are influencing others to feel the same way. So really, hair-care is about influencing how other people feel about you. We’re all social animals, so there’s nothing wrong with that. The world only works when we care how other people think.

关于女性头发的话题，我只能从一个异性恋男性的角度来谈。我建议你问问你生活中的男性，确认一下。我猜我接下来说的，应该算是男性所能拥有的最普遍的看法了：

On the topic of women’s hair, I can only speak from a heterosexual man’s perspective. I encourage you to check with the men in your life for confirmation. My best guess is that what I say next is as near a universal opinion as men can have:

我们更希望您健康。

We Prefer You Healthy.

我从未见过哪个男人会喜欢长得不健康、头发像电影明星一样的女人，而不是扎着马尾辫的健美女人。如果我真遇到这种人，我会尽量躲着他，因为他听起来像个怪人。

I’ve never known a man who would prefer an unhealthy-looking woman with movie star hair over a fit woman with a ponytail. And if I ever do meet that guy, I’ll try to avoid him because he sounds like a creep.

招聘经理总是会潜意识地偏爱看起来更健康的求职者，无论男女。人类进化出对任何看起来健康的人都抱有好感的印象，因为健康是良好生育能力的标志。这就是为什么社会需要法律来限制对残障人士的歧视。如果你花时间打理头发的主要原因是为了自我感觉良好，那么健康的身体永远比一头漂亮的发型更重要。

A hiring manager will always have a subconscious bias for the healthier-looking applicant, male or female. Humans evolved to have favorable opinions about anyone who looks healthy because it’s a marker for good reproductive odds. That’s why society needs laws that limit discrimination against the differently abled. If your main reason for spending time on your hair is to feel good about yourself, a healthy body will always trump a good hairdo.

说到头发，我可不想假装了解女人的想法。每个女人都不一样。有些女人午饭前就像三个不同的人。但我可以肯定地告诉你，男人更喜欢你身体健康，即使这意味着我们无法让你的头发达到最佳状态。

I won’t pretend to understand the minds of women when it comes to hair. And every woman is different. Some women are three different people before lunchtime. But I can tell you with certainty that men prefer you to be in good health, even if it means we miss the best of your hair potential.

我想，要改变多年来已成为你生活一部分的护发习惯肯定很难。但换个角度思考或许会有所帮助。如果你因为头发问题而放弃锻炼，那么在梳头、卷发、拉直和吹干头发的漫长时间里，提醒自己，你长期的努力最终会降低你的吸引力、就业竞争力和健康状况。当你改变思维方式时，最终你的行为也会改变。

I would imagine it’s very hard to break a hair-care routine that has been part of your life for years. But it might help to think of this in a different way. If you skip exercise because of your hair, remind yourself during those many hours of brushing, curling, straightening, and drying that the long-term payoff for your efforts is to become less attractive, less employable, and less healthy. When you change how you think, you eventually change how you behave.

拥有一头秀发只是短期目标。健身是一个系统，而这个系统是为赢家而设的。

Having great hair is a short-term goal. Fitness is a system. Systems are for winners.

第33章

Chapter 33

语音更新 II

Voice Update II

T我失声已经三年了。越来越难以想象它还能恢复。表面上看，我的生活似乎步入正轨。《呆伯特》在65个国家的2000多家报纸上连载。我嫁给了雪莉，开始组建家庭。外表看来，一切都很美好，但内心却受到了严重的伤害。我的乐观精神一天24小时都在遭受打击，但不知何故，它依然充满活力。

Three years had passed since I lost my voice. It was getting hard to imagine it could ever be fixed. Outwardly, my life looked to be on track. Dilbert was running in over 2,000 newspapers in sixty-five countries. I married Shelly, and we started building a home. Externally, things were great, but on the inside, I was badly damaged. My optimism was getting its ass kicked twenty-four hours a day, but somehow it still had a pulse.

生活中的琐事都变成了恐惧。每次电话铃响，我的心就沉了下去。每次有人问问题，我的内心都会崩溃。情感上，这令人困惑。我的生活一半美好，一半却阴暗破碎。我继续默念着我的誓言——“我，斯科特，会完美地表达。”——但我已经没有什么补救措施可以尝试了。我的未来一片黯淡。

The simple things in life had become terrors. Every time the phone rang, my heart sank. Every time someone asked a question, I died a little on the inside. Emotionally, it was confusing. Half my life was great while half was darkly broken. I continued doing my affirmation—“I, Scott, will speak perfectly.”— but I was running out of potential remedies to try. My future looked bleak.

有一天，我的邮箱里又出现了一条谷歌快讯。与之前无数的虚假信息不同，这条快讯看起来很有希望。一位日本医生报告说，通过颈部手术成功治疗了痉挛性发声障碍。如果需要，我愿意飞往日本。如果有必要，我甚至愿意游过去。那时，我在寻求治愈方法的过程中已经经历了太多的失望，以至于雪莉对我这个渺茫的新希望提不起多少热情。我知道，她不喜欢看到我和她都燃起希望，却一次又一次地落空。

One day, another Google Alert showed up in my email inbox. Unlike the numerous false leads, this one looked promising. A doctor in Japan was reporting success treating spasmodic dysphonia with a surgical procedure on the neck. I was willing to fly to Japan if needed. I would have swum there if I had to. By then,I had experienced so many disappointments in my search for a cure that Shelly couldn’t muster much enthusiasm for my new longshot hope. I know she didn’t enjoy seeing me get my hopes up and hers as well just to be thrown against the rocks time and time again.

按照惯例，我把这项新手术的消息告诉了我的常规医生史密斯医生，他把我转介给了我的耳鼻喉科医生科尼利厄斯·詹森三世医生。詹森医生之前从未听说过这项新手术，他担心成功的报道可能被夸大了。他解释说，有些所谓的医学突破比其他的更可信，所以我不应该认为这份报道是准确的。我并不感到惊讶。实际上，通过在颈部进行某种变通手术来修复脑部异常的可能性有多大？这听起来甚至对我来说都有些可疑。

Following protocol, I took the news of this new operation to my regular doctor, Dr. Smith, who referred me to my Ear-Nose-Throat doctor, Dr. Cornelius Jansen III. Dr. Jansen hadn’t yet heard of this new surgery, and he was concerned that the reports of success might be exaggerated. He explained that some proclaimed medical breakthroughs are more credible than others, so I shouldn’t assume this report was accurate. I wasn’t surprised. Realistically, how likely is it that you can fix a brain abnormality by rigging up some sort of workaround in the neck? It sounded iffy even to me.

但为了探索所有可能方案，Jansen医生建议我咨询该领域的顶尖专家之一，斯坦福医学院耳鼻喉科的Edward Damrose医生。Damrose医生熟悉来自日本的报告，但他建议我联系一位离我家较近的医生，这位医生正在开创一种治疗痉挛性发声障碍的另一种手术。他把我介绍给了加州大学洛杉矶分校医学中心的Gerald Berke医生。

But in the interest of exploring every option, Dr. Jansen recommended I speak to one of the top professionals in the field, Dr. Edward Damrose of the otolaryngology department at the Stanford School of Medicine. Dr .Damrose was familiar with the reports coming from Japan, but he suggested I contact a doctor closer to home who was pioneering a different type of surgery for spasmodic dysphonia. He referred me to Dr. Gerald Berke at the UCLA Medical Center.

我挂断了和达姆罗斯医生的电话，感到很困惑。我之前都没听说过这种病，怎么可能通过手术治愈呢？如果专门针对这种疾病的网站都没有提到，这怎么可能呢？我能想到的唯一解释是，这又是一个错误的线索，最终却又走进了死胡同。但我的原则是，无论多么荒谬或不可能，我都会追查所有线索。

I got off the phone with Dr. Damrose feeling puzzled. How could there be a surgical fix for this condition that I hadn’t heard about until now? How could this be true if there was no mention of it on websites dedicated specifically to this disorder? The only explanation I could imagine was that this would be another false lead to another dead end. But my system was to follow all leads, no matter how ridiculous or unlikely.

我和伯克医生预约了初诊，并从旧金山附近的家飞到洛杉矶与他见面。伯克医生是个很有意思的人物：才华横溢、自信满满，还有点神秘感。一小群来自其他诊所的医生跟着他从一个房间到另一个房间，学习他的诊疗方法。伯克医生和他的随行医生给我做了检查，确诊我患有痉挛性发声障碍。然后他解释说，过去几年他一直在完善一种针对这种疾病的手术，成功率大约为85%，这意味着病人术后的声音比术前更好——虽然不是完美，但也有很大的改善。不幸的是，有些人术后病情恶化，甚至失去了仅存的声音。但伯克医生很清楚为什么有些病人的手术成功率较低，并且正在改进他的技术来解释这种现象。

I made an appointment with Dr. Berke for an initial visit and flew from my home near San Francisco to Los Angeles to meet with him. Dr. Berke is an interesting character: brilliant, confident, and a little bit mysterious. A small herd of doctors from other practices followed him from room to room to learn his ways. Dr. Berke and his tag-along doctors examined me and confirmed the diagnosis of spasmodic dysphonia. Then he explained that he had been perfecting a surgery for this condition over the past several years, with about an 85 percent success rate, which in this context means the patient had a better voice after surgery than before—not a perfect voice, but substantially improved. Unfortunately, some people got worse after surgery, losing what little was left of their voices. But Dr. Berke had a good idea why some patients were less successful, and he was refining his technique to account for it.

但有趣的是，伯克医生的手术需要打开颈部前部，切断连接大脑和声带的神经，然后利用从颈部其他部位借来的神经建立新的通路。重新连接完成后，患者需要等待三个半月，直到新的神经通路再生，声音恢复。在此之前，患者的大脑和声带无法连接。术后无需复诊。手术要么成功，要么失败。

But here’s the interesting part. Dr. Berke’s surgery involved opening the front of the neck, cutting the nerves that lead from the brain to the vocal cords, then building a new path using nerves borrowed from elsewhere in your neck. Once the rewiring was done, the patient waited three-and-a-half months until the new nerve pathways regenerated and the voice came back. Until then, the patient’s brain and vocal cords wouldn’t be connected. There were no follow-up visits to the doctor. It either worked or it didn’t.

这听起来像是修复脑部异常的方法吗？在我看来，这似乎不太合理。所以我索要了一份既往患者名单作为参考。我既充满希望，又心存疑虑。我觉得这个手术毫无意义，而且我还在琢磨为什么网上到处都找不到这些信息。

Does that sound like the way you fix a brain abnormality? It didn’t sound like a logical solution to me. So I asked for a list of past patients as references. I was hopeful but skeptical. The operation didn’t make sense to me, and I was still scratching my head as to why none of this had appeared on the Internet yet.

我给伯克医生的几位病人发了邮件，约好时间跟他们通话——如果可以这么说的话——电话。这是唯一一个我能自信地跟他们通话的人，因为他们能听懂我断断续续、沙哑的言语。他们也明白，这通电话主要是他们自己说的。

I emailed some of Dr. Berke’s patients and set up a time to speak with them—if you can call it that—by phone. This was the one group of folks I could speak to confidently on the phone because they were skilled at deciphering my broken, raspy attempts at words. They also understood that the call was mostly about them doing the talking.

他们确实说话了，完美无缺。他们说话时没有一丝停顿或犹豫。没有嘶哑或断断续续的声音。每个人都说手术后的恢复过程很不愉快，因为在相当长的一段时间里，几乎每次吃东西或喝水都会被呛到，但他们一致认为这是值得的。

And talk they did. Perfectly. Not one of them had a hitch or a hesitation in their words. There was no hoarseness or clipped syllables. Each described the recovery from the operation as unpleasant because you choke nearly every time you try to eat or drink for quite some time, but they were unanimous in saying it was worth it.

显然，我只是在和那些取得最佳结果的幸运儿交谈，但我对这种可能性感到乐观。不过，我需要满足一下我的好奇心：我问伯克医生，他是如何发现颈部神经手术可以修复脑部异常的。他发现了哪些其他人没有发现的证据？

Obviously, I was only talking to the lucky people who had the best results, but I was feeling good about the possibility. Still, I needed to satisfy my curiosity about one thing: I asked Dr. Berke how he figured out that nerve surgery in the neck could fix a brain abnormality. What evidence did he see that others did not?

他的回答让我着迷。我想这解释了为什么医生们都围着他转。我转述一下，但伯克医生解释说，这是一种灵感，不知何故源于他对颈部、喉咙、声音、神经等等的全面了解。他没说这是天才之举，但如果这次手术成功了，其他任何形容都再合适不过了。

His answer fascinated me. I suppose it explains why doctors follow him around. I’m paraphrasing, but Dr. Berke explained that it was an inspiration that somehow emerged from the sum of his knowledge about necks and throats and voices and nerves and all the rest. He didn’t call it genius, but if this surgery worked, no other description would fit quite as well.

如果我决定做手术，我的声音大概有15%的可能性无法改善。在这种情况下，手术本身可能会让我失去任何未来治疗的机会。这就像一场通往未知目的地的单程旅行。

If I decided to do the surgery, there was something on the order of a 15 percent chance my voice would not improve. In that scenario, the surgery itself might eliminate any chance I could benefit from some future treatment. It was a one-way trip to a destination unknown.

我安排了手术。

I scheduled the surgery.

第34章

Chapter 34

运气

Luck

左当讨论成功时，我们来谈谈一个显而易见的问题：运气。

Let’s talk about the elephant in the room when it comes to any discussion of success: luck.

我的世界观是，所有成功，如果追溯其根源，都是运气。史蒂夫·乔布斯需要天生就带有史蒂夫·乔布斯的DNA，也需要遇到一个叫史蒂夫·沃兹尼亚克的人。如果比尔·盖茨出生在我出生的地方，他周末就会去打土拨鼠，帮助当地的奶农，而不是学习电脑编程。沃伦·巴菲特也对自己的技能有过类似的评价，他实际上是说，如果他出生在更早的时代，他的天赋就无法与机遇相匹配。

My worldview is that all success is luck if you track it back to its source. Steve Jobs needed to be born with Steve Jobs’ DNA, and he needed to meet a fellow named Steve Wozniak. If Bill Gates had been born where I was born, he would have been shooting woodchucks on weekends to help the local dairy farmers instead of learning to program computers. Warren Buffett makes a similar observation about his own skills, saying, in effect, that if he had been born in an earlier time, his natural talents wouldn’t have matched the opportunities.

我的世界观是，你性格中的每一个元素——从你的毅力到你的风险承受能力，从你的雄心壮志到你的智力——都是纯粹机遇的产物。你需要与生俱来的基因和你人生的具体经历，才能塑造出你现在的样子和你拥有的机会。你做的每一个决定，都是这些变量简单的数学积。

My worldview is that every element of your personality—from your perseverance to your risk tolerance to your ambition to your intelligence—is a product of pure chance. You needed the genes you were born with and the exact experiences of your life to create the person you are with the opportunities you have. Every decision you make is a simple math product of those variables.

如果成功完全是运气，那么一本探讨成功的书还有什么意义呢？这种想法完全合情合理。而且这很重要，因为如果你相信所有成功都取决于运气，你就不太可能像相信成功源于努力那样努力。无论你拥有什么样的基因和环境，历史告诉我们，你仍然需要努力才能成功。相信纯粹的运气会对你不利吗？

What good is a book that discusses success if success is entirely luck? That’s a perfectly reasonable thing to wonder. And it matters because if you believe all success is based on luck, you’re not likely to try as hard as if you believe success comes from hard work. No matter what genes and circumstances you have, history tells us you still need to work hard to pull it off. Does a belief in pure luck work against you?

可以，但没必要。

It can, but it doesn’t need to.

这本书已经成为你人生经历的一部分。如果我做得对，书中的某些部分会在你的脑海中反复出现，并通过你的观察得到强化。就像任何经历一样，一本书会不由自主地改变你，哪怕只是微不足道的改变。但每个人都是不同的。一本书可以对一个人产生深远的影响，而对另一个人的影响却微乎其微。

This book has just become part of your experience. If I did my job right, some parts of it will repeat in your head and be reinforced by your own observations. Like any experience, you can’t help but be changed by a book, if only a trivial amount. But everyone is different. One book can have a profound effect on one person and a tiny impact on another.

假设你在接下来的一年里读完了这本书，请留意我写的内容有多少次让你想起。有没有哪次你不想运动，却又想起我教你穿上运动服的小妙招？你是否因为注意到简单碳水化合物会让你在白天犯困而避免在午餐时吃它们？你是否正在寻找将失败转化为成功的方法？

In the coming year, assuming you made it through this entire book, notice how many times you are reminded of something I wrote. Is there a time you don’t feel like exercising but you remember my trick of putting on your exercise clothes anyway? Do you steer clear of the simple carbs for lunch because you noticed they make you sleepy during the day? Are you looking for ways to turn your failures into something good?

如果一本书无法以某种方式改变你，你就不会买它，即使这种改变只是娱乐或增长你的知识。书籍会自动改变我们，就像任何经历一样。如果一本书能帮助你以更有意义的方式看待世界，或增强你的能量，它就会成为你个人运气的一部分。

You wouldn’t buy a book if it didn’t have the potential to change you in some way, even if that change is just entertainment or an increase in your knowledge. Books change us automatically, just as any experience does. And if a book helps you see the world in a more useful way or amps up your energy, it becomes part of the fabric of your personal luck.

现在的你和刚开始读这本书时的你完全不同了——真的。你的一些细胞已经死亡并被替换。你的身体已经成熟，即使只有几个小时。你的大脑根据自身的化学反应以及所有外界影响（包括你所读的内容）调整了其内部结构。如果这本书中的任何内容让你印象深刻，那么随着时间的推移，它很可能会得到强化。你现在是一个全新的人了。

You’re a different person now than you were when you started this book—literally. Some of your cells have died and been replaced. Your body has matured, even if only a few hours. And your brain has modified its internal structure based on its chemistry and all your outside influences, including what you read. If anything in this book sticks in your mind, it will probably get reinforced over time. You’re a new person now.

读完这本书，你不需要做任何事情。你已经改变了。

You don’t need to do anything as a result of reading this book. You’ve already changed.

第35章

Chapter 35

语音更新 III

Voice Update III

T护士们用轮床把我推进了手术室。我已经注射了减压药物，效果非常好。麻醉师让我从100开始倒数​​，我高兴极了。我数到了98。感觉就像是幸福地死去一样。

The nurses rolled me into the operating room on a gurney. I was already drugged up with stress-reducing medicines that were working wonders. I couldn’t have been happier as the anesthesiologist asked me to count backwards from a hundred. I made it to ninety-eight. It felt like dying happy.

恢复期真是糟透了。我几乎把所有想吞下去的东西都噎住了，这种情况持续了好几个月。我可以低声说话，因为那不用声带。但就我的大脑而言，我的声带就像在月球上一样。它们之间没有交流。

The recovery period was wretched. I choked on nearly everything I tried to swallow, and that situation lasted months. I could whisper because that doesn’t involve the vocal cords. But my vocal cords might have been on the moon as far as my brain was concerned. They weren’t talking to each other.

幸运的是，画漫画不需要说话。手术后的迷雾消散后，几天后我就回去工作了。我等待着。伯克医生告诉我，神经再生的速度非常可预测。如果手术成功，三个半月后，神经就能在我的大脑和声带之间建立起第一次完整的连接。之后，我可能需要一年时间才能真正正常地说话。而且，这还得在手术成功的情况下。

Luckily, cartooning doesn’t require speaking. I was back to work in a few days once the brain-fog of surgery lifted. And I waited. Dr. Berke told me that nerves regenerate at a very predictable rate. In three-and-a-half months, if the surgery worked, the nerves would make their first full connection between my brain and my vocal cords. And after that, it might take a year to speak in a truly normal way. And that is only if the surgery worked.

那几个月里，我经常试着说话，只是想看看会发生什么。但事实上，我的大脑已经无法与声带沟通了。那种感觉很奇怪。所以我在家时会低声说话，在嘈杂的环境中会做笔记，把所有想说的话都咽下去，然后等待。我还会在脑海里反复念叨我的肯定句，哪怕只是为了支撑我的乐观。

I often tried to speak during those months, just to see what would happen. But indeed, my brain was no longer communicating with my vocal cords. It was an odd feeling. So I whispered when I was at home, wrote notes when I was in noisy environments, choked on everything that went down my throat, and waited. I also repeated my affirmations in my head, if for no other reason than to prop up my optimism.

我，斯科特·亚当斯，将会讲得非常完美。

I, Scott Adams, will speak perfectly.

手术三个半月后，几乎是手术当天，雪莉站在客厅里，难以置信地盯着我。她说：“你刚才……说话了。” 果然，我说话了。我的声音不怎么样，很虚弱，带着呼吸声，一次只能说几个字。不过，正如计划所料，我的大脑和声带开始重新适应。这不算成功，只是一个开始。我还要几个月才能知道手术是否真的有效。我离“完美”地说话还差得远呢。但这确实很了不起，意义非凡……我哭了。

Three-and-a-half months after the surgery, almost to the day, Shelly stood in our living room and stared at me with disbelief. She said, “You just . . . talked.” And indeed, I had. It wasn’t much of a voice. It was weak and breathy, and I couldn’t sustain it beyond a few words at a time. But right on schedule, my brain and my vocal cords were becoming reacquainted. It wasn’t success. It was just a start. I had months to go before knowing if the surgery had worked in any meaningful way. And I was worlds away from my affirmation of speaking “perfectly.” But it was something. It was a lot. I cried.

在接下来的几个月里，我的声音逐渐好转。痉挛性发声障碍的音节脱落症状已经完全消失，但我的声音仍然虚弱、不均匀，有时还有些嘶哑。幸运的是，只要时间和练习，这些问题都是可以解决的。到那时，我已经对正确的发声技巧有了相当的了解，这要归功于我在寻求治愈方法期间进行了大量的声音治疗。

In the months that followed, my voice steadily improved. The dropping of syllables that defines spasmodic dysphonia was 100 percent gone, but my voice was weak, uneven, and sometimes hoarse. Luckily, these were fixable problems given time and practice. And by that point, I was quite knowledgeable about proper voice technique, thanks to my many hours of voice therapy while I was searching for a cure.

有趣的是，我的大脑不再训练声音的流畅性。即使我的声带功能恢复正常很久，我仍然难以形成连贯的句子。我已经近四年没能流利地说出完整的句子了。但随着时间的推移，我的流利程度也恢复了。

Interestingly, my brain was no longer practiced in vocal fluency. Long after my vocal cords were functioning normally, I had trouble forming coherent sentences. Speaking fluently in full sentences was something I hadn’t done for nearly four years. But over time, my fluency returned, too.
