手术几年后，我甚至不敢说自己已经达到了“完美说话”的境界——如果这种事真的存在的话。在患上痉挛性发声障碍之前，我的声音就很虚弱，而且鼻音很重，所以这似乎是我康复的现实上限。而且在我的大部分时间里，由于人群嘈杂，人们根本听不清我说话，因为我的语调似乎与背景完全混在一起。对我来说，恢复正常意味着回到糟糕的嗓音状态。那感觉就像成功了一样。

Several years after the surgery, I couldn’t say I had necessarily achieved my affirmation of speaking “perfectly,” if such a thing even exists. I had a weak and nasally voice before I ever got spasmodic dysphonia, so that seemed like the realistic upper limit for my recovery. And for most of my life, people couldn’t hear me over crowd noise because my tone seemed to blend exactly with the background. For me, getting back to normal meant getting back to a crappy voice. That would have felt like success.

令我惊讶的是，事实并非如此。这主要归功于我在手术前进行的所有发声训练，以及伯克医生推测我一生中可能存在的“潜在痉挛性发声障碍”，最终我的声音功能比以往任何时候都更加强大。在嘈杂的环境中，我的声音也能清晰地表达，而由于生活中很多地方都充满噪音，这对我来说是一个很大的进步。

To my surprise, that’s not exactly what happened. Thanks largely to all my voice training before the operation and to what Dr. Berke hypothesized might have been a “latent spasmodic dysphonia” all my life, I ended up with a far more functional voice than ever before. I have no problem projecting in noisy environments, and since much of life is noisy, that is a big, big improvement.

运动后我的声音还是有点嘶哑。而且我永远也拥有不了像广播里那样的音质。所以，从审美角度来说，我的声音仍然不够理想。但从功能角度来说，我的声音确实完美无缺。我终于摆脱了沉默的牢笼。生活从未如此愉悦，也从未如此满足。

I still get a bit hoarse after exercise. And I’ll never have a radio-quality voice. So aesthetically, my voice remains less than ideal. But functionally, my voice is indeed perfect. I have escaped from my prison cell of silence. And life has never been more enjoyable or more satisfying.

但如果你还记得的话，我还有一件事要做，或者说还有几件事。我当时的计划并非简单地逃离我的声音牢笼。我曾承诺，如果我成功逃脱，我将释放其他囚犯，杀死典狱长，烧毁监狱。这是我写这本书的一大动机。我写这本书的部分原因，是为了那些身处偏远地区、因痉挛性发声障碍而失去声音，并因此失去所有生活乐趣的可怜人。它也献给所有身处困境的人，无论健康或其他方面。如果你认为你解决问题的几率很小，不要排除这样一种可能性：真正的原因是你不善于估计概率。

But there’s one more thing I need to do, if you recall, or perhaps a few more things. I wasn’t planning a simple escape from my voice prison. I had promised myself that if I escaped, I would free the other inmates, kill the warden, and burn down the prison. That was one of my big motivations for this book. I wrote it, in part, for some poor soul in the middle of nowhere who has lost his voice to spasmodic dysphonia, and with it, all enjoyment of life. It’s also for anyone who has an unsolvable problem, health-wise or otherwise. If you think your odds of solving your problem are bad, don’t rule out the possibility that what is really happening is that you are bad at estimating odds.

更新：自从这本书出版以来，我的声音一直在不断练习，进步很快。现在我每天都会进行近两个小时的直播，收到的最多的赞美之一就是人们喜欢我的声音。

Update: Since the original publication of this book, my voice has steadily improved with use. These days, I do nearly two hours of livestreaming daily, and one of the most common compliments I receive is that people like my voice.

第36章

Chapter 36

关于肯定句的最后说明

A Final Note about Affirmations

我我从经验中知道，这本书的读者会对我关于肯定的故事格外感兴趣。我确信我会被冠以女巫、白痴，或者两者兼而有之。所以，让我提前回应这些不可避免的反对意见。

I know from experience that readers of this book will be disproportionally interested in my stories about affirmations. I’m sure I will be proclaimed a witch, a moron, or both. So let me answer those inevitable objections in advance.

如今，每当我谈论肯定句时，我都会尽可能清楚地表明它们似乎具有有益的价值。事实上，如果肯定句真的像魔法一样掌控宇宙，那么科学很可能早就发现了这种力量。我预见不到肯定句会得到科学支持的那一天，至少在检验魔法或灵异力量是否存在的意义上不会。

When I speak of affirmations these days, I try to say as clearly as possible that they appear to have a beneficial value. The reality is if affirmations somehow steered the universe like magic, science probably would have discovered that force by now. I don’t foresee the day when affirmations get scientific backing, at least not in the sense of testing for the existence of magic or psychic powers.

我想你我都同意，肯定是一种心智现象，属于心理学范畴。从这个角度来看，我们可以想象，做肯定的事情可能会对大脑产生可预测的影响，比如专注力、动力或其他一些化学反应。我们可以假设，这些反应对追求成功有利或有害。所以，从某种意义上说，肯定并不比任何形式的积极思考、祈祷、观想、吟诵或类似的行为更特殊。

I think you and I can agree that affirmations are a phenomenon of the mind and belong in the domain of psychology. Viewed in that light, we can imagine that doing affirmations might have a predictable impact on the brain, perhaps in terms of focus, motivation, or any number of other chemical reactions. Those reactions would, we can assume, either be beneficial or harmful to the pursuit of success. So in one sense, affirmations are no more special than any form of positive thinking, prayers, visualization, chanting, or the like.

话虽如此，我可以告诉你，就我而言，肯定句的力量似乎比你想象的积极思考更大。它给人一种错觉，仿佛世界本身正在改变，以迎合这些肯定句。请允许我解释一下，为什么肯定句似乎不仅仅影响着使用它们的人。

That said, I can tell you that in my case affirmations appear to have more power than you might expect from positive thinking. The illusion is that the world itself is changing to satisfy the affirmations. Allow me to offer some explanations of why affirmations appear to be influencing more than just the person using them.

对于肯定句的明显威力，最显而易见的解释是选择性记忆。大量科学证据支持这一观点：我们人类倾向于记住我们想记住的，忘记我们宁愿忘记的。通过肯定句，我们或许会期望记住偶然的好运，而忘记厄运。这种选择性记忆的结果会给我们一种错误的印象，即肯定句的有效性比你仅仅依靠偶然性所能合理预期的要高。

The most obvious explanation for the apparent power of affirmations is selective memory. There is plenty of science to support the idea what we humans tend to remember what we want to remember and forget what we’d rather forget. With affirmations, we might expect to remember the coincidental good luck and forget the bad luck. The result of that selective remembering gives us the incorrect impression that affirmations work more often than you might reasonably expect from chance alone.

关于肯定句明显威力的另一个完美解释是，那些声称用肯定句成功的人都是骗子，他们的可信度丝毫不亚于那些声称被外星人绑架的人。就我而言，我知道我没有就自己的经历撒谎，但你无法确定我说的是真话。

Another perfectly good explanation of the apparent power of affirmations is that people who report success with it are liars, with no more credibility than the people who report being abducted by aliens. In my case, I know I didn’t lie about my experiences, but you have no way to be sure I’m telling the truth.

错误记忆是肯定句看似有效的另一个可能解释。也许我们记得的胜利在现实中并不那么惊艳，或者我们把普通事件记成巨大的巧合。错误记忆如此常见，你肯定经历过。例如，你可能记得童年时发生的某个事件的细节，后来才发现它发生在你的兄弟姐妹身上，而不是你身上。人类很容易形成错误记忆，所以这肯定是肯定句看似有效的一个潜在解释。

False memory is another possible explanation for why affirmations appear to work. Perhaps we remember victories that weren’t so amazing in reality, or we remember normal events as being huge coincidences. False memories are so common that you’ve certainly experienced them. For example, you might remember a childhood event in some detail and learn later that it happened to your sibling, not you. Humans form false memories quite easily, so that must be one potential explanation of why affirmations appear to work.

肯定句之所以有效，另一个原因是乐观者往往能发现悲观者错过的机会。1,2一个日复一日勤奋地写下肯定句的人，即使只是通过行动，也正是乐观主义者的典型代表。任何形式的积极思考——祈祷之类的——都可能使人拥有更乐观的心态。研究表明，乐观者比悲观者能发现更多机会，因此乐观的结果看起来就像运气一样。

Another reason affirmations appear to work is that optimists tend to notice opportunities that pessimists miss.1,2 A person who diligently writes affirmations day after day is the very definition of an optimist, even if only by actions. Any form of positive thinking—prayer or the like—would presumably put a person in a more optimistic mindset. And because optimists have been shown in studies to notice more opportunities than pessimists, the result can look like luck.

研究还表明，一个人不需要天生乐观就能获得更好的感知能力。3,4你可以训练自己像一个乐观主义者一样行事——写肯定句可能就是很好的训练——这样，在注意到机会时，你就能获得与天生乐观主义者相同的好处。

Studies also show that a person need not be a natural-born optimist to get the benefits of better perception.3,4 You can train yourself to act like an optimist—and writing affirmations is probably good training—so you get the same benefits as natural optimists when it comes to noticing opportunities.

无论你是天生乐观，还是通过自我肯定、祈祷或积极思考成为乐观主义者，你最终都会拥有一些优势，让好运更容易降临。乐观主义者会注意到更多机会，因为想象中的未来成功而拥有更多能量，也更敢于冒险。乐观主义者更容易让好运降临。

Whether you are a born optimist or you become one through affirmations, prayer, or positive thinking, you end up with several advantages that make it easier for luck to find you. Optimists notice more opportunities, have more energy because of their imagined future successes, and take more risks. Optimists make themselves an easy target for luck to find them.

关于肯定句看似强大的另一种解释是，我们误解了因果关系。或许只有内心深处确信自己拥有成功所需条件的人，才会费心去运用肯定句。就我而言，这意味着在我写第一本书之前，我的潜意识不知何故就知道我拥有写出一本好书的天赋——尽管我没有任何相关的写作经验或训练。这种解释听起来很有道理，但它仍然意味着肯定句是有用的，只是方式可能与你想象的不同。根据这种对肯定句力量的解释，它们就像一种信息，从你的潜意识传递到你的理性思维，告诉你你拥有成功所需的条件，即使你的常识与你相反。这对于那些拥有真正天赋但不相信自己拥有天赋的人来说很有用；肯定有很多人属于这一阵营。

Another explanation for the apparent power of affirmations is that we have the causation wrong. Perhaps only the people who know deep down that they have the right stuff to succeed will even bother with affirmations. In my case, that would mean that somewhere in my mind, before I had written my first book, my subconscious somehow knew I had the talent to write a proper book—despite having no relevant writing experience or training. That explanation sounds reasonable to me, but it still means affirmations are useful, just in a different way than you might imagine. Under this explanation of the power of affirmations, they act as a sort of message from your subconscious to your rational mind telling you that you have the right stuff even if your common sense argues otherwise. This would be useful for people who have real talent but don’t believe in it; surely there are a lot of people in that camp.

另一种解释是，肯定句的明显威力在于，我们微小的人类大脑尚未进化到能够准确反映现实的程度。相反，我们小小的大脑只会创造出一些幻觉，这些幻觉不仅能带来生存优势，还能保持某种内在一致性，仅此而已。

Another explanation for the apparent power of affirmations is that our tiny human brains have not evolved to the point where they can give us an accurate impression of our reality. Instead, our little brains create illusions that have survival benefits and some sort of internal consistency, nothing more.

我们知道大脑会产生幻觉，因为世界上有太多互相竞争的宗教。假设你选择了正确的宗教，那么其他可怜的灵魂就生活在谎言之中。你的邻居可能认为他记得前世，而你却认为在心脏手术期间看到了上帝。你们不可能都正确。但你们也可能都错了，而且你们俩都可能经历着对现实的错觉，而这些错觉不知何故不会置你于死地。

We know the brain creates illusions because there are so many competing religions in the world. Assuming you picked the right religion, all those other poor souls are living in lies. Your neighbor might think he remembers his previous life while you think you saw God during your heart surgery. You can’t both be right. But you could both be wrong, and both of you might be experiencing delusions of reality that somehow don’t kill you.

关键在于，肯定句可能存在一个完全合理的科学解释，涉及从多重宇宙到量子奇异性的任何事物，或者任何其他让我们的大脑困惑不已，并导致我们制造错觉来弥补不确定感的事物。简而言之，肯定句可能出于我们大脑无法理解的完全合乎逻辑的理由而起作用。

The point is that affirmations might have a perfectly sensible scientific explanation that involves anything from multiple universes to quantum strangeness, or anything else that baffles our tiny brains and causes us to invent delusions to compensate for our feelings of uncertainty. To put it in simpler terms, affirmations might work for perfectly logical reasons our brains aren’t equipped to understand.

如果你在X上关注我，你就会知道我对人类不过是生活在计算机模拟中的全息图的可能性非常着迷。这个想法乍一听可能荒唐可笑，但背后的数学原理却出奇地令人信服。想象一下，如果我们知道一颗小行星正朝着我们飞来，而且我们无处可逃，1000年后我们人类会怎么做。我想我们会把我们的个性上传到电脑里，或许我们的DNA也会作为代码的一部分，然后把电脑发射到太空，这样我们的文化、记忆和思想就能永存。现在来谈谈数学：假设宇宙大爆炸标志着时间的开始，如果你选择任何一个时间点，那么在任何给定时间点之后都会比之前经历的时间多出无限倍。所以，如果你相信人类有一天会因为某种原因濒临灭绝，那么我们很可能已经是被模拟世界遗留下来的了。

If you follow me on X, you know I’m fascinated by the possibility that we humans are nothing but holograms living in a computer simulation. It sounds ludicrous when you first hear the idea, but the math is oddly compelling. Consider what we humans would do 1,000 years from now if we knew an asteroid was heading our way and there were no escape. I think we’d upload our personalities to computers, perhaps with our DNA as part of the code, and launch the computers into space so our culture, memories, and minds could live forever. Now for the math: If you pick any point in time, there will be infinitely more time transpiring after any given time than before, assuming the Big Bang marks the start of time. So if you believe humans will someday be on the brink of extinction for any reason, there is a vastly greater chance we are already the simulations left behind.

有人认为宇宙太年轻，全息图的场景不可能实现。但如果我们自身就是全息图，那么我们感知到的宇宙年龄只不过是程序员设定的一个变量而已。宇宙的真实年龄可能是数万亿年。

Some have argued that the universe is too young for the hologram scenario to have played out. But if we are holograms, the age of the universe as we perceive it is nothing but a variable from the programmer. The real age could be trillions of years.

这是一个有趣的思想实验，但你可能不信。所以我只是为了完整性才把它加进去。如果我们真的只是计算机生成的实体，那么肯定句可能只不过是一段平凡的程序代码而已。

It’s a fun thought experiment, but you probably don’t buy into it. So I only include it for completeness. If we are indeed nothing but computer-generated entities, affirmations could be nothing more than an unremarkable bit of programming code.

我要重申，我没有任何客观信息表明肯定练习对我有效，或者对你也可能有效。也请不要直接给我发信息，询问关于肯定练习的详细说明，以便你能“正确”地进行练习。我已经收到数百个这样的请求，我总是说“我不知道”。但无论如何，我认为肯定练习并不在意你写了多少次，是否使用键盘或笔，是否扔掉写过的纸，写了多少周，或者任何其他细节。我无法想象肯定练习的过程——如果它真的有效的话——会对小细节敏感。我认为你只需要深入而持续地关注你想要的东西。但这只是我的直觉。

I’ll reiterate that I have no objective information to suggest affirmations have worked for me or that they might work for you. And please don’t direct-message me to ask for the detailed instructions on affirmations so you can do it “right.” I’ve gotten hundreds of those requests already, and I always say some version of “I dunno.” But for what it’s worth, I don’t think affirmations are sensitive to exactly how many times you write them, whether you use a keyboard or pen, whether you throw away the paper you wrote on, how many weeks you do it, or any other detail. I can’t imagine the process of affirmations—if it works at all—is sensitive to the little details. I think a deep and consistent focus on what you want is all that is required. But that’s just my gut feeling.

你可能会发现肯定句与本书主题不一致，尤其是在我提到目标适合失败者而系统适合成功者的部分。肯定句看起来很像专注于目标。但我认为，进行肯定句是一种系统，它能帮助你集中注意力，提升你的乐观和活力，或许还能验证你潜意识中一直知道的天赋和动力。如果你打算尝试肯定句，我建议你把目标定得足够宽泛，以便留出一些运气。肯定未来的财富或许比试图赢得一张特定的彩票更好。

You might see an inconsistency between affirmations and the theme of this book, specifically the parts where I say goals are for losers and systems are for winners. Affirmations look a lot like focusing on goals. But I would argue that doing affirmations is a system that helps you focus, boosts your optimism and energy, and perhaps validates the talent and drive that your subconscious always knew you had. If you plan to try affirmations, I recommend keeping your objectives broad enough to allow some luck. It’s probably better to affirm future wealth than to try to win a specific lottery.

人类总是会以目标为导向思考。我们的大脑就是这样运作的。但只有当你拥有一个引导你朝着正确方向前进的系统时，目标才有意义。

Humans will always think in terms of goals. Our brains are wired that way. But goals only make sense if you also have a system that moves you in the right direction.

那么我对肯定句有何看法？

So what do I believe about affirmations?

我记得我尝试过几次肯定疗法，我记得——或者自认为我记得——效果简直不可思议。所以对我来说，肯定疗法一直是一个谜。我唯一确定的是，我从未听说过有人因为肯定疗法而受到情感或其他方面的伤害。我尝试肯定疗法是出于好奇，也因为它免费。我不需要更好的理由。

I believe I tried affirmations on several occasions and the results I remember—or think I remember—appear to be borderline miraculous. So to me, affirmations are an ongoing mystery. All I know for sure is that I’ve never heard of anyone being harmed, emotionally or otherwise, by affirmations. I tried affirmations out of curiosity and because it was free. I didn’t need a better reason.

现在你知道我所知道的了。

Now you know what I know.

第37章

Chapter 37

概括

Summary

我本书涵盖了诸多主题，因此我认为有必要提供一个总结来总结一下。请记住，如果你直接跳到书末阅读此部分，脱离上下文来看，会显得非常缺乏说服力。

I covered a lot of topics in this book, so I thought it would be helpful to provide a summary to wrap it all up. Keep in mind that if you skipped to the end of the book to read this section, it will seem extraordinarily unpersuasive out of context.

我在此描述的成功模式大致如下：首先关注你的饮食，并做好饮食，这样你才有足够的精力去锻炼。锻炼会进一步提升你的精力，这反过来会让你更有效率、更有创造力、更积极向上、更有社会吸引力，也更有能力应对生活中的小挫折。

The model for success I described herein looks roughly like this: Focus on your diet first and get that right so you have enough energy to want to exercise. Exercise will further improve your energy, and that in turn will make you more productive, more creative, more positive, more socially desirable, and more able to handle life’s little bumps.

一旦你优化了个人能量，成功所需的就只剩下运气了。你无法直接掌控运气，但你可以从胜算不大的策略转向胜算高的策略。例如，学习多种技能——天赋叠加——比只学习一两项技能能大幅提升你的成功几率。如果你学会控制自我，就能选择一些吓跑那些害怕尴尬的人的策略，从而在更小的范围内竞争。如果你在这个领域坚持得足够久，运气就更有可能找到你。要避免职业陷阱，比如追求那些需要你出卖有限时间却无法为你做好充分准备的工作。

Once you optimize your personal energy, all you need for success is luck. You can’t directly control luck, but you can move from strategies with bad odds to strategies with good odds. For example, learning multiple skills—talent-stacking—raises your odds of success dramatically compared to learning just one or two skills. If you learn to control your ego, you can pick strategies that scare off the people who fear embarrassment, thus competing against a smaller field. And if you stay in the game long enough, luck has a better chance of finding you. Avoid career traps such as pursuing jobs that require you to sell your limited supply of time while preparing you for nothing better.

幸福是人生中唯一有用的目标。除非你是反社会人格者，否则你的幸福取决于善待他人。只要你拥有健康的身体、充足的资源和灵活的时间安排，幸福就会自然而然地到来。首先要保持健康，通过努力工作获取资源和新技能，并寻找能让你拥有灵活时间安排的机会。

Happiness is the only useful goal in life. Unless you are a sociopath, your own happiness will depend on being good to others. And happiness tends to happen naturally whenever you have good health, resources, and a flexible schedule. Get your health right first, acquire resources and new skills through hard work, and look for opportunities that will give you a flexible schedule.

有些技能比其他技能更重要，你应该尽可能多地掌握这些关键技能，包括公开演讲、商务写作、对说服心理学的实用理解、基本的技术概念、社交技巧、正确的语音技巧、良好的语法以及会计基础知识。养成简化的习惯。学习如何与陌生人闲聊，避免表现得像个混蛋。如果你能掌握这些技能——几乎每个人都能做到——你将很难停下来。

Some skills are more important than others, and you should acquire as many of those key skills as possible, including public speaking, business writing, a working understanding of the psychology of persuasion, basic technology concepts, social skills, proper voice technique, good grammar, and the fundamentals of accounting. Develop a habit of simplifying. Learn how to make small talk with strangers and avoid being an asshole. If you get that stuff right—and almost anyone can—you will be hard to stop.

或许，把自己想象成一个湿润的机器人，而不是一个充满魔法和神秘的皮囊会对你有所帮助。如果你能控制输入，就能决定结果，哪怕运气不好。合理饮食，锻炼身体，积极思考，尽可能多学习，远离牢狱之灾，美好的事情就会发生。

It might help you to think of yourself as a moist robot, not a skin-bag full of magic and mystery. If you control the inputs, you can determine the outcomes, give or take some luck. Eat right, exercise, think positively, learn as much as possible, stay out of jail, and good things can happen.

从饮食到运动，在生活的方方面面寻找规律。试着为你观察到的规律寻找科学依据，并将自己作为实验室，看看这些规律是否适用于你。

Look for patterns in every part of life, from diet to exercise. Try to find scientific backing for your observed patterns and use yourself as a laboratory to see if the patterns hold for you.

最重要的是，要明白目标是为失败者准备的，而系统是为成功者准备的。那些看似运气好的人，往往拥有一套能让运气降临到他们身上的系统。我在这本书里列出了一些对我来说似乎很有效的系统。你的经验可能会有所不同，但用系统而不是目标来思考总是有益的。

Most important, understand that goals are for losers and systems are for winners. People who seem to have good luck are often the people who have a system that allows luck to find them. I’ve laid out some systems in this book that seem to work for me. Your experience will differ, but it always helps to be thinking in terms of systems and not goals.

永远记住，失败是你的朋友。它是成功的原材料。接纳它，从中学习。别让它离开，直到你掏空它的口袋。这才是真正的成功之道。

And always remember that failure is your friend. It’s the raw material of success. Invite it in. Learn from it. And don’t let it leave until you pick its pocket. That’s a system.

结束

The End
